module.exports = {"m.3.multimeadow":[{"p":"Maya puts 3 crackers on each plate. She fills 4 plates. How many crackers does she use in all?","a":"12 crackers","w":["7 crackers","9 crackers","15 crackers"],"h":"Think of 4 equal groups with 3 in each group. You can skip count: 3, 6, 9...","e":"This is equal groups: 4 groups of 3 is 4 x 3 = 12. Multiplication finds the total of equal groups."},{"p":"There are 5 puppies, and each puppy has 6 spots. How many spots are there altogether?","a":"30 spots","w":["11 spots","25 spots","35 spots"],"h":"Count 5 groups of 6. Try skip counting by 6: 6, 12, 18...","e":"5 groups of 6 is 5 x 6 = 30. Multiplying joins equal groups into one total."},{"p":"A ladybug has 8 legs pictured on each card. Sam has 2 cards. How many legs in all?","a":"16 legs","w":["10 legs","14 legs","18 legs"],"h":"You have 2 groups of 8. You can also double 8.","e":"2 x 8 = 16. Multiplying by 2 is the same as doubling the number."},{"p":"At recess, 3 friends each score 7 points in a bean-bag game. How many points did they score together?","a":"21 points","w":["10 points","18 points","24 points"],"h":"Add 7 three times, or think 3 x 7. Skip count by 7: 7, 14...","e":"3 x 7 = 21. Repeated groups of 7 add up to the total."},{"p":"A snack box has 6 rows with 6 raisins in each row. How many raisins are in the box?","a":"36 raisins","w":["12 raisins","30 raisins","42 raisins"],"h":"This is 6 rows of 6. Skip count by 6 six times.","e":"6 x 6 = 36. An array of equal rows is multiplied: rows times items per row."},{"p":"A garden has an array of flowers: 3 rows with 5 flowers in each row. How many flowers are there?","a":"15 flowers","w":["8 flowers","10 flowers","20 flowers"],"h":"Multiply the number of rows by how many are in each row.","e":"An array of 3 rows of 5 is 3 x 5 = 15. Rows times columns gives the total."},{"p":"Leo skip counts by 4s to feed 4 fish in each tank: 4, 8, 12, 16... What number does he say for the 5th tank?","a":"20","w":["16","24","5"],"h":"Keep adding 4 each time after 16.","e":"Skip counting by 4 gives 4, 8, 12, 16, 20. The 5th number is 5 x 4 = 20."},{"p":"Nine kids each bring 2 stickers to school. How many stickers do they bring in all?","a":"18 stickers","w":["11 stickers","16 stickers","20 stickers"],"h":"You have 9 groups of 2. Try doubling 9.","e":"9 x 2 = 18. Nine groups of two is the same as doubling nine."},{"p":"A pet store has 8 cages with 5 hamsters in each cage. How many hamsters are there?","a":"40 hamsters","w":["13 hamsters","35 hamsters","45 hamsters"],"h":"Count by 5s eight times: 5, 10, 15...","e":"8 x 5 = 40. Skip counting by 5 for each group gives the total."},{"p":"Grandma bakes 4 trays of muffins with 6 muffins on each tray. How many muffins did she bake?","a":"24 muffins","w":["10 muffins","20 muffins","28 muffins"],"h":"Four equal groups of 6. Skip count by 6 four times.","e":"4 x 6 = 24. Equal groups are combined by multiplying."},{"p":"Each week Ben reads 3 comic books. How many comic books does he read in 10 weeks?","a":"30 comics","w":["13 comics","27 comics","33 comics"],"h":"You are counting 10 groups of 3. Multiplying by 10 is quick!","e":"10 x 3 = 30. To multiply by 10, add a zero to the other number."},{"p":"There are 2 wagons, and each wagon holds 7 pumpkins. How many pumpkins in all?","a":"14 pumpkins","w":["9 pumpkins","12 pumpkins","16 pumpkins"],"h":"Two groups of 7, or double 7.","e":"2 x 7 = 14. Multiplying by 2 doubles the number."},{"p":"A board game has 5 players, and each player gets 5 cards. How many cards are handed out?","a":"25 cards","w":["10 cards","20 cards","30 cards"],"h":"Five groups of 5. Skip count by 5 five times.","e":"5 x 5 = 25. Equal groups of 5 are counted by multiplying."},{"p":"Three kittens each chase 6 yarn balls. How many yarn balls are chased in all?","a":"18 yarn balls","w":["9 yarn balls","15 yarn balls","21 yarn balls"],"h":"Three groups of 6. Skip count by 6: 6, 12...","e":"3 x 6 = 18. Multiplying joins the 3 equal groups of 6."},{"p":"A checkerboard corner has an array of 4 rows with 4 squares in each row. How many squares is that?","a":"16 squares","w":["8 squares","12 squares","20 squares"],"h":"Rows times squares per row. You can also double 4 and double again.","e":"4 x 4 = 16. An equal array multiplies rows by columns."},{"p":"Read: \"On the class hike, students walk in pairs. There are 8 pairs, and each pair carries the same number of kids.\" How many kids are hiking?","a":"16 kids","w":["10 kids","14 kids","18 kids"],"h":"A pair means 2. Count 8 groups of 2.","e":"8 x 2 = 16. Eight pairs is 8 groups of 2, which is doubling."},{"p":"Skip count by 5s to fill juice cups: 5, 10, 15, 20... What number comes for the 6th cup?","a":"30","w":["25","35","6"],"h":"Keep adding 5 each time after 20.","e":"Skip counting by 5 gives 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30. The 6th number is 6 x 5 = 30."},{"p":"In the meadow, there are 7 flower patches. Each patch has 6 butterflies resting on it. How many butterflies are there in all?","a":"42","w":["13","36","48"],"h":"Try skip counting by 6 seven times, or by 7 six times.","e":"This is 7 equal groups of 6, so 7 x 6 = 42. It is a multiplication problem about equal groups."},{"p":"Farmer Dale has 3 egg cartons. Each carton holds 12 eggs. How many eggs does he have in all?","a":"36","w":["15","24","33"],"h":"Think of 3 groups of 12, or count by 12s three times.","e":"3 groups of 12 is 3 x 12 = 36. Equal groups make a multiplication problem."},{"p":"Nina makes 4 bracelets. She puts 9 beads on each bracelet. How many beads does she use in all?","a":"36","w":["13","32","45"],"h":"Skip count by 9 four times: 9, 18, ...","e":"4 x 9 = 36, which is four equal groups of nine beads."},{"p":"Ravi has some baskets. Each basket holds 6 apples, and he has 48 apples in all. How many baskets does he have?","a":"8","w":["7","9","42"],"h":"Ask yourself: 6 times what number equals 48?","e":"Since 6 x 8 = 48, there are 8 baskets. This finds a missing factor."},{"p":"Mia skip counts by 6s to count crayons in boxes: 6, 12, 18, 24... What number does she say for the 7th box?","a":"42","w":["36","40","48"],"h":"Keep adding 6 each time until you reach the 7th number.","e":"The 7th multiple of 6 is 6 x 7 = 42. This is skip counting by 6s."},{"p":"There are 4 shelves in the toy room. Each shelf holds 11 toy cars. How many toy cars are there in all?","a":"44","w":["15","40","48"],"h":"Count by 11s four times, or think 4 x 10 plus 4 x 1.","e":"4 x 11 = 44, which is four equal groups of eleven."},{"p":"A sticker sheet has 8 rows with 3 stickers in each row. How many stickers are on the sheet?","a":"24","w":["11","21","27"],"h":"Multiply the number of rows by the number in each row.","e":"8 rows of 3 is 8 x 3 = 24. An array shows equal rows."},{"p":"Ben arranges his blocks in 4 rows of 7. Which arrangement uses the SAME number of blocks?","a":"7 rows of 4 blocks","w":["4 rows of 6 blocks","5 rows of 7 blocks","7 rows of 7 blocks"],"h":"Switching the number of rows with the number in each row keeps the total the same.","e":"4 x 7 equals 7 x 4 = 28. This is the commutative property of multiplication."},{"p":"At the game booth, Team Red scores 6 baskets worth 4 points each. Team Blue scores 5 baskets worth 5 points each. Which team scored MORE points?","a":"Team Blue with 25 points","w":["Team Red with 24 points","Team Blue with 20 points","Team Red with 30 points"],"h":"Find each team's total first, then compare the two totals.","e":"Red made 6 x 4 = 24 and Blue made 5 x 5 = 25, so Blue scored more. You compare two products."},{"p":"Each spider has 8 legs. Ella counts 7 spiders on a web. How many spider legs are there in all?","a":"56","w":["15","48","64"],"h":"Skip count by 8 seven times: 8, 16, ...","e":"7 x 8 = 56, which is seven equal groups of eight legs."},{"p":"A big checkerboard has 12 rows with 12 squares in each row. How many squares are on the whole board?","a":"144","w":["24","132","121"],"h":"Multiply 12 by 12; try 12 x 10 plus 12 x 2.","e":"12 x 12 = 144. It is a square array of twelve rows and twelve columns."},{"p":"Tom has 3 packs of trading cards with 8 cards in each pack. Sara has twice as many packs as Tom, with 8 cards in each pack. How many cards does Sara have?","a":"48","w":["24","16","32"],"h":"First find how many packs Sara has, then multiply by 8.","e":"Sara has 6 packs (twice 3), and 6 x 8 = 48. This problem takes two steps."},{"p":"A pizza shop puts 9 pepperoni slices on each pizza. They make 10 pizzas. How many pepperoni slices do they use in all?","a":"90","w":["19","81","99"],"h":"Multiplying by 10 just adds a zero to the other factor.","e":"10 x 9 = 90, which is ten equal groups of nine."},{"p":"Jay skip counts by 7s to count the days in each week: 7, 14, 21... What number does he say for the 5th week?","a":"35","w":["28","30","42"],"h":"Add 7 each time until you reach the 5th number.","e":"The 5th multiple of 7 is 7 x 5 = 35. This is skip counting by 7s."},{"p":"Some friends share grapes at a table. Each friend gets 9 grapes, and 27 grapes are given out in all. How many friends are there?","a":"3","w":["4","2","18"],"h":"Ask yourself: 9 times what number equals 27?","e":"Since 9 x 3 = 27, there are 3 friends. This finds a missing factor."},{"p":"A muffin tin has 5 rows with 8 muffin cups in each row. How many muffin cups are there in all?","a":"40","w":["13","32","45"],"h":"Multiply the number of rows by the cups in each row.","e":"5 x 8 = 40, an array of five rows of eight cups."},{"p":"A pack of markers has 12 markers. Miss Kim buys 5 packs for art class. How many markers does she have in all?","a":"60","w":["17","55","72"],"h":"Count by 12s five times, or by 5s twelve times.","e":"5 x 12 = 60, which is five equal groups of twelve."},{"p":"There are 7 baskets at the picnic. Each basket has 11 sandwiches. How many sandwiches are there in all?","a":"77","w":["18","70","84"],"h":"Try 7 x 10 plus 7 x 1 to build the answer.","e":"7 x 11 = 77, which is seven equal groups of eleven."},{"p":"Zoe skip counts by 8s to count octopus arms at the aquarium: 8, 16, 24... What number does she say for the 6th octopus?","a":"48","w":["40","56","42"],"h":"Keep adding 8 each time, and count how many jumps you make: 1st, 2nd, 3rd...","e":"Skip counting by 8 is the same as 6 x 8 = 48."},{"p":"Owen skip counts by 9s to count the crayons in each box: 9, 18, 27... What number does he say for the 8th box?","a":"72","w":["63","81","71"],"h":"Each box adds 9 more. Land on the 8th number in the count.","e":"Skip counting by 9 gives 8 x 9 = 72."},{"p":"Each pack of gum has 10 pieces. Dev buys 7 packs. How many pieces of gum does he have in all?","a":"70","w":["17","60","80"],"h":"Multiplying by 10 just adds a zero to the other number.","e":"This is 7 x 10 = 70, the times-10 fact."},{"p":"There are 6 flower pots on the porch, and each pot has 0 seeds planted in it. How many seeds are planted in all?","a":"0","w":["6","60","12"],"h":"How many seeds do you have if every group is empty?","e":"Any number times 0 is 0, so 6 x 0 = 0."},{"p":"There are 8 bird nests in the tree, and each nest has exactly 1 egg. How many eggs are there in all?","a":"8","w":["1","9","18"],"h":"When each group has just 1, the total matches the number of groups.","e":"Any number times 1 stays the same, so 8 x 1 = 8."},{"p":"A crayon box holds 6 rows with 8 crayons in each row. Which arrangement holds the SAME number of crayons?","a":"8 rows with 6 crayons in each row","w":["8 rows with 8 crayons in each row","6 rows with 6 crayons in each row","6 rows with 12 crayons in each row"],"h":"You can flip the rows and columns and get the same total.","e":"This shows the commutative property: 6 x 8 = 8 x 6 = 48."},{"p":"Read: \"Four dogs are at the park, and each dog buries 5 bones.\" Which number sentence shows how many bones in all?","a":"4 x 5 = 20","w":["4 + 5 = 9","5 x 5 = 25","4 x 4 = 16"],"h":"Equal groups means you multiply the number of groups by the size of each group.","e":"Four groups of 5 is 4 x 5 = 20 bones."},{"p":"A baker fills trays that each hold 8 cupcakes. She made 56 cupcakes on full trays. How many trays did she use?","a":"7","w":["6","8","48"],"h":"Think: what number times 8 gives you 56?","e":"This is a missing-factor problem: 7 x 8 = 56, so 7 trays."},{"p":"There are 3 tables with 4 kids at each table. Each kid gets 2 cookies. How many cookies are handed out in all?","a":"24","w":["12","9","20"],"h":"First find how many kids there are, then find the cookies.","e":"This is a two-step problem: 3 x 4 = 12 kids, then 12 x 2 = 24 cookies."},{"p":"One bag has 7 boxes with 4 crayons each. Another bag has 5 boxes with 6 crayons each. Which bag holds MORE crayons?","a":"The bag with 5 boxes of 6 crayons","w":["The bag with 7 boxes of 4 crayons","Both bags hold the same amount","Neither bag has any crayons"],"h":"Find the total in each bag, then compare the two totals.","e":"7 x 4 = 28 and 5 x 6 = 30, so the second bag has more."},{"p":"A calendar page shows 6 rows with 11 days marked in each row. How many days are marked in all?","a":"66","w":["55","77","61"],"h":"To multiply by 11, think 11 as 10 and 1 more of the number.","e":"This is the times-11 fact: 6 x 11 = 66."},{"p":"A dozen eggs means 12 eggs. For a big pancake breakfast, the cooks use 8 dozen eggs. How many eggs is that?","a":"96","w":["84","108","92"],"h":"A dozen is 12, so multiply 12 by the number of dozens.","e":"This is the times-12 fact: 8 x 12 = 96 eggs."},{"p":"A parking lot has 9 rows with 7 cars in each row. How many cars are parked in all?","a":"63","w":["56","72","16"],"h":"An array of rows and columns means you multiply them together.","e":"This is 9 x 7 = 63, the total in the array."},{"p":"Priya reads 5 pages each night. Her brother reads double that many each night. How many pages does her brother read in 4 nights?","a":"40","w":["20","30","45"],"h":"First find how many pages the brother reads each night, then multiply by 4.","e":"Double 5 is 10 pages a night, and 10 x 4 = 40 pages."},{"p":"Each toy car at the shop costs $4. Sam buys 6 toy cars. How much money does he spend in all?","a":"$24","w":["$10","$20","$28"],"h":"Each car is the same price, so multiply the price by how many he buys.","e":"This is equal groups of money: 6 x $4 = $24."},{"p":"Read: \"The class plants a garden with 6 rows. Each row has 9 carrot plants, and every plant grows one carrot.\" How many carrots grow in all?","a":"54","w":["15","45","63"],"h":"The rows and plants form an array, so multiply them.","e":"Six rows of 9 is 6 x 9 = 54 carrots."},{"p":"Read: \"At the aquarium there are 4 big tanks. Each tank has 8 seahorses swimming inside, and every tank has the same number.\" How many seahorses are there in all?","a":"32","w":["12","24","36"],"h":"Equal tanks means you can multiply instead of adding four times.","e":"Four groups of 8 is 4 x 8 = 32 seahorses."},{"p":"Which multiplication fact matches the repeated addition 7 + 7 + 7 + 7 + 7?","a":"5 x 7 = 35","w":["7 x 7 = 49","5 + 7 = 12","7 x 6 = 42"],"h":"Count how many 7s are being added together.","e":"There are five 7s, so 5 x 7 = 35."}],"m.4.fracpizza":[{"p":"Mia cuts a pizza into 4 equal slices and eats 1 slice. What fraction of the pizza did she eat?","a":"1/4","w":["1/3","3/4","4/1"],"h":"The top number is how many slices she ate; the bottom is the total number of equal slices.","e":"A fraction shows part of a whole: 1 slice out of 4 equal slices is 1/4."},{"p":"A chocolate bar is split into 2 equal pieces and Sam takes 1 piece. What fraction did he take?","a":"1/2","w":["1/1","2/1","2/2"],"h":"Think about one part out of two equal parts.","e":"One out of two equal parts is one half, written 1/2."},{"p":"Which fraction means the SAME amount as 1/2?","a":"2/4","w":["1/4","3/4","1/3"],"h":"Look for a fraction where the top number is exactly half of the bottom number.","e":"Equivalent fractions name the same amount: 2/4 equals 1/2 because 2 is half of 4."},{"p":"A sub sandwich is cut into 3 equal parts. Which fraction shows 2 of those parts?","a":"2/3","w":["3/2","1/3","2/2"],"h":"Count the parts you have over the total number of equal parts.","e":"Two of three equal parts is 2/3; the top number counts the parts you have."},{"p":"Which fraction is BIGGER: 3/4 or 1/4?","a":"3/4","w":["1/4","They are equal","4/4"],"h":"When the bottom numbers match, more parts means a bigger fraction.","e":"With the same denominator, comparing top numbers works: 3/4 is greater than 1/4."},{"p":"What is 1/5 + 2/5?","a":"3/5","w":["3/10","2/5","3/25"],"h":"When the bottom numbers are the same, add the top numbers and keep the bottom.","e":"Adding fractions with like denominators: 1/5 + 2/5 = 3/5, keeping the denominator 5."},{"p":"A bag has 6 apples and 3 of them are red. What fraction of the apples are red?","a":"3/6","w":["6/3","3/3","6/6"],"h":"Put the number of red apples over the total number of apples.","e":"A fraction of a set puts the part (3 red) over the whole group (6 apples): 3/6."},{"p":"Leo colored 2 out of 8 equal squares on his snack chart. What fraction did he color?","a":"2/8","w":["8/2","2/6","6/8"],"h":"The top is how many squares he colored; the bottom is the total squares.","e":"Part over whole: 2 colored squares out of 8 equal squares is 2/8."},{"p":"Which fraction is the SMALLEST: 1/6, 3/6, or 5/6?","a":"1/6","w":["5/6","3/6","They are equal"],"h":"When bottoms are the same, fewer parts means a smaller fraction.","e":"With equal denominators, the smallest top number is smallest, so 1/6 is least."},{"p":"A whole pizza has 8 equal slices. If all 8 slices are eaten, what fraction is that?","a":"8/8","w":["1/8","8/1","0/8"],"h":"When you have every equal part, the top and bottom numbers are the same.","e":"A whole made of all its parts is 8/8, which equals one whole pizza."},{"p":"Two friends share a cookie split into 6 equal parts. Which fraction equals 1/2 of the cookie?","a":"3/6","w":["1/6","2/6","6/6"],"h":"Half means the top number should be exactly half of the bottom number.","e":"Equivalent fractions: 3/6 equals 1/2 because 3 is half of 6."},{"p":"What is 2/7 + 3/7?","a":"5/7","w":["5/14","6/7","5/49"],"h":"The bottoms are the same, so add only the top numbers.","e":"Adding like fractions: 2/7 + 3/7 = 5/7, keeping the denominator 7."},{"p":"What is 5/8 - 2/8?","a":"3/8","w":["7/8","3/16","1/8"],"h":"Subtract the top numbers and keep the same bottom number.","e":"Subtracting like fractions: 5/8 - 2/8 = 3/8, keeping the denominator 8."},{"p":"A pan of brownies has 10 equal pieces. If 4 have nuts, what fraction has nuts?","a":"4/10","w":["10/4","4/6","6/10"],"h":"Put the pieces with nuts over the total number of pieces.","e":"A fraction of a set: 4 pieces with nuts out of 10 pieces is 4/10."},{"p":"Jack pours 1/3 of a juice jug, then pours 1/3 more. How much has he poured in all?","a":"2/3","w":["2/6","1/3","2/9"],"h":"The bottom numbers are the same, so add the top numbers together.","e":"Adding like fractions: 1/3 + 1/3 = 2/3, keeping the denominator 3."},{"p":"A pizza is cut into 4 equal slices, and 2 slices are cheese. Which fraction from a pizza cut into 8 equal slices shows the SAME amount as those 2 cheese slices?","a":"4/8","w":["2/8","6/8","8/8"],"h":"Try doubling both the top and the bottom numbers.","e":"2/4 and 4/8 are equivalent fractions because they cover the same amount of pizza."},{"p":"Which is the BIGGEST piece of pizza: 1/3, 1/4, 1/6, or 1/8?","a":"1/3","w":["1/4","1/6","1/8"],"h":"When the top number is 1, more pieces means each piece is smaller.","e":"With the same numerator, a smaller denominator makes bigger pieces, so 1/3 is largest."},{"p":"What is 3/8 + 3/8?","a":"6/8","w":["6/16","5/8","9/8"],"h":"The size of the pieces, shown by the bottom number, stays the same when you add.","e":"Add the numerators and keep the denominator: 3/8 + 3/8 = 6/8."},{"p":"What is 7/10 - 3/10?","a":"4/10","w":["4/20","4/7","10/10"],"h":"The bottom number tells the piece size and does not change.","e":"Subtract the numerators and keep the denominator: 7/10 - 3/10 = 4/10."},{"p":"A box has 12 donuts, and 1/4 of them have sprinkles. How many donuts have sprinkles?","a":"3 donuts","w":["4 donuts","6 donuts","8 donuts"],"h":"Split the 12 donuts into 4 equal groups.","e":"Finding 1/4 of a set means splitting 12 into 4 equal groups, so each group has 3."},{"p":"There are 15 kids at recess, and 1/3 of them are playing tag. How many kids are playing tag?","a":"5 kids","w":["3 kids","10 kids","12 kids"],"h":"Share the 15 kids into 3 equal teams.","e":"Finding 1/3 of a set means splitting 15 into 3 equal groups of 5."},{"p":"Which fraction shows the SAME amount as 3/4?","a":"6/8","w":["3/8","4/6","6/6"],"h":"Try multiplying the top and the bottom by the same number.","e":"3/4 and 6/8 are equivalent fractions because both the top and bottom were doubled."},{"p":"Is 3/8 of a cookie MORE or LESS than 1/2 of the cookie?","a":"Less than 1/2","w":["More than 1/2","Exactly 1/2","Equal to a whole"],"h":"Half of 8 equal pieces would be 4 pieces.","e":"Half of 8 is 4, and 3 is fewer than 4, so 3/8 is less than 1/2."},{"p":"Read: \"Tom eats 2/6 of a veggie tray, then eats 1/6 more.\" What fraction of the tray has Tom eaten in all?","a":"3/6","w":["3/12","3/18","2/6"],"h":"Add the parts he ate while keeping the piece size the same.","e":"2/6 + 1/6 = 3/6; add the numerators and keep the denominator."},{"p":"A pie is cut into 5 equal slices, and the family eats 3 slices. What fraction of the pie is LEFT?","a":"2/5","w":["3/5","2/3","5/2"],"h":"Start with the whole pie, which is 5/5.","e":"5/5 - 3/5 = 2/5, so two slices are left."},{"p":"A bag has 8 marbles: 5 are blue and 3 are green. What fraction of the marbles are green?","a":"3/8","w":["3/5","5/8","8/3"],"h":"The bottom number is the total number of marbles.","e":"Green marbles are 3 out of 8 total, so the fraction is 3/8."},{"p":"Which fraction does NOT equal 1/2?","a":"3/5","w":["2/4","4/8","5/10"],"h":"Check whether the top number is exactly half of the bottom number.","e":"1/2 means the top is half the bottom; 3 is not half of 5, so 3/5 does not equal 1/2."},{"p":"What is 1/4 + 2/4?","a":"3/4","w":["3/8","3/16","2/8"],"h":"Keep the fourths the same size as you combine them.","e":"1/4 + 2/4 = 3/4; add the numerators and keep the denominator."},{"p":"Read: \"Maya has 5/6 of a chocolate bar and gives 2/6 of the bar to her brother.\" What fraction of the bar does Maya have left?","a":"3/6","w":["2/6","7/6","3/12"],"h":"Take away the part she gave, keeping the piece size the same.","e":"5/6 - 2/6 = 3/6; subtract the numerators and keep the denominator."},{"p":"Which is the SMALLEST piece of sandwich: 2/3, 2/5, 2/6, or 2/9?","a":"2/9","w":["2/3","2/5","2/6"],"h":"When the top numbers match, more pieces means each one is smaller.","e":"With equal numerators, the largest denominator gives the smallest piece, so 2/9 is smallest."},{"p":"A carton holds 6 eggs, and 4 of them are brown. What fraction of the eggs are brown?","a":"4/6","w":["4/2","2/6","6/4"],"h":"The total number of eggs goes on the bottom.","e":"Brown eggs are 4 out of 6 total, so the fraction is 4/6."},{"p":"2/3 of a granola bar is the same as how many sixths?","a":"4/6","w":["2/6","3/6","5/6"],"h":"Think about how many sixths fit inside each third.","e":"Multiplying the top and bottom of 2/3 by 2 gives 4/6, an equivalent fraction."},{"p":"Ben ate 2/6 of a pizza and Lily ate 3/6 of the same pizza. Who ate MORE?","a":"Lily, because 3/6 is more than 2/6","w":["Ben, because 2/6 is more than 3/6","They both ate the same amount","You cannot tell who ate more"],"h":"The pieces are the same size, so just compare how many pieces each ate.","e":"With the same denominator, the larger numerator is bigger, so 3/6 > 2/6 means Lily ate more."},{"p":"There are 20 kids in art class, and 3/4 of them brought their own snack. How many kids brought a snack?","a":"15 kids","w":["5 kids","3 kids","12 kids"],"h":"First find how many kids are in one fourth of the class, then think about how many fourths you need.","e":"Finding a fraction of a set: 20 split into 4 equal groups is 5, and 3 groups of 5 make 15."},{"p":"Put these slice sizes in order from SMALLEST to LARGEST: 1/2, 1/8, 1/4.","a":"1/8, 1/4, 1/2","w":["1/2, 1/4, 1/8","1/8, 1/2, 1/4","1/4, 1/8, 1/2"],"h":"When the top number is 1, more equal pieces means each piece is tinier.","e":"For unit fractions, a bigger bottom number means a smaller piece, so 1/8 is smallest and 1/2 is largest."},{"p":"Sara eats 3/4 of one small pizza and 3/4 of another small pizza. How much pizza did she eat in all?","a":"1 and 1/2 pizzas","w":["6/8 of a pizza","3/4 of a pizza","1 and 1/4 pizzas"],"h":"Add the fourths together, then see how many whole pizzas that makes.","e":"Adding like fractions gives 3/4 + 3/4 = 6/4, which is one whole pizza plus another 1/2 pizza."},{"p":"Which fraction is EQUIVALENT to 2/5 of a chocolate bar?","a":"4/10","w":["2/10","4/5","3/6"],"h":"Try doubling both the top number and the bottom number of 2/5.","e":"Equivalent fractions name the same amount; doubling 2/5 gives 4/10, the same size piece."},{"p":"A pitcher is completely full (8/8) of lemonade. Kids pour out 3/8 of it. What fraction of the lemonade is LEFT?","a":"5/8","w":["3/8","5/16","11/8"],"h":"Start from the full pitcher as eighths and take away what was poured out.","e":"This is subtracting like fractions: 8/8 - 3/8 = 5/8, keeping the bottom number the same."},{"p":"A box has 12 cupcakes, and 2/3 of them have frosting. How many cupcakes have frosting?","a":"8 cupcakes","w":["4 cupcakes","2 cupcakes","6 cupcakes"],"h":"Split the 12 cupcakes into 3 equal groups first, then count two of those groups.","e":"To find 2/3 of a set, divide 12 into 3 groups of 4 and take 2 groups, which is 8."},{"p":"Which is the BIGGEST piece of pizza: 2/3, 3/4, or 1/2?","a":"3/4","w":["2/3","1/2","They are all the same size"],"h":"Picture how close each piece comes to a whole pizza.","e":"Comparing fractions, 3/4 is closest to a whole pizza, so it is the biggest piece."},{"p":"One pizza has 5/6 left and another pizza has 5/8 left. Which one has MORE pizza left?","a":"The pizza with 5/6 left","w":["The pizza with 5/8 left","They have the same amount left","You cannot tell at all"],"h":"With the same number of pieces on top, fewer total pieces means each piece is larger.","e":"Since both have 5 pieces, the sixths are bigger than the eighths, so 5/6 is more pizza."},{"p":"Which fraction is CLOSEST to zero: 1/2, 1/10, or 1/3?","a":"1/10","w":["1/2","1/3","They are all equal"],"h":"A tiny piece comes from cutting the whole into many, many equal parts.","e":"For unit fractions, the largest bottom number makes the smallest piece, so 1/10 is closest to zero."},{"p":"Read: \"A pizza has 8 equal slices. Mario eats 2 slices and his sister eats 3 slices.\" What fraction of the pizza did they eat together?","a":"5/8","w":["5/16","3/8","6/8"],"h":"Combine the slices they ate, then compare to the total number of slices.","e":"Add the slices eaten (2 + 3 = 5) over the 8 total slices to get 5/8 of the pizza."},{"p":"There are 9 juice boxes in a cooler, and 1/3 of them are apple juice. How many juice boxes are NOT apple juice?","a":"6 juice boxes","w":["3 juice boxes","9 juice boxes","2 juice boxes"],"h":"First find how many ARE apple, then see how many are left over.","e":"1/3 of 9 is 3 apple boxes, so the other 6 boxes are not apple juice."},{"p":"Which is the SMALLEST piece of a sandwich: 4/5, 4/9, or 4/7?","a":"4/9","w":["4/5","4/7","They are all equal"],"h":"When the top numbers match, more total pieces makes each piece smaller.","e":"With the same numerator, the largest denominator gives the smallest piece, so 4/9 is smallest."},{"p":"A whole veggie wrap counts as 5/5. If someone eats 2/5 of it, what is 1 whole minus 2/5?","a":"3/5","w":["2/5","3/10","1/5"],"h":"Think of the whole wrap written as fifths before you subtract.","e":"Writing the whole as 5/5, then 5/5 - 2/5 = 3/5 of the wrap is left."},{"p":"Which of these equals exactly 1 WHOLE pizza?","a":"6/6","w":["6/12","1/6","12/6"],"h":"You have a whole when the number of slices you have matches the number the pizza was cut into.","e":"A fraction equals one whole when the top and bottom numbers are the same, like 6/6."},{"p":"Anna ate 1/2 of a small personal pizza. Ben ate 1/2 of a giant party pizza. Did they eat the SAME amount of pizza?","a":"No, because the pizzas are different sizes","w":["Yes, because 1/2 always equals 1/2","No, because Anna ate more pizza","No, because 1/2 is not a real fraction"],"h":"A fraction only tells you the amount when you know how big the whole is.","e":"Equal fractions match only when the wholes are the same size; half of a giant pizza is more food than half of a small one."},{"p":"Read: \"A tray of nachos is cut into 12 equal parts. The team eats 7 parts.\" What fraction of the nachos is LEFT?","a":"5/12","w":["7/12","5/7","19/12"],"h":"Take the eaten parts away from the total number of parts.","e":"This is subtracting like fractions: 12/12 - 7/12 = 5/12 of the nachos remain."}],"m.5.decimoney":[{"p":"Maya buys a juice box for $1.25 and a granola bar for $0.60. How much does she spend in all?","a":"$1.85","w":["$1.65","$1.95","$0.65"],"h":"Line up the decimal points, then add the cents and the dollars.","e":"Adding decimals: $1.25 + $0.60 = $1.85. Line up the decimal points when adding money."},{"p":"Leo has $3.00. He buys stickers for $1.45. How much money does he have left?","a":"$1.55","w":["$1.45","$2.55","$1.65"],"h":"Subtract the cost from what Leo started with.","e":"Subtracting decimals: $3.00 - $1.45 = $1.55. Line up the decimal points to subtract money."},{"p":"A toy car costs $4.30. Priya pays with a $5 bill. How much change should she get back?","a":"$0.70","w":["$0.80","$1.70","$0.30"],"h":"Count up from the price to $5.00, or subtract the price from $5.00.","e":"Making change: $5.00 - $4.30 = $0.70. Change is the money left after paying."},{"p":"Which amount of money is the greatest?","a":"$0.72","w":["$0.27","$0.70","$0.68"],"h":"Compare the tens of cents first, then the ones of cents.","e":"Comparing decimals: 72 cents is more than 70, 68, or 27 cents, so $0.72 is greatest."},{"p":"Round $6.75 to the nearest dollar. About how much is it?","a":"$7.00","w":["$6.00","$6.50","$7.50"],"h":"Look at the cents: are they closer to $6 or to $7?","e":"Rounding money: $6.75 is more than halfway to $7, so it rounds up to $7.00."},{"p":"Round $2.34 to the nearest ten cents (the nearest dime).","a":"$2.30","w":["$2.40","$2.00","$2.35"],"h":"Look at the pennies digit to decide whether to round up or down.","e":"Rounding to the nearest tenth: the 4 pennies round down, so $2.34 becomes $2.30."},{"p":"A quarter is 25 cents. What fraction of one dollar is a quarter?","a":"1/4","w":["1/2","1/25","1/10"],"h":"There are 100 cents in a dollar. Write 25 out of 100 and simplify.","e":"Decimal-fraction link: 25 cents is 25/100 of a dollar, which simplifies to 1/4."},{"p":"One dime is 10 cents. Written as a decimal part of a dollar, how much is one dime?","a":"$0.10","w":["$0.01","$1.00","$0.20"],"h":"Ten cents means 10 out of the 100 cents in a dollar.","e":"Decimal money: 10 cents is written $0.10, since the tenths place holds dimes."},{"p":"In the price $5.38, what is the value of the digit 8?","a":"8 cents","w":["8 dollars","80 cents","8 dimes"],"h":"The last digit is in the hundredths (pennies) place.","e":"Place value: the 8 is in the hundredths place, so it is worth 8 cents ($0.08)."},{"p":"Sam has 3 dimes and 2 nickels in his pocket. How much money does he have?","a":"$0.40","w":["$0.35","$0.50","$0.32"],"h":"A dime is 10 cents and a nickel is 5 cents. Add each group up.","e":"Coin values: 3 dimes = 30 cents and 2 nickels = 10 cents, so 30 + 10 = $0.40."},{"p":"Read: \"At the school fair, popcorn costs $0.75 and lemonade costs $0.50. Ben buys one of each.\" How much does Ben spend in all?","a":"$1.25","w":["$1.15","$1.35","$0.25"],"h":"Add the two prices, lining up the decimal points.","e":"Adding decimals: $0.75 + $0.50 = $1.25, which is more than one dollar."},{"p":"A pencil costs $0.45 and an eraser costs $0.30. How much more does the pencil cost than the eraser?","a":"$0.15","w":["$0.75","$0.25","$0.05"],"h":"To find 'how much more,' subtract the smaller price from the bigger one.","e":"Subtracting decimals: $0.45 - $0.30 = $0.15, the difference in cost."},{"p":"Ana buys a snack for $2.60 and pays with a $5 bill. How much change does she get?","a":"$2.40","w":["$2.60","$3.40","$2.50"],"h":"Subtract the cost of the snack from $5.00.","e":"Making change: $5.00 - $2.60 = $2.40 back to Ana."},{"p":"Which amount is the same as 5 dimes?","a":"$0.50","w":["$0.05","$5.00","$0.15"],"h":"Each dime is worth 10 cents. Add five of them together.","e":"Coin values: 5 dimes = 5 x 10 cents = 50 cents = $0.50."},{"p":"Round $9.20 to the nearest dollar.","a":"$9.00","w":["$10.00","$9.50","$9.20"],"h":"Look at the cents: are 20 cents closer to $9 or $10?","e":"Rounding money: $9.20 is less than halfway to $10, so it rounds down to $9.00."},{"p":"Jada has $0.65. How much more does she need to have exactly $1.00?","a":"$0.35","w":["$0.45","$0.25","$0.40"],"h":"Count up from 65 cents to 100 cents.","e":"Making a dollar: $1.00 - $0.65 = $0.35 more needed."},{"p":"Two quarters make 50 cents. What fraction of a dollar is 50 cents?","a":"1/2","w":["1/4","1/5","2/5"],"h":"There are 100 cents in a dollar. Write 50 out of 100 and simplify.","e":"Decimal-fraction link: 50 cents is 50/100 of a dollar, which simplifies to 1/2."},{"p":"Read: \"Marcus saves $3.25 in January and $2.50 in February.\" How much has Marcus saved in all?","a":"$5.75","w":["$5.65","$5.85","$0.75"],"h":"Add both months together, lining up the decimal points.","e":"Adding decimals: $3.25 + $2.50 = $5.75 saved in total."},{"p":"Tara buys an apple for $0.55, a milk carton for $0.40, and a muffin for $1.15. How much does she spend in all?","a":"$2.10","w":["$2.00","$1.90","$2.15"],"h":"Add the two smaller prices first, then add the muffin. Line up the decimal points.","e":"Adding three money amounts: $0.55 + $0.40 + $1.15 = $2.10. Keep the decimal points lined up when you add."},{"p":"Rosa has $5.00 in her piggy bank. She buys a toy dinosaur for $2.75. How much money is left?","a":"$2.25","w":["$3.25","$2.75","$2.35"],"h":"You'll need to regroup a dollar into cents to subtract $0.75 from $0.00.","e":"Subtracting across zeros: $5.00 - $2.75 = $2.25. Trade one dollar for 100 cents so you can take away 75 cents."},{"p":"Grandma gives Eli a $10 bill. He buys a book for $6.45. How much change should he get back?","a":"$3.55","w":["$4.55","$3.65","$4.45"],"h":"Count up from $6.45 to $10.00, or subtract carefully with regrouping.","e":"Making change: $10.00 - $6.45 = $3.55. Regroup when the cents you subtract are bigger than the cents you have."},{"p":"Which of these amounts of money is the least?","a":"$0.09","w":["$0.19","$0.90","$0.91"],"h":"A longer-looking number is not always bigger. Compare the tenths place first.","e":"Comparing decimals: $0.09 has 0 tenths, so it is the smallest. Always compare the tenths place before the hundredths."},{"p":"Round $4.50 to the nearest dollar. About how much is it?","a":"$5.00","w":["$4.00","$4.50","$5.50"],"h":"When the cents are exactly 50, we round up to the next whole dollar.","e":"Rounding to the nearest dollar: $4.50 is halfway, so it rounds up to $5.00."},{"p":"Round $3.47 to the nearest ten cents (the nearest dime).","a":"$3.50","w":["$3.40","$3.45","$4.00"],"h":"Look at the pennies digit. Is it closer to 40 cents or 50 cents?","e":"Rounding to the nearest dime: 47 cents is closer to 50 than to 40, so $3.47 rounds to $3.50."},{"p":"Buddy the dog's tag jingles because he has 3 quarters taped to his collar. What fraction of one dollar is 3 quarters?","a":"3/4","w":["3/10","1/4","1/3"],"h":"One dollar is made of 4 quarters. How many of those 4 parts do you have?","e":"Decimal-fraction link: 4 quarters make one whole dollar, so 3 quarters is 3/4 of a dollar."},{"p":"One nickel is 5 cents. Written as a decimal part of a dollar, how much is one nickel?","a":"$0.05","w":["$0.50","$0.15","$0.10"],"h":"5 cents is less than a dime. Think about the hundredths place in a dollar.","e":"Cents as decimals: 5 cents is 5 hundredths of a dollar, written $0.05. The 5 goes in the hundredths (pennies) place."},{"p":"In the price $7.92, what is the value of the digit 9?","a":"$0.90","w":["$0.09","$9.00","$0.99"],"h":"The 9 sits right after the decimal point, in the dimes (tenths) place.","e":"Place value: the 9 is in the tenths place, so it means 9 dimes, or $0.90."},{"p":"Nina empties her coin jar and finds 2 quarters, 3 dimes, and 1 nickel. How much money does she have?","a":"$0.85","w":["$0.80","$0.75","$0.90"],"h":"Add the quarters, then the dimes, then the nickel: 50 + 30 + 5.","e":"Counting coins: 2 quarters = 50 cents, 3 dimes = 30 cents, 1 nickel = 5 cents, so 50 + 30 + 5 = $0.85."},{"p":"Read: \"At the bake sale, a cookie costs $1.20 and a brownie costs $1.35. Dev buys one of each and pays with a $5 bill.\" How much change should Dev get back?","a":"$2.45","w":["$2.55","$3.55","$2.35"],"h":"First find the total cost of both treats, then subtract from $5.00.","e":"Multi-step money: $1.20 + $1.35 = $2.55, then $5.00 - $2.55 = $2.45. Add before you subtract to find change."},{"p":"Read: \"At the pet store, a small bag of fish food costs $2.85 and a big bag costs $4.50.\" How much more does the big bag cost than the small bag?","a":"$1.65","w":["$2.65","$1.75","$1.35"],"h":"To find how much more, subtract the smaller price from the bigger price with regrouping.","e":"Comparing with subtraction: $4.50 - $2.85 = $1.65. Regroup a dollar into cents so you can take away 85 cents."},{"p":"Kira has $0.38. How much more does she need to have exactly $1.00?","a":"$0.62","w":["$0.72","$0.68","$0.52"],"h":"Count up from 38 cents to 100 cents, or subtract $0.38 from $1.00.","e":"Finding the missing part: $1.00 - $0.38 = $0.62. The two amounts must add up to one whole dollar."},{"p":"Nico buys 2 erasers, and each eraser costs $0.35. How much does he pay in all?","a":"$0.70","w":["$0.75","$0.65","$0.35"],"h":"Two erasers means adding $0.35 to itself, or doubling 35 cents.","e":"Repeated addition with money: $0.35 + $0.35 = $0.70. Two of the same price is double the amount."},{"p":"Which amount is the same as 75 cents?","a":"$0.75","w":["$7.50","$0.57","$0.075"],"h":"Cents go in the two places right after the decimal point in a dollar amount.","e":"Writing cents as dollars: 75 cents is 75 hundredths of a dollar, written $0.75."},{"p":"Read: \"Owen saved $4.15 and his sister Mia saved $4.05.\" Who saved more, and by how much?","a":"Owen, by $0.10","w":["Mia, by $0.10","Owen, by $1.00","They saved the same"],"h":"The dollars are equal, so compare the cents. Then find the difference.","e":"Comparing decimals: $4.15 is more than $4.05, and $4.15 - $4.05 = $0.10, so Owen saved 10 cents more."},{"p":"Round $7.49 to the nearest dollar. About how much is it?","a":"$7.00","w":["$8.00","$7.50","$7.40"],"h":"Look only at the cents. Are 49 cents closer to $0 or to a whole dollar?","e":"Rounding to the nearest dollar: 49 cents is less than 50, so $7.49 rounds down to $7.00."},{"p":"A jump rope costs $1.65. Zoe pays with four one-dollar bills ($4.00). How much change should she get?","a":"$2.35","w":["$3.35","$2.45","$2.65"],"h":"Subtract $1.65 from $4.00, regrouping a dollar into cents.","e":"Making change: $4.00 - $1.65 = $2.35. Trade one dollar for 100 cents to subtract 65 cents."},{"p":"Read: \"At the movies, Tessa buys popcorn for $2.35, water for $1.25, and an apple for $0.80. She pays with a $10 bill.\" How much change should Tessa get back?","a":"$5.60","w":["$4.40","$6.60","$5.50"],"h":"First add up the three prices, then take that total away from $10.00.","e":"This is a multi-step money problem: add the costs ($2.35 + $1.25 + $0.80 = $4.40), then subtract from $10.00 to find the change."},{"p":"Bella drops two dimes into her bank. Two dimes make 20 cents. What fraction of one dollar is 20 cents?","a":"1/5","w":["1/10","1/20","1/2"],"h":"A dollar is 100 cents, so think of 20 out of 100 and then simplify.","e":"Decimal-fraction link: 20 cents is 20/100 of a dollar, which simplifies to 1/5."},{"p":"A muffin costs $1.25. Grandpa buys 4 muffins that are all the same price. How much does he pay in all?","a":"$5.00","w":["$5.25","$4.25","$4.00"],"h":"You can add $1.25 four times, or think of it as 4 groups of $1.25.","e":"Repeated addition (multiplication): $1.25 + $1.25 + $1.25 + $1.25 = $5.00."},{"p":"Read: \"Three friends find $4.50 on the sidewalk and share it equally.\" How much money does each friend get?","a":"$1.50","w":["$2.25","$1.35","$1.00"],"h":"Split $4.50 into 3 equal parts.","e":"Sharing money equally: $4.50 divided into 3 equal groups is $1.50 each."},{"p":"Round $8.95 to the nearest ten cents (the nearest dime).","a":"$9.00","w":["$8.90","$8.95","$9.10"],"h":"The nearest dimes are $8.90 and $9.00. When you are exactly halfway, round up.","e":"Rounding to the nearest dime: $8.95 sits halfway between $8.90 and $9.00, so it rounds up to $9.00."},{"p":"In the price $4.06, what is the value of the digit 6?","a":"6 cents","w":["60 cents","6 dimes","6 dollars"],"h":"Look at which spot the 6 sits in after the decimal point: the tenths spot or the hundredths spot.","e":"Place value: the 6 is in the hundredths place, so it means 6 cents ($0.06)."},{"p":"A whistle costs $1.60. Cole pays with two one-dollar bills ($2.00). How much change should he get back?","a":"$0.40","w":["$0.60","$0.50","$1.40"],"h":"Subtract the price from $2.00.","e":"Making change: $2.00 - $1.60 = $0.40."},{"p":"Written as a decimal part of one dollar, how much is 3/4 of a dollar?","a":"$0.75","w":["$0.34","$0.30","$0.25"],"h":"Three quarters of a dollar means three 25-cent coins.","e":"Fraction-to-decimal link: 3/4 of a dollar is 75 cents, written $0.75."},{"p":"Milo has 85 cents and finds 35 more cents under the couch. How much money does he have now?","a":"$1.20","w":["$1.10","$1.30","$1.00"],"h":"Add 85 and 35 cents; remember that 100 cents makes a whole dollar.","e":"Adding money across a dollar: 85 + 35 = 120 cents, which is $1.20."},{"p":"Four dimes make 40 cents. What fraction of one dollar is 40 cents?","a":"2/5","w":["1/4","4/5","1/40"],"h":"A dollar is 100 cents, so start with 40 out of 100 and simplify.","e":"Decimal-fraction link: 40 cents is 40/100 of a dollar, which simplifies to 2/5."},{"p":"Read: \"Jamal has $8.00. He buys a comic book for $3.50 and a snack for $1.25.\" How much money does Jamal have left?","a":"$3.25","w":["$4.75","$3.75","$2.25"],"h":"First add the two things he bought, then take that total from $8.00.","e":"Multi-step subtraction: $3.50 + $1.25 = $4.75, and $8.00 - $4.75 = $3.25."},{"p":"Which amount is the same as 2 quarters and 1 dime?","a":"$0.60","w":["$0.35","$0.75","$0.45"],"h":"A quarter is 25 cents and a dime is 10 cents. Add up all the coins.","e":"Coin value: 25 + 25 + 10 = 60 cents, or $0.60."},{"p":"Round $7.68 to the nearest ten cents (the nearest dime).","a":"$7.70","w":["$7.60","$7.65","$8.00"],"h":"The nearest dimes are $7.60 and $7.70. Which one is $7.68 closer to?","e":"Rounding to the nearest dime: 8 cents is past halfway, so $7.68 rounds up to $7.70."},{"p":"A kite costs $6.75. Nadia pays with a $10 bill. How much change should she get back?","a":"$3.25","w":["$4.25","$3.35","$2.25"],"h":"Subtract the price of the kite from $10.00.","e":"Making change: $10.00 - $6.75 = $3.25."},{"p":"Read: \"Kim has $0.50 in her pocket and Sam has $0.45 in his.\" Who has more money, and by how much?","a":"Kim, by 5 cents","w":["Sam, by 5 cents","Kim, by 50 cents","They have the same amount"],"h":"Compare the two amounts, then subtract the smaller from the larger to find the difference.","e":"Comparing and subtracting money: $0.50 is greater than $0.45, and $0.50 - $0.45 = $0.05, so Kim has 5 cents more."}],"m.6.ratesreal":[{"p":"A pack of 6 identical water bottles costs $3.00. What is the price per bottle (the unit rate)?","a":"$0.50 per bottle","w":["$0.60 per bottle","$2.00 per bottle","$18.00 per bottle"],"h":"A unit rate tells you the cost for exactly ONE bottle. Which number should you divide by which?","e":"This is a unit rate: divide total cost by the number of items, $3.00 / 6 = $0.50 per bottle."},{"p":"Read: \"During a track meet, a cheetah mascot cart rolls 210 meters in 3 seconds at a steady speed.\" What is the cart's speed as a unit rate?","a":"70 meters per second","w":["63 meters per second","207 meters per second","630 meters per second"],"h":"Speed as a unit rate means distance for ONE second. Should you divide or multiply the two numbers?","e":"A unit rate for speed divides distance by time: 210 / 3 = 70 meters per second."},{"p":"A soccer team's ratio of wins to losses is 3:2. If they kept the same ratio and won 12 games, how many games did they lose?","a":"8 losses","w":["11 losses","6 losses","18 losses"],"h":"Find what number multiplies the '3' to make 12, then apply that SAME multiplier to the '2'.","e":"Equivalent ratios scale both parts by the same factor: 3 x 4 = 12, so 2 x 4 = 8 losses."},{"p":"A jacket normally costs $80. It is on sale for 25% off. How much money do you SAVE with the discount?","a":"$20","w":["$25","$60","$55"],"h":"The savings is 25% OF $80, not the number 25 by itself. What is one quarter of 80?","e":"Finding a percent of a number: 25% = 1/4, and 1/4 of $80 = $20 saved."},{"p":"On a science quiz, Maria answered 15 out of 20 questions correctly. What percent did she get correct?","a":"75%","w":["15%","5%","133%"],"h":"A percent compares the part to the whole out of 100. Try writing 15/20 as an equivalent fraction with 100 on the bottom.","e":"Percent means 'out of 100': 15/20 = 75/100 = 75%."},{"p":"A fruit basket holds 8 apples and 12 oranges. Written in simplest form, what is the ratio of apples to oranges?","a":"2:3","w":["4:6","3:2","8:12"],"h":"Divide BOTH numbers by their greatest common factor until they can't be reduced any further.","e":"Simplifying a ratio means dividing both terms by the GCF: 8 and 12 share a factor of 4, giving 2:3."},{"p":"Store A sells 4 pens for $2.00. Store B sells 6 pens for $3.60. Which store is the better buy per pen?","a":"Store A, at $0.50 per pen","w":["Store B, at $0.60 per pen","Store A, at $0.40 per pen","Store B, at $0.50 per pen"],"h":"Find each store's price for ONE pen, then compare those unit rates. Smaller price per pen wins.","e":"Comparing unit rates: Store A is $2.00/4 = $0.50 per pen and Store B is $3.60/6 = $0.60 per pen, so A is cheaper."},{"p":"Concert tickets cost the same price each. If 3 tickets cost $24, how much do 5 tickets cost?","a":"$40","w":["$29","$45","$72"],"h":"First find the price of ONE ticket, then multiply by 5. This is a proportion.","e":"Solving a proportion with a unit rate: $24/3 = $8 per ticket, and $8 x 5 = $40."},{"p":"A printer prints 20 pages in 4 minutes at a steady rate. How many pages will it print in 10 minutes?","a":"50 pages","w":["40 pages","26 pages","80 pages"],"h":"Find how many pages print in ONE minute first, then scale up to 10 minutes.","e":"Using a unit rate: 20/4 = 5 pages per minute, so 5 x 10 = 50 pages."},{"p":"A paint mixture uses red and blue paint in the ratio 2:3. What fraction of the whole mixture is red paint?","a":"2/5","w":["2/3","3/5","1/2"],"h":"Add both parts of the ratio to find the total number of equal parts, then ask how many are red.","e":"A part-to-whole fraction uses the total: 2 + 3 = 5 parts, and 2 of them are red, so 2/5."},{"p":"A rice recipe for 4 people uses 2 cups of rice. Using the same rate, how much rice is needed for 6 people?","a":"3 cups","w":["4 cups","2.5 cups","12 cups"],"h":"How much rice does ONE person need? Multiply that amount by 6 people.","e":"Scaling with a unit rate: 2 cups / 4 people = 0.5 cup per person, and 0.5 x 6 = 3 cups."},{"p":"A restaurant meal costs $30. Your family leaves a 20% tip. How much is the tip?","a":"$6","w":["$20","$24","$36"],"h":"The tip is 20% OF $30. Finding 10% first can make this easier to double.","e":"Finding a percent of a number: 10% of $30 is $3, so 20% is $6."},{"p":"A car travels 150 miles using 5 gallons of gas. What is the car's fuel efficiency in miles per gallon?","a":"30 miles per gallon","w":["145 miles per gallon","155 miles per gallon","750 miles per gallon"],"h":"Miles per gallon is a unit rate: the number of miles for exactly ONE gallon.","e":"This unit rate divides miles by gallons: 150 / 5 = 30 miles per gallon."},{"p":"The ratios in this table are equivalent: 1:4 and 5:?. What number completes the second ratio?","a":"20","w":["8","9","25"],"h":"Figure out what you multiply the '1' by to get '5', then use that SAME factor on the '4'.","e":"Equivalent ratios scale by the same factor: 1 x 5 = 5, so 4 x 5 = 20."},{"p":"Read: \"A nurse counts a patient's heartbeats and records 15 beats in 10 seconds at a steady rate.\" What is the heart rate in beats per minute?","a":"90 beats per minute","w":["25 beats per minute","15 beats per minute","150 beats per minute"],"h":"There are 60 seconds in a minute. First find beats in one second, or scale 10 seconds up to 60.","e":"Scaling a rate to a full minute: 15 beats in 10 seconds means 15 x 6 = 90 beats in 60 seconds."},{"p":"Written as a ratio of part to whole in simplest form, what is 60% equal to?","a":"3:5","w":["6:10","60:100","3:2"],"h":"Percent means 'out of 100', so start with 60 to 100, then reduce by the greatest common factor.","e":"Percent as a ratio: 60% = 60:100, which simplifies by dividing both by 20 to get 3:5."},{"p":"A student types 180 words in 3 minutes at a steady pace. What is the typing speed as a unit rate?","a":"60 words per minute","w":["177 words per minute","183 words per minute","540 words per minute"],"h":"A unit rate here is the number of words typed in exactly ONE minute.","e":"This unit rate divides words by minutes: 180 / 3 = 60 words per minute."},{"p":"A muffin recipe uses 1 cup of milk for every 4 muffins. Using the same ratio, how much milk is needed for 12 muffins?","a":"3 cups","w":["9 cups","6 cups","48 cups"],"h":"How many groups of 4 muffins are in 12 muffins? Each group needs 1 cup.","e":"Equivalent ratios: 12 muffins is 3 groups of 4, and each group uses 1 cup, so 3 cups."},{"p":"A smoothie recipe uses 3 cups of berries to make 5 servings. Using the same rate, how many cups of berries are needed for 15 servings?","a":"9 cups","w":["13 cups","45 cups","5 cups"],"h":"15 servings is a whole-number multiple of 5 servings. Find the multiplier first.","e":"This is scaling equivalent ratios: 15 divided by 5 is 3, so multiply the berries by 3 to get 3 x 3 = 9 cups."},{"p":"An online game had 250 players last month. This month the number of players increased by 30%. How many players are there now?","a":"325 players","w":["75 players","280 players","175 players"],"h":"A percent increase is added on top of the original amount.","e":"This is a percent increase: 30% of 250 is 75, and 250 + 75 = 325 players."},{"p":"A cyclist rides 12 miles in 40 minutes at a steady speed. At this rate, how far will the cyclist travel in 60 minutes?","a":"18 miles","w":["12 miles","20 miles","24 miles"],"h":"Find how many miles the cyclist covers in one minute, then scale up to 60 minutes.","e":"The unit rate is 12 divided by 40 = 0.3 miles per minute, and 0.3 x 60 = 18 miles."},{"p":"On a math test, 20% of a number is 14. What is the whole number?","a":"70","w":["2.8","34","280"],"h":"The value 14 represents only one-fifth (20%) of the whole, so the whole must be larger.","e":"This is a reverse percent problem: 14 divided by 0.20 = 70."},{"p":"A bag of trail mix contains peanuts, raisins, and chocolate pieces in the ratio 4:3:2. If there are 45 pieces total, how many are raisins?","a":"15 pieces","w":["20 pieces","10 pieces","5 pieces"],"h":"Add the parts of the ratio to find how many equal shares the total splits into.","e":"Using ratios as parts of a whole: 4 + 3 + 2 = 9 parts, 45 divided by 9 = 5 per part, and raisins are 3 x 5 = 15 pieces."},{"p":"A backpack costs $45 and is on sale for 20% off. What is the final sale price you pay?","a":"$36","w":["$9","$25","$54"],"h":"The sale price is what is LEFT after the discount is removed from the original.","e":"This is a percent discount: 20% of 45 is 9 saved, so 45 - 9 = 36."},{"p":"A bread recipe mixes flour and sugar in the ratio 5:2. If a baker uses 15 cups of flour, how much sugar is needed to keep the same ratio?","a":"6 cups","w":["12 cups","3 cups","10 cups"],"h":"Ask what number the flour amount was multiplied by to reach 15.","e":"These are equivalent ratios: 15 divided by 5 = 3, so sugar is 2 x 3 = 6 cups."},{"p":"A board game costs $60, and the store adds 5% sales tax. What is the total amount you pay?","a":"$63","w":["$5","$65","$57"],"h":"Sales tax is added on top of the listed price.","e":"This is a percent tax: 5% of 60 is 3, so the total is 60 + 3 = 63."},{"p":"A 12-ounce bottle of juice costs $2.40, and a 20-ounce bottle costs $3.60. Which is the better buy per ounce?","a":"The 20-ounce bottle at $0.18 per ounce","w":["The 12-ounce bottle at $0.20 per ounce","The 12-ounce bottle at $0.18 per ounce","Both bottles cost the same per ounce"],"h":"Divide each price by its number of ounces to get the cost of one ounce.","e":"Comparing unit rates: 2.40 divided by 12 = 0.20 and 3.60 divided by 20 = 0.18, so the 20-ounce bottle is cheaper per ounce."},{"p":"At a store, 4 notebooks cost $10. At the same price each, how many notebooks can you buy with $25?","a":"10 notebooks","w":["19 notebooks","6 notebooks","40 notebooks"],"h":"Find the price of a single notebook first, then see how many fit in $25.","e":"Using the unit rate: 10 divided by 4 = $2.50 per notebook, and 25 divided by 2.50 = 10 notebooks."},{"p":"Read: \"At a track meet, Runner A covers 400 meters in 80 seconds and Runner B covers 300 meters in 50 seconds, both at steady speeds.\" Who is running faster?","a":"Runner B at 6 meters per second","w":["Runner A at 5 meters per second","Runner A at 6 meters per second","Both run at the same speed"],"h":"Compute meters per second for each runner and compare.","e":"Comparing unit rates: 400 divided by 80 = 5 m/s and 300 divided by 50 = 6 m/s, so Runner B is faster."},{"p":"Read: \"A hummingbird beats its wings 90 times in 2 seconds at a steady rate.\" How many times does it beat its wings in one full minute?","a":"2,700 beats per minute","w":["45 beats per minute","180 beats per minute","1,350 beats per minute"],"h":"Find the beats per second first, then scale up to the 60 seconds in a minute.","e":"The unit rate is 90 divided by 2 = 45 beats per second, and 45 x 60 = 2,700 beats per minute."},{"p":"A restaurant meal costs $40, and your family adds a 15% tip. What is the total amount paid, including the tip?","a":"$46","w":["$6","$55","$34"],"h":"The total is the cost of the meal PLUS the tip, not just the tip.","e":"This is a percent added on: 15% of 40 is 6, so the total is 40 + 6 = 46."},{"p":"At a summer camp, the ratio of counselors to campers is 1:18. If there are 108 campers, how many counselors are there to keep the same ratio?","a":"6 counselors","w":["108 counselors","90 counselors","3 counselors"],"h":"Figure out how many groups of 18 campers fit into 108.","e":"Using equivalent ratios: 108 divided by 18 = 6 counselors."},{"p":"On a music playlist, 9 out of 25 songs are pop songs. What percent of the playlist is pop?","a":"36%","w":["9%","16%","25%"],"h":"Rewrite the fraction with a denominator of 100 to read the percent directly.","e":"Converting a ratio to a percent: 9/25 = 36/100 = 36%."},{"p":"A cookie recipe that makes 24 cookies uses 3 cups of flour. Using the same rate, how much flour is needed to make just 8 cookies?","a":"1 cup","w":["9 cups","2 cups","1.5 cups"],"h":"8 cookies is a fraction of 24 cookies, so scale the flour down by the same amount.","e":"Scaling ratios down: 24 divided by 8 = 3, so 3 cups divided by 3 = 1 cup."},{"p":"Read: \"A delivery truck travels 240 miles on 8 gallons of gas, while a van travels 210 miles on 6 gallons.\" Which vehicle gets better gas mileage?","a":"The van at 35 miles per gallon","w":["The truck at 30 miles per gallon","The van at 30 miles per gallon","The truck at 35 miles per gallon"],"h":"Divide miles by gallons for each vehicle and compare the results.","e":"Comparing unit rates: 240 divided by 8 = 30 mpg and 210 divided by 6 = 35 mpg, so the van is more efficient."},{"p":"A store buys a video game for $50 and marks up the price by 40% to sell it. What is the new selling price?","a":"$70","w":["$40","$90","$54"],"h":"A markup adds a percent of the original price on top of it.","e":"This is a percent increase: 40% of 50 is 20, so the price becomes 50 + 20 = 70."},{"p":"A pair of sneakers is on sale for $36 after a 25% discount. What was the original price before the discount?","a":"$48","w":["$45","$27","$54"],"h":"The sale price is 75% of the original price. What number times 0.75 gives 36?","e":"This is a reverse-percent (finding the whole) problem: since 25% off means you pay 75%, divide 36 by 0.75 to get $48."},{"p":"A popular video game dropped in price from $50 to $40. What was the percent decrease in price?","a":"20%","w":["25%","10%","80%"],"h":"Percent decrease = (amount of decrease divided by the original price) times 100. What was the original price?","e":"Percent decrease compares the change ($10) to the original ($50): 10/50 = 20%."},{"p":"A collector buys a trading card for $20 and later sells it for $50. By what percent did the card's value increase?","a":"150%","w":["250%","60%","30%"],"h":"Percent increase = (amount of increase divided by the original value) times 100. The increase is the difference between $50 and $20.","e":"The value rose by $30 from a $20 start: 30/20 = 1.5 = 150% increase (an increase can be more than 100%)."},{"p":"Which ratio is equivalent to 3:5?","a":"12:20","w":["6:8","5:7","9:12"],"h":"Multiply both numbers of 3:5 by the same factor. Which option keeps that relationship?","e":"Equivalent ratios come from multiplying both parts by the same number: 3:5 times 4 gives 12:20."},{"p":"A cookie recipe for 8 servings uses 3/4 cup of sugar. Using the same rate, how much sugar is needed for just 2 servings?","a":"3/16 cup","w":["1/4 cup","3/8 cup","1/2 cup"],"h":"2 servings is one-fourth of 8 servings, so you need one-fourth of the sugar.","e":"Scaling down by the ratio 2/8 = 1/4: (3/4) times (1/4) = 3/16 cup."},{"p":"A garden snail crawls 6 inches every 2 minutes at a steady pace. What is its speed in inches per hour?","a":"180 inches per hour","w":["12 inches per hour","90 inches per hour","360 inches per hour"],"h":"First find inches per minute, then remember there are 60 minutes in an hour.","e":"The unit rate is 3 inches per minute; multiplying by 60 minutes gives 180 inches per hour."},{"p":"At a currency exchange, 3 U.S. dollars trade for 45 Mexican pesos. At the same rate, how many pesos would you get for 8 U.S. dollars?","a":"120 pesos","w":["105 pesos","135 pesos","90 pesos"],"h":"Find how many pesos equal one dollar, then multiply by 8.","e":"The unit rate is 45 divided by 3 = 15 pesos per dollar, so 8 dollars times 15 = 120 pesos."},{"p":"On a map, 2 centimeters represents 5 real kilometers. Two towns are 14 centimeters apart on the map. How far apart are they in real life?","a":"35 kilometers","w":["28 kilometers","70 kilometers","17.5 kilometers"],"h":"How many 2-cm groups fit in 14 cm? Each group stands for 5 km.","e":"Using the scale as a ratio, 14 cm is 7 groups of 2 cm, and 7 times 5 = 35 kilometers."},{"p":"A $100 winter coat is marked 50% off. At the register, an extra 20% is taken off the already-reduced price. What is the final price?","a":"$40","w":["$30","$35","$50"],"h":"Apply the 50% off first to get a new price, then take 20% off that new price (not off the original).","e":"Successive discounts multiply: $100 times 0.50 = $50, then $50 times 0.80 = $40 — you cannot simply add 50% and 20%."},{"p":"In a class, the ratio of boys to girls is 4:5. If there are 16 boys, how many students are in the class in total?","a":"36 students","w":["20 students","25 students","45 students"],"h":"Find how many students make up one 'part' of the ratio, then account for all 4 + 5 parts.","e":"Each part equals 16 divided by 4 = 4 students; with 9 parts total (4 + 5), the class has 9 times 4 = 36 students."},{"p":"A grocery store sells a 3-pound bag of apples for $5.40 and a 5-pound bag for $8.50. Which is the better buy per pound?","a":"The 5-pound bag, at $1.70 per pound","w":["The 3-pound bag, at $1.80 per pound","The 3-pound bag, at $1.70 per pound","They cost the same amount per pound"],"h":"Divide each price by its number of pounds to find the cost per pound, then compare.","e":"Unit price: $5.40 divided by 3 = $1.80 versus $8.50 divided by 5 = $1.70, so the 5-pound bag is cheaper per pound."},{"p":"Read: \"On a sunny afternoon, a 4-foot fence post casts a 6-foot shadow. At the same moment, a nearby tree casts a 15-foot shadow.\" Using equal ratios, how tall is the tree?","a":"10 feet","w":["13 feet","9 feet","22.5 feet"],"h":"Set up equal ratios of height to shadow: 4 to 6 equals the tree's height to 15.","e":"Proportion: 4/6 = h/15, and cross-multiplying gives 6h = 60, so h = 10 feet."},{"p":"A car travels 30 miles in 45 minutes at a steady speed. What is the car's speed in miles per hour?","a":"40 miles per hour","w":["30 miles per hour","45 miles per hour","67.5 miles per hour"],"h":"There are 60 minutes in an hour. Find the distance per minute first, or scale 45 minutes up to 60.","e":"At 30 miles per 45 minutes, the rate is 2/3 mile per minute; times 60 minutes gives 40 mph."},{"p":"A 500-milliliter sports drink contains 30 grams of sugar. What is the sugar concentration in grams per 100 milliliters?","a":"6 grams per 100 mL","w":["3 grams per 100 mL","15 grams per 100 mL","0.6 grams per 100 mL"],"h":"How many 100-mL portions are in 500 mL? Split the 30 grams evenly among them.","e":"500 mL is five 100-mL portions, so 30 grams divided by 5 = 6 grams per 100 mL (a unit rate)."},{"p":"Read: \"Two gears are connected so that their turns stay in the ratio 3:8, small gear to large gear.\" When the large gear makes 24 turns, how many turns does the small gear make?","a":"9 turns","w":["19 turns","64 turns","6 turns"],"h":"Find what number multiplies 8 to give 24, then multiply 3 by that same number.","e":"The ratio 3:8 scales up by 3 (since 8 times 3 = 24), so the small gear makes 3 times 3 = 9 turns."},{"p":"A store served 800 customers last week. This week, 15% fewer customers came in. How many customers came this week?","a":"680 customers","w":["785 customers","120 customers","920 customers"],"h":"15% fewer means you keep 85% of last week's customers.","e":"A 15% decrease keeps 85%: 800 times 0.85 = 680 customers."},{"p":"Read: \"Three volunteers fold event flyers at steady rates. Ana folds 45 flyers in 5 minutes, Ben folds 70 in 10 minutes, and Cara folds 24 in 3 minutes.\" Who folds flyers the fastest?","a":"Ana, at 9 flyers per minute","w":["Ben, at 7 flyers per minute","Cara, at 8 flyers per minute","They all fold at the same rate"],"h":"Find each person's flyers-per-minute unit rate, then compare the three numbers.","e":"Unit rates: Ana 9, Ben 7, and Cara 8 flyers per minute, so Ana is the fastest."},{"p":"In a parking lot, the ratio of cars to trucks is 7:3. What percent of the vehicles are trucks?","a":"30%","w":["43%","3%","70%"],"h":"Add the parts to find the total number of parts, then compare trucks to that total.","e":"Trucks are 3 out of every 7 + 3 = 10 vehicles, and 3/10 = 30% (a part-to-whole percent)."}],"m.8.funcstories":[{"p":"What is the slope of the line y = 4x + 9?","a":"4","w":["9","13","-4"],"h":"In the form y = mx + b, look at which number is multiplied by x.","e":"In slope-intercept form y = mx + b, the slope is m, the coefficient of x, so the slope is 4."},{"p":"What is the y-intercept of the line y = 6x - 2?","a":"-2","w":["6","2","4"],"h":"The y-intercept is the constant term, the value of y when x = 0.","e":"In y = mx + b, the y-intercept is b, the number added or subtracted, which is -2 here."},{"p":"A skate rental costs $8 plus $3 for each hour, modeled by c = 3h + 8. What does the slope, 3, represent?","a":"The cost goes up $3 for each additional hour.","w":["The starting fee before skating is $3.","The total cost of renting is always $3.","You are allowed to skate for 3 hours."],"h":"Slope is the rate of change: how much c changes each time h increases by 1.","e":"Slope is the rate of change, so 3 means the cost rises $3 for every extra hour."},{"p":"A skate rental costs $8 plus $3 for each hour, modeled by c = 3h + 8. What does the 8 represent?","a":"The flat fee charged before any hours are added.","w":["The cost added for each hour of skating.","The number of hours you may skate.","The total cost after skating all day."],"h":"The constant term is the value of c when h = 0, before any hours pass.","e":"The y-intercept 8 is the starting value: the flat fee charged before any hourly charges."},{"p":"A line passes through the points (2, 3) and (4, 7). What is its slope?","a":"2","w":["0.5","4","10"],"h":"Slope = change in y divided by change in x between the two points.","e":"Slope = (7 - 3)/(4 - 2) = 4/2 = 2, the rise over the run."},{"p":"A function table shows x = 0, 1, 2, 3 giving y = 5, 8, 11, 14. What is the rate of change?","a":"3","w":["5","8","2"],"h":"See how much y increases each time x increases by 1.","e":"Each step in x of 1 raises y by 3, so the constant rate of change (slope) is 3."},{"p":"On a distance-versus-time graph of a walk, one part of the line is perfectly flat (horizontal). What does the flat part mean?","a":"The walker is standing still while time keeps passing.","w":["The walker is speeding up over that time.","The walker is moving backward toward the start.","The walker reached the fastest speed of the trip."],"h":"A flat line means the y-value (distance) is not changing even as x (time) increases.","e":"A horizontal segment has slope 0, so distance stays the same, meaning no movement."},{"p":"Which equation has a slope of 5 and a y-intercept of -3?","a":"y = 5x - 3","w":["y = -3x + 5","y = 5x + 3","y = 3x - 5"],"h":"Match the coefficient of x to the slope and the constant to the y-intercept.","e":"In y = mx + b, slope 5 and y-intercept -3 give y = 5x - 3."},{"p":"A line crosses the y-axis at the point (0, -4). What is its y-intercept?","a":"-4","w":["0","4","-1"],"h":"The y-intercept is the y-value where the line meets the y-axis.","e":"The y-intercept is the y-coordinate where x = 0, which is -4 here."},{"p":"For the function f(x) = 2x + 1, what is f(3)?","a":"7","w":["6","5","9"],"h":"Substitute 3 in place of x, then follow order of operations.","e":"f(3) = 2(3) + 1 = 6 + 1 = 7, found by substituting the input into the rule."},{"p":"Which equation represents a proportional relationship (a line through the origin)?","a":"y = 7x","w":["y = 7x + 2","y = x + 7","y = 2x - 1"],"h":"A proportional relationship has a y-intercept of 0, so no number is added or subtracted.","e":"y = 7x has y-intercept 0, passing through the origin, which makes it proportional."},{"p":"A function table shows x = 1, 2, 3, 4 giving y = 10, 7, 4, 1. What is the slope?","a":"-3","w":["3","-1","-7"],"h":"Find how y changes each time x increases by 1; a decrease means a negative slope.","e":"y drops by 3 for each increase of 1 in x, so the slope is -3."},{"p":"Two phone plans are graphed as two lines, with cost on the y-axis and minutes on the x-axis. What does the point where the lines cross mean?","a":"The two plans cost the same for that number of minutes.","w":["The two plans can never be equal in cost.","One plan has run out of minutes at that point.","Both plans are free at that number of minutes."],"h":"At an intersection point, both lines share the same x-value and the same y-value.","e":"The intersection of a system is where both equations agree, so both plans cost the same there."},{"p":"Read: \"Maya starts a savings jar with $20 and adds $5 every week. Her savings are modeled by s = 5w + 20.\" How much is in the jar after 4 weeks?","a":"$40","w":["$45","$25","$100"],"h":"Substitute w = 4 into the rule, multiplying before adding.","e":"s = 5(4) + 20 = 20 + 20 = 40; substitute the input and follow order of operations."},{"p":"A tank of water is modeled by g = -6t + 50, where g is gallons and t is minutes. What does the slope, -6, mean?","a":"The tank loses 6 gallons each minute.","w":["The tank gains 6 gallons each minute.","The tank starts with 6 gallons of water.","The tank can hold 6 gallons in total."],"h":"A negative slope means the y-value is decreasing as time goes on.","e":"A slope of -6 is a rate of change downward, so 6 gallons drain away each minute."},{"p":"Maya's savings are modeled by s = 5w + 20, where w is weeks. What does the 20 represent?","a":"The amount in the jar before any weeks pass.","w":["The amount added to the jar each week.","The number of weeks she has been saving.","The most money the jar can ever hold."],"h":"The constant term is the value of s when w = 0.","e":"The y-intercept 20 is the starting amount in the jar before any weekly deposits."},{"p":"A runner's distance is modeled by d = 8t, where d is miles and t is hours. What does the slope, 8, represent?","a":"8 miles per hour","w":["8 hours per mile","8 miles in total","8 hours in total"],"h":"Slope compares the units on the y-axis to the units on the x-axis.","e":"Slope is a rate: miles (y) per hour (x), so 8 means 8 miles for each hour."},{"p":"Which of these equations describes a line that is decreasing (going down from left to right)?","a":"y = -2x + 6","w":["y = 2x + 6","y = x + 1","y = 4x"],"h":"A line decreases when its slope is a negative number.","e":"A negative slope makes a line fall from left to right, so y = -2x + 6 is decreasing."},{"p":"On a graph, a line rises 6 units up for every 2 units it moves to the right. What is its slope?","a":"3","w":["6","1/3","8"],"h":"Slope compares how far the line goes up to how far it goes across: rise over run.","e":"Slope = rise / run = 6/2 = 3. It measures steepness as vertical change divided by horizontal change."},{"p":"A line passes through the points (1, 8) and (3, 2). What is its slope?","a":"-3","w":["3","-6","-2"],"h":"Find the change in y over the change in x, and watch which way the y-values move.","e":"Slope = (2 - 8)/(3 - 1) = -6/2 = -3. The negative sign shows the line goes down from left to right."},{"p":"A line has a slope of 3 and passes through the point (2, 10). What is its y-intercept?","a":"4","w":["10","6","2"],"h":"Plug the point and slope into y = mx + b, then solve for b.","e":"Using y = 3x + b with (2, 10): 10 = 3(2) + b, so b = 4. The y-intercept is where the line crosses the y-axis (x = 0)."},{"p":"Which point lies on the line y = 2x - 1?","a":"(3, 5)","w":["(1, 3)","(2, 4)","(0, 1)"],"h":"Substitute each x-value into the equation and see if you get the matching y-value.","e":"For (3, 5): 2(3) - 1 = 5, which matches. A point lies on a line only when its coordinates make the equation true."},{"p":"Two teams' scores in a game are graphed as lines, with score on the y-axis and time on the x-axis. The lines cross at the point (5, 20). What does this mean?","a":"At time 5, both teams have a score of 20.","w":["The teams' scores always differ by 5 points.","Together the teams scored 25 points.","The two teams never have equal scores."],"h":"An intersection point is a spot the two lines share, so both must have the same x and y there.","e":"The intersection of two lines is the point where both relationships hold at once, so both teams share the same score at that time. This is the idea behind solving a system."},{"p":"A water tank drains according to g = -4t + 20, where g is gallons and t is minutes. At what time is the tank empty?","a":"5 minutes","w":["20 minutes","4 minutes","16 minutes"],"h":"The tank is empty when the number of gallons g equals 0, so set the equation equal to 0.","e":"Setting g = 0: 0 = -4t + 20, so t = 5. This value of t is the x-intercept, where the line crosses the horizontal axis."},{"p":"A function table shows x = 0, 1, 2, 3 giving y = 1, 4, 9, 16. Is this a linear function, and why?","a":"No, because y does not increase by the same amount each step.","w":["Yes, because y increases every time x increases.","Yes, because x goes up by 1 each time.","No, because the y-values are all even."],"h":"A linear function has a constant rate of change; check the difference between each pair of y-values.","e":"The y-values jump by 3, then 5, then 7, so the rate of change is not constant and the function is not linear."},{"p":"A function table shows x = 0, 1, 2, 3 giving y = 7, 10, 13, 16. Which equation models it?","a":"y = 3x + 7","w":["y = 7x + 3","y = 3x","y = x + 7"],"h":"The y-value at x = 0 gives the starting point, and the step size between y-values gives the slope.","e":"The y-values increase by 3 each step (slope 3) and start at 7 (y-intercept), giving y = 3x + 7."},{"p":"Line A has a slope of 2 and line B has a slope of 5. Which line is steeper, and why?","a":"Line B, because a larger slope rises more steeply.","w":["Line A, because a smaller slope is steeper.","They are equally steep because both are positive.","Line A, because 2 is listed first."],"h":"Think about how much each line climbs for every step to the right.","e":"A greater slope means a steeper climb, so line B (slope 5) rises faster than line A (slope 2)."},{"p":"Which of these lines is the steepest: a slope of -1, a slope of 3, or a slope of -5?","a":"The line with slope -5","w":["The line with slope 3","The line with slope -1","They are all equally steep."],"h":"Steepness depends on how far the slope is from zero, not on whether it is positive or negative.","e":"Steepness is measured by the absolute value of the slope, and |-5| = 5 is the largest, so slope -5 is the steepest."},{"p":"For the function f(x) = -2x + 10, what is f(4)?","a":"2","w":["18","-8","12"],"h":"Substitute 4 for x, and remember the -2 multiplies the x before you add 10.","e":"f(4) = -2(4) + 10 = -8 + 10 = 2. Evaluating a function means replacing x with the given input and simplifying."},{"p":"Read: \"A phone battery starts at 80% and drops 5% each hour, modeled by b = -5h + 80.\" What does the 80 represent?","a":"The battery percentage at the start, when h = 0.","w":["How much the battery drops each hour.","The number of hours until the battery is empty.","The battery percentage after one hour."],"h":"Which number tells you the value before any time has passed (h = 0)?","e":"The 80 is the y-intercept, the battery level at the starting time. The -5 is the slope, the drop per hour."},{"p":"Which equation represents a horizontal line with a slope of 0?","a":"y = 7","w":["x = 7","y = 7x","y = x + 7"],"h":"A horizontal line keeps the same y-value no matter what x is, so x should not appear.","e":"y = 7 keeps y fixed for every x, giving a flat horizontal line with slope 0."},{"p":"On a distance-versus-time graph of a bike ride, which part of the line shows the bike moving fastest?","a":"The steepest upward part of the line.","w":["The flattest part of the line.","The part closest to the x-axis.","The part where the line is lowest."],"h":"On a distance-time graph, speed is the slope, so a faster speed shows up as a certain kind of steepness.","e":"Speed equals slope on a distance-time graph, so the steepest section represents the greatest speed."},{"p":"Read: \"Runner A's distance is d = 6t and Runner B's distance is d = 8t, where t is hours.\" Who is faster and how do you know?","a":"Runner B, because a larger slope means a faster speed.","w":["Runner A, because 6 is an easier number to run.","They run at the same speed because both are lines.","Runner A, because it is listed first."],"h":"In these equations the number multiplying t is the speed; compare those two numbers.","e":"The slope is the speed, and 8 is greater than 6, so Runner B travels faster."},{"p":"A linear function table shows x = 0, 1, 2, 3 giving y = 5, 9, 13, and a missing value. What is the missing y-value?","a":"17","w":["15","16","21"],"h":"Find the constant amount the y-values increase by, then apply it one more time.","e":"The y-values rise by 4 each step, so after 13 comes 13 + 4 = 17. The constant rate of change extends the pattern."},{"p":"Read: \"At a vending machine, 3 waters cost $6 and 5 waters cost $10.\" What is the cost per water (the slope)?","a":"$2 per water","w":["$3 per water","$6 per water","$0.50 per water"],"h":"Compare the change in cost to the change in number of waters, like rise over run.","e":"Slope = (10 - 6)/(5 - 3) = 4/2 = $2 per water. The slope here is the unit rate, or cost for each water."},{"p":"A drone's height is modeled by h = -10t + 100, where h is meters and t is seconds. Is the drone rising or falling, and why?","a":"Falling, because the slope is negative.","w":["Rising, because it starts at 100 meters.","Falling, because 100 is a large number.","Rising, because the slope is 10."],"h":"The sign of the slope, not the size of the starting value, tells you the direction.","e":"A negative slope (-10) means height decreases over time, so the drone is falling."},{"p":"A function table shows x = 2, 4, 6, 8 giving y = 3, 8, 13, 18. What is the slope?","a":"2.5","w":["5","2","0.4"],"h":"Slope is the change in y divided by the change in x — notice that x jumps by more than 1 each step.","e":"Rate of change (slope) equals Δy/Δx; y rises 5 for every 2 in x, so slope = 5/2 = 2.5."},{"p":"Read: \"A hot-air balloon descends according to h = -20t + 300, where h is height in meters and t is minutes.\" What does the x-intercept (where h = 0) represent?","a":"The time when the balloon reaches the ground","w":["The starting height of the balloon","The speed at which the balloon descends","The height of the balloon after 1 minute"],"h":"The x-intercept is where the output value (height) equals zero — picture what h = 0 means for a balloon.","e":"The x-intercept is where the output is 0; here height 0 means the balloon has landed."},{"p":"A line passes through the points (-2, 5) and (2, -3). What is its slope?","a":"-2","w":["2","-8","-0.5"],"h":"Subtract the y-values and the x-values in the same order, then divide — track the negative signs carefully.","e":"Slope = (y2−y1)/(x2−x1) = (−3−5)/(2−(−2)) = −8/4 = −2."},{"p":"A table pairs inputs x = 1, 2, 2, 3 with outputs y = 4, 5, 7, 9. Is this a function, and why?","a":"No, because the input 2 gives two different outputs","w":["Yes, because every output value is different","Yes, because the outputs keep increasing","No, because the inputs are not evenly spaced"],"h":"A function gives exactly one output for each input — look for any input that appears more than once.","e":"A relation is a function only if each input has one output; input 2 maps to both 5 and 7, so it is not a function."},{"p":"Read: \"Gym A charges c = 10m + 20 and Gym B charges c = 15m, where m is months.\" For a 3-month membership, which gym is cheaper?","a":"Gym B, because it costs $45 versus $50","w":["Gym A, because it costs $45 versus $50","They cost the same, $50 each","Gym A, because it has no monthly fee"],"h":"Substitute m = 3 into each equation and compare the two totals.","e":"Evaluating the system at m = 3 gives Gym A = 50 and Gym B = 45, so Gym B is cheaper."},{"p":"For the function f(x) = 3x - 5, what value of x makes f(x) = 16?","a":"7","w":["43","11","3.67"],"h":"Set the expression equal to 16, then undo the operations step by step to isolate x.","e":"Solve 3x − 5 = 16 by adding 5 and dividing by 3, giving x = 7 — this reverses evaluating the function."},{"p":"Read: \"A candle burns so that its height drops 1 centimeter every 4 minutes.\" What is the slope of its height-versus-time line?","a":"-1/4 cm per minute","w":["-4 cm per minute","1/4 cm per minute","-1 cm per minute"],"h":"Slope is the change in height over the change in time, and remember the candle is getting shorter.","e":"Height decreases 1 cm per 4 minutes, so slope = −1/4; the negative sign shows it is shrinking."},{"p":"A line passes through (0, 7) and (2, 17). What is its y-intercept?","a":"7","w":["17","5","10"],"h":"The y-intercept is the y-value when x = 0 — one of the given points already shows that moment.","e":"The y-intercept is the output when x = 0, which the point (0, 7) gives directly as 7."},{"p":"Read: \"Taxi X charges $2 per mile with no base fee. Taxi Y charges $3 plus $1.50 per mile.\" Which is a proportional relationship?","a":"Taxi X, because its cost is $0 when miles are 0","w":["Taxi Y, because it has a base fee","Both, because cost rises as miles rise","Neither, because both charge a rate"],"h":"A proportional relationship passes through the origin — think about what each taxi charges for 0 miles.","e":"Proportional relationships have a y-intercept of 0; Taxi X costs $0 at 0 miles, but Taxi Y starts at $3."},{"p":"Read: \"On a graph, a pool's temperature rises along a straight line from 60°F at 0 hours to 72°F at 6 hours.\" What is the rate of change?","a":"2°F per hour","w":["12°F per hour","6°F per hour","0.5°F per hour"],"h":"Divide the total change in temperature by the number of hours it took.","e":"Rate of change = Δtemperature/Δtime = 12/6 = 2°F per hour."},{"p":"A line passes through the points (4, 1) and (4, 9). What is its slope?","a":"Undefined (the line is vertical)","w":["0 (the line is horizontal)","8","2"],"h":"Look at how much x changes between the two points before you divide.","e":"Both points have x = 4, so Δx = 0; dividing by zero makes the slope undefined, giving a vertical line."},{"p":"Read: \"A car speeds up from a stop, then drives at a steady speed, then slows to a stop.\" On a speed-versus-time graph, which describes the line?","a":"Rising, then flat, then falling","w":["Flat, then rising, then flat","Falling, then flat, then rising","Rising the whole time"],"h":"Match each phase — speeding up, steady, slowing — to going up, staying level, or going down.","e":"On a speed-time graph, speeding up rises, steady speed is horizontal, and slowing down falls."},{"p":"Read: \"A club sells shirts. Cost is C = 5n + 100 and revenue is R = 15n, where n is shirts. At n = 10, both equal $150.\" What does n = 10 represent?","a":"The break-even point where cost equals revenue","w":["The maximum profit the club can make","The number of shirts left unsold","The point where the club runs out of money"],"h":"The two lines meet where their outputs are equal — think about what equal cost and revenue means.","e":"Where a system's lines intersect, the outputs are equal; here cost equals revenue, the break-even point."},{"p":"Read: \"A phone plan costs C = 0.10t + 15, where t is texts and C is dollars.\" What is the bill for 200 texts?","a":"$35","w":["$20","$215","$30"],"h":"Multiply the per-text rate by 200 first, then add the fixed monthly charge.","e":"Substitute t = 200: 0.10(200) + 15 = 20 + 15 = 35 dollars."},{"p":"Read: \"A recipe scales by the line f = 2s, where s is servings and f is cups of flour.\" What are the units of the slope, 2?","a":"Cups of flour per serving","w":["Servings per cup of flour","Cups of flour","Servings"],"h":"Slope is output over input — pair the y-axis unit with the x-axis unit.","e":"Slope is Δy/Δx, so its units are (cups of flour) per (serving)."},{"p":"A linear function table shows x = 0, 5, 10, 15 giving y = 4, 19, 34, and a missing value. What is the missing y-value?","a":"49","w":["39","44","47"],"h":"Find the constant amount y changes for each step in x, then continue the pattern.","e":"Each x-step of 5 raises y by 15, so the next value is 34 + 15 = 49."},{"p":"Read: \"Two savings plans are graphed. Plan 1 starts at $50 and Plan 2 starts at $10, and both rise at the same rate.\" What does the higher y-intercept tell you?","a":"Plan 1 began with more money saved","w":["Plan 1 saves money faster each week","Plan 2 will always have more money","Plan 1 has a steeper line"],"h":"The y-intercept is the value at the very start, before any time has passed.","e":"The y-intercept is the output when x = 0, the starting amount; Plan 1's higher intercept means it started with more."}],"m.10.trig":[{"p":"In a right triangle, which ratio defines the sine of an acute angle?","a":"length of the opposite side divided by the hypotenuse","w":["length of the adjacent side divided by the hypotenuse","length of the opposite side divided by the adjacent side","length of the hypotenuse divided by the opposite side"],"h":"Recall the mnemonic SOH-CAH-TOA and focus on the S.","e":"By the SOH part of SOH-CAH-TOA, sine equals opposite over hypotenuse."},{"p":"A right triangle has an acute angle theta whose opposite side is 3, adjacent side is 4, and hypotenuse is 5. What is sin(theta)?","a":"3/5","w":["4/5","3/4","5/3"],"h":"Sine uses the side across from the angle over the longest side.","e":"Using sine = opposite/hypotenuse, sin(theta) = 3/5."},{"p":"A right triangle has an acute angle theta whose opposite side is 3, adjacent side is 4, and hypotenuse is 5. What is cos(theta)?","a":"4/5","w":["3/5","4/3","5/4"],"h":"Cosine pairs the side next to the angle with the longest side.","e":"Using cosine = adjacent/hypotenuse, cos(theta) = 4/5."},{"p":"A right triangle has an acute angle theta whose opposite side is 3, adjacent side is 4, and hypotenuse is 5. What is tan(theta)?","a":"3/4","w":["4/3","3/5","4/5"],"h":"Tangent compares the two legs, not the hypotenuse.","e":"Using tangent = opposite/adjacent, tan(theta) = 3/4."},{"p":"The two legs of a right triangle measure 6 and 8. What is the length of the hypotenuse?","a":"10","w":["14","2*sqrt(7)","100"],"h":"Add the squares of the legs, then undo the squaring.","e":"By the Pythagorean Theorem, c = sqrt(6^2 + 8^2) = sqrt(100) = 10."},{"p":"In a 45-45-90 right triangle, each leg measures 5. What is the length of the hypotenuse?","a":"5*sqrt(2)","w":["5","10","5*sqrt(3)"],"h":"Recall the fixed side ratio for an isosceles right triangle.","e":"In a 45-45-90 triangle the sides are in ratio 1 : 1 : sqrt(2), so the hypotenuse is 5*sqrt(2)."},{"p":"In a 30-60-90 right triangle, the hypotenuse measures 10. What is the length of the side opposite the 30-degree angle?","a":"5","w":["5*sqrt(3)","5*sqrt(2)","10*sqrt(3)"],"h":"The shortest side lies opposite the smallest angle and is half the hypotenuse.","e":"In a 30-60-90 triangle the sides are in ratio 1 : sqrt(3) : 2, so the side opposite 30 degrees is half the hypotenuse: 5."},{"p":"What is the exact value of sin(30 degrees)?","a":"1/2","w":["sqrt(3)/2","sqrt(2)/2","1"],"h":"Use the 30-60-90 side ratios with sine as opposite over hypotenuse.","e":"From the 30-60-90 triangle, the side opposite 30 degrees is half the hypotenuse, so sin(30 degrees) = 1/2."},{"p":"What is the exact value of cos(60 degrees)?","a":"1/2","w":["sqrt(3)/2","sqrt(2)/2","sqrt(3)/3"],"h":"Cosine is adjacent over hypotenuse; use the 30-60-90 ratios.","e":"From the 30-60-90 triangle, the side adjacent to 60 degrees is half the hypotenuse, so cos(60 degrees) = 1/2."},{"p":"What is the exact value of tan(45 degrees)?","a":"1","w":["0","sqrt(3)","sqrt(3)/3"],"h":"In a 45-45-90 triangle the two legs are equal.","e":"Since the legs of a 45-45-90 triangle are equal, tan(45 degrees) = opposite/adjacent = 1."},{"p":"A straight ladder leans against a wall, reaching 12 feet up the wall while its base sits 5 feet from the wall. How long is the ladder?","a":"13 feet","w":["17 feet","sqrt(119) feet","11 feet"],"h":"The wall, ground, and ladder form a right triangle with the ladder as the hypotenuse.","e":"By the Pythagorean Theorem, ladder = sqrt(12^2 + 5^2) = sqrt(169) = 13 feet."},{"p":"From a point 20 feet from the base of a tree, the top of the tree is sighted. The tree is 15 feet tall. What is the angle of elevation to the top, to the nearest tenth of a degree?","a":"about 36.9 degrees","w":["about 53.1 degrees","about 48.6 degrees","about 41.4 degrees"],"h":"You know the side opposite the angle and the side adjacent to it.","e":"Using tangent = opposite/adjacent, theta = arctan(15/20) = arctan(0.75) is about 36.9 degrees."},{"p":"An acute angle theta in a right triangle satisfies sin(theta) = 0.5. What is the measure of theta?","a":"30 degrees","w":["60 degrees","45 degrees","90 degrees"],"h":"Ask which standard angle has this well-known sine value.","e":"Since sin(30 degrees) = 1/2, the inverse sine of 0.5 is 30 degrees."},{"p":"You know one acute angle of a right triangle and the length of the hypotenuse, and you want the length of the side opposite that angle. Which trigonometric ratio should you use?","a":"sine","w":["cosine","tangent","cotangent"],"h":"Match the ratio that connects the opposite side with the hypotenuse.","e":"Sine relates the opposite side to the hypotenuse (sine = opposite/hypotenuse), so it isolates the opposite side."},{"p":"A lighthouse keeper looks down at a boat. The angle of depression from the keeper to the boat is equal to which angle?","a":"the angle of elevation from the boat to the keeper","w":["the angle of elevation from the boat to the base of the lighthouse","the complement of the angle of elevation from the boat to the keeper","the supplement of the angle of elevation from the boat to the keeper"],"h":"The horizontal line of sight at the top and the water surface are parallel.","e":"Because the horizontal lines are parallel, the angle of depression and the angle of elevation are equal alternate interior angles."},{"p":"In a right triangle, an acute angle measures 40 degrees and the hypotenuse is 10. What is the length of the side adjacent to the 40-degree angle, to the nearest hundredth?","a":"about 7.66","w":["about 6.43","about 8.39","about 13.05"],"h":"The adjacent side and hypotenuse are linked by one specific ratio.","e":"Using cosine = adjacent/hypotenuse, adjacent = 10 * cos(40 degrees) is about 7.66."},{"p":"Read: \"A wheelchair ramp rises 2 feet over a horizontal run of 24 feet.\" What is the angle of elevation of the ramp, to the nearest tenth of a degree?","a":"about 4.8 degrees","w":["about 85.2 degrees","about 7.6 degrees","about 2.4 degrees"],"h":"The rise is opposite the angle and the run is adjacent to it.","e":"Using tangent = opposite/adjacent, theta = arctan(2/24) is about 4.8 degrees."},{"p":"Which set of side lengths forms a right triangle?","a":"5, 12, 13","w":["4, 5, 6","6, 7, 8","2, 3, 4"],"h":"Test whether the squares of the two shorter sides add up to the square of the longest.","e":"By the converse of the Pythagorean Theorem, 5^2 + 12^2 = 25 + 144 = 169 = 13^2, so 5, 12, 13 forms a right triangle."},{"p":"In a right triangle, one acute angle measures 35 degrees and the leg adjacent to it is 20 ft long. What is the length of the leg opposite the 35-degree angle, to the nearest hundredth?","a":"14.00 ft","w":["11.47 ft","16.38 ft","28.56 ft"],"h":"You have the adjacent leg and want the opposite leg, so pick the ratio that relates those two sides.","e":"Since tan(theta) = opposite/adjacent, the opposite leg = 20 * tan(35 degrees) is about 14.00 ft."},{"p":"An airplane flying at an altitude of 2000 ft spots an airport ahead at an angle of depression of 15 degrees. What is the horizontal distance from the plane to the airport, to the nearest foot?","a":"7464 ft","w":["536 ft","7727 ft","2071 ft"],"h":"The angle of depression equals the angle of elevation from the airport; the altitude is opposite that angle and the horizontal distance is adjacent to it.","e":"Using tan(15 degrees) = 2000/horizontal, the horizontal distance = 2000/tan(15 degrees) is about 7464 ft (alternate interior angles make depression equal elevation)."},{"p":"In a right triangle, an acute angle measures 28 degrees and the side adjacent to it is 15 cm. What is the length of the hypotenuse, to the nearest hundredth?","a":"16.99 cm","w":["13.24 cm","31.95 cm","28.21 cm"],"h":"Cosine links the adjacent side and the hypotenuse; solve the equation for the hypotenuse.","e":"Because cos(theta) = adjacent/hypotenuse, the hypotenuse = 15/cos(28 degrees) is about 16.99 cm."},{"p":"An acute angle theta in a right triangle satisfies cos(theta) = 0.8. What is the measure of theta, to the nearest tenth of a degree?","a":"36.9 degrees","w":["53.1 degrees","38.7 degrees","51.3 degrees"],"h":"Use the inverse cosine function, and make sure your calculator is set to degree mode.","e":"Applying the inverse cosine, theta = cos^-1(0.8) is about 36.9 degrees; using inverse sine or tangent by mistake gives the common wrong answers."},{"p":"In a 30-60-90 right triangle, the side opposite the 30-degree angle measures 7. What is the exact length of the side opposite the 60-degree angle?","a":"7√3","w":["7√2","14","7√3/2"],"h":"In a 30-60-90 triangle the sides are in the ratio 1 : √3 : 2 from shortest to longest.","e":"In a 30-60-90 triangle the longer leg equals the shorter leg times √3, so the side opposite 60 degrees is 7√3."},{"p":"In a 45-45-90 right triangle, the hypotenuse measures 8. What is the exact length of each leg?","a":"4√2","w":["8√2","4","8"],"h":"In a 45-45-90 triangle the hypotenuse equals a leg times √2, so divide to reverse it.","e":"Since hypotenuse = leg * √2, each leg = 8/√2 = 4√2 after rationalizing the denominator."},{"p":"The hypotenuse of a right triangle is 26 cm and one leg is 10 cm. What is the length of the other leg?","a":"24 cm","w":["27.9 cm","16 cm","20 cm"],"h":"Rearrange the Pythagorean theorem to solve for a leg, not the hypotenuse.","e":"By the Pythagorean theorem, leg = √(26^2 - 10^2) = √576 = 24 cm (a 5-12-13 triangle scaled by 2)."},{"p":"From a point on level ground 40 m from the base of a tower, the angle of elevation to the top of the tower is 52 degrees. How tall is the tower, to the nearest hundredth?","a":"51.20 m","w":["31.52 m","24.63 m","31.25 m"],"h":"The known 40 m is adjacent to the angle and the height is opposite it.","e":"Since tan(52 degrees) = height/40, the height = 40 * tan(52 degrees) is about 51.20 m."},{"p":"In a right triangle, an acute angle theta satisfies sin(theta) = 7/25. What is cos(theta)?","a":"24/25","w":["25/24","7/24","24/7"],"h":"Recognize the Pythagorean triple, or use the identity sin^2(theta) + cos^2(theta) = 1.","e":"Because 7-24-25 is a Pythagorean triple, the adjacent side is 24 and cos(theta) = adjacent/hypotenuse = 24/25."},{"p":"What is the exact value of tan(30 degrees)?","a":"√3/3","w":["√3","√2/2","1/2"],"h":"Build a 30-60-90 triangle and take the ratio opposite over adjacent for the 30-degree angle.","e":"For a 30-60-90 triangle, tan(30 degrees) = 1/√3 = √3/3 after rationalizing."},{"p":"What is the exact value of sin(60 degrees)?","a":"√3/2","w":["1/2","√2/2","√3/3"],"h":"In a 30-60-90 triangle, sine of 60 degrees is the longer leg over the hypotenuse.","e":"Using the 1 : √3 : 2 ratios, sin(60 degrees) = √3/2."},{"p":"What is the exact value of cos(45 degrees)?","a":"√2/2","w":["1/2","√3/2","1"],"h":"Use a 45-45-90 triangle where both legs are equal and the hypotenuse is a leg times √2.","e":"For a 45-45-90 triangle, cos(45 degrees) = 1/√2 = √2/2 after rationalizing."},{"p":"In a right triangle, sin(37 degrees) is equal to the cosine of which angle?","a":"cos(53 degrees)","w":["cos(37 degrees)","cos(143 degrees)","cos(90 degrees)"],"h":"The two acute angles of a right triangle are complementary; sine and cosine are cofunctions.","e":"By the cofunction identity sin(theta) = cos(90 degrees - theta), so sin(37 degrees) = cos(53 degrees)."},{"p":"An acute angle theta in a right triangle satisfies sin(theta) = 5/13 and cos(theta) = 12/13. What is tan(theta)?","a":"5/12","w":["12/5","13/12","13/5"],"h":"Tangent can be written as sine divided by cosine.","e":"Since tan(theta) = sin(theta)/cos(theta) = (5/13)/(12/13) = 5/12 (a 5-12-13 triangle)."},{"p":"A kite is flown on a taut 100 m string that makes an angle of elevation of 40 degrees with the horizontal ground. How high above the ground is the kite, to the nearest hundredth? Assume the string is held at ground level.","a":"64.28 m","w":["76.60 m","83.91 m","155.57 m"],"h":"The string is the hypotenuse, and the height is the side opposite the 40-degree angle.","e":"Because sin(40 degrees) = height/100, the height = 100 * sin(40 degrees) is about 64.28 m."},{"p":"A straight loading ramp is 20 ft long and rises at an angle of 25 degrees from the horizontal. What is the vertical rise of the ramp, to the nearest hundredth?","a":"8.45 ft","w":["9.33 ft","18.13 ft","47.32 ft"],"h":"The ramp is the hypotenuse and the vertical rise is opposite the 25-degree angle.","e":"Because sin(25 degrees) = rise/20, the rise = 20 * sin(25 degrees) is about 8.45 ft."},{"p":"A boat sails 9 km due east and then 12 km due north. How far is the boat from its starting point, in a straight line?","a":"15 km","w":["21 km","7.94 km","10.5 km"],"h":"The two legs of travel are perpendicular, so the straight-line distance is the hypotenuse.","e":"By the Pythagorean theorem, distance = √(9^2 + 12^2) = √225 = 15 km (a 3-4-5 triangle scaled by 3)."},{"p":"What is the exact value of tan(60 degrees)?","a":"√3","w":["√3/3","3/2","1/2"],"h":"Use a 30-60-90 reference triangle and form the ratio of the side opposite 60 degrees to the side adjacent to it.","e":"In a 30-60-90 triangle the sides are in ratio 1 : √3 : 2, so tan(60°) = (√3)/1 = √3."},{"p":"In a right triangle, cos(72 degrees) is equal to the sine of which angle?","a":"sin(18 degrees)","w":["sin(72 degrees)","sin(28 degrees)","sin(108 degrees)"],"h":"The two acute angles of a right triangle are complementary; a cofunction of one equals the function of the other.","e":"By the cofunction identity, cos(θ) = sin(90° − θ), so cos(72°) = sin(18°)."},{"p":"From the top of a 60 m tall building, the angle of depression to a parked car on level ground is 35 degrees. How far is the car from the base of the building, to the nearest hundredth?","a":"85.69 m","w":["42.01 m","104.61 m","34.41 m"],"h":"The angle of depression equals the angle of elevation from the car; the building height is opposite that angle and the ground distance is adjacent.","e":"Using tan(35°) = 60/distance gives distance = 60/tan(35°) ≈ 85.69 m, an application of the tangent ratio with an angle of depression."},{"p":"A guy wire is attached to the top of a 30 ft vertical pole and anchored to the ground 16 ft from the base of the pole. How long is the guy wire?","a":"34 ft","w":["25.38 ft","46 ft","32.98 ft"],"h":"The pole, the ground distance, and the wire form a right triangle; find the hypotenuse.","e":"By the Pythagorean theorem, wire = √(30² + 16²) = √1156 = 34 ft (an 8-15-17 triple scaled by 2)."},{"p":"A guy wire is attached to the top of a 30 ft vertical pole and anchored to the ground 16 ft from the base. What angle does the wire make with the ground, to the nearest tenth of a degree?","a":"61.9 degrees","w":["28.1 degrees","32.0 degrees","45.0 degrees"],"h":"The pole height is opposite the ground angle and the ground distance is adjacent to it; choose the ratio using those two legs.","e":"tan(θ) = 30/16, so θ = arctan(1.875) ≈ 61.9°, using the inverse tangent to recover an angle from the two legs."},{"p":"A 15 ft ladder leans against a wall and reaches a window 13 ft above the ground. What angle does the ladder make with the ground, to the nearest tenth of a degree?","a":"60.1 degrees","w":["29.9 degrees","40.5 degrees","49.5 degrees"],"h":"The reach up the wall is opposite the ground angle and the ladder is the hypotenuse; select the ratio that pairs those two.","e":"sin(θ) = 13/15, so θ = arcsin(0.8667) ≈ 60.1°, applying the inverse sine with the opposite side and hypotenuse."},{"p":"An isosceles triangle has two equal sides of length 10 and a base of length 12. What is the height drawn from the apex to the base?","a":"8","w":["15.62","4","11.66"],"h":"The altitude to the base of an isosceles triangle bisects the base, creating two congruent right triangles.","e":"Each right triangle has legs 6 and h with hypotenuse 10, so h = √(10² − 6²) = √64 = 8 by the Pythagorean theorem."},{"p":"An acute angle theta in a right triangle satisfies tan(theta) = 2.5. What is the measure of theta, to the nearest tenth of a degree?","a":"68.2 degrees","w":["21.8 degrees","51.3 degrees","66.4 degrees"],"h":"You are given a ratio of opposite to adjacent; use the inverse of the matching trig function.","e":"θ = arctan(2.5) ≈ 68.2°, since the tangent ratio equals opposite over adjacent."},{"p":"A rectangle measures 8 cm by 15 cm. What angle does its diagonal make with the longer (15 cm) side, to the nearest tenth of a degree?","a":"28.1 degrees","w":["61.9 degrees","32.2 degrees","25.6 degrees"],"h":"The diagonal is the hypotenuse; relative to the 15 cm side, the 8 cm side is opposite and the 15 cm side is adjacent.","e":"tan(θ) = 8/15, so θ = arctan(0.5333) ≈ 28.1°, using the tangent ratio of the two legs."},{"p":"A surveyor stands at point A on one bank of a straight river, directly across from point B on the opposite bank, so that AB is perpendicular to the bank. She walks 25 m along the bank to point C and measures angle ACB = 58 degrees. How wide is the river (distance AB), to the nearest hundredth?","a":"40.01 m","w":["15.62 m","21.20 m","47.17 m"],"h":"In right triangle ABC the right angle is at A; the river width is opposite the 58-degree angle and the 25 m walk is adjacent.","e":"tan(58°) = AB/25, so AB = 25·tan(58°) ≈ 40.01 m, an indirect-measurement application of the tangent ratio."},{"p":"In a right triangle, an acute angle theta satisfies sin(theta) = 8/17. What is tan(theta)?","a":"8/15","w":["15/8","8/17","17/15"],"h":"Find the missing leg with the Pythagorean theorem, then form opposite over adjacent.","e":"With opposite 8 and hypotenuse 17, the adjacent leg is √(17²−8²) = 15, so tan(θ) = 8/15 (an 8-15-17 right triangle)."},{"p":"In a right triangle, an acute angle theta satisfies cos(theta) = 9/41. What is sin(theta)?","a":"40/41","w":["41/40","9/41","40/9"],"h":"Use the Pythagorean theorem to find the leg opposite theta, keeping the hypotenuse as 41.","e":"With adjacent 9 and hypotenuse 41, the opposite leg is √(41²−9²) = 40, so sin(θ) = 40/41 (a 9-40-41 right triangle)."},{"p":"In a 30-60-90 right triangle, the side opposite the 60-degree angle measures 6√3. What is the exact length of the hypotenuse?","a":"12","w":["6","12√3","6√3"],"h":"In a 30-60-90 triangle the sides follow the ratio 1 : √3 : 2; work back to the shortest side first.","e":"The long leg equals (short leg)·√3, so the short leg is 6, and the hypotenuse is twice the short leg, giving 12."},{"p":"In a 45-45-90 right triangle, the hypotenuse measures 10√2. What is the area of the triangle?","a":"50","w":["100","50√2","25"],"h":"Find each leg from the 1 : 1 : √2 ratio, then use the right-triangle area formula.","e":"With hypotenuse 10√2, each leg is 10, so the area is (1/2)(10)(10) = 50 square units."},{"p":"Read: \"A person whose eyes are 5 ft above the ground stands 30 ft from a flagpole and sights the top of the pole at an angle of elevation of 55 degrees.\" How tall is the flagpole, to the nearest hundredth?","a":"47.84 ft","w":["42.84 ft","26.01 ft","29.57 ft"],"h":"The tangent gives the height above eye level; remember the sightline starts 5 ft off the ground.","e":"Height above the eyes is 30·tan(55°) ≈ 42.84 ft; adding the 5 ft eye height gives about 47.84 ft, an angle-of-elevation application."},{"p":"From the top of a 40 m vertical cliff, the angles of depression to two boats in line with the base are 30 degrees and 45 degrees. How far apart are the two boats, to the nearest hundredth?","a":"29.28 m","w":["40.00 m","69.28 m","109.28 m"],"h":"Each angle of depression forms its own right triangle sharing the 40 m height; find both horizontal distances and compare.","e":"The distances are 40/tan(30°) ≈ 69.28 m and 40/tan(45°) = 40 m, so the boats are 69.28 − 40 ≈ 29.28 m apart, using the tangent ratio twice."},{"p":"Two acute angles satisfy sin(2x) = cos(50 degrees), where 2x is acute. What is the value of x?","a":"20 degrees","w":["25 degrees","40 degrees","70 degrees"],"h":"Rewrite the cosine as a sine of the complementary angle, then match the arguments.","e":"Since cos(50°) = sin(40°), we set 2x = 40°, giving x = 20° by the cofunction identity."},{"p":"An escalator rises at a constant angle of 30 degrees from the horizontal and carries riders to a vertical height of 8 m. What is the length of the escalator (the distance traveled along the incline)?","a":"16 m","w":["4 m","13.86 m","9.24 m"],"h":"The vertical height is opposite the 30-degree angle and the escalator length is the hypotenuse; choose the ratio linking those two.","e":"sin(30°) = 8/length, so length = 8/sin(30°) = 8/0.5 = 16 m, applying the sine ratio with opposite side and hypotenuse."}],"m.7.datadetect":[{"p":"Jordan scored these points in 5 basketball games: 5, 9, 7, 9, 10. What is the MEAN (average) number of points per game?","a":"8","w":["9","5","40"],"h":"Add up all the game scores first, then split that total evenly across the number of games.","e":"The mean is the sum of the values divided by how many there are: 40 divided by 5 equals 8."},{"p":"A shoe store recorded these sizes sold one morning: 7, 8, 8, 9, 10, 8, 7. What is the MODE?","a":"8","w":["7","3","10"],"h":"The mode is about which value shows up most often, not about its size.","e":"The mode is the value that appears most frequently; size 8 appears three times, more than any other."},{"p":"Five snacks cost these amounts: $12, $8, $15, $20, $9. What is the RANGE of the prices?","a":"$12","w":["$20","$8","$28"],"h":"Range measures the spread from the cheapest to the most expensive item.","e":"Range equals the greatest value minus the least value: 20 minus 8 equals 12."},{"p":"A bag holds 3 red, 5 blue, and 2 green marbles. If you pull one marble without looking, what is the probability it is red?","a":"3/10","w":["3/7","7/10","1/3"],"h":"Compare the number of red marbles to the total number of marbles in the whole bag.","e":"Simple probability is favorable outcomes over total outcomes: 3 red out of 10 marbles equals 3/10."},{"p":"A spinner has 8 equal sections numbered 1 through 8. What is the probability of landing on an ODD number?","a":"1/2","w":["1/8","4/7","3/8"],"h":"First count how many of the eight numbers are odd, then compare to the total sections.","e":"There are 4 odd numbers (1, 3, 5, 7) out of 8 sections, and 4/8 simplifies to 1/2."},{"p":"A weather app says there is a 30% chance of rain today. What is the probability that it does NOT rain?","a":"70%","w":["30%","50%","130%"],"h":"The chance of something happening and the chance of it not happening must together account for everything.","e":"This uses the complement rule: the probabilities of an event and its opposite add to 100%, so 100% minus 30% is 70%."},{"p":"You flip a fair coin and roll a fair six-sided die. What is the probability of getting HEADS and rolling a 4?","a":"1/12","w":["2/3","1/6","1/8"],"h":"These are two separate independent events; think about what operation combines their probabilities.","e":"For independent compound events you multiply: 1/2 times 1/6 equals 1/12."},{"p":"A bag has 4 red and 6 blue chips. You draw one chip, record its color, put it back, then draw again. What is the probability BOTH draws are red?","a":"4/25","w":["4/5","2/5","2/15"],"h":"Because you replace the chip, the bag is exactly the same for both draws; multiply the two chances.","e":"With replacement the draws are independent: 4/10 times 4/10 equals 16/100, which simplifies to 4/25."},{"p":"Read: \"A bar graph shows books read this week: Monday 3, Tuesday 5, Wednesday 2, Thursday 6, Friday 4.\" On which day were the MOST books read?","a":"Thursday","w":["Tuesday","Friday","Monday"],"h":"Look for the tallest bar, which stands for the largest number of books.","e":"Reading a bar graph means comparing bar heights; Thursday's 6 books is the greatest value shown."},{"p":"Read: \"A survey of 20 students recorded favorite fruit: Apple 8, Banana 5, Orange 4, Grape 3.\" What fraction of the students chose apple?","a":"2/5","w":["3/5","8/12","1/8"],"h":"Compare the number who picked apple to the total number of students surveyed, then simplify.","e":"The fraction is 8 out of 20, and 8/20 simplifies to 2/5."},{"p":"Read: \"Maria wants to know the favorite music of her entire school, so she surveys only the students leaving band practice.\" What is the problem with her sample?","a":"Students at band practice may have music tastes that differ from the whole school","w":["The sample is completely random and fair","She surveyed far too many students","Music surveys can never give useful results"],"h":"Ask whether the students she picked are typical of every student in the school.","e":"This is a biased sample because band members are not representative of the entire student population."},{"p":"Over 3 games, Priya's bowling scores had a mean of 12. Two of her games were 10 and 11. What did she score in the third game?","a":"15","w":["12","13","21"],"h":"Use the mean to find the total of all three games first, then subtract what you already know.","e":"If the mean is 12 across 3 games, the total is 36; subtracting 10 and 11 leaves 15 for the third game."},{"p":"A company lists these employee salaries in thousands: 30, 32, 35, 33, 200. Which measure best represents a TYPICAL salary?","a":"Median","w":["Mean","Mode","Range"],"h":"One value is far larger than the rest; think about which measure that extreme value pulls the most.","e":"The median resists outliers, while the mean gets pulled upward by the extreme value of 200."},{"p":"The probability that a spinner lands on blue is 1/4. Written as a PERCENT, what is this probability?","a":"25%","w":["14%","40%","4%"],"h":"Think about how many equal parts of a whole 1/4 represents out of 100.","e":"Converting a probability to a percent: 1/4 equals 25 out of 100, or 25%."},{"p":"A coin was flipped 50 times and landed on heads 30 times. Based on this experiment, what is the EXPERIMENTAL probability of heads?","a":"3/5","w":["1/2","2/5","3/50"],"h":"Experimental probability uses what actually happened; compare heads to the total number of flips.","e":"Experimental probability is observed successes over trials: 30/50 simplifies to 3/5, which can differ from the theoretical 1/2."},{"p":"Sam has 3 shirts and 2 pairs of pants. How many different shirt-and-pants outfits can he make?","a":"6","w":["5","8","3"],"h":"Each shirt can be paired with each pair of pants; think about combining the two choices.","e":"The fundamental counting principle multiplies the choices: 3 shirts times 2 pants equals 6 outfits."},{"p":"Ava jogged these distances over 4 days, in miles: 3, 5, 4, 6. What is the MEAN distance she jogged per day?","a":"4.5 miles","w":["4 miles","9 miles","18 miles"],"h":"Add all four distances together, then share the total equally among the number of days.","e":"The mean (average) is the sum of the values divided by how many there are: 18 ÷ 4 = 4.5 miles."},{"p":"The ages of 8 kids at a party are 11, 12, 12, 13, 14, 15, 16, 18. What is the MEDIAN age?","a":"13.5","w":["13","14","14.5"],"h":"With an even number of values there is no single middle number—look at the two values in the center.","e":"The median of an even-sized set is the average of the two middle values: (13 + 14) ÷ 2 = 13.5."},{"p":"A soccer team scored these goals in 6 games: 1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4. What is the MODE of the goals scored?","a":"2 and 3","w":["2.5","3","no mode"],"h":"Count how many times each number appears—a data set can have more than one most-common value.","e":"The mode is the value that appears most often; here both 2 and 3 appear twice, so the set is bimodal."},{"p":"A weather station recorded these morning temperatures in °C: -3, 5, 8, -1, 10, 2. What is the RANGE of the temperatures?","a":"13","w":["7","10","5"],"h":"Find the highest and lowest values, then subtract—be careful with the negative number.","e":"Range = maximum − minimum = 10 − (−3) = 13."},{"p":"A jar has 3 red and 2 blue gumballs. You take one gumball and eat it, then take another. What is the probability that BOTH gumballs are red?","a":"3/10","w":["9/25","6/25","1/2"],"h":"After you eat the first gumball, the number of gumballs left changes for the second draw.","e":"For dependent events, multiply the changing probabilities: (3/5) × (2/4) = 6/20 = 3/10."},{"p":"You flip a fair coin twice. What is the probability of getting AT LEAST ONE head?","a":"3/4","w":["1/2","1/4","1/3"],"h":"List every possible outcome of two flips, then count how many include a head.","e":"The four outcomes are HH, HT, TH, TT; three of them have at least one head, so the probability is 3/4."},{"p":"Read: \"A class survey of 25 students recorded how they get to school: Walk 10, Bus 8, Car 5, Bike 2.\" If one student is picked at random, what is the probability they get to school by BUS?","a":"8/25","w":["8/17","1/8","8/10"],"h":"Put the number who take the bus over the total number of students surveyed.","e":"Probability from a data display is favorable outcomes over total: 8 out of 25 students, or 8/25."},{"p":"Diego scored 80, 90, and 85 on his first three tests. What must he score on his FOURTH test to have a mean of 88?","a":"97","w":["88","85","92"],"h":"Figure out the total all four scores must add up to for the average to be 88, then compare to what he already has.","e":"To average 88 over 4 tests the total must be 4 × 88 = 352; since 80 + 90 + 85 = 255, he needs 352 − 255 = 97."},{"p":"A game gives a prize with probability 1/5 each play. If you play 40 times, about how many prizes should you expect to win?","a":"8","w":["5","20","35"],"h":"Multiply the probability of winning by the number of times you play.","e":"Expected frequency = probability × number of trials = (1/5) × 40 = 8."},{"p":"A lunch special lets you pick 1 of 3 sandwiches, 1 of 4 sides, and 1 of 2 drinks. How many different lunch combinations are possible?","a":"24","w":["9","12","14"],"h":"Think about how the choices in each category combine—multiply, don't add.","e":"By the counting principle, multiply the choices in each category: 3 × 4 × 2 = 24."},{"p":"The probability that a spinner lands on green is 40%. Written as a fraction in SIMPLEST form, what is this probability?","a":"2/5","w":["2/25","1/40","4/5"],"h":"A percent means 'out of 100'—write it that way first, then reduce the fraction.","e":"40% = 40/100, and dividing both parts by 20 gives 2/5."},{"p":"A spinner is divided into 8 equal sections: 4 red, 2 blue, 1 yellow, and 1 green. What is the probability of landing on RED?","a":"1/2","w":["1/4","1/8","3/4"],"h":"Compare the number of red sections to the total number of equal sections.","e":"Probability = favorable sections over total sections = 4/8 = 1/2."},{"p":"Five homes on a street cost these amounts in thousands of dollars: 150, 155, 160, 170, 900. What is the MEDIAN price?","a":"160","w":["307","170","155"],"h":"Order the values and find the one in the middle—one very large price should not pull it far.","e":"The median is the middle value of ordered data (160); unlike the mean (307), it is not distorted by the outlier of 900."},{"p":"Read: \"A dot plot shows pets owned: 0 pets → 4 students, 1 pet → 7 students, 2 pets → 5 students, 3 pets → 2 students, 4 pets → 2 students.\" How many students own MORE THAN 2 pets?","a":"4","w":["5","9","2"],"h":"'More than 2' does not include students who own exactly 2—only counts above that.","e":"Reading the display, 'more than 2' means 3 pets (2 students) plus 4 pets (2 students) = 4 students."},{"p":"A principal wants to estimate how many of the 600 students like the new lunch menu. Which sample is MOST likely to give reliable results?","a":"100 students chosen at random from across all grades","w":["5 students from the principal's own class","50 students from the football team only","the first 10 students to arrive at school"],"h":"A good sample should be large enough and give every student an equal chance of being picked.","e":"A large random sample drawn from the whole population is representative, while small or one-group samples are biased."},{"p":"In the ordered data set 5, 8, __, 12, 15, the MEDIAN is 10. What is the missing MIDDLE value?","a":"10","w":["9","11","8"],"h":"For a set of five values already in order, think about which position the median sits in.","e":"With five ordered values the median is the third (middle) number, so the missing value equals the median, 10."},{"p":"You roll two fair six-sided dice and add the numbers. What is the probability the sum equals 7?","a":"1/6","w":["1/11","1/12","1/2"],"h":"There are 36 equally likely ordered pairs—count how many of them add up to 7.","e":"Six pairs sum to 7 (1-6, 2-5, 3-4, 4-3, 5-2, 6-1) out of 36 outcomes, giving 6/36 = 1/6."},{"p":"A bag has 6 green, 3 yellow, and 1 orange marble. What is the probability of drawing a marble that is NOT green?","a":"2/5","w":["3/5","4/6","1/4"],"h":"'Not green' includes every other color—or subtract the chance of green from a whole.","e":"By the complement rule, P(not green) = 1 − 6/10 = 4/10 = 2/5."},{"p":"A class recorded the number of siblings each student has in a frequency table: 0 siblings → 5 students, 1 sibling → 8 students, 2 siblings → 4 students, 3 siblings → 3 students. What is the MEAN number of siblings per student?","a":"1.25","w":["1.5","6.25","1"],"h":"Find the total number of siblings across all students, then divide by the total number of students.","e":"This is a mean from a frequency table: total siblings = 0(5)+1(8)+2(4)+3(3) = 25, divided by 20 students = 1.25."},{"p":"Read: \"A stem-and-leaf plot shows quiz scores. 6 | 2 5   7 | 0 3 8   8 | 1 1 5   9 | 4 (where 6 | 2 means 62).\" How many students scored in the 80s?","a":"3","w":["2","1","5"],"h":"Look only at the row whose stem is 8, and count how many leaves are listed beside it.","e":"Reading a stem-and-leaf plot: the stem 8 has leaves 1, 1, 5, giving scores 81, 81, 85, so 3 students scored in the 80s."},{"p":"The heights of 5 plants are 20, 22, 24, 26, and 28 cm. A sixth plant that is 100 cm tall is added to the data. Which value changes the LEAST?","a":"The median","w":["The mean","The range","The total"],"h":"Think about which measure depends on the middle position of the data rather than the actual size of every value.","e":"The median resists outliers: it moves only from 24 to 25, while the mean, range, and total all jump sharply because of the 100 cm value."},{"p":"Find the LOWER quartile (Q1) of the ordered data set 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 16.","a":"5","w":["4","6","9"],"h":"Split the data into a lower half and an upper half, then find the median of the LOWER half.","e":"The lower quartile is the median of the bottom half (2, 4, 6, 8), which is the average of 4 and 6, so Q1 = 5."},{"p":"A bag has 10 tiles numbered 1 through 10. If you draw one tile, what is the probability its number is a multiple of 3 OR a multiple of 5?","a":"1/2","w":["3/10","1/5","7/10"],"h":"List the multiples of 3 and the multiples of 5 from 1 to 10, being careful not to count any number twice.","e":"This is probability of an 'or' event: multiples of 3 are 3, 6, 9 and of 5 are 5, 10, giving 5 favorable tiles, so 5/10 = 1/2."},{"p":"In a sample of 50 candies from a factory, 8 were red. If the factory makes 2,000 candies with the same rate, about how many should be red?","a":"320","w":["160","400","250"],"h":"Find the fraction of the sample that was red, then apply that same fraction to the full 2,000 candies.","e":"Using proportional reasoning from a sample: 8/50 = 0.16, and 0.16 × 2,000 = 320 red candies."},{"p":"Read: \"A two-way table shows students by grade and lunch choice. Grade 6: Pizza 12, Salad 8. Grade 7: Pizza 15, Salad 5.\" How many students chose PIZZA in all?","a":"27","w":["20","15","40"],"h":"Find every pizza entry in the table, across both grades, and add those numbers together.","e":"Reading a two-way table: add the pizza counts from each grade, 12 + 15 = 27 students."},{"p":"Read: \"A histogram shows minutes spent reading: 0–9 min → 3 students, 10–19 min → 6 students, 20–29 min → 8 students, 30–39 min → 4 students.\" How many students read for AT LEAST 20 minutes?","a":"12","w":["8","4","21"],"h":"'At least 20 minutes' includes every interval that starts at 20 or higher — combine those bars.","e":"Reading a histogram: the 20–29 and 30–39 bars cover at least 20 minutes, so 8 + 4 = 12 students."},{"p":"A spinner has 3 equal sections colored red, blue, and green. You spin it and roll a fair six-sided die. What is the probability of landing on GREEN and rolling an EVEN number?","a":"1/6","w":["1/2","1/3","5/6"],"h":"Find the probability of each event separately, then multiply because the two actions are independent.","e":"This is compound probability of independent events: P(green) = 1/3 and P(even) = 1/2, so 1/3 × 1/2 = 1/6."},{"p":"A drawer holds 5 black socks and 5 white socks. You pull out two socks without looking. What is the probability that BOTH are black?","a":"2/9","w":["1/4","5/18","1/2"],"h":"After the first black sock is removed, the number of black socks and the total both decrease before the second pull.","e":"This is dependent probability without replacement: 5/10 × 4/9 = 20/90 = 2/9."},{"p":"Read: \"A radio station asks listeners to call in to vote for the best song of the year.\" Why might this sample be biased?","a":"Only listeners who feel strongly enough to call in will respond, so it is not representative.","w":["The sample is too large, which always makes results inaccurate.","Phone calls are chosen at random, so the results are perfectly fair.","Songs cannot be compared using votes, so no survey would work."],"h":"Think about which people actually end up in a call-in sample versus who is left out.","e":"This is self-selection bias: only motivated listeners choose to call, so the sample does not fairly represent all listeners."},{"p":"A data set contains the values 12, 15, x, and 20, and its RANGE is 15. If x is the smallest value in the set, what is x?","a":"5","w":["7","8","35"],"h":"Range equals the largest value minus the smallest value; identify the maximum first.","e":"Using the range formula: 20 − x = 15, so x = 5, which is indeed the smallest value."},{"p":"The mean of 6 numbers is 15. If one more number, 22, is added to the set, what is the new mean of all 7 numbers?","a":"16","w":["15","18.5","22"],"h":"First find the total of the original six numbers using their mean, then include the new value.","e":"Working backward from the mean: 6 × 15 = 90, then (90 + 22) ÷ 7 = 112 ÷ 7 = 16."},{"p":"Two classes took the same test. Class A has 20 students with a mean of 80, and Class B has 30 students with a mean of 90. What is the mean score of all 50 students combined?","a":"86","w":["85","84","90"],"h":"You cannot just average 80 and 90 — the classes have different sizes, so use total points over total students.","e":"This is a weighted mean: (20×80 + 30×90) ÷ 50 = (1600 + 2700) ÷ 50 = 4300 ÷ 50 = 86."},{"p":"A fair six-sided die is rolled 60 times. About how many times would you EXPECT to roll a 2?","a":"10","w":["6","12","30"],"h":"Find the theoretical probability of rolling a 2 on one roll, then apply it to all 60 rolls.","e":"This uses theoretical probability to predict outcomes: P(2) = 1/6, so 1/6 × 60 = 10 expected rolls."},{"p":"A spinner has 4 equal sections: 1 red and 3 blue. You spin it twice. What is the probability of getting AT LEAST ONE red?","a":"7/16","w":["9/16","1/4","3/8"],"h":"It is easier to first find the probability of getting NO red on both spins, then subtract from 1.","e":"Using the complement rule: P(no red) = 3/4 × 3/4 = 9/16, so P(at least one red) = 1 − 9/16 = 7/16."},{"p":"A bike lock uses a 2-digit code where each digit can be 0 through 9 and digits are allowed to repeat. How many different codes are possible?","a":"100","w":["20","90","45"],"h":"Count the number of choices for the first digit and for the second digit, then combine them.","e":"By the counting principle, each digit has 10 choices, so 10 × 10 = 100 possible codes."},{"p":"A city recorded these daily high temperatures in °F: 45, 52, 48, 60, 55, 50. What is the MEDIAN high temperature?","a":"51","w":["50","52","51.5"],"h":"Put the values in order first; with an even number of values, focus on the two in the middle.","e":"Finding the median of an even set: ordered as 45, 48, 50, 52, 55, 60, the two middle values 50 and 52 average to 51."}],"e.1.rhyme":[{"p":"Which word rhymes with \"cat\"?","a":"hat","w":["dog","sun","cup"],"h":"Say each word out loud and listen to the ending part.","e":"Rhyming words have the same ending sound. \"Cat\" and \"hat\" both end with the -at sound."},{"p":"Which word rhymes with \"bee\"?","a":"tree","w":["bird","book","ball"],"h":"Listen for the long ee sound at the end of each word.","e":"Rhyming words share the same ending sound. \"Bee\" and \"tree\" both end with the ee sound."},{"p":"Which word rhymes with \"star\"?","a":"car","w":["moon","sky","cloud"],"h":"Say the words slowly and listen to how they end.","e":"Rhyming words end the same way. \"Star\" and \"car\" both end with the -ar sound."},{"p":"Which word begins with the same sound as \"sun\"?","a":"sock","w":["moon","bell","cup"],"h":"Say each word and listen to the very first sound.","e":"This is about beginning sounds. \"Sun\" and \"sock\" both start with the /s/ sound."},{"p":"Which word begins with the same sound as \"dog\"?","a":"duck","w":["cat","fish","pig"],"h":"Listen closely to the first sound you hear in each word.","e":"Beginning sounds are the first sounds in words. \"Dog\" and \"duck\" both start with the /d/ sound."},{"p":"Which word begins with the same sound as \"ball\"?","a":"bat","w":["net","log","dish"],"h":"Say \"ball\" slowly and listen to the sound it starts with.","e":"Beginning sounds are the first sounds in words. \"Ball\" and \"bat\" both start with the /b/ sound."},{"p":"Which word ends with the same sound as \"map\"?","a":"cup","w":["mat","man","mad"],"h":"Listen to the very last sound, not the first one.","e":"Ending sounds are the last sounds in words. \"Map\" and \"cup\" both end with the /p/ sound."},{"p":"Which word ends with the same sound as \"bug\"?","a":"dog","w":["bus","bun","bud"],"h":"Say each word and listen to the last sound you hear.","e":"Ending sounds are the last sounds in words. \"Bug\" and \"dog\" both end with the /g/ sound."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-at\" word family, like cat and hat?","a":"rat","w":["rug","red","run"],"h":"A word family shares the same ending letters and sound.","e":"Words in the -at family end with -at. \"Rat\" fits with cat and hat."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-op\" word family, like hop and top?","a":"mop","w":["mat","mud","map"],"h":"Look for the word that ends with the same -op sound.","e":"Words in the -op family end with -op. \"Mop\" fits with hop and top."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-ing\" word family, like ring and king?","a":"sing","w":["sock","sand","seed"],"h":"Find the word that ends with the -ing sound.","e":"Words in the -ing family end with -ing. \"Sing\" fits with ring and king."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"rabbit\"?","a":"2","w":["1","3","4"],"h":"Clap once for each part as you say rab-bit.","e":"Syllables are the beats in a word. \"Rabbit\" has two: rab-bit."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"cat\"?","a":"1","w":["2","3","0"],"h":"Clap the word out loud and count your claps.","e":"Syllables are the beats in a word. \"Cat\" has just one beat."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"banana\"?","a":"3","w":["2","1","4"],"h":"Clap for each part as you say the word slowly.","e":"Syllables are the beats in a word. \"Banana\" has three: ba-na-na."},{"p":"Which sight word finishes the sentence? Read: \"I ___ happy.\"","a":"am","w":["is","are","be"],"h":"Try saying the whole sentence with each word.","e":"Sight words are common words we learn to read quickly. \"I am happy\" is the correct way to say it."},{"p":"Which sight word finishes the sentence? Read: \"We ___ to school.\"","a":"go","w":["goes","going","gone"],"h":"Say the sentence out loud with each choice and pick the one that sounds right.","e":"Sight words are common words we read often. \"We go to school\" is correct."},{"p":"Which word does NOT rhyme with \"pig\"?","a":"pin","w":["big","dig","wig"],"h":"Say each word and listen for the -ig ending.","e":"Rhyming words share the same ending sound. Big, dig, and wig end in -ig, but \"pin\" does not."},{"p":"Read: \"The frog sat on a log.\" Which word rhymes with \"frog\"?","a":"dog","w":["fish","jump","tree"],"h":"Say \"frog\" and listen to its ending sound.","e":"Rhyming words end the same way. \"Frog\" and \"dog\" both end with the -og sound."},{"p":"Which word rhymes with \"run\"?","a":"sun","w":["rug","red","ran"],"h":"Say each word out loud and listen to the ending part after the first sound.","e":"Rhyming words have the same ending sound; \"run\" and \"sun\" both end with the -un sound."},{"p":"Which word does NOT rhyme with \"sock\"?","a":"sick","w":["rock","lock","dock"],"h":"Three of these end the same way. Listen for the one that sounds different.","e":"Rhyming words share an ending sound; rock, lock, and dock all end in -ock, but \"sick\" ends in -ick."},{"p":"Which word does NOT rhyme with \"bake\"?","a":"book","w":["cake","lake","make"],"h":"Say them slowly and find the one whose ending does not match the others.","e":"Rhyming words end the same; cake, lake, and make rhyme with -ake, but \"book\" does not."},{"p":"Which word begins with the same sound as \"fish\"?","a":"fan","w":["van","dish","sock"],"h":"Listen to the very first sound your mouth makes, not the rest of the word.","e":"Beginning sounds match at the start; \"fish\" and \"fan\" both start with the /f/ sound."},{"p":"Which word begins with the same sound as \"top\"?","a":"toy","w":["day","mop","stop"],"h":"Focus only on the first little sound, not what the word rhymes with.","e":"Beginning sounds are the first sound in a word; \"top\" and \"toy\" both start with /t/."},{"p":"Which word begins with the same sound as \"ship\"?","a":"shoe","w":["sun","chip","sock"],"h":"Two letters work together to make one first sound here. Listen closely.","e":"Beginning sounds can be made by two letters; \"ship\" and \"shoe\" both start with the /sh/ sound."},{"p":"Which word ends with the same sound as \"moon\"?","a":"rain","w":["moo","mop","mud"],"h":"Listen to the last sound you hear, not the first sound.","e":"Ending sounds match at the end of a word; \"moon\" and \"rain\" both end with the /n/ sound."},{"p":"Which word ends with the same sound as \"bus\"?","a":"grass","w":["buzz","bug","sun"],"h":"Say the words slowly and listen to the very last sound.","e":"Ending sounds are the last sound in a word; \"bus\" and \"grass\" both end with the /s/ sound."},{"p":"Which word ends with the same sound as \"bed\"?","a":"road","w":["bet","bell","boy"],"h":"Listen for the final sound, not the letter the word starts with.","e":"Ending sounds match at the end; \"bed\" and \"road\" both end with the /d/ sound."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-un\" word family, like fun and run?","a":"bun","w":["bug","but","bat"],"h":"Word family words share the same ending chunk. Look for -un.","e":"A word family shares the same ending; \"bun\" ends in -un, just like fun and run."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-ell\" word family, like bell and well?","a":"shell","w":["belt","ball","bird"],"h":"Find the word that ends with the same chunk, -ell.","e":"A word family shares the same ending chunk; \"shell\" ends in -ell, like bell and well."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-ig\" word family, like pig and wig?","a":"dig","w":["dog","dip","den"],"h":"Look for the word that ends with the -ig chunk, not just the same first letter.","e":"A word family shares the same ending; \"dig\" ends in -ig, like pig and wig."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"butterfly\"?","a":"3","w":["2","4","1"],"h":"Clap once for each part as you say the word slowly: but-ter-fly.","e":"Syllables are the beats in a word; \"butterfly\" has three parts: but-ter-fly."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"pencil\"?","a":"2","w":["1","3","4"],"h":"Put your hand under your chin and count how many times it drops.","e":"Syllables are word parts; \"pencil\" has two: pen-cil."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"watermelon\"?","a":"4","w":["3","2","5"],"h":"Say it slowly and clap each beat: wa-ter-mel-on.","e":"Syllables are the beats in a word; \"watermelon\" has four parts: wa-ter-mel-on."},{"p":"Which sight word finishes the sentence? Read: \"___ you like to play?\"","a":"Do","w":["Is","Am","Are"],"h":"Say the whole question out loud and pick the word that sounds right.","e":"Sight words are common words we know by sight; \"Do you like to play?\" fits here."},{"p":"Which sight word finishes the sentence? Read: \"She ___ a red hat.\"","a":"has","w":["have","is","was"],"h":"Try reading the sentence with each word and listen for the one that fits.","e":"Sight words help sentences make sense; \"She has a red hat\" is correct."},{"p":"Read: \"Ken has a red pen.\" Which word rhymes with \"Ken\"?","a":"pen","w":["red","has","big"],"h":"Find the word in the sentence that ends with the same sound as \"Ken.\"","e":"Rhyming words share an ending sound; \"Ken\" and \"pen\" both end with the -en sound."},{"p":"Which word rhymes with \"tree\"?","a":"knee","w":["tray","truck","tent"],"h":"Listen for the ending sound, not the first letter.","e":"Rhyming words share the same ending sound. Tree and knee both end with the -ee sound."},{"p":"Read: \"The cake is by the lake.\" Which word rhymes with \"cake\"?","a":"lake","w":["road","cup","sun"],"h":"Find a word in the sentence that ends the same way as cake.","e":"Rhyming words end with the same sound. Cake and lake both end with -ake."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-ake\" word family, like cake and lake?","a":"rake","w":["rock","rain","rug"],"h":"The word must end with the same -ake sound.","e":"A word family shares the same ending. Rake ends with -ake, just like cake and lake."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-all\" word family, like ball and tall?","a":"wall","w":["well","wet","win"],"h":"Say each word and listen for the -all ending.","e":"A word family shares the same ending sound. Wall ends with -all, like ball and tall."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-ill\" word family, like hill and fill?","a":"pill","w":["pale","pin","pool"],"h":"The right word ends with the same -ill sound.","e":"Words in a family end the same way. Pill ends with -ill, like hill and fill."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-og\" word family, like dog and log?","a":"hog","w":["hop","hot","house"],"h":"Listen for the -og ending sound at the end of the word.","e":"A word family shares an ending. Hog ends with -og, just like dog and log."},{"p":"Which word is in the \"-en\" word family, like hen and pen?","a":"ten","w":["tan","tin","top"],"h":"Say each word and listen for the -en ending.","e":"Words in the same family end alike. Ten ends with -en, like hen and pen."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"elephant\"?","a":"3","w":["2","4","1"],"h":"Clap once for each part: el-e-phant.","e":"Syllables are the beats you clap in a word. Elephant has three: el-e-phant."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"computer\"?","a":"3","w":["2","4","1"],"h":"Clap it out: com-pu-ter.","e":"Each clap is one syllable. Computer has three parts: com-pu-ter."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"apple\"?","a":"2","w":["1","3","4"],"h":"Clap the word: ap-ple.","e":"Syllables are the beats in a word. Apple has two: ap-ple."},{"p":"How many syllables (word parts) are in \"dinosaur\"?","a":"3","w":["2","4","1"],"h":"Clap for each beat: di-no-saur.","e":"Every clap is a syllable. Dinosaur has three: di-no-saur."},{"p":"Which word begins with the same sound as \"moon\"?","a":"milk","w":["nut","sun","leaf"],"h":"Say each word slowly and listen to the very first sound.","e":"Beginning sounds are the first sounds you hear. Moon and milk both start with the /m/ sound."},{"p":"Which word begins with the same sound as \"rain\"?","a":"rope","w":["wagon","leaf","nose"],"h":"Listen closely to the first sound, not the middle.","e":"Beginning sounds come first in a word. Rain and rope both start with the /r/ sound."},{"p":"Which word ends with the same sound as \"boat\"?","a":"kite","w":["bone","bike","ball"],"h":"Listen to the last sound, not the first letter.","e":"Ending sounds are the last sounds you hear. Boat and kite both end with the /t/ sound."},{"p":"Which word ends with the same sound as \"fish\"?","a":"dish","w":["fin","fan","fun"],"h":"Say each word and listen to the very last sound.","e":"Ending sounds come last in a word. Fish and dish both end with the /sh/ sound."},{"p":"Which sight word finishes the sentence? Read: \"He ___ my best friend.\"","a":"is","w":["are","am","be"],"h":"Which little word sounds right after \"He\"?","e":"Sight words are common words we know by heart. \"He is\" is the correct way to say it."},{"p":"Which sight word finishes the sentence? Read: \"They ___ playing outside.\"","a":"are","w":["is","am","be"],"h":"Which little word sounds right after \"They\"?","e":"Sight words are words we read quickly by sight. \"They are\" is the correct match."}],"m.11.explog":[{"p":"Evaluate the logarithm: log_2(8).","a":"3","w":["4","16","2"],"h":"Ask yourself: 2 raised to what power equals 8?","e":"By the definition of a logarithm, log_2(8) asks for the exponent on base 2 that yields 8; since 2^3 = 8, the value is 3."},{"p":"Evaluate log_5(1).","a":"0","w":["1","5","1/5"],"h":"What exponent on any positive base produces a result of 1?","e":"By the zero-exponent property, b^0 = 1 for any valid base, so log_b(1) = 0 for every base b."},{"p":"Which single expression is equivalent to log_b(M) + log_b(N)?","a":"log_b(MN)","w":["log_b(M + N)","log_b(M/N)","(log_b M)(log_b N)"],"h":"Recall which arithmetic operation on the inputs corresponds to adding logarithms.","e":"The product rule for logarithms states log_b(M) + log_b(N) = log_b(MN)."},{"p":"Which single expression is equivalent to log_b(M) - log_b(N)?","a":"log_b(M/N)","w":["log_b(M - N)","log_b(MN)","(log_b M)/(log_b N)"],"h":"Subtracting logarithms corresponds to a specific operation on the arguments.","e":"The quotient rule for logarithms states log_b(M) - log_b(N) = log_b(M/N)."},{"p":"Rewrite log(x^3) using a logarithm rule so the exponent becomes a coefficient.","a":"3 log(x)","w":["(log x)^3","log(3x)","3 + log(x)"],"h":"There is a rule that lets an exponent inside a log move out in front.","e":"The power rule for logarithms states log_b(M^p) = p·log_b(M), so log(x^3) = 3 log(x)."},{"p":"Solve for x: 2^x = 32.","a":"5","w":["6","16","4"],"h":"Express 32 as a power of 2, then match exponents.","e":"Writing 32 = 2^5 and equating exponents (since the exponential function is one-to-one) gives x = 5."},{"p":"Rewrite the exponential statement 3^4 = 81 in logarithmic form.","a":"log_3(81) = 4","w":["log_4(81) = 3","log_81(3) = 4","log_3(4) = 81"],"h":"In b^e = n, the base of the exponent becomes the base of the log and the exponent becomes the output.","e":"By the definition converting between forms, b^e = n is equivalent to log_b(n) = e, so 3^4 = 81 becomes log_3(81) = 4."},{"p":"A town's population is 500 and grows 8% each year. Which function models the population P after t years?","a":"P = 500(1.08)^t","w":["P = 500(0.08)^t","P = 500(0.92)^t","P = 500(8)^t"],"h":"For growth, the base is 1 plus the decimal rate of increase.","e":"An exponential growth model uses base (1 + r); with r = 0.08 the model is P = 500(1.08)^t."},{"p":"A machine worth $1200 loses 15% of its value each year. Which function models its value V after t years?","a":"V = 1200(0.85)^t","w":["V = 1200(1.15)^t","V = 1200(0.15)^t","V = 1200(15)^t"],"h":"For decay, the base is 1 minus the decimal rate of decrease.","e":"An exponential decay model uses base (1 - r); with r = 0.15 the base is 0.85, giving V = 1200(0.85)^t."},{"p":"You invest $2000 at an annual rate of 6% compounded quarterly. Using A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt), which expression gives the amount after t years?","a":"2000(1 + 0.06/4)^(4t)","w":["2000(1 + 0.06)^(t)","2000(1 + 0.06/4)^(t)","2000(1 + 0.06/12)^(12t)"],"h":"Quarterly means n = 4 compounding periods per year, appearing both inside and in the exponent.","e":"In the compound interest formula A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt), quarterly compounding sets n = 4, giving 2000(1 + 0.06/4)^(4t)."},{"p":"A radioactive sample of 80 grams has a half-life of 5 years. How much remains after 15 years?","a":"10 grams","w":["20 grams","40 grams","5 grams"],"h":"Determine how many half-life periods fit into 15 years, then halve repeatedly.","e":"Fifteen years is three half-lives (15/5 = 3), so the amount halves three times: 80 to 40 to 20 to 10 grams."},{"p":"Solve for x: log_3(x) = 2.","a":"9","w":["6","8","1.5"],"h":"Rewrite the equation in exponential form using the base of the logarithm.","e":"By the definition of a logarithm, log_3(x) = 2 means x = 3^2 = 9."},{"p":"Evaluate log_10(1000).","a":"3","w":["2","100","30"],"h":"Ask what power of 10 produces 1000.","e":"Since the common logarithm has base 10 and 10^3 = 1000, log_10(1000) = 3."},{"p":"Evaluate ln(e^5).","a":"5","w":["e^5","1","0"],"h":"The natural log and base-e exponential are inverse functions.","e":"Because ln is the logarithm base e, the inverse property ln(e^x) = x gives ln(e^5) = 5."},{"p":"Solve for x: 10^x = 0.01.","a":"-2","w":["2","-1","-0.01"],"h":"Write 0.01 as a power of 10 with a negative exponent.","e":"Since 0.01 = 1/100 = 10^(-2), equating exponents gives x = -2."},{"p":"Evaluate log_2(1/8).","a":"-3","w":["3","1/3","-1/3"],"h":"Express 1/8 as a power of 2 using a negative exponent.","e":"Since 1/8 = 2^(-3), by the definition of a logarithm log_2(1/8) = -3."},{"p":"Which formula represents an amount growing under continuous compounding at rate r for time t?","a":"A = Pe^(rt)","w":["A = P(1 + r)^t","A = P(1 + r/n)^(nt)","A = P + rt"],"h":"Continuous compounding involves the natural base e in the exponent.","e":"The continuous compound interest model is A = Pe^(rt), using Euler's number e as the base."},{"p":"Using the change-of-base formula, which expression equals log_2(7)?","a":"ln(7)/ln(2)","w":["ln(2)/ln(7)","ln(7/2)","ln(7)·ln(2)"],"h":"The change-of-base formula puts the argument's log over the base's log.","e":"The change-of-base formula gives log_b(a) = ln(a)/ln(b), so log_2(7) = ln(7)/ln(2)."},{"p":"Solve for x: 5^(x+1) = 125.","a":"x = 2","w":["x = 3","x = 1","x = 25"],"h":"Rewrite 125 as a power of 5, then set the exponents equal.","e":"By the one-to-one property of exponentials, 5^(x+1) = 5^3 gives x + 1 = 3, so x = 2."},{"p":"Condense 2·log(x) + log(y) into a single logarithm.","a":"log(x^2·y)","w":["log(2·x·y)","log(x^2 + y)","log((x·y)^2)"],"h":"Use the power rule to turn the coefficient into an exponent, then combine a sum of logs.","e":"The power rule makes 2·log(x) = log(x^2), and the product rule combines the sum into log(x^2·y)."},{"p":"Expand log_b(x^2·y / z) as a sum and difference of logarithms.","a":"2·log_b(x) + log_b(y) − log_b(z)","w":["2·log_b(x) + log_b(y) + log_b(z)","2·log_b(x) · log_b(y) − log_b(z)","2·[log_b(x) + log_b(y) − log_b(z)]"],"h":"Products become sums, quotients become differences, and exponents become coefficients.","e":"Applying the product, quotient, and power rules gives 2·log_b(x) + log_b(y) − log_b(z)."},{"p":"You invest $3000 at 5% interest compounded annually. What is the account value after 3 years?","a":"$3472.88","w":["$3450.00","$3157.50","$3600.00"],"h":"Compounding annually multiplies the balance by (1 + r) once each year.","e":"Using A = P(1 + r)^t, A = 3000(1.05)^3 ≈ $3472.88; simple interest would give only $3450."},{"p":"A radioactive substance has a half-life of 12 hours. What fraction of the original amount remains after 2 days?","a":"1/16","w":["1/8","1/4","1/32"],"h":"Divide the elapsed time by the half-life to count how many halvings occur.","e":"Two days is 48 hours = 4 half-lives, so the remaining fraction is (1/2)^4 = 1/16."},{"p":"Solve for x: log_2(x) + log_2(x − 2) = 3.","a":"x = 4","w":["x = −2","x = 4 and x = −2","x = 6"],"h":"Combine the two logs with the product rule, rewrite in exponential form, then check the domain.","e":"The product rule gives log_2[x(x−2)] = 3, so x^2 − 2x − 8 = 0; only x = 4 is valid since x = −2 is outside the domain."},{"p":"A bacteria culture starts with 200 cells and doubles every 3 hours. How many cells are present after 12 hours?","a":"3200","w":["1600","800","2400"],"h":"Count the number of doubling periods by dividing the total time by the doubling time.","e":"There are 12 ÷ 3 = 4 doublings, so the population is 200·2^4 = 3200."},{"p":"Solve for x exactly: e^(2x) = 7.","a":"x = (ln 7)/2","w":["x = ln(7/2)","x = 2·ln 7","x = ln 7 − ln 2"],"h":"Take the natural log of both sides to undo the base e, then isolate x.","e":"Since ln and e are inverses, 2x = ln 7, so x = (ln 7)/2."},{"p":"Solve for x exactly using logarithms: 4^x = 20.","a":"x = log(20)/log(4)","w":["x = log(20) − log(4)","x = log(20/4)","x = log(4)/log(20)"],"h":"Take the log of both sides and apply the power rule to bring x down.","e":"Taking logs gives x·log(4) = log(20), so x = log(20)/log(4) by the power rule (change-of-base form)."},{"p":"Evaluate log_9(3).","a":"1/2","w":["2","3","1/3"],"h":"Ask what power of 9 produces 3.","e":"Since 9^(1/2) = 3, log_9(3) = 1/2."},{"p":"Evaluate log_8(4).","a":"2/3","w":["1/2","3/2","2"],"h":"Write both 8 and 4 as powers of the same base, 2.","e":"Since 8^(2/3) = (2^3)^(2/3) = 2^2 = 4, log_8(4) = 2/3."},{"p":"Solve for x: 3^(2x) = 3^(x+4).","a":"x = 4","w":["x = −4","x = 2","x = 4/3"],"h":"With equal bases on both sides, the exponents must be equal.","e":"By the one-to-one property, 2x = x + 4, so x = 4."},{"p":"A sample decays according to N = 500·e^(−0.2t), where t is in hours. After how long will exactly half the sample remain?","a":"t = (ln 2)/0.2 ≈ 3.47 hours","w":["t = (ln 0.5)/0.2 ≈ −3.47 hours","t = ln(250)/0.2 ≈ 27.6 hours","t = 0.2/(ln 2) ≈ 0.29 hours"],"h":"Set N equal to half the starting amount, divide out 500, then take a natural log.","e":"Setting e^(−0.2t) = 0.5 gives −0.2t = ln 0.5, so t = (ln 2)/0.2 ≈ 3.47 hours."},{"p":"The pH of a solution is defined by pH = −log[H+]. If [H+] = 1×10^(−4) mol/L, what is the pH?","a":"4","w":["−4","0.0001","10"],"h":"Substitute into the definition and evaluate the base-10 log of a power of ten.","e":"pH = −log(10^(−4)) = −(−4) = 4."},{"p":"Solve for t exactly: 1000·(1.08)^t = 2000.","a":"t = log(2)/log(1.08)","w":["t = log(2000)/log(1.08)","t = 2/1.08","t = log(1.08)/log(2)"],"h":"Divide both sides by 1000 first, then take the log of both sides and apply the power rule.","e":"Dividing gives (1.08)^t = 2, so t·log(1.08) = log(2) and t = log(2)/log(1.08)."},{"p":"Which single logarithm is equivalent to log_b(x) − 3·log_b(y)?","a":"log_b(x / y^3)","w":["log_b(x − y^3)","log_b((x/y)^3)","log_b(x / 3y)"],"h":"Turn the coefficient into an exponent first, then a difference of logs becomes a quotient.","e":"The power rule gives 3·log_b(y) = log_b(y^3), and the quotient rule yields log_b(x/y^3)."},{"p":"Earthquake magnitude is given by R = log(I/I_0), where I_0 is a reference intensity. If an earthquake has intensity I = 1000·I_0, what is its magnitude R?","a":"3","w":["1000","30","6"],"h":"Substitute the intensity ratio and evaluate the base-10 log of a power of ten.","e":"R = log(1000·I_0 / I_0) = log(1000) = log(10^3) = 3."},{"p":"A car depreciates continuously at 12% per year, modeled by V = 25000·e^(−0.12t). What is its value after 5 years?","a":"≈ $13,720","w":["≈ $10,000","≈ $13,190","≈ $14,000"],"h":"Continuous decay uses e raised to a negative exponent; substitute t = 5 and evaluate.","e":"V = 25000·e^(−0.12·5) = 25000·e^(−0.6) ≈ $13,720; the discrete model 25000·(0.88)^5 ≈ $13,190 is a common mix-up."},{"p":"A cup of coffee cools according to Newton's Law of Cooling: T = 70 + 120·e^(−0.05t), where T is in °F and t is in minutes. What is the temperature after 20 minutes?","a":"About 114°F","w":["About 190°F","About 70°F","About 44°F"],"h":"Substitute t = 20 and evaluate e^(−1) ≈ 0.368 before combining terms.","e":"Newton's Law of Cooling: evaluate 120·e^(−0.05·20) = 120·e^(−1) ≈ 44.2, then add the ambient temperature 70 to get about 114°F."},{"p":"Sound intensity level is β = 10·log(I/I_0) decibels, where I_0 = 10^(−12) W/m². A jackhammer produces I = 10^(−5) W/m². What is its sound level β?","a":"70 dB","w":["7 dB","120 dB","−70 dB"],"h":"Divide the intensities first; the ratio is a power of 10 whose log is the exponent.","e":"Using the logarithmic decibel scale, I/I_0 = 10^(−5)/10^(−12) = 10^7, so β = 10·log(10^7) = 10·7 = 70 dB."},{"p":"An investment grows continuously at 4% per year under A = P·e^(0.04t). Which expression gives the doubling time t in years?","a":"t = ln(2)/0.04","w":["t = ln(2)/ln(0.04)","t = log(2)/2","t = 0.04/ln(2)"],"h":"Set A = 2P, divide by P, then take the natural log of both sides.","e":"Doubling requires 2 = e^(0.04t); taking ln gives ln 2 = 0.04t, so t = ln(2)/0.04 (continuous-growth doubling time)."},{"p":"A colony of insects triples every 10 years under continuous growth P = P_0·e^(rt). What is the growth rate r?","a":"r = ln(3)/10","w":["r = 10/ln(3)","r = ln(3)·10","r = ln(1/3)/10"],"h":"Set P = 3P_0, cancel P_0, and isolate r using the natural log.","e":"From 3 = e^(10r), taking ln gives ln 3 = 10r, so r = ln(3)/10 for continuous exponential growth."},{"p":"A deposit earns 8% nominal annual interest compounded continuously. What is the effective annual yield (APY)?","a":"About 8.33%","w":["Exactly 8.00%","About 8.16%","About 8.24%"],"h":"For continuous compounding the effective yield is e^r − 1, not the nominal rate.","e":"Continuous compounding gives APY = e^(0.08) − 1 ≈ 1.0833 − 1 = 0.0833, or about 8.33%."},{"p":"Solve for x: log_2(x) + log_2(x + 6) = 4.","a":"x = 2","w":["x = −8","x = 2 or x = −8","x = 8"],"h":"Combine the two logs with the product rule, convert to exponential form, then check the domain.","e":"The product rule gives log_2[x(x+6)] = 4, so x² + 6x − 16 = 0, giving x = 2 or −8; −8 is rejected since a log's argument must be positive, leaving x = 2."},{"p":"Which value is closest to log_3(50)?","a":"About 3.56","w":["About 1.70","About 2.34","About 5.61"],"h":"Since 3^3 = 27 and 3^4 = 81, the value lies between 3 and 4; use change of base to refine.","e":"By the change-of-base formula, log_3(50) = ln(50)/ln(3) ≈ 3.912/1.099 ≈ 3.56."},{"p":"Carbon-14 has a half-life of 5730 years. A wooden artifact retains 25% of its original carbon-14. Approximately how old is it?","a":"11,460 years","w":["5,730 years","2,865 years","17,190 years"],"h":"Determine how many successive halvings reduce 100% to 25%.","e":"25% = (1/2)², which is two half-lives, so the age is 2 × 5730 = 11,460 years (half-life decay)."},{"p":"On the Richter scale R = log(I/I_0), one earthquake measures 7 and another measures 5. How many times greater is the intensity of the magnitude-7 quake?","a":"100 times","w":["2 times","20 times","1000 times"],"h":"A difference in magnitude corresponds to a power of 10 in intensity, not a simple subtraction.","e":"The intensity ratio is 10^(7−5) = 10² = 100, because each Richter unit represents a tenfold increase in intensity."},{"p":"A solution has pH = 3, where pH = −log[H+]. What is the hydrogen ion concentration [H+]?","a":"1×10^(−3) mol/L","w":["1×10^(3) mol/L","1×10^(−11) mol/L","3 mol/L"],"h":"Invert the definition: solve −log[H+] = 3 for [H+].","e":"From pH = −log[H+], we get log[H+] = −3, so [H+] = 10^(−3) mol/L."},{"p":"For which value of x is log_5(x − 3) undefined (not a real number)?","a":"x = 2","w":["x = 4","x = 8","x = 28"],"h":"A logarithm is only defined when its argument is strictly positive.","e":"When x = 2, the argument x − 3 = −1 is negative, so log_5(−1) is undefined; the other values give positive arguments."},{"p":"Solve for x exactly: 3·e^(x/2) = 24.","a":"x = 2·ln(8)","w":["x = ln(24)","x = ln(8)","x = ln(21)"],"h":"Divide both sides by 3 to isolate the exponential before taking the natural log.","e":"Dividing gives e^(x/2) = 8, so x/2 = ln 8 and x = 2·ln 8 (isolate the exponential, then apply ln)."},{"p":"How long, to the nearest year, does it take $5000 to grow to $8000 at 6% interest compounded annually?","a":"About 8 years","w":["About 5 years","About 10 years","About 13 years"],"h":"Set 5000(1.06)^t = 8000, divide, then take the log of both sides.","e":"From (1.06)^t = 1.6, t = ln(1.6)/ln(1.06) ≈ 0.470/0.0583 ≈ 8.1, so about 8 years."},{"p":"A radioactive isotope decays as N = N_0·e^(−0.087t), where t is in days. What is its half-life, to the nearest day?","a":"About 8 days","w":["About 12 days","About 4 days","About 1 day"],"h":"The half-life relates to the decay constant by half-life = ln(2)/k.","e":"Half-life = ln(2)/0.087 ≈ 0.693/0.087 ≈ 7.97, so about 8 days."},{"p":"Fully expand log_b(√x / y³) as a sum and/or difference of logarithms.","a":"(1/2)·log_b(x) − 3·log_b(y)","w":["2·log_b(x) − 3·log_b(y)","(1/2)·log_b(x) + 3·log_b(y)","(1/2)·[log_b(x) − 3·log_b(y)]"],"h":"Rewrite the square root as an exponent of 1/2, then apply the quotient and power rules.","e":"Since √x = x^(1/2), the quotient and power rules give (1/2)·log_b(x) − 3·log_b(y)."},{"p":"Solve for x exactly: 2^x = 3^(x − 1).","a":"x = ln(3)/(ln 3 − ln 2)","w":["x = ln(3)/(ln 2 − ln 3)","x = ln(2)/(ln 3 − ln 2)","x = (ln 3 − ln 2)/ln 3"],"h":"Take the natural log of both sides, expand, then collect all x-terms on one side.","e":"ln gives x·ln 2 = (x−1)·ln 3; collecting terms yields x(ln 2 − ln 3) = −ln 3, so x = ln(3)/(ln 3 − ln 2)."},{"p":"A drug's blood concentration is C = 50·e^(−0.3t) mg/L, where t is in hours. After how long does the concentration fall to 10 mg/L?","a":"About 5.4 hours","w":["About 1.6 hours","About 3.0 hours","About 16 hours"],"h":"Divide to isolate the exponential, then take the natural log; watch the negative sign.","e":"From 0.2 = e^(−0.3t), t = ln(0.2)/(−0.3) ≈ (−1.609)/(−0.3) ≈ 5.4 hours (exponential decay)."},{"p":"Simplify using the inverse relationship between exponentials and logarithms: 5^(log_5(20)).","a":"20","w":["5","100","log_5(20)"],"h":"The functions b^x and log_b(x) undo each other.","e":"Because exponentiation base 5 and log base 5 are inverse functions, 5^(log_5(20)) = 20."}],"e.5.figlang":[{"p":"Which sentence is a simile?","a":"Her smile was as bright as the sun.","w":["Her smile lit up the whole room.","She gave a great big happy smile.","The sun was very bright all day."],"h":"A simile compares two things using the words \"like\" or \"as.\"","e":"A simile compares two things using \"like\" or \"as,\" so \"as bright as the sun\" is a simile."},{"p":"Which sentence is a metaphor?","a":"My brother is a couch potato on Saturdays.","w":["My brother sits like a lazy old cat.","My brother naps for hours on Saturdays.","My brother is as slow as a sleepy snail."],"h":"A metaphor says one thing IS another, without using \"like\" or \"as.\"","e":"A metaphor calls one thing another thing directly, so calling him a \"couch potato\" is a metaphor."},{"p":"Read: \"When Mia forgot her lines in the play, her teacher smiled and said, 'Break a leg next time!'\" What does \"break a leg\" mean?","a":"Good luck","w":["Fall down hard","Hurt your leg","Run away fast"],"h":"Idioms do not mean what the words literally say.","e":"\"Break a leg\" is an idiom, a phrase whose real meaning (good luck) is different from its words."},{"p":"Which sentence uses personification?","a":"The wind whispered softly through the trees.","w":["The wind blew hard through the trees.","The wind felt as cold as ice.","The wind knocked over the trash can."],"h":"Personification gives human actions or feelings to something that is not human.","e":"Personification gives human actions to non-human things, and only wind cannot really \"whisper.\""},{"p":"Which sentence uses alliteration?","a":"Silly Sally sang seven sweet songs.","w":["Sally sang a happy little tune.","The girl sang loudly all day long.","Sally really loves to make music."],"h":"Alliteration repeats the same beginning sound in nearby words.","e":"Alliteration repeats the same starting sound, and here many words begin with the \"s\" sound."},{"p":"Which sentence is a hyperbole?","a":"I'm so hungry I could eat a whole cow.","w":["I'm feeling really hungry for lunch.","I ate a big sandwich at lunchtime.","My stomach growled loudly at lunch."],"h":"A hyperbole is a huge exaggeration that is not meant to be believed.","e":"A hyperbole is an extreme exaggeration, and no one could really eat a whole cow."},{"p":"Read: \"During recess, Jake raced across the field. He was as fast as a cheetah chasing its dinner.\" What kind of figurative language is \"as fast as a cheetah\"?","a":"Simile","w":["Metaphor","Idiom","Hyperbole"],"h":"Look for the comparing words \"like\" or \"as.\"","e":"A simile compares two things with \"like\" or \"as,\" so \"as fast as a cheetah\" is a simile."},{"p":"Read: \"Mom laughed and said, 'The classroom was a zoo before the teacher arrived.'\" What does this metaphor mean?","a":"The classroom was wild and noisy","w":["The classroom had real animals","The class took a trip to the zoo","The classroom was quiet and calm"],"h":"Think about what a zoo is like, but remember two things are being compared.","e":"A metaphor compares two things directly, so calling the room a \"zoo\" means it was wild and noisy."},{"p":"Read: \"Dad looked outside and said, 'It's raining cats and dogs, so grab your umbrella!'\" What does \"raining cats and dogs\" mean?","a":"It is raining very hard","w":["Pets are falling from the sky","It is only lightly sprinkling","Animals are outside playing"],"h":"Idioms have a meaning that is different from the actual words.","e":"\"Raining cats and dogs\" is an idiom that really means it is raining very hard."},{"p":"Which sentence gives human actions to something that is not human?","a":"The old car coughed and groaned up the hill.","w":["The old car was very slow on the hill.","The old car looked just like a turtle.","The old car really needed new tires."],"h":"Personification lets objects act like people.","e":"Personification gives human actions to objects, and a car cannot really \"cough and groan.\""},{"p":"Read: \"The bacon went sizzle in the hot pan while Mom made breakfast.\" Which word is onomatopoeia?","a":"Sizzle","w":["Bacon","Breakfast","Hot"],"h":"Which word sounds like the noise it describes?","e":"Onomatopoeia names a sound, and \"sizzle\" sounds like the noise of frying bacon."},{"p":"Read: \"After the game, Ben said, 'I've told you a million times to pass the ball!'\" Why is this a hyperbole?","a":"A million is a huge exaggeration","w":["Ben really counted to a million","Ben passed the ball a million times","Ben was speaking very quietly"],"h":"Hyperbole stretches the truth in a big way.","e":"A hyperbole is an extreme exaggeration, and Ben did not truly say it a million times."},{"p":"Which sentence is a simile, not a metaphor?","a":"The pillow felt like a fluffy cloud.","w":["The pillow was a soft fluffy cloud.","The pillow was white and very soft.","The cloud floated high in the sky."],"h":"A simile uses the word \"like\" or \"as\" to compare two things.","e":"A simile compares with \"like\" or \"as,\" so \"felt like a fluffy cloud\" is a simile, not a metaphor."},{"p":"Which word is an example of onomatopoeia?","a":"Splash","w":["Water","Wet","Puddle"],"h":"Choose the word that names an actual sound.","e":"Onomatopoeia names a sound, and \"splash\" sounds like water when you jump in it."},{"p":"Read: \"When Leo finally understood the math problem, he grinned and said, 'A light bulb went off in my head!'\" What does this idiom mean?","a":"He suddenly got a great idea","w":["A real light bulb turned on","His head began to hurt badly","He walked over to shut off the lights"],"h":"This idiom is about thinking, not about real light bulbs.","e":"\"A light bulb went off\" is an idiom that means someone suddenly understood or got an idea."},{"p":"What kind of figurative language is used in this sentence? \"The stars were tiny diamonds scattered across the dark sky.\"","a":"Metaphor, because it says the stars ARE diamonds","w":["Simile, because it compares the stars using \"as\"","Hyperbole, because it exaggerates how many stars there are","Onomatopoeia, because \"scattered\" is a sound word"],"h":"Look closely at how the stars and diamonds are compared. Do you see the words \"like\" or \"as\"?","e":"This is a metaphor because it says the stars ARE diamonds directly, without using \"like\" or \"as.\""},{"p":"Read: \"When his little sister worried about her spelling test, Sam smiled and said, 'Don't stress, this test is a piece of cake!'\" What does \"a piece of cake\" mean?","a":"It is very easy to do","w":["It is a yummy dessert to share","It is going to be really messy","It will take a very long time"],"h":"Think about why Sam is trying to make his worried sister feel better.","e":"\"A piece of cake\" is an idiom that means something is very easy."},{"p":"Read: \"After a long day at the beach, Grandpa yawned and said, 'I'm going to hit the hay.'\" What does \"hit the hay\" mean?","a":"To go to bed and fall asleep","w":["To punch a big bale of straw","To go outside and feed the horses","To sweep up the dusty barn"],"h":"Grandpa is yawning after a long, tiring day at the beach.","e":"\"Hit the hay\" is an idiom that means to go to sleep."},{"p":"Which sentence is NOT a simile?","a":"I would really like a slice of pizza for lunch.","w":["The puppy is as soft as a cotton ball.","My backpack felt as heavy as a big rock.","She sang like a happy little bird."],"h":"A simile compares two different things using \"like\" or \"as.\" Does every sentence actually compare two things?","e":"A simile compares two things, but \"I would like a slice of pizza\" uses \"like\" to mean \"want,\" so it is not a simile."},{"p":"Which tongue twister uses alliteration?","a":"Silly Sally sold seven small seashells.","w":["The red truck drove down the road.","Peter ate a sweet purple grape.","My lazy cat likes to nap all day."],"h":"Alliteration repeats the same beginning sound in words that are close together.","e":"Alliteration is when nearby words start with the same sound, like the \"s\" in \"Silly Sally sold seven small seashells.\""},{"p":"Read: \"Maria opened her lunchbox and said, 'This sandwich is so big I'll never finish it in a hundred years!'\" Why is this a hyperbole?","a":"It exaggerates with an impossible amount of time","w":["It compares the sandwich to a year using \"like\"","It gives the sandwich its own human feelings","It copies the sound the sandwich makes"],"h":"Could anyone really take a hundred years to finish a sandwich?","e":"Hyperbole is an extreme exaggeration, and \"a hundred years\" is far too long to ever be true."},{"p":"Read: \"The rain began to fall, and the drops went pitter-patter on the roof all night long.\" Which word is onomatopoeia?","a":"pitter-patter","w":["raindrops","rooftop","nighttime"],"h":"Onomatopoeia is a word that sounds like the noise it names.","e":"\"Pitter-patter\" imitates the sound of falling raindrops, so it is onomatopoeia."},{"p":"Which word best completes the simile \"as quiet as a ___\"?","a":"mouse","w":["thunderstorm","marching band","fire truck"],"h":"A simile compares two things that are alike, so pick something known for being very quiet.","e":"\"As quiet as a mouse\" is a common simile because mice are known for being very quiet."},{"p":"Read: \"When Dad saw my messy bedroom, he laughed and said, 'Your room is a jungle!'\" What does this metaphor mean?","a":"The room is very messy and wild","w":["The room is full of real wild animals","The room has many green leafy plants","The room feels hot and very rainy"],"h":"Dad is reacting to how the messy room looks, not to real animals.","e":"This metaphor calls the room a \"jungle\" to show it is very messy and wild."},{"p":"Read: \"Emma covered her mouth and whispered, 'Oops, I almost spilled the beans about the surprise party!'\" What does \"spill the beans\" mean?","a":"To accidentally reveal a secret","w":["To knock over a can of food","To cook dinner for the whole family","To clean up a big kitchen mess"],"h":"Emma is talking about a surprise party she wants to keep hidden.","e":"\"Spill the beans\" is an idiom that means to give away a secret."},{"p":"Read: \"All night long, the thunder grumbled angrily above our little house.\" What kind of figurative language is this?","a":"Personification","w":["Onomatopoeia","Simile","Hyperbole"],"h":"Grumbling angrily is something a person does, not usually the weather.","e":"Giving the thunder the human action of grumbling angrily makes this personification."},{"p":"Which sentence uses onomatopoeia, NOT alliteration?","a":"The firecracker went boom in the night sky.","w":["Brady baked brown banana bread.","Wendy watched wild waves wash away.","Freddy found five funny green frogs."],"h":"Onomatopoeia is a sound word, while alliteration repeats the same beginning sound.","e":"\"Boom\" imitates a real sound, making it onomatopoeia, while the other sentences just repeat starting sounds."},{"p":"Read: \"Ben stayed home from school because he was feeling under the weather.\" What does \"under the weather\" mean?","a":"Feeling sick or unwell","w":["Standing outside in the rain","Feeling very cold and shivery","Looking up at the gray clouds"],"h":"Ben stayed home from school for a reason people usually do.","e":"\"Under the weather\" is an idiom that means feeling sick."},{"p":"Which sentence is a true simile?","a":"The snow was as white as a fresh marshmallow.","w":["I like to build tall snowmen in winter.","My warm gloves are bright blue and cozy.","The soft snow fell down all afternoon."],"h":"A simile compares two different things using \"like\" or \"as.\"","e":"\"As white as a fresh marshmallow\" compares snow to a marshmallow, so it is a simile."},{"p":"Which sentence is an example of hyperbole?","a":"My backpack weighs a thousand pounds today!","w":["My backpack is a little heavier than yesterday.","My backpack is bright blue with two pockets.","My backpack holds all of my school books."],"h":"Hyperbole is a huge exaggeration that could not really be true.","e":"\"A thousand pounds\" is an impossible exaggeration, so this sentence is hyperbole."},{"p":"These sentences all compare a runner to the wind. Which one is a metaphor?","a":"During the race, Tia was the wind.","w":["During the race, Tia ran like the wind.","During the race, Tia was as fast as the wind.","During the race, Tia moved like the wind blows."],"h":"A metaphor says something IS another thing, without using \"like\" or \"as.\"","e":"\"Tia was the wind\" is a metaphor because it says she IS the wind instead of using \"like\" or \"as.\""},{"p":"Read: \"The night before her big science test, Priya told her friend, 'I can't come to the park - I need to hit the books.'\" What does \"hit the books\" mean?","a":"She needs to study hard for her test.","w":["She wants to throw her books across the room.","She is going to play a fun game with books.","She is angry and wants to hide her books."],"h":"Think about what someone does the night before a big test.","e":"\"Hit the books\" is an idiom that means to study hard."},{"p":"Read: \"Right before his turn in the talent show, Marco whispered, 'I have butterflies in my stomach!'\" What does Marco mean?","a":"He feels nervous and jittery inside.","w":["He ate too many snacks at lunch today.","He is feeling very hungry for dinner.","He caught real butterflies in the yard."],"h":"How do you feel right before performing in front of a crowd?","e":"\"Butterflies in my stomach\" is an idiom for feeling nervous."},{"p":"Read: \"As the kids rushed to rip open their presents, Grandma laughed and said, 'Hold your horses!'\" What does \"hold your horses\" mean?","a":"Slow down and wait a moment.","w":["Go outside and grab the horses.","Hold on to something very tight.","Run to the presents as fast as you can."],"h":"Grandma wants them to do the opposite of hurrying.","e":"\"Hold your horses\" is an idiom that means to be patient and wait."},{"p":"Read: \"At the toy store, Dad looked at the price tag and said, 'Wow, that robot costs an arm and a leg!'\" What does \"costs an arm and a leg\" mean?","a":"It is very expensive.","w":["It is on sale for a great deal.","It comes in two separate pieces.","It is completely free to take home."],"h":"Dad is surprised by the big number on the price tag.","e":"\"Cost an arm and a leg\" is an idiom meaning something is very expensive."},{"p":"Read: \"When Tim asked if he could eat candy for breakfast, his mom laughed and said, 'When pigs fly!'\" What does \"when pigs fly\" mean?","a":"It is never going to happen.","w":["It is going to happen very soon.","Some pigs will visit the farm today.","It already happens every morning."],"h":"Have you ever seen a pig with wings up in the sky?","e":"\"When pigs fly\" is an idiom meaning something will never happen."},{"p":"Read: \"At the family picnic, Aunt Rosa smiled and said, 'My little nephew is a busy bee today!'\" What does this metaphor mean?","a":"He is moving around and staying very busy.","w":["He is slowly turning into a real insect.","He is buzzing very loudly like a bee.","He is feeling scared of the bees outside."],"h":"A bee is always flying from flower to flower without stopping.","e":"Calling someone \"a busy bee\" is a metaphor for being very active and busy."},{"p":"Read: \"Silly Sally sold seven seashells.\" Which repeated beginning sound makes this alliteration?","a":"the \"s\" sound","w":["the \"l\" sound","the \"v\" sound","the \"sh\" sound"],"h":"Say the very first sound of each word out loud.","e":"Alliteration is when nearby words begin with the same sound, here the \"s\" sound."},{"p":"Which word best completes the simile \"as busy as a ___\"?","a":"bee","w":["rock","pillow","cloud"],"h":"Think of a tiny insect that never seems to stop working.","e":"A simile compares two things using \"like\" or \"as\"; \"as busy as a bee\" is a common one."},{"p":"Read: \"The bee went buzz as it flew past our lemonade stand.\" Which word is onomatopoeia?","a":"buzz","w":["flew","past","stand"],"h":"Which word sounds like the actual noise it names?","e":"Onomatopoeia is a word that imitates a sound, like \"buzz.\""},{"p":"Which sentence compares two things by saying one thing IS another (a metaphor)?","a":"The classroom rug was an island of calm during story time.","w":["The classroom rug was as soft as a fluffy cloud.","The classroom rug felt just like a fluffy cloud.","The classroom rug was softer than a fluffy cloud."],"h":"A metaphor does not use the words \"like\" or \"as.\"","e":"A metaphor states one thing is another; here the rug \"was an island.\""},{"p":"Which sentence uses onomatopoeia?","a":"The cereal went snap in my breakfast bowl.","w":["The cereal was as sweet as honey.","The cereal spilled on the kitchen floor.","The cereal box was almost empty."],"h":"Look for a word that copies a real sound.","e":"Onomatopoeia is a sound word; \"snap\" imitates the noise the cereal makes."},{"p":"In which sentence does something non-human act like a person (personification)?","a":"The sunflowers nodded happily in the summer breeze.","w":["The sunflowers were as tall as my dad.","The sunflowers grew right beside the fence.","The sunflowers were a bright, sunny yellow."],"h":"Find the sentence where a plant does something only a person would do.","e":"Personification gives human actions to non-human things; the flowers \"nodded happily.\""},{"p":"Which sentence repeats the same beginning sound (alliteration)?","a":"Ben's big brown dog barked at the bus.","w":["The playful puppy chased the yellow ball.","My cat naps on the warm windowsill.","The goldfish swam around its little bowl."],"h":"Look for several words in a row that start with the same sound.","e":"Alliteration repeats the same beginning sound; here it is the \"b\" sound."},{"p":"Read: \"Talking about desserts, Dad said, 'We only get triple-fudge cake once in a blue moon.'\" What does \"once in a blue moon\" mean?","a":"Very rarely, almost never.","w":["Only when the moon looks blue.","Every single night at dinner.","About twice every single day."],"h":"Think about how often the moon actually looks blue.","e":"\"Once in a blue moon\" is an idiom meaning something happens very rarely."},{"p":"Read: \"The angry ocean waves reached out and grabbed the sandcastle.\" What kind of figurative language is this?","a":"personification","w":["simile","hyperbole","onomatopoeia"],"h":"Waves cannot really reach out and grab things the way a person can.","e":"This is personification, giving the waves human actions like reaching and grabbing."}],"e.3.storydet":[{"p":"Read: \"Maya loved recess more than anything. When the bell rang, she was always the first one out the door, running straight for the swings.\" Who is this story mostly about?","a":"Maya","w":["The teacher","The bell","The swings"],"h":"Look for the person the story keeps talking about.","e":"The main character is the person the story is mostly about, and here that is Maya."},{"p":"Read: \"It was a cold winter morning. Snow covered the front yard, and icicles hung from the roof of the little red house.\" Where does this story take place?","a":"At a house on a snowy morning","w":["At a beach in the summer","Inside a warm classroom","At a busy shopping mall"],"h":"Look for words that tell about the place and the weather.","e":"The setting is where and when a story happens, and this one is at a snowy house."},{"p":"Read: \"First, Ben poured cereal into his bowl. Next, he added cold milk. Last, he grabbed a spoon and ate.\" What did Ben do FIRST?","a":"He poured cereal into his bowl","w":["He added cold milk","He grabbed a spoon","He ate his breakfast"],"h":"Look for the word that tells what happened at the start.","e":"Sequence is the order of events, and the word 'first' shows what happened at the beginning."},{"p":"Read: \"The sky turned dark and gray. Big drops began to fall, so Lily ran inside to stay dry.\" Why did Lily run inside?","a":"Because it started to rain","w":["Because she was hungry","Because it was bedtime","Because she heard a bell"],"h":"Look for what happened in the sky right before she ran.","e":"A cause makes something happen; the rain is the reason Lily ran inside."},{"p":"Read: \"Our class helps the school in many ways. We recycle paper, water the garden, and pick up litter on the playground.\" What is this passage mostly about?","a":"Ways the class helps the school","w":["How to grow a garden","Why paper is made from trees","A game played at recess"],"h":"Think about what all the sentences have in common.","e":"The main idea is what the whole passage is mostly about, which here is how the class helps."},{"p":"Read: \"Sam felt happy and proud. He held up his drawing and showed the whole class his picture of a big blue whale.\" How does Sam feel?","a":"Happy and proud","w":["Tired and sleepy","Scared and worried","Angry and grumpy"],"h":"Look for the feeling words in the passage.","e":"We learn about characters from feeling words, and the text says Sam felt happy and proud."},{"p":"Read: \"Grandpa's kitchen smelled like warm cookies. Pots hung on the wall, and a table sat in the middle covered with flour.\" Where does this scene happen?","a":"In Grandpa's kitchen","w":["In a school library","In a pet store","In a garden shed"],"h":"Find the room the sentences are describing.","e":"The setting is the place a story happens, and this scene is in Grandpa's kitchen."},{"p":"Read: \"Zoe planted a seed. Then she watered it every day. After a week, a tiny green sprout popped up.\" What happened LAST?","a":"A tiny green sprout popped up","w":["Zoe planted a seed","Zoe watered it every day","Zoe bought a flower pot"],"h":"Look for what happened at the very end.","e":"Sequence is the order of events, and the sprout popping up happened last."},{"p":"Read: \"Tommy forgot his lunch at home. By noon his tummy was rumbling loudly.\" Why was Tommy's tummy rumbling?","a":"Because he forgot his lunch","w":["Because he ate too much","Because he was excited","Because he was sleepy"],"h":"Look for what Tommy forgot to do.","e":"A cause leads to an effect; forgetting his lunch made Tommy hungry."},{"p":"Read: \"Nina's puppy is named Biscuit. Biscuit loves to chase his tail, dig holes, and nap in the sun.\" Who is the puppy in the story?","a":"Biscuit","w":["Nina","The sun","A hole in the yard"],"h":"Look for the animal's name.","e":"A character can be an animal, and the puppy character here is named Biscuit."},{"p":"Read: \"Every kid at Green School enjoys library day. They read cozy books, listen to fun stories, and pick new books to take home.\" What is the passage mainly about?","a":"Why kids enjoy library day","w":["How to build a school","A pet that lives at school","A fun trip to the beach"],"h":"Think about what all three sentences are describing.","e":"The main idea sums up the whole passage, which is about enjoying library day."},{"p":"Read: \"The wind blew hard. It knocked Jake's kite out of the sky and into a tall tree.\" Why did the kite end up in the tree?","a":"Because the wind blew it there","w":["Because Jake threw it up","Because a bird carried it","Because it started raining"],"h":"Look for what the wind did.","e":"A cause makes an effect happen; the strong wind sent the kite into the tree."},{"p":"Read: \"At the campground, tall trees stood all around. A river bubbled nearby, and a tent sat next to a crackling fire.\" Where does this story take place?","a":"At a campground","w":["At a swimming pool","At a grocery store","At a movie theater"],"h":"Look for clue words like trees, river, and tent.","e":"The setting is the place of the story, and the clues point to a campground."},{"p":"Read: \"Rosa was very kind. She shared her crayons, helped a friend tie his shoe, and let a new girl join her game.\" What kind of person is Rosa?","a":"Kind and helpful","w":["Mean and selfish","Shy and quiet","Silly and loud"],"h":"Look at the nice things Rosa did.","e":"We learn about a character from their actions, and Rosa's actions show she is kind."},{"p":"Read: \"Dad said, 'Let's make a sandwich.' First we got the bread. Next we added cheese. Then we took a big bite.\" What did they do RIGHT AFTER getting the bread?","a":"They added cheese","w":["They took a big bite","They got the bread again","They washed the dishes"],"h":"Find the step that comes after the bread.","e":"Sequence words like 'next' show the order, and cheese came right after the bread."},{"p":"Read: \"Leo studied his spelling words all week. On Friday, he got every word right on the test!\" Why did Leo do well on the test?","a":"Because he studied all week","w":["Because he skipped the test","Because the test was easy","Because he forgot his words"],"h":"Look for what Leo did before the test.","e":"A cause leads to an effect; studying all week helped Leo do well."},{"p":"Read: \"Fireflies are amazing bugs. They glow in the dark, blink like tiny lights, and come out on warm summer nights.\" What is this passage mostly about?","a":"How fireflies are amazing","w":["How to catch a fish","Why summer gets hot","A dog that likes to dig"],"h":"Think about what all the sentences describe.","e":"The main idea is what the passage is mostly about, which is how amazing fireflies are."},{"p":"Read: \"The ice cream truck played happy music. Kids ran outside because they heard it coming down the street.\" Why did the kids run outside?","a":"Because they heard the ice cream truck","w":["Because it was raining hard","Because the school bell rang","Because it was time for bed"],"h":"Look for the sound the kids heard.","e":"A cause makes an effect; the music from the truck made the kids run outside."},{"p":"Read: \"Grandma packed a picnic while Owen tossed a ball for the dog. All morning, Owen ran through the park, laughing as the dog leaped to catch it.\" Who is this story mostly about?","a":"Owen","w":["Grandma","The dog","The park"],"h":"Think about whose name comes up the most and who does the most.","e":"The main character is the person the story follows most, and that is Owen."},{"p":"Read: \"Waves rolled onto the warm sand. Kayla filled her bucket and built a tall castle while seagulls flew above her.\" Where does this story take place?","a":"At the beach","w":["At a pool","In a sandbox","At a park"],"h":"Waves and seagulls are big clues about the place.","e":"The setting is where a story happens; waves and sand tell us it is the beach."},{"p":"Read: \"Mia woke up early. First she brushed her teeth. Then she got dressed. Finally she ate breakfast.\" What did Mia do SECOND?","a":"She got dressed","w":["She brushed her teeth","She ate breakfast","She combed her hair"],"h":"Read the order words like first, then, and finally.","e":"Sequence is the order of events; 'then' shows getting dressed came second."},{"p":"Read: \"Carlos left his bike outside all night. In the morning, the rain had made it wet and rusty.\" Why did the bike get wet and rusty?","a":"It was left outside in the rain","w":["Carlos washed it with a hose","Carlos rode it through a puddle","It fell into the lake"],"h":"What happened to the bike overnight while it sat outside?","e":"This is cause and effect; the rain (cause) made the bike wet and rusty (effect)."},{"p":"Read: \"Bees are busy helpers. They buzz from flower to flower, sip sweet nectar, and make honey in their hive.\" What is this passage mostly about?","a":"Bees and what they do","w":["How to make honey at home","Why flowers smell so sweet","How to build a bee hive"],"h":"Look for the big idea that covers the whole passage, not one small detail.","e":"The main idea is the biggest point; every sentence tells about bees and what they do."},{"p":"Read: \"Priya's stomach flipped as she stepped on stage. Her hands shook and she forgot the first line of her song.\" How does Priya most likely feel?","a":"Nervous","w":["Excited","Proud","Curious"],"h":"Think about what shaky hands and a flipping stomach usually mean.","e":"We infer feelings from clues; shaking and forgetting show Priya feels nervous."},{"p":"Read: \"Before the movie, Jack made popcorn. Right before that, he found a cozy blanket. Then he pressed play.\" What did Jack do just BEFORE making popcorn?","a":"He found a cozy blanket","w":["He pressed play","He watched the movie","He ate the popcorn"],"h":"Find the step that came right before the popcorn.","e":"Sequence words like 'right before' show the blanket came first, then the popcorn."},{"p":"Read: \"The stars twinkled above the quiet town. Owls hooted softly and the streetlights glowed.\" When does this scene take place?","a":"At night","w":["In the morning","At noon","At sunrise"],"h":"Stars, owls, and glowing lights are clues about the time.","e":"Setting can also be a time; stars and owls tell us this happens at night."},{"p":"Read: \"The classroom hamster looked sad and slow. Then the class saw that his water bottle was empty, so they filled it right away.\" Why did the class fill the water bottle?","a":"The bottle was empty","w":["The hamster was hungry","The bottle was dirty","The hamster wanted to play"],"h":"Look for what the class noticed just before they acted.","e":"Cause and effect: the empty bottle (cause) is why they filled it (effect)."},{"p":"Read: \"Our town has a great new park. It has tall slides, a splash pad, and a path for riding bikes.\" What is this passage mainly about?","a":"The town's new park","w":["How to ride a bike safely","The tallest slide ever built","Why splashing is so fun"],"h":"Pick the idea that all three details belong to.","e":"The main idea ties the details together; each one describes the new park."},{"p":"Read: \"No matter how many times he fell, Diego climbed back on his skateboard. By sunset, he finally landed the trick.\" What kind of person is Diego?","a":"He does not give up","w":["He is careless","He is shy","He is grumpy"],"h":"Notice what Diego does each time he falls down.","e":"A character trait is shown by actions; getting back up shows Diego does not give up."},{"p":"Read: \"The recipe was easy. Mom mixed the batter, poured it in a pan, and baked the cake. At last, we ate a warm slice.\" What happened LAST?","a":"They ate a warm slice","w":["Mom mixed the batter","Mom poured the batter","Mom baked the cake"],"h":"Look for the words 'at last' to spot the ending.","e":"Sequence shows order; 'at last' tells us eating the slice happened last."},{"p":"Read: \"Ella wore her boots and coat, but she still shivered outside. She had forgotten her hat and gloves.\" Why was Ella still cold?","a":"She forgot her hat and gloves","w":["Her coat was too big","Her boots got wet","She was sitting in snow"],"h":"The last sentence tells you what Ella was missing.","e":"Cause and effect: forgetting her hat and gloves is why Ella stayed cold."},{"p":"Read: \"Rows of tall shelves were filled with books. A sign near the door read, 'Please whisper.'\" Where is this scene?","a":"In a library","w":["In a bakery","In a gym","In a museum"],"h":"The 'please whisper' sign is a strong clue about the place.","e":"The setting is where the story happens; quiet shelves of books point to a library."},{"p":"Read: \"Penguins are built for the cold. Thick feathers keep them warm, and they huddle close together to share heat.\" What is this passage mainly about?","a":"How penguins stay warm","w":["What penguins like to eat","Why penguins cannot fly","Where penguins go to swim"],"h":"Pick the idea the whole passage actually talks about.","e":"The main idea matches the details; feathers and huddling show how penguins stay warm."},{"p":"Read: \"The new kid, Marcus, sat all alone at lunch. So Aisha waved him over and shared her cookies with him.\" Who was kind in this story?","a":"Aisha","w":["Marcus","The lunch helper","The teacher"],"h":"Think about who did the friendly thing in the story.","e":"A character's actions show their traits; sharing cookies shows Aisha was kind."},{"p":"Read: \"At the party we sang 'Happy Birthday.' After the song, Noah blew out the candles. Then everyone had cake.\" What happened just BEFORE Noah blew out the candles?","a":"Everyone sang the birthday song","w":["Everyone ate the cake","Noah opened his gifts","Noah cut the cake"],"h":"The word 'after' tells you what came right before the candles.","e":"Sequence words help; 'after the song' means the singing came just before the candles."},{"p":"Read: \"Tara practiced piano every single day. At the recital, her fingers moved smoothly and she made no mistakes.\" Why did Tara play so well?","a":"She practiced every day","w":["The piano was brand new","The song was very short","She was just lucky"],"h":"Think about what Tara did before the recital.","e":"Cause and effect: daily practice (cause) led to Tara playing well (effect)."},{"p":"Read: \"Nadia asked question after question. 'Why is the sky blue? How do birds fly? What makes rainbows?' She wanted to know everything.\" What kind of person is Nadia?","a":"Curious","w":["Lazy","Grumpy","Shy"],"h":"Think about someone who always wants to learn new things.","e":"Nadia's many questions show she is curious, which is a character trait."},{"p":"Read: \"Big glass tanks lined both walls. Silver fish darted past, and a sea turtle glided slowly through the blue water.\" Where does this scene take place?","a":"At an aquarium","w":["At a swimming pool","At a pet store","At a lake"],"h":"Think about a place with big tanks where you watch fish and sea animals.","e":"Details like glass tanks and a sea turtle tell us the setting is an aquarium."},{"p":"Read: \"Trays of fresh bread sat behind the counter. The room smelled sweet, and a baker frosted cupcakes near the window.\" Where does this story happen?","a":"At a bakery","w":["At a farm","At a library","At a park"],"h":"Think about a place that sells bread and cupcakes.","e":"Fresh bread and a baker frosting cupcakes show the setting is a bakery."},{"p":"Read: \"First, Kim put on her helmet. Next, she hopped on her bike. Then she rode to the park.\" What did Kim do FIRST?","a":"She put on her helmet","w":["She hopped on her bike","She rode to the park","She parked her bike"],"h":"Look for the step that has the word \"First.\"","e":"The word \"First\" signals the beginning step in the sequence."},{"p":"Read: \"Owen mixed the paint. Then he brushed it on the fence. Finally, he cleaned his brush in the sink.\" What did Owen do LAST?","a":"He cleaned his brush","w":["He mixed the paint","He brushed the fence","He bought new paint"],"h":"Look for the word \"Finally.\"","e":"The word \"Finally\" points to the last step in the order of events."},{"p":"Read: \"At the pool, Dev put on his goggles. Right after that, he jumped in the water. Then he swam to the other side.\" What did Dev do RIGHT AFTER putting on his goggles?","a":"He jumped in the water","w":["He swam to the other side","He put on his goggles","He dried off with a towel"],"h":"Find the step that comes just after the goggles.","e":"Sequence words like \"Right after\" help you find what happens next."},{"p":"Read: \"Before dinner, Grace set the table. Right before that, she washed her hands. Then everyone sat down to eat.\" What did Grace do just BEFORE setting the table?","a":"She washed her hands","w":["She sat down to eat","She set the table","She cooked the dinner"],"h":"Look for what happened right before the table was set.","e":"\"Right before\" is a clue word that shows which action came earlier."},{"p":"Read: \"Sea otters are clever animals. They float on their backs, crack shells with rocks, and wrap up in seaweed so they don't drift away.\" What is this passage mostly about?","a":"Clever things sea otters do","w":["How to swim on your back","Why rocks are so hard","Where seaweed grows"],"h":"Think about what all three sentences are describing.","e":"Each detail describes sea otters, so that is the main idea."},{"p":"Read: \"Our fire station keeps the town safe. Firefighters put out fires, help at accidents, and teach kids about safety.\" What is this passage mainly about?","a":"How the fire station helps the town","w":["How to build a fire truck","Why kids like loud sirens","How to cook food safely"],"h":"Look at what the whole passage is describing.","e":"All the details tell how the fire station helps, which is the main idea."},{"p":"Read: \"Ava left the freezer door open. When she came back, her popsicles had melted into a sticky puddle.\" Why did the popsicles melt?","a":"The freezer door was left open","w":["The popsicles were too old","Ava ate them too fast","The freezer was too cold"],"h":"Think about what happens when cold air escapes a freezer.","e":"The open door let warm air in and made the popsicles melt, showing cause and effect."},{"p":"Read: \"Miguel didn't wear his sunhat at the beach all day. That night, his nose and cheeks were bright red and sore.\" Why were Miguel's nose and cheeks red?","a":"He got sunburned without his hat","w":["He ate too much ice cream","He swam for too long","He was feeling shy"],"h":"Think about what the sun can do to skin with no hat.","e":"Skipping the hat let the sun burn his skin, an example of cause and effect."},{"p":"Read: \"The puzzle had 100 pieces. Ruby did not rush. She tried piece after piece, calmly, until the whole picture came together.\" What kind of person is Ruby?","a":"Patient","w":["Careless","Bossy","Nervous"],"h":"Think about someone who stays calm and doesn't rush.","e":"Ruby's calm, careful work shows she is patient, a character trait."},{"p":"Read: \"Theo found a wallet on the sidewalk. He didn't keep the money. Instead, he brought it straight to the office to return it.\" What kind of person is Theo?","a":"Honest","w":["Greedy","Silly","Sleepy"],"h":"Think about someone who does the right thing with things that aren't theirs.","e":"Returning the wallet shows Theo is honest, which is a character trait."},{"p":"Read: \"Bella had waited all week for the fair. Then dark clouds burst open and the fair was closed. Her smile slipped away.\" How does Bella feel at the end?","a":"Disappointed","w":["Excited","Proud","Surprised"],"h":"Think about how you feel when something you looked forward to is canceled.","e":"Her smile slipping away shows Bella feels disappointed."},{"p":"Read: \"Roosters crowed and the sun peeked over the hills. Dew still sparkled on the grass as the farm woke up.\" When does this scene take place?","a":"In the early morning","w":["In the late evening","In the middle of the night","At lunchtime"],"h":"Think about the time of day when the sun first rises.","e":"Roosters crowing and the rising sun tell us it is early morning, part of the setting."},{"p":"Read: \"While Mom read on the bench and the baby slept, Hana climbed the ladder, whooshed down the slide, and swung across the monkey bars all afternoon.\" Who is this story mostly about?","a":"Hana","w":["Mom","The baby","The slide"],"h":"Think about which person does the most in the story.","e":"Most of the action is about Hana, so she is who the story is mostly about."},{"p":"Read: \"The whole class cheered and clapped. Their teacher had just told them there would be no homework tonight.\" Why did the class cheer?","a":"They were happy about no homework","w":["They just finished a hard test","It was the last day of school","They won a soccer game"],"h":"Look at the news the teacher just shared.","e":"The class cheered because the teacher said no homework, showing cause and effect."}],"e.8.themevoice":[{"p":"Read: \"The stadium lights buzzed as Maya laced her cleats. Her stomach knotted, but she whispered, 'One shot. That's all I need.'\" What is the MOOD of this excerpt?","a":"Tense anticipation before a big moment","w":["Peaceful calm after a victory","Silly playfulness among friends","Gloomy hopelessness about the future"],"h":"Mood is the feeling the reader gets. Notice the buzzing lights and the knotted stomach.","e":"Mood is the overall emotional atmosphere the reader experiences; the nervous energy and 'one shot' create tense anticipation."},{"p":"Read: \"The old skateboard was junk. Chipped, rusted, and slow, it still carried Deon everywhere. He wouldn't trade it for the world.\" What THEME does this excerpt best suggest?","a":"Value can come from meaning, not appearance","w":["New things are always better than old ones","Sports gear should be replaced often","Rust makes objects dangerous to use"],"h":"Theme is the deeper message or lesson. Ask why Deon keeps something described as 'junk.'","e":"Theme is the underlying message about life; Deon's loyalty to a worn board shows that worth can be about meaning rather than looks."},{"p":"Which word has the most NEGATIVE connotation for describing someone who saves money carefully?","a":"Stingy","w":["Thrifty","Frugal","Economical"],"h":"Connotation is the feeling attached to a word beyond its dictionary meaning. Which word sounds unkind?","e":"Connotation is the emotional coloring of a word; 'stingy' carries a negative, judgmental feeling while the others sound neutral or positive."},{"p":"Read: \"Congratulations. You practiced for six weeks and still tripped over the very first hurdle. Truly impressive.\" What is the TONE of the speaker?","a":"Sarcastic","w":["Sincerely proud","Deeply worried","Calmly neutral"],"h":"Tone is the author's or speaker's attitude. Do the praising words match the situation of tripping?","e":"Tone is the attitude conveyed through word choice; praise words paired with a failure signal sarcasm, meaning the opposite of what is said."},{"p":"Read: \"Rain hammered the tin roof. Thunder cracked, and the single candle flickered as the wind clawed at the windows.\" What MOOD does the word choice create?","a":"Eerie and threatening","w":["Cozy and cheerful","Bright and hopeful","Dull and boring"],"h":"Look at verbs like 'hammered,' 'cracked,' and 'clawed.' What feeling do they build?","e":"Mood is built through descriptive word choice; violent verbs and a flickering candle create an eerie, threatening atmosphere."},{"p":"A writer describes a used car as 'pre-owned' instead of 'secondhand.' Why does 'pre-owned' have a more POSITIVE connotation?","a":"It sounds more valued and less worn-out","w":["It means the car is brand new","It is the only correct dictionary term","It describes a faster engine"],"h":"Both words mean the same basic thing. Which one makes the buyer feel better?","e":"Connotation shapes feelings beyond literal meaning; 'pre-owned' sounds more respectable, giving the same object a positive spin."},{"p":"Read: \"Every autumn the geese leave, and every spring they return. The pond waits, patient, knowing they always come back.\" What THEME is suggested?","a":"Change is part of a natural, repeating cycle","w":["Winter destroys everything permanently","Birds are unreliable and forgetful","Ponds are dangerous in the spring"],"h":"Theme is the big idea about life. Think about the pattern of leaving and returning.","e":"Theme is the story's message about life; the repeated leaving and returning shows change as part of a dependable natural cycle."},{"p":"Read: \"Let me tell you, folks, this pizza changed my life. My whole entire life. I have SEEN things.\" What best describes the author's VOICE?","a":"Exaggerated and humorous","w":["Formal and scholarly","Cold and distant","Quiet and shy"],"h":"Voice is the writer's unique personality on the page. Notice the over-the-top claims and casual style.","e":"Voice is the distinctive personality in writing; the dramatic overstatement and casual 'folks' create an exaggerated, humorous voice."},{"p":"Read: \"Jordan crossed the finish line dead last, but he threw his arms up and grinned like he'd won gold.\" What is the TONE toward Jordan?","a":"Admiring of his positive spirit","w":["Ashamed of his poor result","Angry about the slow time","Bored by the whole race"],"h":"Tone is the attitude toward the subject. Focus on how his grin is described.","e":"Tone is the writer's attitude; describing his joy despite losing conveys admiration for his upbeat attitude."},{"p":"Which sentence uses word choice that creates the most PEACEFUL mood?","a":"The lake lay still, glowing softly under the gentle moon","w":["The lake churned as sirens screamed nearby","The lake reeked of smoke and rotting weeds","The crowd shoved past the muddy, trampled shore"],"h":"Mood comes from the feelings words spark. Which sentence uses calm, soft words?","e":"Word choice shapes mood; 'still,' 'glowing softly,' and 'gentle' build a calm, peaceful atmosphere."},{"p":"Read: \"Sure, you can borrow my headphones. And I'd love it if you never returned them, too.\" What does the speaker actually MEAN?","a":"They do not really want to lend the headphones","w":["They are eager to give the headphones away","They lost the headphones already","They want to buy new headphones"],"h":"The words say one thing, but the tone hints at another. Watch for sarcasm.","e":"This is verbal irony, where tone reverses the literal meaning; the sarcastic second line signals reluctance, not generosity."},{"p":"Read: \"Coach spoke slowly, weighing each word. 'You have talent,' she said, 'but talent without work is just a promise you never keep.'\" What THEME does Coach express?","a":"Hard work is needed to fulfill natural talent","w":["Talent alone guarantees success","Promises should never be made","Coaches dislike talented players"],"h":"Theme is the lesson about life. Focus on what Coach says talent needs.","e":"Theme is the underlying life lesson; Coach states that effort must accompany talent for it to matter."},{"p":"A news writer calls a group of fans 'a mob' instead of 'a crowd.' What does the word 'mob' CONNOTE?","a":"An unruly, possibly dangerous group","w":["A calm, orderly group","A small, quiet group","A wealthy, polite group"],"h":"Connotation is the feeling a word carries. How does 'mob' feel compared to 'crowd'?","e":"Connotation adds emotional meaning; 'mob' suggests chaos and danger, unlike the neutral word 'crowd.'"},{"p":"Read: \"The trophy shelf gathered dust. Once it had meant everything; now Priya barely glanced at it as she headed out to help at the shelter.\" What THEME emerges?","a":"What we value can change as we grow","w":["Trophies should be cleaned daily","Shelters are better than sports","Winning is the only goal in life"],"h":"Theme is the message about life. Notice what Priya cares about now versus before.","e":"Theme is the deeper idea; Priya's shift from prized trophies to helping others shows how personal values can change over time."},{"p":"Read: \"Ha! You call that a beat drop? My little cousin makes better music banging pots.\" What is the TONE of this speaker?","a":"Mocking and dismissive","w":["Gentle and encouraging","Nervous and unsure","Respectful and admiring"],"h":"Tone is the speaker's attitude. Notice the insult and the 'Ha!'","e":"Tone is conveyed through word choice; the laugh and the pots comparison create a mocking, dismissive attitude."},{"p":"Which revision changes a sentence's TONE from neutral to hopeful?","a":"Change 'The results come out Friday' to 'The results come out Friday, and I have a good feeling about them'","w":["Change 'The results come out Friday' to 'The results come out Friday, unfortunately'","Change 'The results come out Friday' to 'The results come out Friday, whether we like it or not'","Change 'The results come out Friday' to 'The results come out Friday, as scheduled'"],"h":"Tone is attitude. Which added words point toward optimism and possibility?","e":"Tone is shaped by word choice; adding 'I have a good feeling about them' introduces optimism, creating a hopeful tone."},{"p":"Read: \"I, the undersigned, do hereby acknowledge receipt of one guitar, in accordance with the terms stated above.\" What does this VOICE sound like?","a":"Formal and official","w":["Playful and joking","Sad and grieving","Angry and loud"],"h":"Voice is the personality of the writing. Notice phrases like 'the undersigned' and 'hereby.'","e":"Voice is the writer's distinct style; the legal, ceremonial phrasing creates a formal, official voice."},{"p":"Read: \"The first snow fell like a secret, quiet and slow, tucking the whole neighborhood under a soft white blanket.\" What MOOD does the imagery create?","a":"Gentle and calm","w":["Frantic and rushed","Harsh and violent","Angry and bitter"],"h":"Mood is the feeling the reader gets. Consider the words 'quiet,' 'slow,' and 'soft.'","e":"Mood arises from imagery and word choice; the hushed, soft description of snow creates a gentle, calm feeling."},{"p":"Read: \"Ravi's fingers ached after the third hour of scales. His friends were at the park, but he stayed, because the song in his head demanded to be played.\" What THEME does this excerpt best suggest?","a":"Dedication to a craft can outweigh other desires","w":["Music matters more than having any friends","Practicing scales is dull and pointless work","Real talent shows up without any effort"],"h":"Focus on what Ravi chooses to do and the reason he gives.","e":"Theme is the deeper message about life; here Ravi's choice to keep practicing shows dedication outweighing distraction."},{"p":"Read: \"She'd fallen twice on the ice, but she rose each time, brushed the frost off her knees, and skated back to the exact spot where she slipped.\" What is the TONE toward the skater?","a":"Admiring","w":["Pitying","Mocking","Indifferent"],"h":"Ask how the writer seems to feel about her getting back up each time.","e":"Tone is the writer's attitude; the focus on her rising and returning conveys admiration rather than pity or mockery."},{"p":"Read: \"The arcade was silent now. Dead screens stared back, and a single quarter lay on the sticky floor where a crowd once cheered.\" What MOOD does the word choice create?","a":"Eerie and desolate","w":["Playful and energetic","Hopeful and bright","Tense and suspenseful"],"h":"Notice the emptiness and stillness the words build in the reader.","e":"Mood is the feeling created in the reader; 'silent,' 'dead screens,' and 'once cheered' produce an eerie, empty atmosphere."},{"p":"Read: \"Okay so basically the whole trip? Total disaster. But like, the good kind? You had to be there.\" What best describes the author's VOICE?","a":"Casual and conversational","w":["Formal and precise","Cold and detached","Poetic and lyrical"],"h":"Pay attention to the everyday, chatty phrasing and sentence fragments.","e":"Voice is the writer's distinct personality on the page; the relaxed slang and fragments create a casual, conversational voice."},{"p":"Which word has the most POSITIVE connotation for describing someone who refuses to change their mind?","a":"Determined","w":["Stubborn","Bullheaded","Pigheaded"],"h":"Think about which word you would use to compliment the person.","e":"Connotation is the feeling attached to a word; 'determined' praises the same trait that 'stubborn' and 'pigheaded' criticize."},{"p":"Read: \"The clock ticked. Sweat beaded. His finger hovered over the buzzer as the final question hung in the air.\" What effect does the word choice create?","a":"A tense, suspenseful mood","w":["A relaxed, easygoing mood","A joyful, celebratory mood","A gloomy, mournful mood"],"h":"Consider how 'hovered' and 'hung in the air' make you feel while reading.","e":"Word choice shapes mood; short sentences plus 'hovered' and 'hung' build suspense and tension in the reader."},{"p":"Read: \"The mountain trail grew steeper, and Lena's legs burned. She thought of quitting a hundred times, and a hundred times she took one more step.\" What THEME emerges?","a":"Persistence means continuing despite the urge to quit","w":["Hiking is dangerous and should be avoided","Goals should be abandoned when they get hard","Success can come without any struggle"],"h":"Look at what the repeated phrase 'one more step' reveals about Lena.","e":"Theme is the central message; the contrast between wanting to quit and taking another step expresses persistence."},{"p":"A writer feels amused by a clumsy puppy and describes it fondly, which makes readers feel warm and delighted. Which term names the WRITER'S ATTITUDE toward the puppy?","a":"Tone","w":["Mood","Theme","Voice"],"h":"Separate the writer's attitude from the feeling created in the reader.","e":"Tone is the author's attitude toward the subject, while mood is the emotion the reader feels; the question asks for the attitude."},{"p":"A reviewer calls a phone 'cheap' instead of 'affordable.' What does 'cheap' CONNOTE that 'affordable' does not?","a":"Low quality, not just low price","w":["A generous discount off the price","Careful, high craftsmanship","A fair and reasonable value"],"h":"Both words point to low cost, but one hints at poor worth.","e":"Connotation is a word's implied meaning; 'cheap' suggests flimsy quality, while 'affordable' stays neutral about price only."},{"p":"Read: \"The data indicate a significant correlation between sleep duration and test performance among adolescents.\" What does this VOICE sound like?","a":"Formal and academic","w":["Playful and joking","Angry and bitter","Warm and personal"],"h":"Notice the precise, objective, scientific wording.","e":"Voice reflects the writer's style; the technical vocabulary and objective phrasing create a formal, academic voice."},{"p":"Read: \"Confetti rained from the rafters, the band burst into song, and strangers hugged like old friends.\" What MOOD does the imagery create?","a":"Joyful and celebratory","w":["Calm and reflective","Tense and fearful","Somber and quiet"],"h":"Picture the scene of confetti, music, and hugging strangers.","e":"Mood is the feeling produced in the reader; festive images of confetti and song create a joyful, celebratory mood."},{"p":"Read: \"The caterpillar didn't fight the cocoon. It surrendered to the dark, trusting it would not stay the same forever.\" What THEME is suggested?","a":"Growth often requires embracing change","w":["Insects are fascinating creatures to study","Darkness should always be feared","Staying exactly the same keeps you safe"],"h":"Think about what the cocoon and the dark stand for beyond the insect.","e":"Theme is the underlying message; the caterpillar's surrender to transformation symbolizes accepting change in order to grow."},{"p":"Read: \"The new stadium cost millions, yet the roof leaks, the seats wobble, and the scoreboard freezes every game.\" What is the TONE toward the stadium?","a":"Critical","w":["Admiring","Neutral","Nostalgic"],"h":"Notice which details the writer chooses to point out.","e":"Tone is the writer's attitude; listing flaw after flaw signals a critical attitude toward the stadium."},{"p":"Which word choice makes a small apartment sound most APPEALING?","a":"Cozy","w":["Cramped","Tiny","Boxed-in"],"h":"Which word gives a warm, inviting feeling rather than a limiting one?","e":"Connotation is a word's emotional coloring; 'cozy' feels warm and inviting, while the others stress a lack of space."},{"p":"Which sentence uses word choice that creates the most ENERGETIC mood?","a":"The crowd exploded, feet stomping, voices roaring as the ball rocketed into the net.","w":["The crowd sat quietly, watching the ball drift slowly toward the net.","The crowd murmured softly as the ball rolled gently across the grass.","The crowd waited in stillness while the ball settled into place."],"h":"Look for strong verbs that suggest force and fast motion.","e":"Word choice shapes mood; verbs like 'exploded,' 'roaring,' and 'rocketed' create a high-energy feeling."},{"p":"Read: \"At her old school, Amara hid her accent. Here, the teacher asked her to teach the class a phrase in her language, and for the first time she spoke up loud.\" What THEME emerges?","a":"Acceptance lets people embrace who they are","w":["Learning new languages is difficult","Changing schools is always stressful","Teachers should assign more homework"],"h":"Compare how Amara behaves at each school and what caused the change.","e":"Theme is the larger message; the shift from hiding to speaking up shows that acceptance frees people to embrace their identity."},{"p":"Read: \"I have waited nine thousand years for this bus. Civilizations have risen and fallen. I have aged into dust.\" What best describes the VOICE?","a":"Humorous and exaggerated","w":["Serious and mournful","Formal and reserved","Calm and matter-of-fact"],"h":"Ask whether a person could really wait nine thousand years for a bus.","e":"Voice is the writer's personality; the wild overstatement (hyperbole) creates a humorous, exaggerated voice."},{"p":"Which revision changes the MOOD of \"The dog barked as shadows lunged across the wall\" from tense to calm?","a":"The dog dozed as sunlight drifted across the wall.","w":["The dog snarled as thunder shook the wall.","The dog howled as lightning split the wall.","The dog growled as footsteps pounded past the wall."],"h":"Which choice swaps threatening images for soothing, gentle ones?","e":"Mood comes from word choice; replacing 'barked' and 'lunged' with 'dozed' and 'drifted' turns the tense feeling calm."},{"p":"Read: \"The last note faded, the crowd rose roaring, and Sofia smiled through her tears—after twenty years, her final concert was over.\" What MOOD does this excerpt create?","a":"Bittersweet","w":["Purely joyful","Frightening","Boring"],"h":"Notice that two opposite feelings—celebration and loss—show up in the same moment.","e":"Mood is the feeling a text gives the reader; mixing triumph (roaring crowd) with sorrow (tears, final) creates a bittersweet mood."},{"p":"Read: \"Back then a dollar bought a soda and a comic, and we'd ride our bikes until the streetlights hummed on. Those summers stretched on forever.\" What best describes the author's VOICE?","a":"Nostalgic and reflective","w":["Angry and bitter","Formal and scientific","Anxious and tense"],"h":"Ask what feeling the speaker has while looking back at the past.","e":"Voice is the writer's distinct personality on the page; fond memories of 'those summers' create a nostalgic, reflective voice."},{"p":"Which word has the most POSITIVE connotation for describing someone who spends freely on other people?","a":"Generous","w":["Extravagant","Wasteful","Reckless"],"h":"One word praises the spender's kindness; the others hint the spending is foolish or careless.","e":"Connotation is the feeling attached to a word; 'generous' suggests admirable giving, while the others imply the money is spent poorly."},{"p":"Which sentence uses word choice that creates the most DREARY mood?","a":"Grey drizzle smeared the empty streets, and the gutters choked with soggy leaves.","w":["Soft rain pattered as children splashed in the bright puddles.","The storm roared with thrilling flashes of electric light.","Warm rain drummed a cozy rhythm on the cabin roof."],"h":"Look for words that feel dull, damp, and lifeless rather than lively or cozy.","e":"Word choice shapes mood; 'grey,' 'smeared,' 'empty,' and 'choked' build a gloomy, dreary feeling."},{"p":"Read: \"The glittering mansion had marble floors and forty empty rooms; laughter never echoed there, only footsteps.\" What THEME does this excerpt best suggest?","a":"Wealth alone cannot buy happiness.","w":["Big houses are always better than small ones.","Hard work always leads to riches.","Money should never be spent on a home."],"h":"Contrast what the house has plenty of with what it seems to be missing.","e":"Theme is the deeper message; the rich but joyless, empty mansion suggests that wealth alone cannot buy happiness."},{"p":"Read: \"At seventy, Mr. Alvarez still opened the gym at dawn, sweeping floors no one thanked him for, never missing a single day.\" What is the TONE toward Mr. Alvarez?","a":"Admiring","w":["Mocking","Indifferent","Resentful"],"h":"Notice which details the writer chose to highlight about his effort and reliability.","e":"Tone is the writer's attitude toward the subject; emphasizing quiet, thankless dedication conveys an admiring tone."},{"p":"Which word choice makes food smell the most APPETIZING?","a":"the aroma of fresh bread","w":["the smell of fresh bread","the odor of fresh bread","the stench of fresh bread"],"h":"One word is usually saved for pleasant scents, while another is saved for foul ones.","e":"Connotation gives near-synonyms different feelings; 'aroma' carries a pleasant, appetizing association that 'odor' and 'stench' lack."},{"p":"Read: \"Let's GO, team! Every rep, every drop of sweat—this is where champions are forged. No excuses today!\" What best describes the author's VOICE?","a":"Energetic and motivating","w":["Calm and detached","Gloomy and defeated","Formal and legalistic"],"h":"Read it aloud and notice the volume, punctuation, and urgency of the speaker.","e":"Voice is the personality behind the words; the exclamations and pump-up language create an energetic, motivating voice."},{"p":"Read: \"The hallway stretched longer than she remembered. Every locker hung slightly open, and her own footsteps seemed to echo a beat behind her.\" What MOOD does the word choice create?","a":"Eerie","w":["Cheerful","Peaceful","Triumphant"],"h":"Focus on the strange, off details that make the ordinary hallway feel wrong.","e":"Mood is the reader's feeling; distortions like a stretching hallway and delayed footsteps create an eerie, unsettling mood."},{"p":"Which revision changes the sentence \"Give the form back when you're done\" to a more FORMAL tone?","a":"Please return the completed form once you have finished.","w":["Hand the form back when you're all done.","Toss the form back over whenever, no rush.","Gimme the form after you finish it up."],"h":"Formal writing avoids slang and casual phrasing and often adds polite, complete wording.","e":"Tone can shift with word choice; replacing casual words with polished, courteous language ('Please return the completed form') creates a formal tone."},{"p":"Read: \"The boy had one sandwich, and he split it in half, handing the bigger piece to the new kid who had nothing at all.\" What THEME does this excerpt best suggest?","a":"Generosity means sharing even when you have little.","w":["Always keep the best part for yourself.","New students should be avoided.","Sharing food is against the rules."],"h":"Notice how much the boy has versus how much he gives away.","e":"Theme is the underlying lesson; giving the larger share while having little shows that true generosity means sharing even in scarcity."},{"p":"Read: \"The season ended in last place, but Coach grinned. 'We're younger, faster, and hungrier now,' she said. 'Next year is ours.'\" What is the TONE of Coach's words?","a":"Optimistic","w":["Bitter","Fearful","Sarcastic"],"h":"Look at whether she is focused on the loss behind them or the possibilities ahead.","e":"Tone is the speaker's attitude; framing a loss as a hopeful setup for next year expresses an optimistic tone."},{"p":"Which word has the most POSITIVE connotation for describing a brand-new, untested idea?","a":"Innovative","w":["Risky","Reckless","Unproven"],"h":"Three words warn about danger or doubt; one word celebrates fresh thinking.","e":"Connotation is a word's emotional coloring; 'innovative' praises originality, while the others emphasize uncertainty or danger."},{"p":"A word's plain dictionary meaning, apart from any emotional associations, is called its what?","a":"Denotation","w":["Connotation","Tone","Theme"],"h":"One term is the literal definition; a very similar-sounding term is the feeling attached to the word.","e":"Denotation is a word's literal dictionary meaning, while connotation is the emotional association it carries."},{"p":"Read: \"Pale light crept over the hills, birds tested their first morning songs, and the frost began melting into dew.\" What MOOD does the imagery create?","a":"Fresh and hopeful","w":["Tense and fearful","Mournful and heavy","Chaotic and wild"],"h":"Think about what a sunrise, new songs, and melting frost usually signal.","e":"Mood is built through imagery; dawn, waking birds, and melting frost create a fresh, hopeful feeling."},{"p":"A coach describes a player as 'confident' rather than 'arrogant.' What does 'confident' suggest that 'arrogant' does not?","a":"A healthy, self-assured belief in one's own ability","w":["A boastful sense of being better than others","A nervous doubt hidden behind bravado","A total lack of any strong opinions"],"h":"Both words involve self-belief, but one crosses into looking down on others.","e":"Connotation separates near-synonyms; 'confident' implies positive self-assurance, while 'arrogant' implies looking down on others."},{"p":"Read: \"Malik had the open shot with the whole gym waiting, but he passed to Theo, who hadn't scored all season—and Theo, at the buzzer, finally did.\" What THEME does this excerpt best suggest?","a":"Lifting up a teammate can matter more than personal glory.","w":["Always take the shot yourself to win.","Losing teammates is the key to success.","Practice never pays off in real games."],"h":"Consider what Malik gave up and who benefited from his choice.","e":"Theme is the deeper message; giving up his own shot so a struggling teammate could score shows that teamwork can outweigh personal glory."}],"e.7.argument":[{"p":"In an argument, what is a \"claim\"?","a":"The main position or point the writer is trying to prove","w":["A fact that everyone already agrees is true","A question the writer asks the reader","A neutral summary of both sides of an issue"],"h":"Think about the one big idea a whole argument is built to support.","e":"A claim is the central position an author argues for; everything else in the argument works to support it."},{"p":"Maria writes: \"Our school should start later because students who sleep more get better grades.\" Which part is her claim?","a":"Our school should start later","w":["Students who sleep more get better grades","Because students who sleep more","Students get better grades than before"],"h":"The claim is the thing she wants readers to agree with, not the reason she gives.","e":"The claim is the position being argued; the part after \"because\" is the reason or evidence supporting it."},{"p":"Which of these is the best example of evidence in an argument?","a":"A study found that teens who exercise daily scored 15% higher on memory tests","w":["Exercise is obviously the best thing for everybody","I really believe exercise helps people a lot","Everyone knows exercise is good, so it must be true"],"h":"Evidence gives specific facts, data, or examples someone could check.","e":"Evidence is specific, verifiable support such as data, statistics, or examples, not just a strong opinion."},{"p":"What does \"reasoning\" do in an argument?","a":"It explains how the evidence supports the claim","w":["It lists more and more facts without stopping","It states the writer's feelings about the topic","It repeats the claim in different words each time"],"h":"Reasoning is the bridge that connects the proof to the point.","e":"Reasoning is the logical link that shows why the evidence actually backs up the claim."},{"p":"A gamer argues: \"This game is the best ever because it sold 10 million copies.\" What is the reasoning that connects the evidence to the claim?","a":"High sales show that huge numbers of players chose and enjoyed the game","w":["The game sold 10 million copies last year","This game is the best game ever made","Games are a fun way to spend free time"],"h":"Reasoning explains WHY the sales number should make you believe the claim.","e":"Reasoning is the explanation linking evidence (sales) to the claim (best game); it answers \"so what does that prove?\""},{"p":"What is a counterargument?","a":"A point that argues against your claim, which you then respond to","w":["A second reason that strongly supports your claim","A summary that restates your claim at the end","A fact that both sides completely agree about"],"h":"The prefix \"counter\" means against or opposite.","e":"A counterargument presents the opposing side; strong writers raise it and then respond to it to make their case stronger."},{"p":"Jordan argues that skateboarding should be allowed in the park. Which sentence is a counterargument he addresses?","a":"Some people worry skateboarders will damage the benches, but ramps could be built to protect them","w":["Skateboarding is great exercise for kids and teens","The park has plenty of open space for skating","Skateboarding helps young people make new friends"],"h":"Look for the sentence that first names an objection before answering it.","e":"A counterargument states the opposing view (\"some people worry\"); Jordan addresses it, which strengthens his argument."},{"p":"Which statement is a FACT rather than an opinion?","a":"The Amazon River is more than 4,000 miles long","w":["The Amazon River is the most beautiful river on Earth","Everyone should visit the Amazon River at least once","The Amazon River is the most exciting place to explore"],"h":"A fact can be checked and proven true or false; an opinion tells how someone feels.","e":"A fact can be verified with evidence; opinions express personal judgments like \"beautiful\" or \"should.\""},{"p":"Which statement is an OPINION rather than a fact?","a":"Basketball is the most fun sport to watch","w":["A basketball hoop is 10 feet above the floor","An NBA game has four quarters","A basketball team has five players on the court"],"h":"Opinions often use judgment words like \"best,\" \"most fun,\" or \"should.\"","e":"An opinion states a personal preference (\"most fun\") that cannot be proven true for everyone; the others are verifiable facts."},{"p":"Read: \"The new phone has a 6-inch screen, and honestly it is the coolest gadget anyone could ever own.\" Which words signal the OPINION part?","a":"the coolest gadget anyone could ever own","w":["The new phone has a 6-inch screen","the new phone has a screen","it has a 6-inch screen"],"h":"Which part could different people disagree about?","e":"\"Coolest\" is a judgment that varies by person, making it opinion; the screen size is a measurable fact."},{"p":"You are researching climate for a report. Which source is most likely to be reliable?","a":"An article on a NASA science website written by climate scientists","w":["A random comment left under a social media video","A meme a friend shared in a group chat","An ad trying to sell you a weather app"],"h":"Ask who created it and whether they are experts with no product to sell.","e":"Evaluating sources means checking the author's expertise and purpose; a science agency written by experts is more trustworthy than anonymous or selling sources."},{"p":"When evaluating a website for a school project, which question best helps you judge if it is trustworthy?","a":"Who wrote this, and are they an expert on the topic?","w":["Does the website use my favorite bright colors?","How many funny pictures are on the page?","Does the site load quickly on my phone?"],"h":"Trustworthiness depends on the author and their knowledge, not the design.","e":"Evaluating sources focuses on authorship, expertise, and purpose; visual appeal or speed does not make information accurate."},{"p":"What is the main purpose of PERSUASIVE writing?","a":"To convince the reader to agree with a position or take an action","w":["To give balanced facts without any point of view","To entertain the reader with a made-up story","To list steps for completing a task in order"],"h":"Persuade means to win someone over to your side.","e":"Persuasive writing aims to convince the reader of a viewpoint, unlike informative writing that simply explains."},{"p":"What is the main purpose of INFORMATIVE writing?","a":"To explain a topic and give the reader facts","w":["To convince the reader to buy a product","To argue that one opinion is the correct one","To pressure the reader into changing their mind"],"h":"Informative writing shares knowledge rather than pushing a side.","e":"Informative writing explains or teaches with facts, while persuasive writing tries to change the reader's opinion or actions."},{"p":"Read: \"Vote for Coach Lee! She is the only choice who truly cares about our team's future.\" This writing is mostly:","a":"Persuasive, because it tries to convince you to vote a certain way","w":["Informative, because it only lists neutral facts","Informative, because it explains how voting works","Persuasive, because it teaches the rules of the sport"],"h":"Notice whether the writer wants you to think or to DO something.","e":"The text urges a reader to take an action (vote), which is the goal of persuasive writing."},{"p":"A writer claims skateboards are safe but only gives evidence about how fun they are. What is the problem?","a":"The evidence does not actually support the claim about safety","w":["The claim is missing entirely from the argument","There is far too much evidence to follow","The writing has no opinion words at all"],"h":"Ask whether the proof matches the exact point being made.","e":"Strong arguments need evidence that directly supports the claim; fun does not prove safety, so the evidence is off-topic."},{"p":"Which sentence best states a clear, arguable claim for an essay?","a":"Schools should replace letter grades with written feedback","w":["This essay is about grades in schools today","Do you think grades are fair to students?","Many schools around the world use letter grades"],"h":"A claim takes a side that someone could reasonably disagree with.","e":"A claim states a debatable position; a topic announcement, a question, or a plain fact does not take an arguable stance."},{"p":"Why do writers include a counterargument in a persuasive essay?","a":"To show they considered other views and can respond to them","w":["To confuse the reader so they stop disagreeing","To fill extra space when they run out of ideas","To prove that the other side is completely correct"],"h":"Addressing objections makes a case look more fair and thought-out.","e":"Raising and answering a counterargument shows the writer understands other views, which makes their own argument more convincing."},{"p":"Read: \"Two students argue that Sports Drink X helps runners. Ava says, 'My cousin drank it once and ran faster.' Ben points to a study of 500 runners showing faster times.\" Whose statement is the stronger evidence, and why?","a":"Ben's, because a study of many runners is more reliable than one person's story","w":["Ava's, because a story from a family member feels more real than numbers","Ava's, because one clear example proves a point better than a large study","Ben's, because a larger study always costs more money to run"],"h":"Think about how many people the evidence is based on, and whether the result could be a coincidence.","e":"This tests evidence quality: data from a large sample is more reliable than a single anecdote, which could just be luck."},{"p":"Read: \"Claim: Our town needs more bike lanes. Evidence: Last year, 30 cyclists were injured on roads without lanes. Reasoning: ______.\" Which sentence best completes the reasoning?","a":"Bike lanes separate cyclists from cars, which would likely reduce these injuries","w":["Our town definitely needs more bike lanes right away","Many people in town enjoy riding their bikes on weekends","Last year, 30 cyclists were injured on roads without lanes"],"h":"Reasoning is the bridge that explains WHY the evidence supports the claim, not the claim or evidence repeated.","e":"Reasoning connects evidence to the claim by explaining the logic; the other choices repeat the evidence, restate the claim, or add an unrelated point."},{"p":"Read: \"Leah argues for a longer lunch period. She writes: 'Some say a longer lunch wastes class time, but studies show students focus better after a real break.'\" Which part is her rebuttal (her response to the opposing view)?","a":"\"studies show students focus better after a real break\"","w":["\"Some say a longer lunch wastes class time\"","\"Leah argues for a longer lunch period\"","\"but\" is the only part that counts as the rebuttal"],"h":"A rebuttal is the writer's answer that pushes back AFTER the opposing view is stated.","e":"The opposing view is the counterargument; the rebuttal is the writer's reply that weakens it, here the point about improved focus."},{"p":"Read: \"The recycling center is open Monday to Friday. It accepts glass, paper, and plastic.\" This writing is mostly:","a":"Informative, because it gives facts without trying to change your opinion","w":["Persuasive, because it wants you to start recycling today","Persuasive, because it uses exciting, emotional language","Informative, because it lists reasons the center is the best"],"h":"Ask whether the goal is to share facts or to convince you to feel or do something.","e":"Informative writing explains or gives facts neutrally; there is no emotional or persuasive push here."},{"p":"Read: \"Claim: Our cafeteria should sell more fruit. Evidence: A survey found 70% of students want more fruit options.\" Why is this evidence effective?","a":"It directly supports the claim by showing many students want the change","w":["It uses a big, exciting number to grab the reader's attention","It shares a personal story about one student's lunch choices","It proves that fruit is healthier than every other food"],"h":"Strong evidence should connect straight to what the claim is actually asking for.","e":"Effective evidence is relevant: this survey result directly backs the call for more fruit, rather than just being flashy or off-topic."},{"p":"You want an honest answer about whether a new phone is worth buying. Which source is MOST likely to be biased?","a":"The phone company's own advertisement for the phone","w":["A review site that tests and compares many brands","A consumer magazine that rates products from various makers","A tech reporter comparing several competing phones"],"h":"Ask who benefits if you believe the source. A source that profits from your choice has a reason to slant it.","e":"Evaluating sources includes checking for bias: a company selling the product has a financial reason to praise it."},{"p":"Read: \"Don't miss out! This is the once-in-a-lifetime concert every true fan absolutely needs to see!\" Which feature shows this is PERSUASIVE writing?","a":"It uses urgent, emotional words to push you to act","w":["It lists the concert's date, time, and location clearly","It explains the history of the band step by step","It gives neutral facts without any strong feelings"],"h":"Persuasive writing tries to move your feelings or actions, often with charged language.","e":"Phrases like 'don't miss out' and 'absolutely needs' are emotional appeals meant to convince, a mark of persuasive writing."},{"p":"Read: \"Everyone in my class has this game, so it must be the best game ever made.\" What is the problem with this reasoning?","a":"Being popular does not prove something is the highest quality","w":["The writer did not use enough exciting exclamation points","The writer should have named even more games in the class","Games simply cannot be judged by anyone under 18"],"h":"Just because many people do something, does that make it the best? Check the logic.","e":"This is faulty 'bandwagon' reasoning: popularity is not the same as quality, so the evidence does not truly prove the claim."},{"p":"You are researching the newest space missions. Besides being accurate, why does the source's DATE matter MOST here?","a":"A recent source is more likely to include the latest missions","w":["An older source is always more careful and trustworthy","The date mainly tells you how many people have read it","A newer source is always shorter and easier to read"],"h":"Think about which topics change quickly and need up-to-date information.","e":"Evaluating sources includes currency: for fast-changing topics, a current source is more likely to have complete, up-to-date facts."},{"p":"Read: \"Claim: Students should get more sleep. Evidence: Teens who sleep 9 hours score higher on tests.\" What is MISSING to complete this argument?","a":"Reasoning that explains why more sleep leads to better test scores","w":["A louder, more exciting claim to grab the reader","A second claim that argues the opposite side","More opinions from the writer's friends and family"],"h":"An argument needs a bridge explaining how the evidence proves the claim.","e":"The argument has a claim and evidence but no reasoning, the part that explains why the evidence supports the claim."},{"p":"Read: \"Claim: Skateboarding builds balance.\" Which piece of evidence BEST supports this specific claim?","a":"A study found skateboarders scored higher on balance tests than non-skaters","w":["Many teenagers say skateboarding is a really fun hobby","Skateboards can be bought at most sporting goods stores","Skateboarding has been popular since the 1970s"],"h":"The strongest evidence matches exactly what the claim is about, in this case balance.","e":"Good evidence is relevant to the claim; only the balance-test study directly supports the point about balance."},{"p":"Read: \"It is a well-known fact that pineapple ruins every pizza.\" Why is this NOT actually a fact?","a":"It states a personal taste that cannot be proven true for everyone","w":["It is false because pineapple pizza is clearly the best","It is not a fact only because it is missing exact numbers","It cannot be a fact simply because it mentions food"],"h":"Calling something a 'fact' does not make it one; ask if it can be proven for everyone.","e":"This is an opinion disguised as a fact; taste in food varies by person and cannot be proven, no matter how it is labeled."},{"p":"A writer's main goal is to get readers to donate to an animal shelter. Which type of writing best fits this goal?","a":"Persuasive, because the goal is to convince readers to act","w":["Informative, because the goal is only to share neutral facts","Informative, because it must avoid any strong opinions","Persuasive, because it must avoid giving readers any reasons"],"h":"Match the purpose to the type: is the writer sharing facts or trying to move readers to do something?","e":"Persuasive writing aims to convince readers to think or act a certain way, and it usually DOES give reasons to support that goal."},{"p":"Read: \"Some readers may worry that later school start times will delay sports practice. However, practices can simply shift 30 minutes later too.\" Why did the writer include the first sentence?","a":"To fairly raise an opposing concern before answering it","w":["To agree that later start times are a bad idea overall","To add a random fact unrelated to the argument","To confuse readers so they stop reading the essay"],"h":"Notice the word 'however' right after, signaling the writer plans to respond.","e":"The first sentence states a counterargument; naming an opposing concern and then answering it makes the writer's argument more convincing."},{"p":"You are writing a report about a local river cleanup. Which of these is a PRIMARY source?","a":"An interview with a volunteer who worked at the cleanup","w":["A magazine article that summarizes the cleanup","A textbook chapter about river pollution in general","A blog post reacting to news of the cleanup"],"h":"A primary source comes straight from someone or something directly involved in the event.","e":"A primary source is firsthand evidence, like an interview with an actual participant. The others repackage or comment on the event secondhand."},{"p":"Read: \"I tried one song by this band and didn't like it, so their whole album must be terrible.\" What reasoning error is this?","a":"Drawing a big conclusion from too little evidence (a hasty generalization)","w":["Attacking the person instead of the idea being discussed","Repeating the same claim again as if it were proof","Relying on an expert who is not actually qualified"],"h":"Think about how many songs were actually judged before the decision was made.","e":"A hasty generalization jumps to a broad conclusion from one small sample. One song cannot fairly represent an entire album."},{"p":"Read: \"Only a heartless person would ignore these poor, shivering puppies tonight.\" Which persuasive technique is the writer mainly using?","a":"Emotional (loaded) language to pressure the reader's feelings","w":["Statistics that prove the puppies are actually cold","Expert testimony from a trained animal veterinarian","A balanced look at both sides of the issue"],"h":"Notice the emotionally charged words chosen to make you feel guilty or sad.","e":"Loaded language uses emotionally charged words to sway feelings rather than reasons, a common persuasive technique."},{"p":"Which statement is a FACT that could be verified with a measurement?","a":"A blue whale can weigh more than 150 tons","w":["The blue whale is the most amazing animal in the ocean","Everyone should care a lot more about protecting whales","Whales are far more interesting to watch than sharks"],"h":"Look for the statement you could confirm with a scale or reliable research.","e":"A fact can be checked against evidence, and weight can be measured. The others express opinions or personal preferences."},{"p":"Read: \"It's true that guitars can be expensive. Still, many stores rent them cheaply, so cost shouldn't stop you.\" Which part is the CONCESSION?","a":"\"It's true that guitars can be expensive.\"","w":["\"Still, many stores rent them cheaply\"","\"so cost shouldn't stop you\"","\"many stores rent them cheaply, so cost shouldn't stop you\""],"h":"A concession briefly admits the other side has a point before you answer it.","e":"A concession agrees with part of the opposing view (\"guitars can be expensive\") before the rebuttal answers it."},{"p":"Read: \"Claim: Our team will win the finals. Evidence: We have the newest uniforms.\" What is wrong with this argument?","a":"The evidence does not logically connect to the claim","w":["The claim is actually an opinion and cannot be argued","The evidence is a fact that cannot possibly be checked","The counterargument is missing from the whole essay"],"h":"Ask whether the evidence really gives a reason for the claim to be true.","e":"Evidence must be relevant. New uniforms do not cause wins, so the reasoning link between evidence and claim breaks down."},{"p":"Read: \"Claim: This trail is good for beginners.\" Which piece of evidence is IRRELEVANT to that claim?","a":"The trail's parking lot was recently repaved","w":["The trail is flat with no steep climbs anywhere","The trail is short and clearly marked the whole way","The trail has benches for resting along the route"],"h":"Ask which detail says nothing about how easy the trail is to hike.","e":"Relevant evidence must support the specific claim. A repaved parking lot says nothing about the trail's difficulty for beginners."},{"p":"Which statement would NOT work as an arguable claim because almost no one could dispute it?","a":"The school library is open on weekdays","w":["The school library should also stay open on weekends","Students would read more if the library had a cafe","The library is the best place to study in our school"],"h":"An arguable claim is something reasonable people could disagree about.","e":"An arguable claim invites debate. \"The library is open on weekdays\" is a simple fact no one disputes, so it cannot anchor an argument."},{"p":"Read: \"Skateparks are dangerous. My neighbor sprained his ankle at one last week.\" Why is this weak evidence?","a":"It relies on a single personal story instead of broader data","w":["It uses numbers that are far too large to check","It attacks the skatepark owner in a personal way","It states an opinion the writer can never prove"],"h":"Think about how many people one neighbor's experience really represents.","e":"This is anecdotal evidence, just one personal example. Strong claims need broader data, not a single story."},{"p":"Read: \"The museum opens at 9 a.m., costs $5, and features a new dinosaur exhibit this month.\" This writing is mostly:","a":"Informative, because it gives facts without trying to persuade","w":["Persuasive, because it urges you to visit the museum soon","Persuasive, because it praises the exhibit as amazing","Informative, because it argues dinosaurs are the best exhibit"],"h":"Ask whether the writer is sharing facts or trying to change your mind.","e":"Informative writing delivers facts (hours, price, exhibit) without pushing an opinion or a call to action."},{"p":"You are researching how volcanoes erupt. Whose explanation is MOST credible?","a":"A geologist who studies volcanoes at a university","w":["A traveler who once photographed a volcano","A novelist who wrote a story about a volcano","A blogger who simply finds volcanoes exciting"],"h":"Look for the person with training and expertise in the actual subject.","e":"Credibility rises with relevant expertise. A geologist has the training to explain eruptions accurately."},{"p":"Read: \"Everyone knows that video games always improve your grades.\" Why might a careful reader distrust this sentence?","a":"Words like \"everyone\" and \"always\" overstate the claim without proof","w":["It gives far too many specific statistics to check","It admits the opposing view much too quickly","It relies on expert testimony from a real teacher"],"h":"Notice the absolute words and ask whether they can truly be true in every case.","e":"Sweeping words like \"everyone\" and \"always\" signal overgeneralization, claims too extreme to be supported."},{"p":"Read: \"We shouldn't listen to Dana's plan for the garden. She's not even popular.\" What is wrong with this response?","a":"It attacks the person instead of addressing her plan","w":["It provides evidence that is off-topic but still true","It concedes far too much to the opposing side","It repeats the claim itself as if it were proof"],"h":"Ask whether the response deals with the idea or with the person.","e":"This is a personal attack (ad hominem): it targets Dana rather than the merits of her garden plan."},{"p":"Read: \"This is the best podcast because no other podcast is as good as it.\" Why is this reasoning weak?","a":"It just restates the claim instead of giving a real reason","w":["It relies on only one listener's personal story","It attacks rival podcasts in an unfair way","It uses statistics that cannot actually be checked"],"h":"Compare the \"reason\" to the claim. Are they really saying different things?","e":"This is circular reasoning: the \"reason\" simply repeats the claim (\"best\" means \"none as good\") without new support."},{"p":"You find a surprising fact on one website. What is the BEST way to check if it is trustworthy?","a":"See whether other reliable sources report the same thing","w":["Trust it if the website looks colorful and modern","Believe it because it appears first in the search results","Accept it if it matches what you already hoped was true"],"h":"One source alone is not proof. Think about confirming it somewhere else.","e":"Cross-checking (corroboration) against other reliable sources is the best test. Design, ranking, or wishful thinking do not prove accuracy."},{"p":"Read: \"Claim: Our city should plant more trees. Evidence: Streets with trees were 8 degrees cooler in summer than bare streets.\" Why is this evidence effective?","a":"It gives specific data that directly supports the claim","w":["It uses emotional words to move the reader's feelings","It admits the opposing view before it answers it","It repeats the same claim using different words"],"h":"Look at whether the evidence is specific and clearly on-topic for the claim.","e":"Effective evidence is specific and relevant. A measured 8-degree difference directly backs the call for more trees."},{"p":"Which transition word most often introduces a counterargument in an essay?","a":"However","w":["Therefore","For example","In addition"],"h":"Look for the word that signals a turn toward an opposing idea.","e":"Signal words like \"however\" introduce a counterargument by turning to an opposing point. \"Therefore\" shows a result, and the others add or illustrate."}],"e.10.rhetoric":[{"p":"In classical rhetoric, which term names the appeal to a speaker's credibility, character, or authority?","a":"Ethos","w":["Pathos","Logos","Kairos"],"h":"Think of the English word 'ethical,' which shares this root.","e":"Ethos is the rhetorical appeal based on the speaker's credibility, trustworthiness, and character."},{"p":"Which rhetorical appeal seeks to persuade an audience primarily by arousing their emotions?","a":"Pathos","w":["Logos","Ethos","Syntax"],"h":"Consider the related words 'sympathy' and 'empathy.'","e":"Pathos persuades by evoking emotions such as pity, fear, anger, or pride in the audience."},{"p":"Which rhetorical appeal relies on logic, evidence, facts, and reasoned argument?","a":"Logos","w":["Pathos","Ethos","Rhetos"],"h":"This root also gives us the word 'logic.'","e":"Logos persuades through reasoning, evidence, and structured logical argument."},{"p":"Read: \"As a board-certified cardiologist with twenty years treating heart disease, I can tell you this diet works.\" Which appeal does the speaker most rely on?","a":"Ethos, by citing professional credentials and experience","w":["Logos, by presenting statistical evidence of results","Pathos, by stirring the reader's fear of illness","Kairos, by stressing the urgency of the moment"],"h":"Ask what the speaker offers as the reason to trust the claim.","e":"The speaker builds ethos by emphasizing credentials and experience to establish authority and trust."},{"p":"Read: \"Imagine your own child, hungry and shivering, with no warm bed to sleep in tonight.\" Which appeal is the writer chiefly using?","a":"Pathos, by evoking the reader's compassion and distress","w":["Logos, by supplying data on child poverty rates","Ethos, by establishing the writer's expertise","Anaphora, by repeating a phrase at the start of clauses"],"h":"Notice the vivid image designed to make the reader feel something.","e":"The passage relies on pathos, using emotionally charged imagery to stir sympathy."},{"p":"Read: \"Studies of 10,000 patients show a 42% reduction in symptoms, and three independent trials confirm the result.\" Which appeal is dominant?","a":"Logos, by using data and evidence to support the claim","w":["Pathos, by appealing to the reader's hopes","Ethos, by asserting the writer's good character","Hyperbole, by exaggerating for emphasis"],"h":"Focus on what kind of support the sentence provides.","e":"Logos dominates because the argument rests on statistics and repeated experimental evidence."},{"p":"Which rhetorical device is defined as the repetition of the same word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses or sentences?","a":"Anaphora","w":["Antithesis","Hyperbole","Allusion"],"h":"Think of 'We shall fight on the beaches, we shall fight on the landing grounds...'","e":"Anaphora is the deliberate repetition of an opening word or phrase across successive clauses for emphasis or rhythm."},{"p":"A speaker asks, \"How much longer can we ignore this crisis?\" without expecting a spoken reply. What device is this?","a":"Rhetorical question","w":["Analogy","Understatement","Personification"],"h":"The question is meant to make a point, not to gather information.","e":"A rhetorical question is posed for effect, prompting reflection rather than an answer."},{"p":"Read: \"I've told you a million times to clean your room.\" The phrase 'a million times' is an example of which device?","a":"Hyperbole","w":["Understatement","Metaphor","Irony"],"h":"The number is a deliberate exaggeration, not a literal count.","e":"Hyperbole is deliberate exaggeration used for emphasis or effect, not to be taken literally."},{"p":"Read: \"Ask not what your country can do for you; ask what you can do for your country.\" This balanced, mirrored structure is best identified as which device?","a":"Antithesis","w":["Anaphora","Hyperbole","Alliteration"],"h":"Look at how the two halves contrast while sharing a parallel form.","e":"Antithesis places contrasting ideas in parallel grammatical structure to sharpen the contrast."},{"p":"A candidate delivers a speech at a rally urging citizens to vote for a new education law. What is the primary purpose of this text?","a":"To persuade the audience to take a specific action","w":["To inform the audience of neutral facts only","To entertain the audience with a story","To describe a scene in sensory detail"],"h":"Consider what the speaker wants the listeners to do afterward.","e":"The primary purpose is persuasion, since the speaker aims to influence beliefs and prompt action."},{"p":"An author writes an article for a magazine read mostly by parents of toddlers, using simple examples about naptime and snacks. Who is the intended audience?","a":"Parents of young children","w":["Professional pediatric researchers","High school science teachers","Elderly retirees without children"],"h":"Match the topics and examples to the group most likely to relate to them.","e":"Audience is the specific group a text targets; the content and examples signal parents of young children."},{"p":"Read: \"Because renewable energy lowers costs over time and reduces pollution, cities that adopt it will save money and improve public health.\" Which appeal is central?","a":"Logos, by connecting causes and effects through reasoning","w":["Pathos, by appealing to fear of pollution","Ethos, by asserting expert authority","Hyperbole, by exaggerating the benefits"],"h":"Look for a chain of reasoning linking claims to conclusions.","e":"Logos is central because the sentence uses logical cause-and-effect reasoning to support its claim."},{"p":"Read: \"We will not tire, we will not falter, and we will not fail.\" Besides anaphora, the deliberate use of matching grammatical patterns across the three phrases is called what?","a":"Parallelism","w":["Antithesis","Allusion","Onomatopoeia"],"h":"Notice how each phrase follows the same 'we will not + verb' structure.","e":"Parallelism is the use of matching grammatical structures to create rhythm and emphasis."},{"p":"Read: \"Standing here, we face our own Rubicon; there is no turning back.\" The reference to crossing the Rubicon is an example of which device?","a":"Allusion","w":["Hyperbole","Personification","Rhetorical question"],"h":"The phrase borrows meaning from a well-known historical event.","e":"An allusion is an indirect reference to a familiar historical, literary, or cultural moment to enrich meaning."},{"p":"A writer chooses the word 'thrifty' rather than 'cheap' to describe a shopper. This choice reflects an awareness of what?","a":"Connotation, the emotional associations a word carries","w":["Denotation, the strict dictionary meaning of a word","Syntax, the arrangement of words in a sentence","Alliteration, the repetition of initial consonant sounds"],"h":"Both words point to the same behavior but feel very different.","e":"Connotation refers to the positive or negative associations a word carries beyond its literal denotation."},{"p":"Read: \"As a parent who tucks my own kids in every night, I understand exactly what these families are going through.\" The speaker builds persuasive force here mainly by establishing shared values and character. Which appeal is this?","a":"Ethos","w":["Pathos","Logos","Kairos"],"h":"Focus on how the speaker positions who they are and what they share with the audience, not on data or feelings alone.","e":"Ethos includes credibility built through shared values and character, not just formal credentials; the speaker earns trust by identifying with the audience."},{"p":"Read: \"His argument was as fragile as glass.\" Which rhetorical device does this comparison use?","a":"Simile","w":["Metaphor","Personification","Hyperbole"],"h":"Notice the explicit connecting word used to link the two things being compared.","e":"A simile compares two unlike things using 'like' or 'as'; the word 'as' signals a simile rather than a direct (metaphor) equation."},{"p":"Read: \"This is government of the people, by the people, for the people.\" The repetition of 'the people' at the end of each phrase is best identified as which device?","a":"Epistrophe","w":["Anaphora","Antithesis","Asyndeton"],"h":"Ask yourself where in each phrase the repeated words fall, and compare that position to devices that repeat at the start.","e":"Epistrophe (epiphora) is the repetition of a word or phrase at the END of successive clauses; anaphora, by contrast, repeats at the beginning."},{"p":"Read: \"The new tax will crush shopkeepers, farmers, teachers, nurses.\" Listing items with the conjunctions deliberately left out is called which device?","a":"Asyndeton","w":["Polysyndeton","Anaphora","Parallelism"],"h":"Consider what small connecting words normally appear between the last two items of a list, and what their absence does.","e":"Asyndeton omits conjunctions between listed items to speed the rhythm; polysyndeton is the opposite, adding extra conjunctions."},{"p":"Read: \"We have ships and men and money and stores.\" The deliberate use of extra conjunctions between each item is called which device?","a":"Polysyndeton","w":["Asyndeton","Epistrophe","Hyperbole"],"h":"Count the connecting words and ask whether there are more or fewer than a normal list would use.","e":"Polysyndeton repeatedly inserts conjunctions ('and...and...and') to slow the pace and stress abundance; asyndeton removes them instead."},{"p":"Read: \"You shouldn't believe her report on water safety — she never even finished college.\" This persuasive move attacks the person instead of the argument. What is it called?","a":"Ad hominem","w":["Appeal to authority","Straw man","Red herring"],"h":"Identify what exactly is being criticized: the evidence itself, or the individual who presented it.","e":"An ad hominem fallacy rejects a claim by attacking the character or traits of the person making it rather than addressing the argument's merits."},{"p":"Read: \"With the floodwaters still rising outside this very hour, we cannot wait until next month to act.\" The speaker persuades by stressing the urgency of the present moment. This appeal to timeliness is best called what?","a":"Kairos","w":["Ethos","Logos","Pathos"],"h":"Think about which classical concept concerns the opportune or fitting moment for an argument.","e":"Kairos is the rhetorical appeal to timeliness—seizing the opportune moment—rather than to credibility, emotion, or logic directly."},{"p":"Read: \"All metals expand when heated; steel is a metal; therefore steel expands when heated.\" Moving from a general rule to a specific certain conclusion is which kind of reasoning?","a":"Deductive reasoning","w":["Inductive reasoning","Analogical reasoning","Circular reasoning"],"h":"Consider whether the argument begins with a broad rule and narrows to a guaranteed conclusion, or builds up from individual observations.","e":"Deductive reasoning moves from general premises to a specific conclusion that must be true if the premises are; this is the classic syllogism supporting logos."},{"p":"Read: \"Every swan I have ever seen has been white, so all swans must be white.\" Drawing a general conclusion from specific observations is which kind of reasoning?","a":"Inductive reasoning","w":["Deductive reasoning","Syllogistic reasoning","Circular reasoning"],"h":"Ask whether the conclusion is guaranteed or only probable, and whether it starts from examples or from a rule.","e":"Inductive reasoning generalizes from specific instances to a broader (but not guaranteed) conclusion; here the observed cases may not cover all swans."},{"p":"Read: \"Critics say the program costs too much. True, the upfront price is steep—but over ten years it pays for itself twice over.\" The writer's acknowledgment that the opposing side has a fair point is called what?","a":"Concession","w":["Refutation","Allusion","Understatement"],"h":"Distinguish the moment the writer admits the other side is partly right from the moment they push back against it.","e":"A concession grants that part of the opposing argument is valid; it typically precedes a rebuttal, which then answers or outweighs that point."},{"p":"Read: \"The regime's thugs crushed the peaceful marchers.\" The writer's choice of emotionally charged words like 'thugs' and 'crushed' is best described as which technique?","a":"Loaded language","w":["Euphemism","Understatement","Jargon"],"h":"Consider whether the word choices soften the event or intensify a negative reaction to it.","e":"Loaded (emotionally charged) language uses words with strong connotations to shape the audience's feelings, often supporting a pathos appeal."},{"p":"Read: \"The company announced it would 'let go' three hundred employees.\" Replacing a harsh idea with a milder-sounding phrase is which device?","a":"Euphemism","w":["Loaded language","Hyperbole","Litotes"],"h":"Ask whether the phrasing intensifies the unpleasantness or deliberately softens it.","e":"A euphemism substitutes an inoffensive or gentle expression for one considered harsh or blunt, here softening 'fire' into 'let go'."},{"p":"Read: \"Running a nation's budget is just like running a household budget—you simply can't spend more than you take in.\" Explaining an unfamiliar idea by comparing it to a familiar one is which technique?","a":"Analogy","w":["Allusion","Personification","Antithesis"],"h":"Look at whether the passage draws an extended comparison to clarify a concept, rather than referencing an outside work or history.","e":"An analogy explains or argues by drawing a comparison between two situations; critics may challenge it as a false analogy if the cases differ in key ways."},{"p":"An opinion columnist uses exaggeration and mockery to ridicule a new city ordinance and expose its flaws. What is the primary purpose of this piece?","a":"To persuade readers to oppose the ordinance through satire","w":["To entertain readers with lighthearted jokes","To objectively inform readers about the ordinance's provisions","To narrate the columnist's personal experiences with the ordinance"],"h":"Look past the humor to what the writer wants readers to think or do about the ordinance.","e":"Satire uses irony, mockery, or exaggeration in service of persuasion; the humor is a means to move the audience against the ordinance, not an end in itself."},{"p":"Read: \"The study evaluated myocardial perfusion, ejection fraction, and post-stent restenosis rates across the cohort.\" The dense technical vocabulary signals that the intended audience is most likely which group?","a":"Medical professionals or specialists","w":["The general newspaper-reading public","Elementary school students","Parents of newborns"],"h":"Judge the audience by the level of specialized vocabulary the writer assumes readers already understand.","e":"Analyzing diction and jargon reveals audience: unexplained specialist terms indicate the writer is addressing an expert readership, not a general one."},{"p":"Read: \"Oh, wonderful—another two-hour meeting that could have been a single email.\" The tone of this remark is best described as which of the following?","a":"Sarcastic","w":["Sincere","Nostalgic","Solemn"],"h":"Compare the literally positive word to the clearly negative situation it describes.","e":"Sarcasm (a form of verbal irony) says the opposite of what is meant for critical effect; 'wonderful' mocks rather than praises the meeting."},{"p":"Read: \"We must reject this reckless plan. Yes, my opponent is a decorated veteran—but a hero's résumé cannot fix a broken proposal.\" Which BEST explains why this argument is persuasive yet fair?","a":"It concedes the opponent's strength but keeps the focus on the proposal's merits rather than attacking the person","w":["It uses an ad hominem attack to discredit the opponent's military record","It relies on a straw man by distorting the opponent's actual plan","It appeals purely to emotion by praising the opponent's heroism"],"h":"Weigh whether the speaker shifts to attacking the person or deliberately keeps the argument on the idea itself.","e":"By granting a concession (the veteran's record) yet returning to the proposal, the speaker avoids ad hominem and argues the issue on its merits."},{"p":"Read: \"My opponent wants to trim the military budget slightly. Apparently she wants to leave our nation utterly defenseless against every enemy on earth.\" What flaw does this argument commit?","a":"Straw man fallacy","w":["Slippery slope fallacy","Red herring fallacy","Post hoc fallacy"],"h":"Notice how the speaker restates the opponent's position in a distorted, exaggerated form before attacking it.","e":"The straw man fallacy misrepresents an opponent's argument as a weaker, distorted version that is easier to knock down."},{"p":"Read: \"If we let one student redo a late assignment, soon they'll all expect to redo everything, and eventually grades will mean nothing at all.\" Which reasoning flaw is this?","a":"Slippery slope fallacy","w":["Circular reasoning fallacy","False dilemma fallacy","Hasty generalization fallacy"],"h":"The speaker claims one small step will inevitably trigger a chain leading to an extreme result.","e":"The slippery slope fallacy assumes without proof that one action will set off an unavoidable chain of increasingly negative events."},{"p":"Read: \"Either we cut every school arts program now, or the district goes bankrupt within a year. There is simply no other choice.\" Which fallacy is at work?","a":"False dilemma","w":["Slippery slope","Straw man","Ad hominem"],"h":"Consider whether the speaker fairly presents all available options or forces a choice between two extremes.","e":"A false dilemma (either-or fallacy) presents only two options as if they were the only possibilities when other choices exist."},{"p":"Read: \"Over two million shoppers have already switched to this brand—don't be the last one clinging to the old way.\" Which persuasive technique is this?","a":"Bandwagon appeal","w":["Appeal to authority","Appeal to tradition","Testimonial appeal"],"h":"The pressure comes entirely from the idea that everyone else is already doing it.","e":"The bandwagon appeal (ad populum) urges people to adopt a position because a crowd or majority has supposedly already done so."},{"p":"Read: \"The new principal arrived in September, and by June the test scores had risen, so clearly the principal caused the improvement.\" Which flaw does this show?","a":"Post hoc (false cause) fallacy","w":["Circular reasoning fallacy","Straw man fallacy","Bandwagon fallacy"],"h":"Ask whether one event truly caused another simply because it happened to come first.","e":"The post hoc ergo propter hoc fallacy wrongly assumes that because one event preceded another, the first must have caused the second."},{"p":"Read: \"This ordinance is just because it is the law, and obeying the law is always the just thing to do.\" Which flaw is this?","a":"Circular reasoning","w":["False dilemma","Post hoc fallacy","Red herring"],"h":"Look at whether the conclusion simply restates the premise in slightly different words.","e":"Circular reasoning (begging the question) uses its own conclusion as a supporting premise, so the argument proves nothing new."},{"p":"Read: \"You question my factory's pollution record? Well, let's talk instead about all the jobs I've created for this town.\" Which technique is this?","a":"Red herring","w":["Straw man","Ad hominem","False dilemma"],"h":"Notice that the reply introduces an unrelated point rather than answering the actual charge.","e":"A red herring introduces an irrelevant topic to divert the audience's attention away from the real question or argument."},{"p":"Read: \"When the going gets tough, the tough get going.\" Reversing the order of the same key words in the second half is best identified as which device?","a":"Antimetabole","w":["Anaphora","Antithesis","Epistrophe"],"h":"The defining feature is that identical words reappear, but in reversed grammatical order.","e":"Antimetabole repeats the same words in reverse order across two clauses; it is a specific, word-level form of chiasmus."},{"p":"Read: \"The Crown announced new taxes, and Wall Street reacted with alarm.\" Naming things by 'the Crown' and 'Wall Street' rather than by the monarchy and the finance industry is which device?","a":"Metonymy","w":["Synecdoche","Personification","Metaphor"],"h":"Each term names something closely associated with the thing it stands for, not a physical piece of it.","e":"Metonymy refers to something by the name of a closely related concept or attribute rather than by its literal name."},{"p":"Read: \"The captain needed twenty strong hands on deck before the storm hit.\" Using 'hands' to mean whole workers is which device?","a":"Synecdoche","w":["Metonymy","Hyperbole","Personification"],"h":"Here a single physical part is used to represent each entire person.","e":"Synecdoche uses a part to represent the whole (or the whole for a part), as 'hands' stands for entire crew members."},{"p":"Read: \"She's a licensed pharmacist, so of course she knows which remedy is safest.\" This argument leaves the premise 'licensed pharmacists know safe remedies' unstated. An argument built on such an assumed, unstated premise is called what?","a":"An enthymeme","w":["A syllogism","A tautology","A rebuttal"],"h":"The persuasive force depends on the audience mentally supplying a missing part of the logic.","e":"An enthymeme is a compressed argument in which one premise is left implicit for the audience to fill in."},{"p":"Read: \"I don't trust the crash-test statistics—my uncle survived a wreck precisely because he was thrown clear of his car.\" Relying on one personal story instead of broad data is best described as which technique?","a":"Anecdotal evidence","w":["Statistical evidence","Expert testimony","Analogical reasoning"],"h":"The support offered is a single memorable case rather than a representative sample.","e":"Anecdotal evidence uses an isolated personal example as proof, which is weak because one case may not represent the general pattern."},{"p":"Read: \"A great republic demands courage, wisdom, and sacrifice from its citizens.\" The deliberate grouping of exactly three parallel items for rhythmic emphasis is called what?","a":"Tricolon","w":["Antithesis","Polysyndeton","Anaphora"],"h":"Count the parallel elements and consider why a set of three has such a satisfying rhythm.","e":"A tricolon is a series of three parallel words, phrases, or clauses used together for emphasis and memorable rhythm."},{"p":"Read: \"I won't even mention my opponent's two bankruptcies or his broken promises—that would be beneath this campaign.\" Raising an issue by claiming you will not discuss it is which device?","a":"Paralipsis","w":["Understatement","Concession","Euphemism"],"h":"The speaker draws attention to something precisely by announcing that they will pass over it.","e":"Paralipsis (apophasis) emphasizes a point by pretending to omit or dismiss it while in fact stating it plainly."},{"p":"Read: \"We should keep the ceremony exactly as it is—we've done it this way for a hundred years, and that is reason enough.\" Which flaw does this reasoning show?","a":"Appeal to tradition","w":["Appeal to authority","Bandwagon appeal","Hasty generalization"],"h":"The only justification offered is that something has long been done a certain way.","e":"The appeal to tradition assumes a practice is correct or best simply because it is long-established, offering no other support."},{"p":"Read: \"Two students from that school were rude to me once, so students there clearly have no manners at all.\" Which fallacy is this?","a":"Hasty generalization","w":["Slippery slope","False dilemma","Red herring"],"h":"Consider whether the sample of cases is large enough to justify such a sweeping conclusion.","e":"A hasty generalization draws a broad conclusion from a sample too small or unrepresentative to support it."},{"p":"Read: \"How can the senator lecture me about missing votes when he skipped a dozen sessions himself last year?\" Deflecting criticism by charging the accuser with the same fault is which fallacy?","a":"Tu quoque","w":["Straw man","Red herring","Bandwagon appeal"],"h":"The reply dodges the criticism by accusing the critic of hypocrisy rather than answering it.","e":"The tu quoque ('you too') fallacy rejects a criticism by pointing to the critic's own inconsistency instead of addressing the point."},{"p":"Read: \"After the storm tore off the roof and flooded every room, the homeowner shrugged, 'Well, we've had better weeks.'\" Deliberately describing something as far less serious than it truly is is called what?","a":"Understatement","w":["Litotes","Hyperbole","Verbal irony"],"h":"The speaker downplays the severity of the situation rather than negating an opposite word.","e":"Understatement deliberately represents something as smaller or less important than it really is, often for ironic effect."}],"s.1.weather":[{"p":"It is snowing outside and the ground is white and cold. What season is it most likely to be?","a":"Winter","w":["Summer","Spring","Fall"],"h":"Think about the season when it gets very cold and snowy.","e":"Snow falls when the air is very cold, which usually happens in winter."},{"p":"You look outside and see big fluffy white clouds and bright sunshine. What should you wear to play at recess?","a":"A t-shirt and shorts","w":["A heavy winter coat and mittens","Rain boots and a raincoat","A wool hat and a scarf"],"h":"Sunny and warm weather means you can dress light and cool.","e":"On warm, sunny days we wear light clothes like t-shirts to stay comfortable."},{"p":"It is raining hard outside and you want to stay dry walking to school. What is the best thing to bring?","a":"An umbrella","w":["A pair of sunglasses","A beach towel","A paper fan"],"h":"Think about what keeps the rain off your head.","e":"An umbrella blocks the rain so you stay dry, which is helpful during precipitation."},{"p":"Maria sees the trees bending and her kite flying high in the sky. What is making this happen?","a":"Wind","w":["Rain","Snow","Sunshine"],"h":"Think about the moving air that pushes kites and leaves.","e":"Wind is moving air, and it can push kites, leaves, and tree branches."},{"p":"Which of these is a kind of precipitation that falls from clouds?","a":"Rain","w":["Grass","Sand","Rocks"],"h":"Precipitation is water that falls from the sky.","e":"Rain is precipitation, which is water that falls from clouds to the ground."},{"p":"On a very hot summer day, what is the best snack to help you cool down?","a":"A cold ice pop","w":["A bowl of hot soup","A warm cup of cocoa","A steaming baked potato"],"h":"On hot days we like foods that are cold and icy.","e":"Cold treats like ice pops help cool us down when the weather is hot."},{"p":"The sky is full of dark gray clouds. What kind of weather is probably coming?","a":"Rain","w":["Bright sunshine","A rainbow only","No weather at all"],"h":"Dark, heavy clouds often carry lots of water.","e":"Dark gray clouds are usually full of water and often bring rain."},{"p":"Which season do many trees grow new green leaves and flowers begin to bloom?","a":"Spring","w":["Winter","Fall","Summer"],"h":"Think about the season after the cold snow melts.","e":"In spring the weather warms up, so plants grow new leaves and flowers bloom."},{"p":"It is cold and windy outside. What should you put on your hands to keep them warm?","a":"Mittens","w":["Sandals","Sunglasses","A swimsuit"],"h":"Think about what covers your hands on a chilly day.","e":"Mittens cover our hands and keep them warm in cold weather."},{"p":"Ben looks up and sees fluffy white clouds floating in a blue sky. What are clouds made of?","a":"Tiny drops of water","w":["Soft cotton balls","Puffs of white smoke","Bits of white paper"],"h":"Clouds are part of the water in the sky, not something you can hold.","e":"Clouds are made of many tiny water droplets floating in the air."},{"p":"In the fall, what do the leaves on many trees do?","a":"They change color and fall down","w":["They turn into flowers","They grow bigger and stay green","They melt into water"],"h":"Think about the season when the ground gets covered in crunchy leaves.","e":"In fall the leaves change color and drop from the trees as it gets cooler."},{"p":"A thermometer helps us measure something about the weather. What does it tell us?","a":"How hot or cold it is","w":["How windy it is","How many clouds there are","How loud the rain is"],"h":"Think about what a thermometer measures when you feel warm or cold.","e":"A thermometer measures temperature, which tells us how hot or cold it is."},{"p":"Read: \"Sam wakes up and sees the puddles are frozen and his breath looks like a cloud.\" What is the weather like?","a":"Very cold","w":["Very hot","Very sunny and warm","Very dry and dusty"],"h":"Water freezes and your breath shows when the air is a certain temperature.","e":"Water freezes and breath is visible when it is very cold outside."},{"p":"Which of these is a good activity to do outside on a warm, sunny summer day?","a":"Swimming at the pool","w":["Building a big snowman","Ice skating on a pond","Sledding down a snowy hill"],"h":"Pick the activity that matches hot weather, not snow.","e":"Warm, sunny summer days are perfect for swimming to stay cool."},{"p":"When the sun warms a puddle of water, the water slowly disappears into the air. What is this called?","a":"Evaporation","w":["Freezing","Raining","Snowing"],"h":"The sun turns the water into a gas that floats up into the sky.","e":"Evaporation is when the sun heats water and it turns into vapor that rises into the air."},{"p":"You see raindrops falling but the sun is also shining. What colorful thing might appear in the sky?","a":"A rainbow","w":["A snowflake","A cloud of dust","A shooting star"],"h":"Sunlight shining through raindrops makes colorful arcs.","e":"A rainbow appears when sunlight shines through raindrops in the sky."},{"p":"It is a chilly, rainy morning. What is the best way to keep your feet dry on the way to the bus?","a":"Wear rain boots","w":["Wear open sandals","Wear soft slippers","Wear no shoes at all"],"h":"Think about shoes made to keep water off your feet.","e":"Rain boots are waterproof, so they keep your feet dry in the rain."},{"p":"Which of these words best describes a nice day with the sun out and no clouds?","a":"Sunny","w":["Snowy","Stormy","Foggy"],"h":"Think about the weather word for a bright sky with the sun shining.","e":"A sunny day is bright and clear with the sun shining and few or no clouds."},{"p":"Where does the rain that falls from clouds come from?","a":"Water that went up into the sky from lakes and oceans","w":["The clouds make brand new water out of the air","The whole sky is made of water","Birds carry the water up to the clouds"],"h":"Think about what happens to a puddle after a sunny day.","e":"This is the water cycle: water rises into the air, forms clouds, and falls back down as rain."},{"p":"Read: \"Jayden hears loud thunder and sees a bright flash of lightning while playing outside.\" What is the safest thing for Jayden to do?","a":"Go inside the house right away","w":["Stand under the tallest tree in the yard","Keep playing in the open field","Lie down flat in the wet grass"],"h":"Lightning is dangerous, so think about where you are safest.","e":"During thunder and lightning, the safest place is indoors, away from tall trees and open spaces."},{"p":"The thermometer said 30 degrees in the morning and 75 degrees in the afternoon. What happened to the temperature during the day?","a":"It got warmer","w":["It got colder","It stayed exactly the same","It turned into ice"],"h":"Bigger numbers on a thermometer mean more heat.","e":"A higher number on the thermometer means it is warmer, so the temperature went up during the day."},{"p":"Winter is ending and the last of the snow is melting away. Which season comes next?","a":"Spring","w":["Summer","Fall","Winter all over again"],"h":"Think about the order the seasons go in each year.","e":"The seasons go winter, spring, summer, fall, so spring comes right after winter."},{"p":"Emma built a snowman, but the next day the sun came out and it got warm. What will most likely happen to her snowman?","a":"It will melt into water","w":["It will grow much bigger","It will float up into a cloud","It will stay exactly the same"],"h":"Think about what warm weather does to snow and ice.","e":"Warm temperatures make snow and ice melt back into water."},{"p":"Which tool at the airport shows people which way the wind is blowing?","a":"A windsock","w":["A thermometer","A rain gauge","A ticking clock"],"h":"One of these fills with air and points the way the wind goes.","e":"A windsock catches the wind and points to show its direction, while a thermometer measures temperature."},{"p":"Read: \"One morning the air was so thick and misty that Noah could barely see the houses down the street.\" What kind of weather is this?","a":"Foggy","w":["Snowy","Sunny","Windy"],"h":"This weather is like a cloud sitting down on the ground.","e":"Fog is a cloud near the ground that makes it hard to see very far."},{"p":"It was cold in the morning, so Zoe wore a warm coat. By lunchtime the sun made it hot outside. What should Zoe do?","a":"Take off her warm coat","w":["Put on a second thick coat","Add a scarf and a hat","Pull on some wool mittens"],"h":"When you feel too warm, you can wear fewer clothes.","e":"We wear layers so we can take some off when it warms up and stay comfortable."},{"p":"On a cold fall morning, the grass is covered in tiny white ice crystals. What is this called?","a":"Frost","w":["Rain","Fog","Wind"],"h":"It forms on very cold nights and looks white on the grass.","e":"Frost is a thin layer of ice that forms on cold surfaces when the temperature drops very low."},{"p":"You are going to play at the beach all day in the hot, bright sun. What is the best way to protect your skin?","a":"Put on some sunscreen","w":["Put on a heavy winter coat","Carry a closed-up umbrella","Wear thick wool mittens"],"h":"Think about what keeps the sun's rays from hurting your skin.","e":"Sunscreen protects your skin from the sun's strong rays on a hot, sunny day."},{"p":"Small balls of ice sometimes fall from storm clouds and bounce on the ground. What is this kind of precipitation called?","a":"Hail","w":["Fog","A rainbow","A breeze"],"h":"It is frozen and can bounce when it lands.","e":"Hail is small pieces of ice that fall from storm clouds, and it is a type of precipitation."},{"p":"Aiden opened his umbrella because it was raining. Now the rain has stopped and the sun is out. What should he do with his umbrella?","a":"Close it and put it away","w":["Open a second umbrella too","Put on his rain boots","Hold it upside down to fill it"],"h":"You only need an umbrella when water is falling from the sky.","e":"An umbrella keeps you dry from rain, so when the rain stops you can close it and put it away."},{"p":"Families pick pumpkins from the patch and the air turns cool and crisp. Which season is this most likely to be?","a":"Fall","w":["Spring","Summer","Winter"],"h":"This happens when the leaves start to change color.","e":"Fall is when the weather cools down and pumpkins are ready to pick."},{"p":"Read: \"The morning weather report says it will be cold and snowy all day long.\" What should Mia wear to school?","a":"A warm coat and snow boots","w":["A t-shirt and sandals","A swimsuit and a sun hat","Short shorts and a tank top"],"h":"Match your clothes to cold, snowy weather.","e":"Cold, snowy weather calls for warm clothes like a coat and boots to stay warm and dry."},{"p":"When water from a warm lake rises into the air and then cools down high in the sky, what does it help make?","a":"Clouds","w":["The sun","The moon","Big gray rocks"],"h":"Think about the fluffy things that float in the sky and hold water.","e":"Water rises into the air, cools, and forms clouds as part of the water cycle."},{"p":"Yesterday a gentle breeze barely moved the leaves. Today the wind is so strong it knocks over trash cans. How is today's wind compared to yesterday's?","a":"Today's wind is much stronger","w":["Today's wind is much weaker","The wind is the same both days","There is no wind at all today"],"h":"Think about how much each day's wind can move.","e":"Wind that can knock things over is stronger than a gentle breeze that barely moves leaves."},{"p":"Which tool would you use to find out how much rain fell during a storm?","a":"A rain gauge","w":["A thermometer","A pair of sunglasses","A bright flashlight"],"h":"This tool collects the rain so you can measure it.","e":"A rain gauge collects rainwater and measures how much rain has fallen."},{"p":"Read: \"Grace pours cold lemonade into a glass on a hot day. Soon she sees tiny water drops on the outside of the glass.\" Where did the water drops come from?","a":"Water in the air turned into drops on the cold glass","w":["The lemonade leaked out through the glass","The glass was slowly melting into water","The drops are little pieces of ice from the sky"],"h":"The glass is very cold and the air around it is warm and damp.","e":"This is condensation, when water vapor in the air cools and turns into liquid drops on a cold surface."},{"p":"Early in the morning, Leo walks on the grass and sees it is covered in tiny water drops, even though it did not rain during the night. What are these drops called?","a":"Dew","w":["Rain","Snow","Hail"],"h":"It forms overnight when the air cools, not from clouds.","e":"Dew is water that forms on cool surfaces like grass in the morning when the air cools down."},{"p":"On a cold day, rain falls and freezes into tiny icy bits before it lands on the ground. What is this kind of precipitation called?","a":"Sleet","w":["Fog","Dew","Steam"],"h":"It is rain that turns icy on the way down.","e":"Sleet is rain that freezes into small ice pellets as it falls through cold air."},{"p":"Read: \"Ella looks up and sees thin, feathery white clouds very high in the sky, and the day is calm and fair.\" These wispy high clouds are called what?","a":"Cirrus clouds","w":["Storm clouds","Snow clouds","Fog clouds"],"h":"These feathery clouds float higher and thinner than puffy clouds.","e":"Thin, feathery clouds high in the sky are called cirrus clouds, and they often appear on fair days."},{"p":"A person on TV studies the weather and tells people if it will be sunny or rainy tomorrow. What is this person's job called?","a":"A weather forecaster","w":["A firefighter","A mail carrier","A farmer"],"h":"Their job is to study and predict what the weather will do.","e":"A weather forecaster, also called a meteorologist, studies and predicts the weather."},{"p":"It is a very hot, sunny day at the park and Diego feels too warm. What is a good way to cool off?","a":"Sit in the shade under a big tree","w":["Put on a thick winter coat","Run laps in the hot sun","Wrap up in a warm blanket"],"h":"Getting out of the direct sunlight can help you feel cooler.","e":"Shade blocks the sun's heat, so sitting in the shade helps you cool down."},{"p":"The sun is very bright and Priya's eyes hurt when she looks outside. What should she wear to protect her eyes?","a":"Sunglasses","w":["Mittens","A scarf","Rain boots"],"h":"These go over your eyes to block the bright light.","e":"Sunglasses protect your eyes from the sun's bright light on sunny days."},{"p":"Read: \"Snow on Jack's roof melts a little in the sun, drips down, and freezes again into long, pointy ice.\" What are these pointy pieces of ice called?","a":"Icicles","w":["Raindrops","Puddles","Snowballs"],"h":"They hang down from the roof and are made of frozen water.","e":"Icicles form when dripping water freezes into long, pointy ice."},{"p":"It has been hot and sunny with no rain for two weeks, and the flowers in the garden are drooping. What do the flowers most need?","a":"Water from rain or a hose","w":["Much more bright sunshine","A cold winter wind","A big pile of dry leaves"],"h":"Plants get thirsty when it does not rain for a long time.","e":"Plants need water, so during a long dry spell rain or watering helps them stay healthy."},{"p":"The sun rises in the morning, climbs high at midday, and sets in the evening. When is it usually warmest outside?","a":"In the afternoon","w":["Late at night","Early before sunrise","Just after the sun sets"],"h":"It keeps getting warmer after the sun has been up for a while.","e":"The afternoon is usually the warmest part of the day, after the sun has been heating the ground for hours."},{"p":"Read: \"Aria is playing outside in the sunshine when a big cloud moves in front of the sun, and suddenly it feels cooler.\" Why did it feel cooler?","a":"The cloud blocked some of the sun's warmth","w":["The sun turned itself off","It suddenly became winter","The cloud poured out cold water"],"h":"The sun warms us, and something moved in the way of it.","e":"Clouds can block the sun's light and warmth, so it feels cooler when a cloud passes in front of the sun."},{"p":"Grandpa hangs wet towels on a line outside on a breezy, sunny day. Why do the towels dry faster?","a":"The sun and wind help the water dry into the air","w":["The wind pours more water on them","The towels soak up extra rain","The cold air freezes them dry"],"h":"Warmth and moving air help water disappear into the air.","e":"Sun and wind speed up evaporation, drying the wet towels faster."},{"p":"Snowflakes float down and land on Maya's glove, and one melts into a drop. What are snowflakes made of?","a":"Frozen water","w":["Cold sand","Tiny cotton balls","White sugar"],"h":"When a snowflake lands on your warm hand, it melts into a drop of water.","e":"Snowflakes are made of frozen water, which is why they melt into water when they warm up."},{"p":"The thermometer says the same temperature all day, but when a strong cold wind blows, Sam feels colder. Why?","a":"Moving wind makes the air feel colder on our skin","w":["The wind changed the thermometer number","The wind itself is made of ice","The sun completely stopped shining"],"h":"Think about how a breeze feels on your skin even when the number stays the same.","e":"Wind can make us feel colder than the actual temperature because moving air pulls heat away from our skin."},{"p":"Read: \"The weather app shows a picture of the sun peeking out from behind a cloud for tomorrow.\" What kind of day will it probably be?","a":"Partly cloudy with some sun and some clouds","w":["A stormy day with heavy rain all day","A dark night with no sun at all","A snowy day with deep, deep snow"],"h":"The picture shows both the sun and a cloud together.","e":"A sun peeking out from behind a cloud means a partly cloudy day with a mix of sun and clouds."},{"p":"After a heavy rain stops, Theo notices water sitting in the low dips of the playground. What are these called?","a":"Puddles","w":["Rivers","Clouds","Ocean waves"],"h":"Rainwater collects in the low spots on the ground.","e":"Puddles are small pools of rainwater that collect in low spots on the ground after it rains."}],"s.4.ecosystems":[{"p":"Maria has a pet goldfish in a bowl of water. What is a habitat?","a":"The place where a living thing finds food, water, and shelter","w":["A game animals play together at recess","A snack that animals eat every morning","A group of baby animals born in spring"],"h":"Think about WHERE an animal lives and gets what it needs.","e":"A habitat is the home place where a living thing gets food, water, and shelter to survive."},{"p":"On a nature walk, Sam sees a tall green plant making its own food using sunlight. What do we call a living thing that makes its own food?","a":"A producer","w":["A consumer","A decomposer","A predator"],"h":"Plants use sunlight to cook up their own food.","e":"A producer, like a plant, makes its own food using sunlight through photosynthesis."},{"p":"A rabbit nibbles on grass in the field. Because the rabbit eats other living things instead of making its own food, the rabbit is a —","a":"consumer","w":["producer","decomposer","sunbeam"],"h":"This animal has to eat plants or other animals to get energy.","e":"A consumer is a living thing that eats other living things because it cannot make its own food."},{"p":"In the forest, mushrooms and worms break down a fallen log until it turns into soil. What is the job of a decomposer?","a":"To break down dead plants and animals into soil","w":["To make food from sunlight all day","To hunt and chase after fast animals","To build cozy nests high in the trees"],"h":"Think about what happens to leaves and logs after they die.","e":"Decomposers break down dead plants and animals, returning nutrients to the soil."},{"p":"Read: \"Sunlight helps grass grow. A grasshopper eats the grass. Then a bird eats the grasshopper.\" In this food chain, where does the energy START?","a":"The sunlight","w":["The bird","The grasshopper","The soil"],"h":"Look for where everything begins before any eating happens.","e":"Energy in a food chain starts with the Sun, which helps producers like grass grow."},{"p":"In the food chain grass then rabbit then fox, what does the arrow between grass and rabbit mean?","a":"The rabbit eats the grass, so energy flows to the rabbit","w":["The grass eats the rabbit for a snack","The rabbit and grass are best friends","The grass turns into a rabbit over time"],"h":"An arrow points in the direction the food energy travels.","e":"In a food chain, arrows show the direction energy flows, from the food to the eater."},{"p":"A polar bear has thick fur and a layer of fat to stay warm in the freezing cold. This special body feature that helps it survive is called an —","a":"adaptation","w":["a habitat","a decomposer","a life cycle"],"h":"It is a body part or feature that helps an animal live in its home.","e":"An adaptation is a body feature or behavior that helps a living thing survive in its habitat."},{"p":"Leo is watching a caterpillar in a jar. What will the caterpillar turn into as part of its life cycle?","a":"A butterfly","w":["A grasshopper","A ladybug","A honeybee"],"h":"Think about the beautiful winged insect with colorful wings.","e":"In its life cycle, a caterpillar forms a chrysalis and then becomes a butterfly, a change called metamorphosis."},{"p":"Which of these describes the correct order of a frog's life cycle?","a":"Egg, tadpole, froglet, adult frog","w":["Adult frog, egg, tadpole, froglet","Tadpole, egg, adult frog, froglet","Froglet, adult frog, tadpole, egg"],"h":"A frog starts very tiny in the water before it can hop.","e":"A frog's life cycle goes egg, tadpole, froglet, then adult frog."},{"p":"A camel lives in a hot, dry place with lots of sand and very little rain. Which biome is the camel's home?","a":"The desert","w":["The ocean","The rainforest","The tundra"],"h":"Think about a sandy place where it almost never rains.","e":"A desert is a biome that is very dry and often hot, and camels are adapted to live there."},{"p":"Read: \"This place is very cold and covered in ice and snow almost all year. Few trees grow here.\" Which biome is being described?","a":"The tundra","w":["The tropical rainforest","The grassland prairie","The sandy desert"],"h":"Think about a frozen place where it is icy most of the year.","e":"The tundra is a very cold biome with ice, snow, and few trees."},{"p":"Ducks have webbed feet that help them push through the water when they swim. What is a webbed foot an example of?","a":"An adaptation for swimming","w":["A food chain in the pond","A producer making food","A decomposer eating logs"],"h":"It is a body feature that helps the duck do something in its home.","e":"Webbed feet are an adaptation that helps ducks swim by pushing against the water."},{"p":"A food web shows many food chains connected together. Why is a food web helpful to understand?","a":"It shows how many different living things depend on each other for food","w":["It shows how plants grow taller than animals","It shows which animals sleep the longest at night","It shows how far animals travel each day"],"h":"Think about lots of eating connections all linked together.","e":"A food web shows how many food chains connect, showing that living things depend on each other for food."},{"p":"Every animal needs certain things to survive in its habitat. Which of these does a deer need to live?","a":"Food, water, air, and shelter","w":["A television and toys to play","New shoes and a warm blanket","Homework and a school backpack"],"h":"Think about the basic things every living animal must have.","e":"All animals need food, water, air, and shelter to survive in their habitat."},{"p":"Read: \"A hawk soars high in the sky, then swoops down to catch and eat a mouse.\" In this food chain, the hawk is a —","a":"consumer that eats other animals","w":["producer that makes its own food","decomposer that breaks down soil","plant that grows from a seed"],"h":"The hawk hunts and eats other living things for energy.","e":"The hawk is a consumer because it eats other animals instead of making its own food."},{"p":"A cactus stores water inside its thick stem so it can survive when there is no rain for a long time. This is an example of —","a":"an adaptation to the desert","w":["a life cycle stage","a food web link","a decomposer job"],"h":"Think about how this feature helps the plant live in a dry place.","e":"Storing water in a thick stem is an adaptation that helps a cactus survive in the dry desert."},{"p":"Which of these is an example of a producer you might see in a pond habitat?","a":"Green pond weed","w":["A hungry turtle","A splashing frog","A darting minnow"],"h":"Look for the living thing that makes its own food from sunlight.","e":"Green pond weed is a producer because it makes its own food using sunlight."},{"p":"Read: \"A sunflower seed is planted. It sprouts, grows into a tall flower, and makes new seeds.\" What does this passage describe?","a":"A plant's life cycle","w":["A food web in the garden","An animal's adaptation","A cold winter biome"],"h":"Think about the steps a living thing goes through as it grows.","e":"This is a plant's life cycle: a seed sprouts, grows, and makes new seeds to start again."},{"p":"Read: \"In a meadow food web, grass feeds grasshoppers, and frogs eat the grasshoppers to live.\" One summer, ALL the grasshoppers disappear. What will most likely happen to the frogs?","a":"The frogs will have less food, so their numbers may go down.","w":["The frogs will start making their own food from sunlight.","The frogs will grow thick fur to keep warm.","The frogs will turn into producers for the grass."],"h":"Think about what the frogs eat and what happens when that food is gone.","e":"In a food web, removing one animal affects the ones that eat it; losing prey means predators like the frogs have less food."},{"p":"At the family picnic, a raccoon grabs some berries AND then eats a beetle. An animal that eats both plants and animals is called a —","a":"omnivore","w":["herbivore","producer","decomposer"],"h":"Look closely at whether the raccoon eats only plants, only animals, or both.","e":"An omnivore eats both plants and animals, so the raccoon fits perfectly."},{"p":"A grasshopper in the garden only munches on leaves, grass, and other plants. An animal that eats ONLY plants is called a —","a":"herbivore","w":["carnivore","omnivore","decomposer"],"h":"Focus on the fact that it never eats other animals.","e":"An herbivore is a consumer that eats only plants."},{"p":"Read: \"A ladybug crawls along a leaf and eats the tiny aphid bugs living there.\" Because the ladybug eats only other animals, it is a —","a":"carnivore","w":["herbivore","producer","decomposer"],"h":"Think about whether aphids are plants or animals.","e":"A carnivore is a consumer that eats only other animals, like the ladybug eating aphids."},{"p":"A stick insect looks just like a brown twig, so hungry birds fly right past without noticing it. This blending-in trick that keeps it safe is called —","a":"camouflage","w":["migration","hibernation","metamorphosis"],"h":"Think about how its color and shape help it hide.","e":"Camouflage is an adaptation that lets an animal blend into its surroundings to avoid predators."},{"p":"When cold winter comes, a flock of geese flies far south to find warmer weather and food. Traveling to a new place when the seasons change is called —","a":"migration","w":["hibernation","camouflage","photosynthesis"],"h":"Think about animals moving to a whole new place, not staying put.","e":"Migration is when animals travel to another place as seasons change to find food or warmth."},{"p":"A bear eats a huge amount of food in the fall, then sleeps deep in a den all winter without eating. This long winter sleep is called —","a":"hibernation","w":["migration","camouflage","metamorphosis"],"h":"Think about the deep sleep that lasts the whole cold season.","e":"Hibernation is a deep winter sleep that helps some animals survive when food is scarce."},{"p":"Read: \"A caterpillar climbs onto a branch and forms a hard case around its body. Inside, it slowly changes into a butterfly.\" What is this hard case called?","a":"a chrysalis","w":["a cocoon","an egg","a tadpole"],"h":"It is the butterfly stage that comes AFTER the caterpillar but BEFORE the wings appear.","e":"A butterfly forms a chrysalis, the stage where it changes into an adult; moths make cocoons instead."},{"p":"Which of these shows the correct order of a butterfly's life cycle?","a":"egg, caterpillar, chrysalis, butterfly","w":["caterpillar, egg, butterfly, chrysalis","egg, butterfly, caterpillar, chrysalis","chrysalis, egg, caterpillar, butterfly"],"h":"Think about which tiny stage comes first, before anything hatches.","e":"A butterfly's life cycle goes egg, caterpillar, chrysalis, then adult butterfly."},{"p":"When worms and mushrooms break down dead leaves in the garden, they put nutrients back into the soil. Why does this matter for the habitat?","a":"The nutrients help new plants grow.","w":["It makes the sunlight brighter for plants.","It gives nearby animals thicker fur.","It turns the dead leaves into small rocks."],"h":"Think about what plants need from the soil to grow big and healthy.","e":"Decomposers return nutrients to the soil, which helps new plants grow and keeps the habitat healthy."},{"p":"Read: \"This biome is a huge stretch of salty water where fish, whales, and dolphins swim.\" Which biome is being described?","a":"the ocean","w":["the desert","the tundra","the grassland"],"h":"Pay attention to the clue about salty water.","e":"The ocean biome is a vast area of salt water that is home to many sea animals."},{"p":"Read: \"Wide open land is covered with lots of grass and only a few trees. Zebras, lions, and antelopes live here.\" Which biome is this?","a":"grassland","w":["ocean","tundra","rainforest"],"h":"Focus on the clue about grass and very few trees.","e":"A grassland biome is open land full of grass with few trees, home to grazing animals and their predators."},{"p":"A colorful tree frog lives where it is warm and rains almost every single day, surrounded by tall, leafy trees. Which biome is its home?","a":"rainforest","w":["desert","tundra","grassland"],"h":"Think about the biome with lots of rain and tall trees packed together.","e":"A rainforest biome is warm and wet with tall trees, giving frogs plenty of water and hiding spots."},{"p":"In the food chain grass, then mouse, then snake, then hawk, which living thing gets its energy STRAIGHT from the sun?","a":"the grass","w":["the mouse","the snake","the hawk"],"h":"Only one of these can make its own food using sunlight.","e":"Producers like grass capture the sun's energy first, then pass it along the food chain."},{"p":"In the field, a fox chases and eats a rabbit. In this pair, the rabbit is the —","a":"prey","w":["predator","producer","decomposer"],"h":"Think about which animal is being hunted and eaten.","e":"The prey is the animal that gets hunted and eaten, while the predator does the hunting."},{"p":"A fish uses its gills to take in oxygen from the water so it can breathe. Gills are an adaptation that helps the fish —","a":"get oxygen underwater","w":["make its own food from sunlight","stay warm in freezing ice","hide from hungry predators"],"h":"Think about what a fish needs to breathe while living in water.","e":"Gills are an adaptation that let fish pull oxygen out of water so they can breathe underwater."},{"p":"Why do most food chains almost always START with a plant?","a":"Plants make their own food using sunlight, giving energy to the whole chain.","w":["Plants hunt and eat other animals for energy.","Plants are usually the biggest living things.","Plants break down dead things into fresh soil."],"h":"Think about where the energy in a food chain first comes from.","e":"Plants are producers that turn sunlight into food, so they start the food chain by giving energy to everything else."},{"p":"Read: \"A jackrabbit in the hot desert has very large ears. Warm blood flowing through the thin ears lets heat escape into the air.\" How do the big ears help the jackrabbit?","a":"They help it stay cool in the heat.","w":["They help it stay warm in the cold.","They help it make its own food.","They help it swim across water."],"h":"Remember the passage says heat escapes through the ears, and the desert is very hot.","e":"Letting heat escape through big ears is an adaptation that helps the jackrabbit cool off in the hot desert."},{"p":"Read: \"A vulture glides down to eat a zebra that was already lying dead on the ground. The vulture did not hunt or kill it.\" An animal that eats animals that are already dead is called a —","a":"scavenger","w":["predator","decomposer","herbivore"],"h":"Think about whether the vulture killed its meal or found it already dead.","e":"A scavenger eats animals that are already dead instead of hunting them, so the vulture is a scavenger."},{"p":"Read: \"An owl sleeps all day and comes out at night. Its very large eyes help it see in the dark to find food.\" An animal that is awake and active at night is called —","a":"nocturnal","w":["migrating","hibernating","camouflaged"],"h":"Think about what time of day the owl is busy looking for food.","e":"Animals that are active at night and rest during the day are nocturnal; the owl's big eyes help it see in the dark."},{"p":"Read: \"A harmless hoverfly has yellow and black stripes that make it look just like a stinging wasp. Birds leave it alone because they think it will sting.\" A harmless animal copying a dangerous one to stay safe is called —","a":"mimicry","w":["camouflage","hibernation","migration"],"h":"The fly can't really sting; it only looks like something that can.","e":"Mimicry is when a harmless animal looks like a dangerous one so predators leave it alone."},{"p":"Read: \"In a forest, wolves hunt and eat deer. One year, all the wolves move away and none are left.\" What will most likely happen to the number of deer?","a":"The deer population will grow because nothing is hunting them.","w":["The deer will all die out right away without the wolves.","The deer will become producers and make their own food.","The deer will stop eating plants and start eating meat."],"h":"Think about what the wolves were doing to the deer before they left.","e":"Predators keep prey numbers in check, so with no wolves hunting them the deer population will most likely grow."},{"p":"Read: \"In a meadow there are thousands of grasshoppers but only a few hawks near the top of the food chain.\" Why are there usually FEWER hawks than grasshoppers?","a":"Energy is lost at each step, so there is less food to support animals near the top.","w":["Hawks make their own food, so they do not need to eat very much.","Grasshoppers are producers that never run out of energy.","Hawks are much smaller, so many more can fit in the meadow."],"h":"Think about how much energy is passed along each time one animal eats another.","e":"Energy is lost at every step of a food chain, so top predators like hawks are fewer than the animals below them."},{"p":"Read: \"One bird has a short, thick beak that cracks hard seeds. Another bird has a long, thin beak that sips nectar from flowers.\" What does the shape of a bird's beak best help it do?","a":"get the kind of food it eats","w":["fly faster through the sky","stay warm in cold weather","hide from hungry predators"],"h":"Notice that each beak shape matches a different meal.","e":"A beak's shape is an adaptation that helps a bird eat its particular food."},{"p":"Read: \"A bee lands on a flower to drink sweet nectar. As it drinks, yellow pollen sticks to its body and rubs onto the next flower it visits.\" How does this help BOTH living things?","a":"The bee gets food, and the flower gets its pollen carried to make seeds.","w":["The bee gets pollen to eat, and the flower gets to fly away.","The flower gets food, and the bee grows brand-new petals.","The bee makes its own food, and the flower hunts insects."],"h":"Think about what the bee takes and what it carries to the next flower.","e":"In pollination the bee gets nectar for food while it moves pollen so the flower can make seeds, helping both."},{"p":"Read: \"A fox runs through tall weeds, and prickly seeds called burrs stick to its fur. Later the burrs fall off far away, and new plants grow there.\" How do the burrs help the plant?","a":"They help the plant's seeds travel to new places to grow.","w":["They help the plant make its own food from sunlight.","They help the plant scare away all hungry animals.","They help the plant stay warm during the cold winter."],"h":"Think about where the seeds end up after the fox runs away.","e":"This is seed dispersal: sticking to animal fur helps a plant spread its seeds to new places."},{"p":"Read: \"A baby grasshopper hatches from an egg and already looks like a tiny grasshopper. It just grows bigger and never forms a cocoon or chrysalis.\" How is a grasshopper's life cycle DIFFERENT from a butterfly's?","a":"A grasshopper's young looks like a small adult and skips the cocoon stage.","w":["A grasshopper hatches as a caterpillar and then forms a cocoon.","A grasshopper starts life as an adult and slowly grows younger.","A grasshopper makes its own food and never needs to hatch."],"h":"Compare the baby grasshopper's shape to a fuzzy caterpillar.","e":"A young grasshopper already looks like a small adult, so it does not go through a cocoon or chrysalis stage like a butterfly."},{"p":"Read: \"This place has four seasons. Many trees grow leaves in spring and drop them every fall. Deer, squirrels, and owls live among the trees.\" Which biome is being described?","a":"deciduous forest","w":["desert","tundra","ocean"],"h":"Think about a biome with trees that lose their leaves each autumn.","e":"A deciduous forest has four seasons and trees that drop their leaves in the fall."},{"p":"Read: \"A calm lake is full of lily pads, frogs, and fish. The water is not salty at all.\" Which biome best matches this place?","a":"freshwater","w":["ocean","desert","grassland"],"h":"The clue is in the water: is it salty or not salty?","e":"Lakes, ponds, and rivers with water that is not salty are freshwater biomes, unlike the salty ocean."},{"p":"Read: \"A field has just enough grass to feed about 20 rabbits. This spring, 60 rabbits are living in the field.\" What will most likely happen?","a":"There will not be enough grass, so some rabbits will go hungry.","w":["The grass will make extra energy so every rabbit eats plenty.","The rabbits will start eating other rabbits to survive.","The extra rabbits will become producers and grow more grass."],"h":"Compare how much grass there is to how many mouths need to eat.","e":"A habitat can only feed so many animals; when there are too many rabbits for the food, some will go hungry."},{"p":"Read: \"When wolves hunt, they work together in a group called a pack to chase down a large animal like an elk.\" Hunting together in a pack is an example of what kind of adaptation?","a":"a behavioral adaptation, something an animal does","w":["a structural adaptation, a special body part","a stage in the animal's life cycle","a type of habitat where it lives"],"h":"Is 'hunting in a group' a body part or an action?","e":"A behavioral adaptation is something an animal does to survive, like wolves hunting together in a pack."},{"p":"Read: \"A tiny poison dart frog is bright red and blue. Its flashy colors warn predators, 'I taste terrible and I'm poisonous, so don't eat me!'\" These bright warning colors help the frog by —","a":"telling predators it is dangerous to eat","w":["helping it blend in with the green leaves","helping it make its own food from sunlight","keeping it warm on cold rainy nights"],"h":"The frog is easy to see on purpose; why might that be helpful?","e":"Bright warning colors are an adaptation that tells predators the animal is poisonous or tastes bad, so they leave it alone."},{"p":"Read: \"A whale swims in the icy cold ocean. Under its skin is a thick layer of fat called blubber.\" How does the blubber most help the whale?","a":"It keeps the whale warm in the cold water.","w":["It helps the whale make its own food.","It helps the whale breathe underwater.","It helps the whale hide from other fish."],"h":"Think about what a thick layer of fat does in freezing water.","e":"Blubber is a thick fat layer, a structural adaptation that keeps the whale warm in cold ocean water."},{"p":"Read: \"In a forest, worms, mushrooms, and tiny bacteria normally break down dead leaves and animals. Imagine one day ALL the decomposers disappeared.\" What would most likely happen?","a":"Dead plants and animals would pile up and nutrients would not return to the soil.","w":["Plants would grow faster because the soil would be cleaner.","The dead leaves would turn into producers all on their own.","Nothing would change because decomposers are not important."],"h":"Remember what decomposers do with dead stuff and with the soil.","e":"Decomposers recycle nutrients back into the soil; without them, dead things would pile up and the soil would lose its nutrients."},{"p":"Read: \"When winter comes, an apple tree drops all its leaves and stops growing. It rests until warm weather returns in spring.\" A plant resting and stopping its growth through the cold winter is called —","a":"dormancy","w":["migration","hibernation","pollination"],"h":"Animals rest deeply in winter; this is the plant's version of that winter rest.","e":"Dormancy is when a plant stops growing and rests through the cold winter, then grows again in spring."},{"p":"Read: \"In a food web, an owl eats both mice and voles. One year, all the mice disappear from the area.\" Why can the owl most likely still survive?","a":"It can eat voles instead of the missing mice.","w":["It can start making its own food from sunlight.","It can turn into a producer to feed itself.","It will stop needing to eat any food at all."],"h":"Remember the owl had more than one thing on its menu.","e":"In a food web, animals often have more than one food source, so the owl can eat voles when the mice are gone."}],"s.3.forces":[{"p":"Maya opens her desk drawer by grabbing the handle and moving it toward her body. Is she using a push or a pull?","a":"A pull, because she moves it toward herself","w":["A push, because she moves it away from herself","Neither, because drawers move by themselves","Both a push and a pull at the same time"],"h":"Think about which way the drawer moves compared to Maya's body.","e":"A pull is a force that moves an object closer to you, so pulling the handle toward her is a pull."},{"p":"Diego lets go of his apple above his lunch tray. Which way will the apple move?","a":"Down toward the tray","w":["Up toward the ceiling","Sideways across the table","It stays floating in the air"],"h":"Think about what happens every time you drop something.","e":"Gravity is a force that pulls objects down toward the ground, so the apple falls down."},{"p":"Zoe rolls her toy car on a smooth wood floor and then on a fuzzy carpet. Where will the car roll farther?","a":"On the smooth wood floor","w":["On the fuzzy carpet","The same distance on both","The car will not roll on either one"],"h":"Think about which surface is bumpier and slows the car more.","e":"Friction is a rubbing force that slows things down, and rough carpet makes more friction than smooth wood."},{"p":"Ava wants to move heavy boxes up into a truck more easily. A slanted board leaning from the ground to the truck is which simple machine?","a":"A ramp (inclined plane)","w":["A wheel","A magnet","A spring"],"h":"A slanted board helps you go up without lifting straight up.","e":"A ramp, also called an inclined plane, is a simple machine that makes it easier to move things to a higher place."},{"p":"Leo pushes an empty wagon and then the same wagon full of bricks with the same little push. Which one is harder to get moving?","a":"The heavy wagon full of bricks","w":["The empty wagon","They are exactly the same","Neither one can move at all"],"h":"Think about which wagon weighs more.","e":"Heavier objects need a bigger force to move, so the wagon full of bricks is harder to push."},{"p":"During recess, Priya kicks a soccer ball across the field. What kind of force does her foot give the ball?","a":"A push","w":["A pull","A magnet force","No force at all"],"h":"Think about which way the ball goes compared to her foot.","e":"A push is a force that moves an object away from you, and kicking pushes the ball away."},{"p":"Grandpa puts round wheels on the bottom of a heavy toy box. Why do wheels make the box easier to move?","a":"Wheels roll and make less friction with the floor","w":["Wheels make the box much heavier","Wheels stop the box from moving","Wheels turn off gravity under the box"],"h":"Think about how wheels touch the floor as they turn.","e":"Wheels roll instead of dragging, which lowers friction and makes the box easier to move."},{"p":"Nina jumps up as high as she can on the playground. What happens to her after she jumps?","a":"She comes back down to the ground","w":["She keeps floating higher and higher","She stays stuck in the air","She flies off sideways"],"h":"Think about what pulls everything back toward the ground.","e":"Gravity pulls Nina back down to the Earth after she jumps up."},{"p":"Theo pushes his toy truck softly and then gives it a much harder push. What happens when he pushes harder?","a":"The truck goes faster and farther","w":["The truck goes slower and stops sooner","The truck does not move at all","The truck moves backward instead"],"h":"Think about a big push compared to a tiny push.","e":"A bigger push is a bigger force, so it makes the truck move faster and farther."},{"p":"Ella climbs to the top of the slide and lets go. What force pulls her down the slide?","a":"Gravity","w":["A magnet","A pull from her friend","Friction pushing her up"],"h":"Think about the same force that makes things fall.","e":"Gravity pulls Ella down the slide toward the ground."},{"p":"Jordan pulls his little sister in a red wagon down the street. The rope goes tight and the wagon follows him. What is Jordan doing to the wagon?","a":"Pulling it, because it moves toward him","w":["Pushing it, because it moves away from him","Lifting it straight up off the ground","Making it float with no force"],"h":"Which way does the wagon move compared to Jordan?","e":"A pull moves an object toward you, and the wagon follows Jordan as he pulls the rope."},{"p":"Two friends play on a seesaw at the park. One end goes up when the other end goes down. A seesaw is which simple machine?","a":"A lever","w":["A ramp","A wheel","A magnet"],"h":"It balances and tips on a middle point.","e":"A seesaw is a lever, a simple machine that turns on a balance point in the middle."},{"p":"Kai rubs his cold hands together very fast on a chilly morning. What does he feel his hands become?","a":"Warmer, because rubbing makes heat","w":["Colder, because rubbing makes ice","Wetter, because rubbing makes water","Heavier, because rubbing adds weight"],"h":"Think about what rubbing two things together makes.","e":"Friction between his rubbing hands makes heat, so his hands feel warmer."},{"p":"Mia puts a paperclip on top of a thin sheet of paper and moves a magnet under the paper. What happens to the paperclip?","a":"It moves and follows the magnet","w":["It stays still and does nothing","It falls straight through the paper","It turns into plastic"],"h":"Think about whether a magnet's pull can reach through thin paper.","e":"A magnet's pulling force can work through thin paper, so the paperclip follows the magnet."},{"p":"A ball is rolling across the floor. What force will slowly make it stop even if nobody touches it?","a":"Friction between the ball and the floor","w":["A push from the air behind it","A magnet inside the floor","Gravity pulling it sideways"],"h":"Think about the rubbing between the ball and the ground.","e":"Friction is the rubbing force between the ball and floor that slows the ball until it stops."},{"p":"Ling raises the school flag by pulling down on a rope that runs over a little wheel at the very top of the flagpole. The flag goes up as she pulls down. Which simple machine is she using?","a":"A pulley","w":["A wedge","A screw","A ramp"],"h":"Think about the spinning wheel at the top that the rope goes over.","e":"A pulley is a wheel with a rope over it that lets you change the direction of your pull to lift things."},{"p":"Marcus pops the cap off a bottle by pushing down on the far end of a bottle opener, and the cap lifts up. He pushes down on one end to lift the other end. Which simple machine works this way?","a":"A lever","w":["A pulley","A wheel and axle","A ramp"],"h":"Think about pushing down on one end to make the other end go up.","e":"A lever turns on a resting point so pushing one end down makes the other end lift up."},{"p":"Priya turns a round doorknob, which spins a little rod that pulls the latch back so the door opens. A round handle turns a rod in the middle. Which simple machine is the doorknob?","a":"A wheel and axle","w":["A pulley","A wedge","A lever"],"h":"Notice the round part turning the skinny rod in the center.","e":"A wheel and axle is a round wheel joined to a rod (the axle) that turns together to do work."},{"p":"At snack time Owen presses a knife straight down onto an apple, and the thin blade splits the apple into two pieces. The sharp, slanted blade pushes the apple apart. Which simple machine is the blade?","a":"A wedge","w":["A screw","A pulley","A wheel and axle"],"h":"Think about the thin sharp edge that pushes two sides apart.","e":"A wedge is a thin, slanted edge that pushes things apart when you press it into them."},{"p":"Grandma screws the lid onto a jar of jam. The lid has spiral ridges that wind around and around, pulling the lid down tight as she twists. Which simple machine has these spiral ridges?","a":"A screw","w":["A lever","A pulley","A wedge"],"h":"Look for the ridges that wind around like a spiral staircase.","e":"A screw is a ridge wrapped in a spiral around a post that holds things together when you twist it."},{"p":"Two teams play tug-of-war and pull on the rope exactly as hard as each other. The knot in the middle does not move at all. Why does the rope stay still?","a":"The two pulls are equal, so the forces are balanced","w":["Nobody is pulling on the rope at all","There are no forces on the rope right now","Only one team is really pulling"],"h":"Think about what happens when two forces are the same size but point opposite ways.","e":"When forces are balanced (equal and opposite), they cancel out and the object does not move."},{"p":"Sofia skates on smooth ice and glides a long, long way without stopping. On the sidewalk she can barely slide at all. Why does she slide so far on the ice?","a":"Ice is very smooth, so there is very little friction to slow her","w":["Ice pushes her forward with extra force","Ice has more friction than the sidewalk","Gravity is stronger on the ice"],"h":"Think about how bumpy or smooth each surface is.","e":"Smooth surfaces like ice have very little friction, so moving things slide much farther."},{"p":"Jamal holds a magnet near four things on the table: a plastic ring, a wooden block, a steel spoon, and a rubber eraser. Which one will the magnet pull toward it?","a":"The steel spoon","w":["The plastic ring","The wooden block","The rubber eraser"],"h":"Magnets only grab things made of certain metals.","e":"Magnets attract objects made of iron or steel, but not plastic, wood, or rubber."},{"p":"Ruby drops her toy soldier that has a small parachute. Instead of falling fast, it floats down slowly. What pushes up on the parachute to slow the toy's fall?","a":"Air pushing against the parachute (air resistance)","w":["A magnet inside the parachute","The parachute has no gravity on it","Friction from the ground below"],"h":"Think about what the wide parachute has to push through as it falls.","e":"Air resistance is the air pushing back on a falling object, and a wide parachute catches lots of air to fall slowly."},{"p":"Ethan drops a heavy rock and a light feather from the same shelf at the same time. Which way do BOTH of them move?","a":"Both are pulled straight down toward the ground","w":["Only the rock is pulled down; the feather is not","Both float up toward the ceiling","Both move sideways across the room"],"h":"Think about the force that pulls every object toward the Earth.","e":"Gravity pulls all objects down toward the Earth, no matter how heavy or light they are."},{"p":"Noah holds two bar magnets and slowly pushes the ends together, but they shove apart and will not touch. What does this tell him about those two ends?","a":"They are the same kind of pole, so they push each other away","w":["They are opposite poles, so they pull together","One magnet has run out of magnet power","They are made of wood, not metal"],"h":"Remember what happens when two of the SAME magnet poles meet.","e":"Like poles (two norths or two souths) repel, or push away from each other."},{"p":"Coach tells Ava to run and stop quickly on the gym floor without slipping, so she wears rubber-soled sneakers. How do the rubber soles help her stop without sliding?","a":"The rough rubber makes more friction to grip the floor","w":["The rubber makes the floor more slippery","The rubber removes all friction with the floor","The rubber makes gravity pull harder"],"h":"Think about grip, and whether rough rubber makes sliding easier or harder.","e":"Friction is a force that grips between surfaces, and rough rubber soles make more friction so shoes do not slide."},{"p":"Dad wants to roll a wheelbarrow up to the porch. He can push it up a short, steep ramp or a long, gentle ramp to the same porch height. Which ramp makes the job feel easier?","a":"The long, gentle ramp","w":["The short, steep ramp","Both ramps feel exactly the same","Neither ramp helps at all"],"h":"Think about which slope is less steep to climb.","e":"A longer, gentler ramp lets you use less force at a time, so the same load feels easier to move up."},{"p":"Mila's bike squeaks and is hard to pedal because the chain is dry. Dad adds slippery oil to the chain and now it moves easily. Why does the oil help?","a":"The oil lowers the friction between the moving parts","w":["The oil adds more friction to the chain","The oil makes the bike heavier to push","The oil turns the chain into a magnet"],"h":"Think about whether oil makes surfaces slide more easily or less easily.","e":"Oil is a lubricant that lowers friction, so the parts rub less and slide past each other easily."},{"p":"Ben is swinging on the playground. His friend gives him a push forward each time he swings backward to the top. What does pushing at the right moment do to Ben's swing?","a":"It makes him swing higher and faster","w":["It makes him slow down and stop","It makes him swing exactly the same as before","It turns his swing into a straight line"],"h":"Think about adding a force in the same direction the swing is going.","e":"Adding a push in the direction of motion adds force, so the swing speeds up and goes higher."},{"p":"Carmen is riding her scooter downhill and squeezes the brake, which presses a rubber pad against the spinning wheel. The scooter slows and stops. What force does the brake pad use to stop the wheel?","a":"Friction between the pad and the wheel","w":["Magnetism pulling the wheel still","Gravity pushing the scooter backward","A pull from the handlebars"],"h":"Think about the rubbing between the pad and the moving wheel.","e":"Brakes work by pressing a pad against the wheel to make friction, which slows the moving wheel down."},{"p":"Hana rolls a ball straight ahead, then a friend gently taps it from the side as it rolls. The ball keeps moving but now heads in a new direction. What did the friend's tap do to the ball?","a":"The tap was a force that changed the ball's direction","w":["The tap made the ball heavier","The tap removed all forces from the ball","The tap stopped the ball completely"],"h":"Think about what a push from the side does to which way something travels.","e":"A force can change an object's direction, so a side tap makes the rolling ball turn a new way."},{"p":"Ravi stretches a rubber band around his finger, then lets it go. The rubber band snaps forward and flings a small paper wad across the desk. What pushed the paper wad forward?","a":"The stretched rubber band springing back to its shape","w":["Gravity pulling the paper wad across the desk","A gust of air pushing the paper wad along","A magnet pulling the paper wad forward"],"h":"Think about the stored-up force in something stretched that wants to go back to normal.","e":"A stretched rubber band stores elastic force; when released it springs back to its shape and pushes the object forward."},{"p":"Ana builds a machine with two gears whose teeth fit together. When she turns the first gear to the right (clockwise), what does the second gear do?","a":"It turns the opposite way, to the left","w":["It turns the same way, to the right","It does not move at all","It slides straight backward"],"h":"Picture the teeth of one gear pushing on the teeth of the gear next to it.","e":"When two meshed gears touch, one pushes the other's teeth the opposite way, so connected gears spin in opposite directions."},{"p":"Milo floats a toy sailboat in the pool and blows air at the sail. The boat glides forward across the water. What kind of force does the moving air give the sail?","a":"A push","w":["A pull","A magnetic force","A sticky force"],"h":"Think about whether the moving air moves the boat toward it or away from it.","e":"Moving air (wind) presses against the sail and pushes it away, so wind is a pushing force."},{"p":"A heavy book sits still on the kitchen table. Gravity pulls the book down, but the book does not move at all. Why does the book stay still?","a":"The table pushes up as hard as gravity pulls the book down","w":["Gravity stops working when a book is on a table","The book is too heavy for any force to ever move it","There are no forces acting on the resting book"],"h":"For something to stay still, the forces on it must be even.","e":"The book has balanced forces: the table's upward push equals gravity's downward pull, so the book stays still."},{"p":"Nadia tries to run across the shallow end of the pool, but her legs move much slower than they do on land. Why is it so hard to move fast in the water?","a":"The water pushes back against her body and slows her down","w":["The water makes gravity much stronger on her legs","The water turns her legs into magnets","There are no forces on her while in the water"],"h":"Think about something pressing back on you as you push through it.","e":"Water resistance (drag) is the water pushing back against a moving object, making it harder to move quickly."},{"p":"Owen slowly slides a magnet closer and closer to a steel paperclip lying on the table. When is the magnet's pull on the paperclip the strongest?","a":"When the magnet is very close to the paperclip","w":["When the magnet is far across the table","When the magnet is halfway to the paperclip","The pull is exactly the same at every distance"],"h":"Think about whether being nearer or farther makes a magnet grab better.","e":"A magnet's force is stronger the closer it is; the pull grows weaker as the distance increases."},{"p":"Layla pushes a beach ball down under the water, and it pops right back up to the top the moment she lets go. What force pushes the beach ball up out of the water?","a":"The water pushing up on the ball","w":["Gravity pushing the ball up","A magnet at the bottom of the pool","The wind blowing across the water"],"h":"Think about what the water does to something you try to hold under it.","e":"Water pushes up on objects with a force called buoyancy, which can be strong enough to make light things float."},{"p":"One kid alone cannot budge a stuck cart, but when a friend pushes right beside them in the same direction, the cart finally rolls. Why does adding a second pusher help?","a":"The two pushes add together into one bigger force","w":["The two pushes cancel each other out to zero","The second kid removes the cart's gravity","One of the pushes turns into a pull"],"h":"Think about what happens when two forces point the same way.","e":"Forces in the same direction add together, so two pushes combine into a larger total force that can move the cart."},{"p":"Kira jumps down onto a trampoline. The stretchy springs stretch, then quickly bounce her back up into the air. What do the springs do to send her upward?","a":"They spring back to their shape and push her up","w":["They turn gravity upside down for a moment","They pull her up using tiny magnets","They make her weigh nothing at all"],"h":"Think about what a stretched spring wants to do when it is let go.","e":"A stretched spring stores elastic force and pushes back as it returns to its shape, launching Kira upward."},{"p":"Sam holds two bar magnets. When he brings the red end of one near the blue end of the other, they snap together. What are these two different ends doing?","a":"Pulling toward each other, called attracting","w":["Pushing away from each other, called repelling","Turning slowly into pieces of wood","Losing all of their magnet power"],"h":"Opposite ends of magnets behave differently than matching ends.","e":"Opposite magnetic poles attract, pulling toward each other, while matching poles push apart."},{"p":"Tomas coasts his bike to the top of a hill, then rolls down the other side without pedaling. As he goes down the hill, what happens to his speed?","a":"He speeds up because gravity pulls him downhill","w":["He slows down because gravity pushes him uphill","He stays at exactly the same speed the whole way","He stops right away because no force acts on him"],"h":"Think about which way gravity pulls and which way he is heading.","e":"Gravity pulls objects downhill, so a bike rolling down a slope speeds up as it goes."},{"p":"Priya presses her hands down hard onto a soft ball of playdough, and it flattens into a wide pancake shape. What did her push do to the playdough?","a":"It changed the playdough's shape","w":["It changed the playdough into metal","It made the playdough weigh much more","It removed all gravity from the playdough"],"h":"A force does not only move things; it can also do something to how they look.","e":"A push is a force, and a force can change an object's shape, like squashing playdough flat."},{"p":"Ben drops a flat sheet of paper and a tightly crumpled paper ball at the exact same time. The crumpled ball hits the floor first. Why does the flat sheet fall more slowly?","a":"The wide flat sheet catches more air pushing up against it","w":["The flat sheet is much heavier than the ball","Gravity does not pull on flat pieces of paper","The flat sheet is made of a different material"],"h":"Think about how much air each piece has to push through as it falls.","e":"Air resistance pushes up on falling objects; a flat sheet has more surface catching air, so it falls slower even though both weigh the same."},{"p":"Diego pushes an empty shopping cart and stops it easily. Then he pushes a cart full of heavy groceries at the same speed. What is true about stopping the full cart?","a":"It needs a bigger force to stop","w":["It needs a smaller force to stop","It stops instantly all by itself","It cannot be stopped by any force"],"h":"Think about how the heavy load changes how hard it is to change the cart's motion.","e":"Heavier objects have more mass, so a bigger force is needed to stop (or start) their motion."},{"p":"In a tug-of-war, the Blue team pulls harder than the Red team. Which way does the knot in the middle of the rope move?","a":"Toward the Blue team, because their pull is stronger","w":["Toward the Red team, because they pull less","It stays perfectly still in the middle","Straight up into the air"],"h":"When the two sides do not pull evenly, the stronger side wins.","e":"Unbalanced forces cause motion toward the stronger pull, so the knot moves toward the team pulling harder."},{"p":"Amara lifts an empty backpack with one finger, but the same backpack stuffed full of textbooks is much harder to lift off the ground. Why is the full backpack harder to lift?","a":"Gravity pulls down harder on the heavier backpack","w":["Gravity pushes up on the heavier backpack","The full backpack has turned into a magnet","There is no gravity at all on an empty backpack"],"h":"Think about how the amount of stuff inside changes the downward pull.","e":"The more mass an object has, the harder gravity pulls it down, so it weighs more and is harder to lift."},{"p":"Two players slide a puck back and forth on an air-hockey table. The puck always moves in the same direction the paddle strikes it. What decides which way the puck slides?","a":"The direction of the push from the paddle","w":["The color painted on the top of the puck","The gravity underneath the game table","The temperature of the room they play in"],"h":"Watch which way the paddle pushes and which way the puck goes.","e":"A force moves an object in the direction of the push, so the puck slides the way the paddle strikes it."},{"p":"Emma holds a compass, and its little needle always swings around to point north, no matter which way she turns her body. Why does the compass needle point north?","a":"The needle is a magnet, and the whole Earth acts like a giant magnet","w":["The needle always points toward the bright sun","North is downhill, so the needle slides that way","Wind in the room keeps blowing the needle around"],"h":"The needle itself is magnetic, and something very large is affecting it.","e":"A compass needle is a small magnet that lines up with Earth's magnetism, because Earth behaves like a giant magnet."}],"s.6.cells":[{"p":"A scientist states that all living things are made of cells, cells are the basic unit of life, and all cells come from other cells. What big idea in biology is she describing?","a":"The cell theory","w":["The theory of gravity","The food chain rule","The water cycle law"],"h":"Think about which 'theory' is specifically about the building blocks of living things.","e":"The cell theory has three parts: all organisms are made of cells, the cell is the basic unit of life, and cells come from existing cells."},{"p":"Maria looks at an onion skin and her own cheek cell under a microscope. Which part is found ONLY in the plant (onion) cell and NOT in her animal cell?","a":"A cell wall","w":["A nucleus","A cell membrane","Cytoplasm"],"h":"One structure gives plants their sturdy, boxy shape that animal cells lack.","e":"Plant cells have a rigid cell wall for support; animal cells do not, though both share a membrane, nucleus, and cytoplasm."},{"p":"A green pigment in plant cells captures sunlight to make food, which is why leaves look green. Which organelle does this job?","a":"The chloroplast","w":["The mitochondrion","The nucleus","The vacuole"],"h":"The name of this organelle sounds like the word for the green color it contains.","e":"Chloroplasts carry out photosynthesis, using the green pigment chlorophyll to turn sunlight into food for the plant."},{"p":"People sometimes call the mitochondria the 'powerhouse of the cell.' Why do they earn that nickname?","a":"They release energy the cell can use","w":["They store the cell's DNA","They make new copies of the cell","They control what enters the cell"],"h":"A powerhouse is a place that produces power, or energy.","e":"Mitochondria perform cellular respiration, breaking down food to release usable energy for the cell's activities."},{"p":"Think of a cell as a school. The principal makes the big decisions and holds the important records. Which organelle acts like the principal by controlling the cell and storing its DNA?","a":"The nucleus","w":["The ribosome","The vacuole","The cell membrane"],"h":"Look for the control center that holds the genetic instructions.","e":"The nucleus directs the cell's activities and stores the DNA, the instructions for how the cell works."},{"p":"A bouncer at a club decides who gets in and who stays out. Which cell part works like a bouncer by controlling what enters and leaves the cell?","a":"The cell membrane","w":["The nucleus","The mitochondrion","The ribosome"],"h":"Think about the thin outer layer that surrounds every cell.","e":"The cell membrane is selectively permeable, controlling which substances move into and out of the cell."},{"p":"A single-celled amoeba lives its whole life as one cell, while a horse is made of trillions of cells. What word describes an organism made of only ONE cell?","a":"Unicellular","w":["Multicellular","Bicellular","Noncellular"],"h":"The prefix 'uni-' means one, like a unicycle has one wheel.","e":"Unicellular organisms, such as bacteria and amoebas, carry out all life functions within a single cell."},{"p":"When you first put a slide under a microscope, which objective lens should you start with to find your sample most easily?","a":"The lowest-power lens","w":["The highest-power lens","No lens at all","The medium then remove it"],"h":"A wider view makes it easier to locate something small before zooming in.","e":"Starting with the lowest-power (shortest) objective gives the widest field of view, making it easy to locate and center the specimen."},{"p":"A gummy, jelly-like fluid fills the inside of a cell and holds the organelles in place, like water holding fruit in a bowl of jello. What is this fluid called?","a":"Cytoplasm","w":["Chlorophyll","Chromosome","Chloroplast"],"h":"The word starts with 'cyto-,' which means cell.","e":"Cytoplasm is the jelly-like substance that fills the cell and surrounds the organelles."},{"p":"A plant cell often has one large storage sac that holds water and helps the plant stay firm, like a full water balloon keeping its shape. Which organelle is this?","a":"The vacuole","w":["The nucleus","The ribosome","The mitochondrion"],"h":"Think of the big storage tank inside plant cells.","e":"The large central vacuole stores water and nutrients and helps keep plant cells firm and upright."},{"p":"Both plant and animal cells make proteins using tiny structures that act like factory workers assembling parts. What are these protein-builders called?","a":"Ribosomes","w":["Vacuoles","Chloroplasts","Cell walls"],"h":"These tiny structures share the first three letters with 'ribbon' and build proteins.","e":"Ribosomes are the sites of protein synthesis in both plant and animal cells."},{"p":"To calculate the total magnification of a microscope, what should you do with the eyepiece power and the objective lens power?","a":"Multiply them together","w":["Add them together","Subtract the smaller one","Divide the larger by the smaller"],"h":"The two lenses each magnify, so their effects combine by multiplication.","e":"Total magnification equals the eyepiece magnification multiplied by the objective lens magnification (for example, 10x times 40x equals 400x)."},{"p":"An elephant, an oak tree, and a human are all made of many cells working together. What word describes organisms made of many cells?","a":"Multicellular","w":["Unicellular","Microcellular","Anticellular"],"h":"The prefix 'multi-' means many, like a multivitamin has many vitamins.","e":"Multicellular organisms are made of many cells that often specialize to perform different jobs."},{"p":"Robert Hooke looked at a thin slice of cork under a microscope and saw tiny box-like spaces. What did he name these spaces, giving us a word we still use today?","a":"Cells","w":["Atoms","Molecules","Tissues"],"h":"The boxy spaces reminded him of the small rooms monks lived in.","e":"Hooke named the box-like structures 'cells' because they reminded him of the small rooms (cells) in a monastery."},{"p":"Both plant and animal cells contain a nucleus. What does this shared feature tell you about the nucleus?","a":"It is important in both types of cells","w":["It is only useful in plants","It is only useful in animals","It is not really needed at all"],"h":"Structures found in both cell types usually do a job both cells need.","e":"The nucleus is essential in both plant and animal cells because it controls activities and stores genetic information."},{"p":"A cheek cell and a leaf cell both have a cell membrane, cytoplasm, a nucleus, mitochondria, and ribosomes. Based on this list, which structure do BOTH cells share?","a":"Mitochondria","w":["Chloroplasts","A cell wall","A large central vacuole"],"h":"Cross out any parts found only in plants and see what is left.","e":"Both plant and animal cells contain mitochondria; chloroplasts, cell walls, and large vacuoles are typical of plant cells."},{"p":"A microscope uses lenses to make small objects appear larger. What is the main reason scientists needed to invent the microscope to study cells?","a":"Most cells are too small to see with the eyes alone","w":["Cells are too colorful to look at directly","Cells move too quickly to catch by hand","Cells are too heavy to lift and examine"],"h":"Think about the size of a single cell compared to what your eyes can see.","e":"Cells are usually microscopic, so a microscope is needed to magnify them enough to be seen and studied."},{"p":"According to the cell theory, where does a brand-new cell come from?","a":"From an existing cell that divides","w":["From nonliving dust and water","From air trapped in a container","From sunlight striking a surface"],"h":"One part of the cell theory is about how cells are produced.","e":"The cell theory states that all cells come from pre-existing cells, meaning new cells form when existing cells divide."},{"p":"A stalk of celery stays stiff and crunchy, while a slice of cooked chicken is soft and floppy. Plant cells have a tough outer layer that gives them a fixed shape and extra support. Which structure provides this rigid support?","a":"Cell wall","w":["Cell membrane","Cytoplasm","Central vacuole"],"h":"Think about the stiff, boxy layer found on the OUTSIDE of a plant cell's membrane.","e":"The cell wall is a rigid layer outside the membrane that gives plant cells their firm shape and support."},{"p":"In a busy warehouse, workers package finished products into boxes and ship them to the right addresses. Which organelle acts like this shipping department, packaging proteins and sending them where they are needed?","a":"Golgi apparatus","w":["Ribosome","Mitochondria","Nucleus"],"h":"Think about what happens to a protein AFTER it has been built, before it leaves the cell.","e":"The Golgi apparatus modifies, packages, and ships proteins to their destinations, like a cell's shipping department."},{"p":"A recycling center breaks down old, broken items and clears out waste so the building stays clean. Which organelle does a similar cleanup job by digesting worn-out parts and waste inside the cell?","a":"Lysosome","w":["Central vacuole","Chloroplast","Ribosome"],"h":"Think about the part of a cell that acts like a garbage disposal or recycling crew.","e":"Lysosomes contain enzymes that break down waste and worn-out cell parts, acting as the cell's recycling center."},{"p":"Imagine a network of hallways and conveyor belts that carry materials from one area of a factory to another. Which organelle acts like this transport system, moving materials through the cell?","a":"Endoplasmic reticulum","w":["Cell membrane","Golgi apparatus","Cytoplasm"],"h":"Its name means a 'network inside' the cell.","e":"The endoplasmic reticulum is a folded network of membranes that transports materials throughout the cell."},{"p":"A microscope has an eyepiece labeled 10x and a low-power objective lens labeled 4x. What is the total magnification when using this objective?","a":"40x","w":["14x","4x","400x"],"h":"Combine the two lens powers using multiplication, not addition.","e":"Total magnification equals eyepiece power times objective power: 10 x 4 = 40x."},{"p":"Jamal uses a 10x eyepiece with a 10x objective lens. Priya uses a 10x eyepiece with a 40x objective lens. Whose microscope makes the sample look larger, and by how much?","a":"Priya's, because 400x is larger than 100x","w":["Jamal's, because 100x is larger than 400x","Priya's, because 50x is larger than 20x","They are equal, because both use a 10x eyepiece"],"h":"Multiply each person's two lens powers first, then compare the totals.","e":"Multiplying the lenses gives Priya 10 x 40 = 400x and Jamal 10 x 10 = 100x, so Priya's image is larger."},{"p":"Under a compound microscope, letters look upside down and backward. When Sam slowly moves the slide to the LEFT, the image appears to move to the RIGHT. Why does this happen?","a":"The microscope's lenses flip and reverse the image","w":["The slide is moving too fast to see clearly","The sample is dead, so it cannot move","The light is too bright and confuses your eyes"],"h":"Think about how the lenses change the image before it reaches your eye.","e":"A compound microscope inverts and reverses the image, so movements appear in the opposite direction."},{"p":"Read: 'A bacterium is a single living cell, but unlike a plant or animal cell it has no nucleus. Its genetic material floats freely inside the cell.' Which statement about the bacterium is correct?","a":"It is a living cell even though it has no nucleus","w":["It cannot be alive because it has no nucleus","It must be a plant cell because it contains DNA","It is not really a cell because it is so tiny"],"h":"Remember the cell theory's rule about what counts as living, and that a nucleus is not on that list.","e":"Bacteria are prokaryotes: living cells that lack a nucleus but still carry DNA freely in the cytoplasm."},{"p":"Long ago, people believed rotting meat created maggots out of nothing. Later experiments showed maggots only appeared when flies laid eggs on the meat. Which part of the cell theory does this evidence support?","a":"All cells come from other living cells","w":["Cells are the smallest unit of life","All living things are made of cells","Plant and animal cells are different"],"h":"Focus on the question of where brand-new living things come from.","e":"Cell theory states that cells arise only from pre-existing cells, disproving the idea of spontaneous generation."},{"p":"A student says, 'Plant cells make their own food, so they don't need mitochondria.' Why is this reasoning WRONG?","a":"Plant cells still need mitochondria to release energy from the food they make","w":["Plant cells have no mitochondria, so the student is correct","Plant cells use chloroplasts instead of mitochondria for every job","Plant cells get all their energy straight from sunlight with no organelle"],"h":"Making food and releasing the energy stored in that food are two different jobs.","e":"Plant cells have chloroplasts to make food AND mitochondria to release its stored energy, so both organelles are needed."},{"p":"A houseplant left without water for a week goes limp and droops over the side of its pot. Which cell structure lost water, causing the plant to lose its firmness?","a":"The large central vacuole","w":["The nucleus","The mitochondria","The ribosomes"],"h":"Think about which plant organelle normally stores water and keeps cells plump.","e":"The central vacuole stores water; when it empties, plant cells lose their firmness (turgor) and the plant wilts."},{"p":"Oxygen is more concentrated outside a cell than inside it, and oxygen moves into the cell through the membrane. What does this show about the cell membrane?","a":"It lets certain substances pass through it","w":["It blocks everything from entering the cell","It only allows water to leave the cell","It is a solid barrier with no way through"],"h":"Think about what the word 'selectively permeable' is describing.","e":"The cell membrane is selectively permeable, allowing some materials such as oxygen to move across it."},{"p":"In an experiment, scientists carefully remove the nucleus from a single cell. What is the most likely result for that cell?","a":"It loses its control center and cannot function properly for long","w":["It grows much faster because it now has more space inside","It instantly changes into a plant cell","It becomes a whole multicellular organism"],"h":"Recall which organelle directs the cell's activities and stores its instructions.","e":"The nucleus controls the cell and holds its DNA, so a cell without it cannot function normally for long."},{"p":"A cell's instructions for building proteins and carrying out its activities are written in a special molecule kept safely inside one organelle. What is this instruction-carrying molecule called?","a":"DNA","w":["Cytoplasm","Chlorophyll","Ribosome"],"h":"It works like the cell's recipe book or instruction manual.","e":"DNA stores the genetic instructions for the cell and is kept inside the nucleus."},{"p":"On a soccer team, the goalie, forwards, and defenders each have different jobs but work together to win the game. How is a multicellular organism like this team?","a":"Different cells specialize in different jobs and work together","w":["Every cell performs the exact same job at the same time","Each cell lives completely on its own with no help","One single cell does all of the body's work alone"],"h":"Think about division of labor, where different members handle different tasks.","e":"In multicellular organisms, specialized cells cooperate, dividing the labor much like teammates with different roles."},{"p":"A student wants to view a bacterium, an ant's leg, and a strand of human hair. The bacterium is by far the smallest of the three. Which one would require the HIGHEST magnification to see clearly?","a":"The bacterium","w":["The ant's leg","The strand of human hair","All three need the same magnification"],"h":"The smaller an object is, the more it must be enlarged to see it.","e":"Smaller objects require higher magnification, and the bacterium is the smallest object listed."},{"p":"While preparing a slide, a student places a drop of water on the sample and gently lowers a thin coverslip on top before viewing. Why add the water and coverslip?","a":"To keep the sample flat, moist, and held in place for viewing","w":["To magnify the sample without using any lenses","To kill the sample so that it stops moving","To color the sample a darker shade"],"h":"Think about what keeps a living, see-through sample steady and clear under the lens.","e":"A wet mount keeps specimens hydrated and flat so that light passes through them clearly for viewing."},{"p":"Cheek cells are almost see-through, so a student adds a drop of blue dye before placing them under the microscope. Why do scientists stain cells like this?","a":"To make cell structures easier to see and tell apart","w":["To make the cells grow larger under the lens","To turn animal cells into plant cells","To increase the microscope's magnification power"],"h":"Think about the problem of contrast when structures are nearly transparent.","e":"Stains add contrast, making transparent structures like the nucleus stand out and easier to identify."},{"p":"On high power, a student's slide looks blurry. Because the lens is already very close to the slide, which control should be used to sharpen the image without cracking the slide?","a":"The fine adjustment knob","w":["The coarse adjustment knob","The diaphragm that controls light","A switch to the highest objective lens"],"h":"On high power the lens is already near the slide, so only a small, gentle movement is safe.","e":"The fine adjustment knob makes tiny focus changes; the coarse knob moves the stage too far and can crash the lens into the slide on high power."},{"p":"A shriveled raisin is dropped into a cup of plain water and by morning it has swelled up plump and round. Water moved into the raisin's cells. What does this show about the cell membrane?","a":"It lets water pass across it into the cell","w":["It blocks every substance from entering the cell","It is a solid wall that water cannot cross","It makes food inside the cell using water"],"h":"Think about which direction the water traveled and what it had to cross to get there.","e":"This is osmosis: the cell membrane is selectively permeable, so water can move across it from where there is more water to where there is less."},{"p":"A leaf cell captures sunlight to build sugar and later breaks that sugar down to release usable energy. Which pair of organelles carries out these two jobs?","a":"Chloroplast builds sugar; mitochondria releases energy","w":["Nucleus builds sugar; ribosome releases energy","Vacuole builds sugar; cell wall releases energy","Cell membrane builds sugar; cytoplasm releases energy"],"h":"One organelle is green and uses light; another is nicknamed the powerhouse.","e":"Chloroplasts perform photosynthesis to make sugar, while mitochondria perform cellular respiration to release energy from that sugar. Plant cells have both."},{"p":"Almost all cells are microscopically tiny instead of large. Being small gives a cell much more surface area compared to its volume. What does this extra surface help the cell do more efficiently?","a":"Exchange nutrients and wastes across its membrane","w":["Store far more DNA inside its nucleus","Produce a larger amount of chlorophyll","Build a thicker and stronger cell wall"],"h":"Materials enter and leave a cell only through its outer boundary.","e":"A high surface-area-to-volume ratio lets small cells move nutrients in and wastes out quickly through the membrane, which is why cells stay tiny."},{"p":"A plant cell's stiff outer wall is built mainly from a tough structural fiber that also makes wood and paper strong. What is this material?","a":"Cellulose","w":["Starch","Protein","Fat"],"h":"This is a support fiber, not a molecule used to store energy or build enzymes.","e":"Plant cell walls are made largely of cellulose, a strong carbohydrate fiber that provides rigid structural support."},{"p":"Using a tiny single-lens microscope he built himself, a Dutch cloth merchant was the first person to observe tiny creatures swimming in a drop of pond water, which he called 'animalcules.' What did he discover?","a":"Living microorganisms too small to see with the eye","w":["The nucleus at the center of a cell","The first box-like cells in a slice of cork","The rule that cells come from other cells"],"h":"His name was Anton van Leeuwenhoek, and he looked at living things in water.","e":"Leeuwenhoek discovered microorganisms (microbes), revealing an entire living world invisible to the unaided eye."},{"p":"A microscope's eyepiece is labeled 10x and its strongest objective lens is labeled 100x. What is the highest total magnification this microscope can reach?","a":"1000x","w":["110x","100x","10,000x"],"h":"Total magnification comes from combining the two lens powers, not adding them.","e":"Total magnification equals eyepiece power times objective power: 10 x 100 = 1000x."},{"p":"Two microscopes both magnify a sample 400 times, yet one shows blurry blobs while the other shows sharp, separate details. The clearer scope can tell two very close points apart. What is this ability called?","a":"Resolution","w":["Magnification","Illumination","Total power"],"h":"This describes clarity and detail, not just how large something looks.","e":"Resolution is the ability to distinguish two close points as separate; a microscope can magnify greatly yet still have poor resolution, giving blurry images."},{"p":"Both a plant cell and an animal cell can contain vacuoles, but the plant cell usually has one that is far larger. Which statement about vacuoles is TRUE?","a":"Plant cells often have one large vacuole, while animal cells have small ones","w":["Only animal cells contain any vacuoles at all","Both cells always have equally large vacuoles","Vacuoles are found only in plant cells and never in animal cells"],"h":"Think about which cell uses a big water-filled sac to stay firm.","e":"A plant cell typically has one large central vacuole for water storage and support, while animal cells have small vacuoles or several tiny ones."},{"p":"A red blood cell has no nucleus and a flattened, dented disc shape, giving it extra room and surface for carrying oxygen through your veins. This close match between shape and job is an example of what?","a":"A cell's structure being suited to its function","w":["All cells in the body being exactly identical","A cell that is no longer considered alive","A single-celled organism living on its own"],"h":"Ask why this cell's unusual shape might make its specific task easier.","e":"This shows cell specialization: in multicellular organisms, different cells have structures shaped to fit the specific jobs they perform."},{"p":"After making a wet mount, a student sees several perfectly round shapes with thick dark rims and clear empty centers. These are not cells. What are they most likely?","a":"Air bubbles trapped under the coverslip","w":["Unusually large cell nuclei","Water-filled plant vacuoles","Stained bacteria clustered together"],"h":"Think about what can get trapped when a coverslip is lowered onto water too quickly.","e":"Air bubbles trapped under the coverslip look like round rings with dark outlines; lowering the coverslip slowly at an angle helps avoid them."},{"p":"The image under a microscope looks too dark to make out any details. Which part should the student adjust to allow more light to pass up through the slide?","a":"The diaphragm","w":["The fine adjustment knob","The eyepiece lens","The objective lens"],"h":"Look for the part that controls how much light reaches the specimen, not the part that focuses it.","e":"The diaphragm controls how much light passes through the specimen; opening it brightens a too-dark image without changing focus."},{"p":"In your body, similar muscle cells join to form muscle tissue, and several tissues combine to build your heart. In the levels of organization, your heart is an example of what?","a":"An organ","w":["A tissue","A single cell","An organ system"],"h":"It is one step above tissues but not yet a whole cooperating system of parts.","e":"The levels go cells to tissues to organs to organ systems; the heart is an organ made of several tissues working together."},{"p":"When a student switches from the 4x objective to the 40x objective, the sample looks much bigger but only a small part is visible and the view looks dimmer. Why does less of the sample appear at higher magnification?","a":"Higher magnification shows a smaller area, called the field of view","w":["The sample physically shrank on the slide","The eyepiece lens stopped working correctly","The microscope's light source turned off"],"h":"Zooming in on anything means you see a closer look at less of it.","e":"Higher magnification narrows the field of view and spreads the available light, so you see a smaller, dimmer portion of the specimen in greater detail."},{"p":"Biology classes often start by viewing thin onion skin or a single elodea leaf under the microscope. Why do these make good samples for seeing plant cells?","a":"They are thin enough for light to pass through and reveal clear box-like cells","w":["They contain no cells, so they are easy to focus on","They are the only living things that actually have cells","They glow brightly on their own under the lens"],"h":"A compound microscope shines light up through the specimen, so thickness matters.","e":"Light must pass through a specimen in a compound microscope, so thin plant tissues like onion skin let you clearly see the boxy cells and their walls."},{"p":"Read: 'Yeast, used to make bread dough rise, is a fungus made of just a single cell. Unlike a bacterium, each yeast cell contains a true nucleus.' Which statement is correct?","a":"Yeast is a unicellular organism that has a nucleus","w":["Yeast is multicellular, like the body of a mushroom","Yeast has no genetic material anywhere inside it","Yeast is a plant cell packed with green chloroplasts"],"h":"The passage tells you both how many cells yeast has and whether it has a nucleus.","e":"Yeast is a single-celled (unicellular) fungus with a true nucleus, showing that not all one-celled organisms are nucleus-free bacteria."},{"p":"Scientists sort cells into two groups: those that lack a nucleus and those that have one. What term describes a cell WITHOUT a nucleus, such as a bacterium?","a":"A prokaryotic cell","w":["A eukaryotic cell","A multicellular cell","A plant cell"],"h":"One prefix means 'before a nucleus' and the other means 'true nucleus.'","e":"Prokaryotic cells, such as bacteria, have no nucleus and keep their DNA free in the cytoplasm, unlike eukaryotic cells."}],"e.11.litanalysis":[{"p":"Read: \"The old lighthouse had gone dark years ago, but Mara still climbed its stairs each evening, running her palm along the cold, rusted rail. She told no one why.\"\n\nThe darkened lighthouse most likely symbolizes what?","a":"A guiding hope or purpose that has faded but is not forgotten","w":["The literal danger of ships wrecking near the rocky coast","Mara's private fear of heights that she tries to overcome","The town's ongoing plan to rebuild its tourism industry"],"h":"Consider what a lighthouse normally provides and what \"gone dark\" adds to that meaning.","e":"Symbolism uses a concrete object to stand for an abstract idea; the darkened lighthouse represents lost guidance or hope that Mara still tends."},{"p":"Read: \"The fire station on Maple Street burned to the ground on Tuesday. The crew had been three towns over, teaching a seminar titled 'Preventing Household Fires.'\"\n\nWhich type of irony is present in this passage?","a":"Situational irony, because the outcome contradicts what one would expect","w":["Verbal irony, because the narrator states the opposite of the truth","Dramatic irony, because readers know a secret the crew does not","No irony, because the events are simply an unlucky coincidence"],"h":"Ask whether the actual outcome sharply contradicts a reasonable expectation.","e":"Situational irony occurs when the actual outcome (a fire station burning while its crew teaches fire prevention) contradicts expectations."},{"p":"Read: \"'This tea is perfectly safe,' Aunt Vera said, smiling as she poured. The reader, however, had watched her stir the strange powder into the pot ten minutes earlier.\"\n\nThe passage relies primarily on which technique?","a":"Dramatic irony, a gap between reader and character knowledge","w":["Verbal irony, a speaker meaning the opposite of the words","Situational irony, an outcome that reverses expectation","Understatement, a deliberate softening of a serious fact"],"h":"Focus on the gap between what the reader knows and what a character does not.","e":"Dramatic irony occurs when the audience knows something crucial (the poisoned tea) that a character remains unaware of."},{"p":"Read: \"Soaked to the bone and shivering under the collapsing tent, Dan wiped rain from his eyes and muttered, 'What a perfect day for camping.'\"\n\nDan's remark is an example of what?","a":"Verbal irony, saying the opposite of what he means","w":["Dramatic irony, revealing what only the reader knows","Situational irony, an event that reverses expectation","A literal observation of the weather conditions"],"h":"Compare what Dan actually says with what he clearly feels.","e":"Verbal irony occurs when a speaker states the opposite of the intended meaning, as Dan does about his ruined trip."},{"p":"Read: \"Elena never raised her voice. When the clerk shorted her change, she simply counted it twice, set the coins on the counter, and waited, arms folded, until he finally looked up.\"\n\nWhat method of characterization does the author primarily use?","a":"Indirect characterization revealing traits through her actions","w":["Direct characterization stating her traits through narration","Characterization built through another character's dialogue","Characterization drawn only from her physical appearance"],"h":"Notice whether traits are stated outright or shown through behavior.","e":"Indirect characterization reveals personality through behavior; Elena's calm persistence shows her resolve without the narrator naming it."},{"p":"Read: \"By the end of final exams, Jacob's patience was a threadbare coat, worn so thin it no longer kept anything out.\"\n\nThe figurative comparison suggests that Jacob is:","a":"Nearly out of patience and easily affected by stress","w":["Literally cold and in need of warmer winter clothing","Careless about how he dresses during the exam period","Generous, giving away his belongings to other students"],"h":"Interpret the qualities of a worn-out coat applied to patience.","e":"This metaphor equates patience with a threadbare coat to convey that Jacob's tolerance is almost entirely gone."},{"p":"Read: \"The wind pried at the shutters all night, muttering complaints against the glass and testing every latch it could find.\"\n\nThe figurative language in this passage is best identified as:","a":"Personification, giving human actions to the wind","w":["Hyperbole, exaggerating the strength of the wind","Simile, comparing the wind using like or as","Metonymy, naming the wind by a related thing"],"h":"Notice the human actions the wind is described as performing.","e":"Personification assigns human behaviors (prying, muttering, testing) to the nonhuman wind."},{"p":"Read: \"Priya froze at the smell of chlorine. Suddenly she was nine again, gripping the pool's edge while her coach shouted from the deck. Then a car horn snapped her back to the parking lot.\"\n\nWhich structural device does the author use?","a":"Flashback, returning to an earlier scene before the present","w":["Foreshadowing, hinting at an event still to come","In medias res, opening in the middle of the action","Frame narrative, a story enclosed within another story"],"h":"Determine whether the narrative moves backward or forward in time.","e":"A flashback interrupts the present to depict an earlier event (Priya at age nine) before returning to the present moment."},{"p":"Read: \"The village rebuilt the bridge three times after three floods. Each time the timbers were rougher and the hands more tired, but by spring, someone always crossed to the other side.\"\n\nWhich statement best expresses the theme?","a":"Persistence within a community can outlast repeated hardship","w":["Wooden bridges are poorly suited to flood-prone regions","Spring is the safest season for major construction work","Villages ought to relocate far away from active rivers"],"h":"A theme is a general insight about life, not a plot detail.","e":"Theme is the underlying universal message; the repeated rebuilding conveys collective perseverance against adversity."},{"p":"Read: \"On her desk sat a snow globe she never shook, a tiny frozen town under permanent glass, exactly as her hometown had been the day she left it.\"\n\nThe unshaken snow globe most likely symbolizes:","a":"A past she preserves untouched rather than disturbs","w":["Her casual interest in collecting inexpensive souvenirs","A literal prediction of the coming winter weather","Her secret wish to travel to much colder climates"],"h":"Consider why she keeps it perfectly still and what it mirrors.","e":"Symbolism: the frozen, unshaken globe represents a memory she deliberately keeps fixed and undisturbed."},{"p":"Read: \"The narrator tells us plainly: 'Mr. Alden was a stingy man, mistrustful of everyone he met, and quietly proud of both traits.'\"\n\nThis is an example of:","a":"Direct characterization, in which traits are stated outright","w":["Indirect characterization, in which traits are implied","Foil characterization, defining one figure against another","Dynamic characterization, in which a figure changes"],"h":"Notice whether the narrator states the traits or merely implies them.","e":"Direct characterization occurs when the narrator explicitly names a character's traits, as with Mr. Alden."},{"p":"Read: \"The new intern moved through the newsroom like a leaf caught in a draft, pulled toward whichever desk called loudest, never settling anywhere for long.\"\n\nThe simile emphasizes the intern's:","a":"Lack of direction and tendency to be pulled by others","w":["Physical grace and quiet, deliberate way of moving","Deep familiarity with established newsroom procedures","Loud and commanding presence among the coworkers"],"h":"Interpret the traits of a drifting leaf applied to the intern.","e":"A simile uses like or as to compare; the drifting leaf conveys the intern's aimless, easily swayed behavior."},{"p":"Read: \"Fog swallowed the streetlamps one by one. Somewhere a gate creaked, then stopped. The narrator's footsteps were the only sound, and they seemed to belong to someone else.\"\n\nThe details primarily create a mood of:","a":"Eerie unease","w":["Cheerful nostalgia","Peaceful contentment","Bustling excitement"],"h":"Mood is the feeling the imagery evokes in the reader.","e":"Mood is the atmosphere created by imagery; the fog, creaking gate, and detached footsteps produce an eerie, unsettling feeling."},{"p":"Read: \"The marriage counselor, famous for saving troubled couples, quietly filed for her own divorce the same week her bestselling book on lasting love reached number one.\"\n\nThe irony here is best described as:","a":"Situational, because the outcome contradicts the expert's public role","w":["Verbal, because she states the opposite of what she means","Dramatic, because readers know a secret she does not","Absent, because the two events are entirely unrelated"],"h":"Weigh the counselor's public reputation against her private outcome.","e":"Situational irony arises when reality (her divorce) contradicts the expectation set by her role as a love expert."},{"p":"Read: \"Tomas gave his last coins to a stranger who never thanked him. Walking home lighter in pocket, he found himself, oddly, walking lighter in step as well.\"\n\nWhich choice best states the theme rather than merely the subject?","a":"Generosity can reward the giver even without any gratitude","w":["The passage is mainly about money and acts of charity","The passage is mainly about a boy's walk home at night","The passage is mainly about a stranger and a young boy"],"h":"A subject is a topic; a theme is the insight the story makes about that topic.","e":"Theme is a complete insight about life, while the distractors name only topics; the answer states what the passage says about generosity."},{"p":"Read: \"Each autumn Grandfather planted bulbs he might not live to see bloom. 'The garden isn't really for me,' he'd say, patting the dark soil closed.\"\n\nThe act of planting bulbs he won't see bloom chiefly symbolizes:","a":"Selfless investment in a future beyond one's own life","w":["A simple hobby pursued only to pass the idle hours","Growing anxiety about the changing autumn weather","A stubborn preference for flowers over vegetables"],"h":"Consider who benefits from bulbs planted so late in life.","e":"Symbolism: planting for blooms he won't witness represents legacy and selfless care for future generations."},{"p":"Read: \"'Take the long road,' the ferryman warned, not meeting her eyes. She laughed and chose the short path through the marsh. The reeds, she noticed, had already swallowed more than one careless traveler's boots.\"\n\nThe mention of reeds swallowing boots functions as:","a":"Foreshadowing, hinting at danger that awaits ahead","w":["Flashback, returning to an earlier moment in time","Verbal irony, meaning the opposite of the words","Resolution, tying up the conflict of the story"],"h":"Ask whether the detail hints at something still to come.","e":"Foreshadowing plants hints of future events; the boot-swallowing reeds warn of the danger awaiting the traveler."},{"p":"Read: \"The debate team was a machine: Rosa the engine driving each rebuttal, Kane the brakes cooling rash claims, and Lila the steering, turning every point toward the judges.\"\n\nThe extended metaphor characterizes the team by:","a":"Assigning each member a mechanical role to show how they function together","w":["Suggesting the students are cold and unfeeling like robots","Implying the team relies on technology to win its rounds","Arguing that machines can debate better than people do"],"h":"Track how each part of the machine maps onto a member's job.","e":"An extended metaphor sustains one comparison across several details; each member's part clarifies the team's coordinated roles."},{"p":"Read: \"In chapter one a caged canary sang by the door; midway through, a moth battered the parlor window; near the end, a hawk wheeled above the pasture. Each bird appeared just as Nora weighed whether to leave home.\"\n\nThe recurring bird imagery throughout the narrative is best identified as:","a":"a motif","w":["a single symbol","an allegory","an extended simile"],"h":"Consider what we call an image or idea that returns repeatedly across a whole work.","e":"A motif is a recurring image, idea, or element woven through a work; unlike a lone symbol, its meaning accumulates through repetition."},{"p":"Read: \"After the hurricane peeled the roof from the house and left three feet of water in the kitchen, Grandpa gazed at the ruin and sighed, 'Looks like we've got a bit of cleaning up to do.'\"\n\nGrandpa's remark is an example of:","a":"understatement","w":["hyperbole","dramatic irony","personification"],"h":"Compare the scale of the disaster with the size of the reaction he describes.","e":"Understatement deliberately presents something as smaller or less serious than it truly is, often for ironic or wry effect."},{"p":"Read: \"The crown announced a new tax at dawn, and by nightfall every farmer complained that the palace had forgotten the fields that fed it.\"\n\nUsing \"the crown\" to mean the ruling monarchy is an example of:","a":"metonymy","w":["synecdoche","hyperbole","personification"],"h":"Decide whether 'crown' is a physical part of the king or simply an object closely associated with royal power.","e":"Metonymy substitutes something closely associated with a thing for the thing itself (the crown for the monarchy), rather than naming a literal part of it."},{"p":"Read: \"With the storm bearing down, the captain shouted for more hands on deck and roused every sailor from the bunks below.\"\n\nThe phrase \"more hands\" is an example of:","a":"synecdoche","w":["metonymy","an idiom","hyperbole"],"h":"Notice that a body part is being used to stand for the whole people it belongs to.","e":"Synecdoche uses a part to represent a whole (hands for sailors), whereas metonymy uses an associated concept rather than a literal part."},{"p":"Read: \"The reunion was a bittersweet affair; the guests shared a loud silence whenever anyone mentioned the friend who had not come home.\"\n\nThe phrase \"loud silence\" is best identified as:","a":"an oxymoron","w":["a hyperbole","a pun","an allusion"],"h":"Look for two words placed together whose meanings seem to contradict each other.","e":"An oxymoron pairs two contradictory terms ('loud silence') side by side to create a compressed, paradoxical effect."},{"p":"Read: \"As the newlyweds boarded the ship, a gull dropped a cracked mirror shard at Ana's feet. She laughed and stepped over it, but the deckhand beside her quietly touched the rail and said nothing.\"\n\nThe cracked mirror and the deckhand's reaction primarily serve to:","a":"foreshadow misfortune to come","w":["flash back to an earlier event","resolve the story's central conflict","establish the setting through sensory detail"],"h":"Consider how these ominous details hint at events the story has not yet revealed.","e":"Foreshadowing plants early hints or clues suggesting what will happen later, building suspense before the events unfold."},{"p":"Read: \"On the left side of the avenue, chandeliers blazed above a banquet of untouched food; on the right, a line of shivering figures waited outside a shuttered soup kitchen.\"\n\nBy placing these two scenes directly side by side, the author primarily uses:","a":"juxtaposition","w":["flashback","personification","hyperbole"],"h":"Think about the effect of setting two sharply contrasting images next to each other.","e":"Juxtaposition positions contrasting elements close together to spotlight their differences and imply commentary—here, on wealth and poverty."},{"p":"Read: \"The knife was already at his throat when Owen realized he had left the map, the money, and any hope of explanation back at the inn. How he had come to this alley he would remember only later.\"\n\nBy opening at this moment, the author uses which structural technique?","a":"beginning in medias res","w":["framing one story within another","telling events in strict chronological order","using an unreliable narrator"],"h":"Notice that the passage drops us into the middle of the action before supplying any background.","e":"In medias res ('into the middle of things') launches a narrative amid ongoing action, providing the necessary background only afterward."},{"p":"Read: \"'Gather close,' the old sailor told the children, 'and I'll tell you how I lost this hand.' The tale that followed, of storms and sea monsters, took all evening—and when it ended, the fire had burned to embers and the sailor fell silent once more.\"\n\nThe structure in which the sailor's tale is enclosed by the scene at the fire is called:","a":"a frame narrative","w":["a flashback","an epilogue","dramatic irony"],"h":"Consider how one story is set inside, and bracketed by, another situation.","e":"A frame narrative (frame story) encloses an inner tale within an outer story that introduces and later closes it."},{"p":"Read: \"When Marcus finally returned from his years abroad, worn and unrecognizable, only the old dog by the door seemed to know him at once—a homecoming worthy of Odysseus himself.\"\n\nThe reference to Odysseus is an example of:","a":"an allusion","w":["a metaphor","an extended analogy","a personification"],"h":"Think about what we call a brief reference to a well-known figure or work outside the text.","e":"An allusion is a brief, indirect reference to a person or work (here, Homer's Odyssey) that the reader is expected to recognize."},{"p":"Read: \"The reviewer wrote of the new novel: 'Three hundred pages, and not one of them necessary—a triumph of stamina over storytelling, sure to cure the most stubborn insomniac.'\"\n\nThe passage best reveals the reviewer's tone as:","a":"mocking","w":["nostalgic","reverent","anxious"],"h":"Tone reflects the writer's attitude toward the subject—here, toward the novel being reviewed.","e":"Tone is the author's or speaker's attitude toward the subject; the sarcastic jabs establish a mocking, disdainful tone."},{"p":"Read: \"In the first act, Belen refused to share her notes, guarded her rank, and trusted no one. By the final scene she was tutoring the very rivals she once feared, having learned that a locked door keeps out friends as surely as enemies.\"\n\nBelen is best described as which kind of character?","a":"a dynamic character","w":["a static character","a foil","a stock character"],"h":"Consider whether the character is essentially the same at the end as at the start, or fundamentally changed.","e":"A dynamic character undergoes significant internal change across a narrative, unlike a static character who remains essentially unchanged."},{"p":"Read: \"Reckless and loud, Diego charged into every argument fists first; his brother Mateo, calm and deliberate, weighed each word twice. Beside Mateo's restraint, Diego's temper seemed all the more blazing.\"\n\nMateo functions in the passage primarily as:","a":"a foil to Diego","w":["a dynamic character","the story's antagonist","an unreliable narrator"],"h":"Consider how one character's traits are used to highlight, by contrast, another character's traits.","e":"A foil is a character whose contrasting qualities emphasize the distinct traits of another—Mateo's calm sharpens our sense of Diego's temper."},{"p":"Read: \"Every morning the widow set two cups on the table, filled one, and left the other clean and empty beside it, exactly where he used to sit.\"\n\nThe empty second cup most likely symbolizes:","a":"the enduring presence of her absent husband","w":["her hope of hosting a future guest","her preference for drinking alone","her habit of wasting household supplies"],"h":"Consider whom the second place at the table is reserved for, and why she keeps it.","e":"A symbol is a concrete object standing for an abstract idea; the empty cup at his old seat represents the husband's absence and her continuing devotion."},{"p":"Read: \"The more the museum guarded the ancient vase behind glass and alarms, the less anyone could truly see it—locked so safely away that it might as well have crumbled to dust.\"\n\nThe claim that protecting the vase makes it \"as well have crumbled to dust\" is best described as:","a":"a paradox","w":["an understatement","an allusion","a simile"],"h":"Look for a statement that seems self-contradictory yet points toward a deeper truth.","e":"A paradox is a seemingly self-contradictory statement that nonetheless reveals a truth—here, that over-protection can defeat the very purpose of preserving something."},{"p":"Read: \"The article never called the mayor 'thrifty' or 'careful'; it called him 'miserly,' 'grasping,' and 'tight-fisted,' and readers understood exactly how the writer felt.\"\n\nThe writer shapes the reader's view of the mayor chiefly through:","a":"negative connotation","w":["literal denotation","hyperbole","alliteration"],"h":"Consider the emotional associations the chosen words carry beyond their dictionary definitions.","e":"Connotation is the emotional or cultural association a word carries beyond its literal meaning; the writer selects synonyms with strongly negative connotations to color the reader's judgment."},{"p":"Read: \"'He was not the least talented pianist the conservatory had ever produced,' the critic wrote of the young virtuoso who had just swept three international prizes.\"\n\nThe critic's phrasing is best identified as:","a":"Litotes (affirmation through the negation of its opposite)","w":["Hyperbole (deliberate, extravagant exaggeration)","Verbal irony (stating the reverse of one's meaning)","Euphemism (softening a harsh or unpleasant truth)"],"h":"Consider the effect of praising someone strongly by denying the contrary quality.","e":"Litotes is a form of understatement that affirms a point by negating its opposite ('not the least talented' = highly talented)."},{"p":"Read: \"As Nadia read the letter announcing her sister's death, the sky darkened, the willows bowed low, and a cold rain began to beat against the windows.\"\n\nThe use of the weather to mirror Nadia's grief is best identified as:","a":"Pathetic fallacy","w":["Situational irony","Foreshadowing","Allusion"],"h":"Think of the term for nature or weather reflecting a character's inner emotional state.","e":"Pathetic fallacy attributes human emotions to nature so that the environment mirrors a character's mood."},{"p":"Read: \"Cole picked pockets, lied to the guards, and cared nothing for the law—yet it was he, not the decorated constable, who carried the lost child through the burning slum to safety.\"\n\nCole is best described as which kind of character?","a":"An antihero","w":["A foil","A static character","An antagonist"],"h":"Consider a central character who lacks conventional heroic virtues yet drives the story's good outcome.","e":"An antihero is a protagonist who lacks traditional heroic qualities such as nobility or morality while still occupying the hero's role."},{"p":"Read: \"From the first chapter to the last, Uncle Reginald wanted only his newspaper, his armchair, and silence—unmoved by the wedding, the flood, or the fortune that passed through his house.\"\n\nUncle Reginald is best described as:","a":"A static character","w":["A dynamic character","A foil character","A round character"],"h":"Focus on whether the character's personality or outlook changes across the narrative.","e":"A static character remains essentially unchanged in nature or outlook from the beginning of a work to its end."},{"p":"Read: \"Standing alone at the grave, the old soldier lifted his eyes and cried, 'O cruel Death, why must you always steal the young and leave the weary old behind?'\"\n\nThe soldier's direct address to 'Death' is an example of:","a":"Apostrophe","w":["Allusion","Hyperbole","Onomatopoeia"],"h":"Consider the figure in which a speaker addresses an abstraction or absent thing as if it could hear.","e":"Apostrophe is a figure of speech in which the speaker directly addresses an absent person, an abstract idea, or a personified entity."},{"p":"Read: \"In the fable, the sleek Fox convinces the plodding Ox that fences are prisons; the Ox breaks free, wanders into the wolf's meadow, and is never seen again. The tale, readers understood, warned every citizen tempted to tear down the law.\"\n\nThe passage works chiefly as:","a":"An allegory","w":["A flashback","An anecdote","A soliloquy"],"h":"Consider a narrative whose characters and events stand for larger moral or political ideas.","e":"Allegory is an extended narrative in which characters and events represent abstract ideas or moral lessons beyond the literal story."},{"p":"Read: \"The coach closed every practice with the same reversal: 'When the going gets tough, the tough get going.'\"\n\nThe inverted repetition in the coach's saying is an example of:","a":"Chiasmus","w":["Anaphora","Hyperbole","Assonance"],"h":"Look at how the second half reverses the grammatical order of the first.","e":"Chiasmus is a rhetorical figure in which words or grammatical structures are repeated in reversed order (ABBA)."},{"p":"Read: \"We will not yield in the valleys. We will not yield on the ridges. We will not yield though the winter itself marches against us.\"\n\nThe repeated opening phrase is an example of:","a":"Anaphora","w":["Epistrophe","Chiasmus","Onomatopoeia"],"h":"Focus on where in each clause the identical wording appears.","e":"Anaphora is the deliberate repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses for emphasis."},{"p":"Read: \"'I remember every detail perfectly,' the narrator insisted, 'the blue door, the red door, whichever it was—and I certainly never took the money, or if I did, I always meant to give it back.'\"\n\nThe passage signals that the reader is dealing with:","a":"An unreliable narrator","w":["An omniscient narrator","A frame narrative","A foil character"],"h":"Consider what the self-contradictions reveal about how far the account can be trusted.","e":"An unreliable narrator is one whose credibility is compromised, here exposed through self-contradiction and evasion."},{"p":"Read: \"Halfway through folding the laundry, Priya stopped, a warm shirt still in her hands, and understood all at once that she had never truly chosen this life—she had only failed, year after year, to leave it.\"\n\nThe sudden realization Priya experiences is best identified as:","a":"An epiphany","w":["A flashback","A denouement","A soliloquy"],"h":"Consider the term for a character's sudden moment of illuminating insight.","e":"An epiphany is a sudden, revelatory moment in which a character grasps a deeper truth about their life or situation."},{"p":"Read: \"The duel was over, the villain had confessed, and the crowd dispersed. In the quiet chapters that followed, the sisters divided the estate, paid the servants, and slowly returned to ordinary mornings.\"\n\nThe final section describing events after the conflict's peak is called the:","a":"Denouement","w":["Climax","Rising action","Exposition"],"h":"Consider the stage of plot structure that follows and settles the climax.","e":"The denouement (falling action/resolution) is the part of the plot after the climax where conflicts are resolved and loose ends tied up."},{"p":"Read: \"Ravi trained ten years for the Olympic trials, and on the morning of the race a freak lightning strike closed the stadium; the meet was never rescheduled, and he understood then that some doors are shut by hands no effort can reach.\"\n\nThe irony in this passage is best described as:","a":"Cosmic irony","w":["Verbal irony","Dramatic irony","Understatement"],"h":"Consider irony that suggests fate or the universe itself thwarting a character regardless of effort.","e":"Cosmic irony (irony of fate) occurs when fate or a higher power seems to frustrate a character's hopes no matter how deserving the character is."},{"p":"Read: \"Every dress in Eleni's closet was gray, brown, or black—until the morning after the divorce papers were signed, when she walked into the office in a coat of blazing scarlet.\"\n\nThe scarlet coat most likely symbolizes:","a":"Eleni's reclaimed vitality and independence","w":["Eleni's guilt over the failed marriage","Eleni's wish to hide from her coworkers","Eleni's grief at now being alone"],"h":"Consider what the sudden bold color breaks away from, and the moment it appears.","e":"The vivid scarlet, shattering a drab wardrobe just after her liberation, symbolizes renewed energy and self-assertion."},{"p":"Read: \"Congratulations to our leadership on another visionary reorganization—our fourth this year—which promises, like the last three, to finally fix everything by rearranging precisely nothing.\"\n\nThe passage best reveals the speaker's tone as:","a":"Sardonic","w":["Reverent","Nostalgic","Earnest"],"h":"Consider the bitter, mocking edge lurking beneath the mock-congratulation.","e":"A sardonic tone is grimly mocking or cynically derisive, conveyed here through hollow praise of a change that changes nothing."},{"p":"Read: \"Sunlight lay gold across the porch where the swing still creaked, and somewhere a screen door clapped shut just as it had every summer of her childhood, though all those summers were long gone now.\"\n\nThe details primarily create a mood of:","a":"Wistful nostalgia","w":["Mounting dread","Bitter resentment","Frantic urgency"],"h":"Focus on the tender, faintly sorrowful longing for a vanished past.","e":"The warm sensory details tied to lost summers create a wistful, nostalgic mood—a gentle longing for what is gone."},{"p":"Read: \"Old Baptiste refused the surgeon's quick cure and chose instead the slow herbs of his grandmother; he healed no faster, but he died, years later, still speaking her language and singing her songs.\"\n\nWhich statement best expresses the theme rather than merely the subject?","a":"Holding onto one's heritage can matter more than seeking the quickest cure.","w":["Traditional herbal remedies always cure illness faster than modern surgery.","An old man chose his grandmother's herbs instead of a surgeon's treatment.","Older generations pass down their languages and songs to their children."],"h":"A theme states a general insight about life, not a plot summary or a sweeping factual claim.","e":"Theme is the universal insight a text conveys—here, that cultural inheritance can outweigh mere efficiency; the other options restate the subject or overgeneralize a detail."},{"p":"Read: \"By the time the meeting reached its ninth hour, Devon had aged a thousand years, his soul had left his body twice, and he was fairly sure entire civilizations had risen and fallen outside the windowless room.\"\n\nThe passage relies chiefly on:","a":"Hyperbole","w":["Understatement","Metonymy","Allusion"],"h":"Consider the deliberate, obviously impossible exaggeration used for effect.","e":"Hyperbole is intentional, extravagant exaggeration not meant to be taken literally, used here for comic emphasis."},{"p":"Read: \"The boy left his village at dawn, crossed the dark forest where an old hermit pressed a silver blade into his hand, faced the thing waiting in the cave, and returned so changed that the village barely knew him.\"\n\nThe pattern of departure, trial, and transformed return is best identified as:","a":"The hero's journey archetype","w":["A frame narrative","An unreliable narration","A situational irony"],"h":"Consider the recurring universal story pattern of leaving home, undergoing an ordeal, and coming back changed.","e":"The hero's journey is an archetypal narrative pattern—departure, initiation/trial, and transformed return—that recurs across cultures and texts."}],"s.7.matter":[{"p":"A skateboard is made of many tiny pieces you can't see with your eyes. What is the smallest building block of any element, like the aluminum in the board's trucks?","a":"An atom","w":["A cell","A crystal","A molecule of air"],"h":"Think about the smallest unit that still counts as that specific element.","e":"An atom is the smallest particle of an element that still has the properties of that element."},{"p":"On a soda can the ingredient list shows nothing about metal, but the can itself is aluminum. Aluminum is best described as which of these?","a":"An element","w":["A mixture","A compound","A chemical change"],"h":"Ask whether aluminum is made of only one kind of atom.","e":"An element is a pure substance made of only one type of atom, like aluminum (Al)."},{"p":"Water (H2O) is written with two kinds of letters. What does this tell you about water?","a":"It is a compound made of two different elements joined together","w":["It is a single element that cannot be broken down","It is a mixture you can separate with a filter","It is an atom with two centers"],"h":"Count how many different element symbols appear in the formula.","e":"A compound forms when two or more different elements chemically bond, as hydrogen and oxygen do in water."},{"p":"A gamer's controller warms up, but ice cubes in their drink stay solid until they melt. Which best describes why a solid holds its shape?","a":"Its particles are packed closely and vibrate in fixed positions","w":["Its particles have completely stopped moving","Its particles float far apart and move freely","Its particles have turned into a new substance"],"h":"Think about how tightly packed and how mobile the particles are.","e":"In a solid, particles are tightly packed and vibrate in place, giving solids a fixed shape and volume."},{"p":"A chef slices a banana into pieces for a smoothie. Is slicing the banana a physical or chemical change, and why?","a":"Physical, because it changes shape but not the substance","w":["Chemical, because a new substance forms","Chemical, because the size changes","Physical, because new atoms are created"],"h":"Ask whether the banana is still banana after slicing.","e":"A physical change alters appearance or state but does not create a new substance."},{"p":"When a campfire log burns, it turns to ash, smoke, and gases and cannot become a log again. What kind of change is burning?","a":"A chemical change, because new substances are formed","w":["A physical change, because only the shape changed","A physical change, because the wood just got smaller","No change, because the atoms disappear"],"h":"Consider whether you could easily turn the ash back into wood.","e":"Burning is a chemical change because it produces new substances (ash, smoke, gases) and cannot be easily reversed."},{"p":"On the periodic table, the elements are lined up in order of a number that keeps increasing. What does the atomic number tell you about an atom?","a":"The number of protons in its nucleus","w":["The number of molecules it can form","The total weight of all its atoms","The number of compounds it appears in"],"h":"Focus on a particle found in the center of the atom.","e":"The atomic number equals the number of protons in an atom's nucleus and identifies the element."},{"p":"A helium balloon at a birthday party floats up. Helium sits in a column on the far right of the periodic table with other gases that rarely react. This far-right column is known as which group?","a":"The noble gases","w":["The metals","The halogens","The alkali metals"],"h":"Think about the group of gases known for being unreactive and stable.","e":"Noble gases occupy the far-right column and are known for being very unreactive."},{"p":"In a basketball, the air inside is a gas that spreads out to fill the whole ball. Which statement about gases explains this?","a":"Gas particles move freely and spread to fill any container","w":["Gas particles stay in a fixed shape no matter the container","Gas particles pack together tightly like in a solid","Gas particles stop moving once inside a container"],"h":"Recall what happens to a gas's shape and volume in a container.","e":"Gases have no fixed shape or volume; their particles move freely and fill their container."},{"p":"Rust forms on an old bike chain left out in the rain, turning shiny metal into a reddish-brown flaky coating. Which sign suggests a chemical change happened?","a":"A new substance with a different color and texture formed","w":["The chain became a bit shorter","The chain got wet from the rain","The chain changed from solid to liquid"],"h":"Look for evidence that the material became something new, not just wet.","e":"A color change and formation of a new substance (rust) are signs of a chemical change."},{"p":"A student says table salt (sodium chloride, NaCl) is just one element. Why is this incorrect?","a":"It is a compound made of two elements, sodium and chlorine","w":["It is a mixture that a magnet can separate","It is a single atom of salt","It is only the element sodium"],"h":"Count the different element symbols in the formula NaCl.","e":"Salt is a compound because two different elements, sodium and chlorine, are chemically bonded."},{"p":"On the periodic table, most elements on the left and middle are shiny, bend without breaking, and carry electricity well, like the copper in a phone charger. These elements are called which of these?","a":"Metals","w":["Noble gases","Nonmetals","Compounds"],"h":"Think about the properties of copper, iron, and gold.","e":"Metals are typically shiny, bendable, and good conductors of heat and electricity."},{"p":"Two hydrogen atoms bond with one oxygen atom to make one particle of water. What is the name for a group of atoms bonded together like this?","a":"A molecule","w":["An element","A proton","A mixture"],"h":"Think of the word for two or more atoms joined by bonds.","e":"A molecule is two or more atoms chemically bonded together, like H2O."},{"p":"When you put liquid water in the freezer, it becomes solid ice, but it is still water. What kind of change is freezing?","a":"A physical change, because it is still the same substance","w":["A chemical change, because a new substance forms","A chemical change, because water disappears","No change at all, because nothing moved"],"h":"Ask whether the ice is still made of water molecules.","e":"Changing state (freezing, melting, boiling) is a physical change; the substance stays the same."},{"p":"A comic book shows an atom as a center with tiny particles zooming around it. What are the two kinds of particles found inside the nucleus, the center of the atom?","a":"Protons and neutrons","w":["Only electrons","Molecules and compounds","Protons and electrons"],"h":"Electrons orbit outside the center, so which two stay inside?","e":"The nucleus contains protons and neutrons; electrons move in the space around the nucleus."},{"p":"In a bottle of lemonade, you can still see and taste both the sugar and the lemon, and you could separate them. Lemonade is best described as which of these?","a":"A mixture, because the substances are combined but not chemically bonded","w":["A compound, because new atoms formed","An element, because it is one pure substance","A single molecule of lemonade"],"h":"Ask whether the ingredients kept their own properties.","e":"A mixture combines substances that keep their own properties and can be separated physically."},{"p":"A candle's wax melts into a liquid pool when the flame heats it, then hardens again when it cools. Melting the wax is which type of change?","a":"A physical change, because the wax is still wax","w":["A chemical change, because a new substance forms","A chemical change, because the wax gets softer","A change that creates brand-new atoms"],"h":"Consider whether cooling the wax brings back the original material.","e":"Melting is a physical change of state; the wax remains the same substance and can re-solidify."},{"p":"Two atoms are compared for a science project: one has 6 protons and the other has 8 protons. A student claims they could still be the same element. Why is the student wrong?","a":"The number of protons decides which element an atom is, so different proton counts mean different elements","w":["Atoms with different numbers of protons are the same element as long as they are the same size","The number of protons is identical in every element, so only electrons make elements different","Elements are decided by how many neutrons an atom has, not by protons"],"h":"Think about which number the periodic table uses to place each element in order.","e":"The atomic number (the number of protons) defines the element; change the number of protons and you change the element."},{"p":"On the periodic table, elements are arranged in horizontal rows and vertical columns, a bit like seats in rows and columns at a stadium. What is a horizontal row across the periodic table called?","a":"A period","w":["A group","A family","A shell"],"h":"Think of the word that also names a block of time, like a class period at school.","e":"Horizontal rows on the periodic table are called periods, while vertical columns are called groups or families."},{"p":"On a hot day, water droplets appear on the outside of a cold soda can, even though no one poured water on it. Where does this water come from?","a":"Water vapor already in the air cooled on the can and turned into liquid","w":["Liquid water leaked out through tiny holes in the metal can","The cold aluminum can slowly melted into water droplets","The soda soaked through the can and formed drops on the outside"],"h":"Think about what happens to an invisible gas when it touches something cold.","e":"This is condensation: water vapor (a gas) in the air loses energy on the cold can and changes into liquid."},{"p":"At a concert, thick 'fog' pours off the stage from dry ice, which is frozen carbon dioxide. The solid dry ice turns straight into gas without ever becoming a puddle. What is this change of state called?","a":"Sublimation","w":["Condensation","Evaporation","Melting"],"h":"Notice that the solid skips the liquid step completely.","e":"Sublimation is when a solid changes directly into a gas without passing through the liquid state."},{"p":"After it rains, a puddle on the basketball court slowly disappears on a sunny day, even though it never gets hot enough to boil. What best explains where the water went?","a":"Surface particles gained energy and escaped into the air as water vapor","w":["The water disappeared completely and simply stopped existing","The court soaked up every last bit of the water like a sponge","The liquid water turned into a solid you could no longer see"],"h":"Water does not have to reach boiling to become a gas.","e":"This is evaporation: particles at the liquid's surface gain enough energy to leave as gas, even below the boiling point."},{"p":"A student mixes baking soda and vinegar in a cup, and it bubbles and fizzes wildly, giving off a new gas. Which reason best shows that this is a chemical change?","a":"A brand-new substance, the gas, formed that was not there before","w":["The mixture grew bigger, which means more baking soda was made","The liquid simply changed shape to fit the cup it was poured into","The vinegar only pushed the baking soda around without any change"],"h":"Look for evidence that a new substance is being created.","e":"Forming a new substance, such as the gas bubbling out, is a key sign of a chemical change."},{"p":"When you fry an egg, the clear runny part turns solid and white and can never be turned back into a raw egg. What kind of change is cooking an egg, and why?","a":"A chemical change, because a new substance forms that cannot be reversed","w":["A physical change, because the egg only changed its shape","A physical change, because you could cool it back into a raw egg","No change at all, because it is still called an egg"],"h":"Ask yourself whether you can turn it back into exactly what it was.","e":"Cooking an egg is a chemical change because new substances form and the process cannot be undone."},{"p":"A science kit has a jar of sand mixed with tiny iron filings. You can pull the iron out with a magnet and leave the sand behind. What does this tell you about the sand and iron together?","a":"They form a mixture, because they are combined but not chemically joined","w":["They form a compound, because two different things are combined","They are a single element, since they are stored in one jar","They form a molecule, because their atoms bonded together"],"h":"Think about whether the atoms are bonded or just resting side by side.","e":"A mixture can be separated by physical methods like a magnet because the substances are not chemically bonded."},{"p":"The oxygen you breathe travels as pairs of oxygen atoms bonded together, written O2. Because it contains only one kind of atom, oxygen gas is best described as which of these?","a":"An element, because it is made of only one type of atom","w":["A compound, because two atoms are bonded together","A mixture, because there is more than one atom present","A metalloid, because the atoms bond with each other"],"h":"Count how many DIFFERENT kinds of atoms are present, not how many atoms total.","e":"An element is made of only one type of atom, even when those atoms pair up into a molecule like O2."},{"p":"Carbon dioxide, the gas you breathe out, has the formula CO2. How many atoms in total are in one molecule of carbon dioxide?","a":"3 atoms: 1 carbon and 2 oxygen","w":["2 atoms: 1 carbon and 1 oxygen","4 atoms: 2 carbon and 2 oxygen","1 atom: just carbon"],"h":"The small number after a letter tells how many of that atom there are.","e":"The subscript shows how many of each atom are present, so CO2 has 1 carbon plus 2 oxygen for 3 atoms total."},{"p":"The yellow sulfur used in some fireworks is dull, crumbles easily into powder, and does not carry electricity well. Elements like this, found toward the right of the periodic table, are called which of these?","a":"Nonmetals","w":["Metals","Metalloids","Noble gases"],"h":"These traits are the opposite of shiny, bendable, electricity-carrying metals.","e":"Nonmetals are usually dull, brittle, and poor conductors of electricity, unlike metals."},{"p":"Silicon, used to make computer chips, is shiny like a metal but brittle like a nonmetal, sharing properties of both types. Elements with this in-between behavior are called which of these?","a":"Metalloids","w":["Noble gases","Pure metals","Liquid elements"],"h":"The name hints at something that is only 'like' a metal, not fully one.","e":"Metalloids sit between metals and nonmetals and share properties of both."},{"p":"A comic-book model of an atom shows a dense center with small particles zooming through the space around it. Where in the atom are the electrons found?","a":"Moving through the space outside the nucleus","w":["Packed tightly inside the nucleus with the protons","Sitting perfectly still at the very center of the atom","Mixed evenly among the neutrons inside the nucleus"],"h":"The nucleus holds protons and neutrons, so the electrons must be somewhere else.","e":"Electrons move in the region outside the nucleus, while protons and neutrons stay in the nucleus."},{"p":"On the periodic table, sodium is shown by the two letters 'Na' instead of by its full name. What are these short one- or two-letter labels for elements called?","a":"Chemical symbols","w":["Atomic numbers","Chemical formulas","Element groups"],"h":"A formula combines several of these labels; here you are looking at just one element's label.","e":"Each element has a chemical symbol, a short abbreviation of one or two letters that stands for it."},{"p":"You pour exactly one cup of juice from a tall glass into a wide bowl. The juice spreads out flat but is still one cup. Why does a liquid change its shape but not its amount?","a":"Its particles can slide past each other but still stay close together","w":["Its particles are locked tightly in place and cannot move at all","Its particles spread far apart to completely fill any container","Its particles vanish in the glass and new ones appear in the bowl"],"h":"Compare how tightly liquid particles are held to those in solids and gases.","e":"Liquid particles stay close but can slide past one another, so a liquid takes a container's shape while keeping the same volume."},{"p":"You stir a spoonful of sugar into hot tea until it seems to vanish. You could get the sugar back by letting all the water evaporate away. What kind of change is dissolving the sugar?","a":"A physical change, because the sugar is still sugar and can be recovered","w":["A chemical change, because the sugar disappeared for good","A chemical change, because a brand-new substance formed in the tea","No change at all, because stirring does nothing to the sugar"],"h":"Ask whether the sugar became a new substance or just spread out among the water.","e":"Dissolving is a physical change: the sugar is unchanged and can be recovered by evaporating the water."},{"p":"A tightly sealed jar holds a fizzy reaction. Before the reaction the whole jar weighs 200 grams. After the reaction finishes, with nothing let in or out, what should the sealed jar weigh?","a":"200 grams, because matter is not created or destroyed in the reaction","w":["Less than 200 grams, because the gas made is lighter than liquid","More than 200 grams, because the new gas adds extra weight","0 grams, because the reaction completely used up the matter"],"h":"Remember that in a sealed jar nothing can escape or enter.","e":"By conservation of mass, the total mass stays the same in a closed reaction because matter is neither created nor destroyed."},{"p":"A balloon left inside a hot car slowly gets bigger as the gas inside warms up. What happens to the gas particles as they get hotter?","a":"They move faster and spread farther apart","w":["They move slower and pack more closely together","They stop moving and freeze completely in place","They shrink into smaller and smaller particles"],"h":"Adding heat gives particles more energy to move.","e":"Heating adds energy, so gas particles move faster and spread apart, which makes the balloon expand."},{"p":"A phone battery uses lithium atoms, each with 3 protons and 4 neutrons. To find lithium's mass number, which particles do you add together?","a":"The protons and the neutrons","w":["The protons and the electrons","The neutrons and the electrons","Only the protons by themselves"],"h":"Think about which particles sit packed inside the nucleus, the heavy center of the atom.","e":"An atom's mass number is the total of its protons and neutrons, the two particles found in the nucleus."},{"p":"Scientists date fossils using carbon-12 and carbon-14. Both kinds of carbon have 6 protons, but carbon-14 has two extra neutrons. Atoms of the same element that differ only in their number of neutrons are called what?","a":"Isotopes","w":["Ions","Compounds","Molecules"],"h":"They are still the same element because the proton count has not changed, only the mass.","e":"Isotopes are atoms of one element with the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons."},{"p":"When natural gas burns, the reaction is written as methane + oxygen goes to carbon dioxide + water. The two substances written before the arrow are the starting materials that get used up. What are these starting substances called?","a":"The reactants","w":["The products","The compounds","The mixtures"],"h":"They are what you begin with, before the arrow, and they get changed into something new.","e":"In a chemical equation the reactants start on the left and turn into the products on the right."},{"p":"A chemistry worksheet writes 3 H2O to stand for three separate water molecules. Counting every atom, how many atoms in total are shown by 3 H2O?","a":"9 atoms","w":["6 atoms","5 atoms","3 atoms"],"h":"Each water molecule has 3 atoms; the big number in front tells you how many molecules there are.","e":"A coefficient multiplies the whole molecule, so 3 molecules times 3 atoms each equals 9 atoms."},{"p":"A candle burns down for an hour, and the leftover wax weighs much less than the candle did at the start. Nothing was trapped or collected. Where did the missing mass go?","a":"It escaped into the air as gases like carbon dioxide and water vapor.","w":["It was destroyed, because burning removes matter permanently.","It turned into pure energy and simply vanished.","It stayed exactly the same and the scale must be broken."],"h":"Matter is never destroyed in a change, only rearranged, and this candle was burning out in the open air.","e":"By conservation of mass, the wax's atoms left as invisible gases, so the total mass is unchanged if you could weigh the escaping gases too."},{"p":"On a freezing winter night, feathery frost forms directly on a cold window from water vapor in the air, turning straight from gas to solid ice without ever becoming a liquid drop first. What is this change of state called?","a":"Deposition","w":["Condensation","Sublimation","Freezing"],"h":"This is the exact reverse of dry ice turning straight from a solid into a gas.","e":"Deposition is when a gas changes directly into a solid, skipping the liquid state entirely."},{"p":"Brass, used to make trumpets, is created by blending copper and zinc metals together without chemically bonding them. A solid blend of two or more metals like brass is best described as which of these?","a":"A mixture of metals, since they are combined but not bonded","w":["A compound with one fixed chemical formula","A single pure element with one kind of atom","A molecule made of atoms bonded together"],"h":"Ask whether the copper and zinc are chemically joined or just physically stirred together.","e":"An alloy such as brass is a mixture of metals; the metals keep their own atoms and are not chemically bonded."},{"p":"Sodium and potassium sit in the far-left column of the periodic table and react so violently with water that they can burst into flame. This far-left column of extremely reactive metals is known as which group?","a":"The alkali metals","w":["The noble gases","The halogens","The alkaline earth metals"],"h":"These are the very first column on the table, and they are famous for being the most reactive metals.","e":"Group 1, the alkali metals, are highly reactive metals found in the far-left column of the periodic table."},{"p":"You stir salt into water until it fully dissolves and the liquid looks completely uniform, the same all the way through with nothing you can pick out. This evenly blended solution is best described as which of these?","a":"A homogeneous mixture, blended evenly throughout","w":["A heterogeneous mixture with visible separate parts","A compound joined by a fixed chemical formula","A pure element made of only one kind of atom"],"h":"Focus on whether you can spot separate pieces in the liquid or whether it looks the same everywhere.","e":"A solution like saltwater is a homogeneous mixture because its parts are spread evenly and look uniform throughout."},{"p":"An instant cold pack turns icy cold the moment you squeeze it, pulling in heat from your hand and the air around it. A change that takes in heat energy from its surroundings is best described as which of these?","a":"An endothermic change that absorbs heat","w":["An exothermic change that gives off heat","A change that creates brand-new heat energy","A physical change that never involves any heat"],"h":"If the pack feels cold, think about whether it is pulling heat in or pushing heat out.","e":"An endothermic change absorbs heat from its surroundings, which is why the cold pack feels cold."},{"p":"A hand warmer packet gets toasty on its own soon after you open it, giving off heat to your fingers on a cold day. A reaction that releases heat energy to its surroundings is best described as which of these?","a":"An exothermic reaction that releases heat","w":["An endothermic reaction that absorbs heat","A reaction that destroys heat energy for good","A change of state that involves no energy at all"],"h":"If the packet feels warm, decide whether heat is flowing out of it or into it.","e":"An exothermic reaction gives off heat to its surroundings, which is why the hand warmer feels warm."},{"p":"After boiling pasta, you pour the whole pot through a strainer so the water drains away while the solid noodles stay behind. Using a strainer or filter to separate a solid from a liquid is called which method?","a":"Filtration","w":["Evaporation","Distillation","Condensation"],"h":"Think about how the holes let the liquid slip through but hold back the larger solid pieces.","e":"Filtration separates a solid from a liquid by passing the mixture through a filter that traps the larger solid particles."},{"p":"To make fresh drinking water from salty seawater, you can boil the water and then cool the rising steam back into a liquid, leaving the salt behind in the pot. This way of separating a mixture by boiling and re-collecting the vapor is called which of these?","a":"Distillation","w":["Filtration","Magnetism","Dissolving"],"h":"Notice that the water is boiled away and the vapor is caught and cooled, while the salt cannot evaporate.","e":"Distillation separates a dissolved solid from a liquid by boiling the liquid off and condensing the pure vapor back to liquid."},{"p":"Fluorine and chlorine sit in the same column of the periodic table, and both react eagerly to form salts. Why do elements in the same column tend to behave in similar ways?","a":"They have similar arrangements of outer electrons","w":["They have the exact same number of protons","They are always the same color and size","They have identical mass numbers"],"h":"Columns group elements together because of a shared feature that controls how they react.","e":"Elements in the same group have similar numbers of outer electrons, which gives them similar chemical behavior."},{"p":"A student gently pours together two clear, colorless liquids, and instantly a cloudy solid appears and settles to the bottom. Which sign best shows that a chemical change has happened?","a":"A new solid, called a precipitate, formed from the liquids","w":["The liquids simply changed shape inside the cup","The liquid was poured from one container to another","The total amount of liquid got a little smaller"],"h":"Look for something appearing that was not there in either liquid before mixing.","e":"Forming a precipitate, a new solid, is a classic sign that a chemical reaction has produced a new substance."},{"p":"Pure water is always exactly two hydrogen atoms for every one oxygen atom, no matter what river, cloud, or faucet it comes from. This fixed, never-changing ratio of atoms is a key feature of which of these?","a":"A compound, which always has a set ratio of atoms","w":["A mixture, whose ingredients can vary in amount","An element, made of only one kind of atom","A solution that can be watered down at will"],"h":"Ask whether you could change the ratio of the atoms and still call it the same pure substance.","e":"A compound has a definite, fixed composition, so water is always 2 hydrogen to 1 oxygen everywhere."},{"p":"Inside a glowing neon sign and in a bolt of lightning, gas becomes so energized that it forms a state of matter that is not solid, liquid, or gas. What is this fourth state of matter called?","a":"Plasma","w":["Vapor","Crystal","Condensate"],"h":"This supercharged state is what stars like our Sun are mostly made of.","e":"Plasma is the fourth state of matter, formed when gas gains so much energy that its particles become electrically charged."},{"p":"Pure gold always melts at the very same temperature, and jewelers use this fact to test whether a shiny nugget is truly gold. A substance's fixed melting point is an example of which of these?","a":"A physical property that helps identify a substance","w":["A chemical change that makes a new substance","A sign that the gold is reacting with the air","A way of permanently destroying the gold's atoms"],"h":"Consider whether measuring the melting point actually creates any new material.","e":"Melting point is a characteristic physical property, so it can be used to identify a substance without changing what it is."}],"s.8.space":[{"p":"A skateboarder notices the Sun is on one side of the park in the morning and the other side by dinnertime. What actually causes the Sun to appear to move across the sky each day?","a":"Earth spins on its axis once a day","w":["The Sun orbits around the Earth once a day","The Sun physically travels across the solar system daily","Earth orbits all the way around the Sun each day"],"h":"Think about what Earth is doing that repeats every 24 hours, not every 365 days.","e":"Earth's rotation on its axis produces the daily apparent motion of the Sun and the cycle of day and night."},{"p":"Your friend says the tilt of a basketball on your finger stays pointed the same way as you carry it around the court. Earth's axis works similarly. What does this constant tilt of Earth's axis mainly cause?","a":"The changing seasons throughout the year","w":["The daily cycle of day and night","The monthly phases of the Moon","The rise and fall of ocean tides"],"h":"Seasons change over months as Earth travels around the Sun, not over a single day.","e":"Earth's axial tilt of about 23.5 degrees causes different hemispheres to receive more direct sunlight at different times, producing seasons."},{"p":"A student thinks summer happens because Earth moves closer to the Sun. Why is this a misconception?","a":"Seasons come from Earth's tilt, not from changing distance to the Sun","w":["Earth actually never changes its distance from the Sun at all","The Sun physically grows hotter in summer and cooler in winter","The Moon blocks sunlight and cools Earth during winter"],"h":"When it is summer in the Northern Hemisphere, it is winter in the Southern Hemisphere at the same time.","e":"Seasons are caused by axial tilt changing the directness of sunlight; distance to the Sun barely varies and does not drive the seasons."},{"p":"During a soccer night game, the stadium lights make the ball look bright while half of it stays shadowed. In a similar way, why does the Moon show different phases?","a":"We see different amounts of the Moon's sunlit half as it orbits Earth","w":["Earth's shadow covers different parts of the Moon each night","The Moon makes its own light and dims on some nights","Clouds in space block part of the Moon from view"],"h":"The Moon always has one half lit by the Sun; what changes is how much of that lit half faces us.","e":"Moon phases result from our changing viewing angle of the Moon's sunlit hemisphere as it orbits Earth."},{"p":"Which planet is closest to the Sun in our solar system?","a":"Mercury","w":["Venus","Earth","Mars"],"h":"Picture the order of planets starting from the Sun and moving outward.","e":"Mercury is the innermost planet, orbiting closer to the Sun than any other planet."},{"p":"Jupiter is often called the giant of the solar system. Which planet is the largest by size?","a":"Jupiter","w":["Saturn","Neptune","Earth"],"h":"This planet is so big that all the other planets could fit inside it combined.","e":"Jupiter is the largest planet in the solar system, with more than twice the mass of all other planets combined."},{"p":"A science video calls the Milky Way home to hundreds of billions of stars. What is a galaxy?","a":"A huge collection of stars, gas, and dust held together by gravity","w":["A group of planets orbiting a single star","One very large, hot ball of glowing gas","A small cloud of dust that forms into planets"],"h":"Think bigger than a single star or solar system.","e":"A galaxy is an enormous, gravitationally bound system of stars, gas, dust, and dark matter."},{"p":"When you look up at the band of faint light stretching across a dark night sky, you are seeing part of your home galaxy. What is its name?","a":"The Milky Way","w":["Andromeda","The Solar System","Orion"],"h":"Our solar system sits inside this spiral galaxy, and it is named for its milky appearance.","e":"The Milky Way is the galaxy that contains our Sun and solar system."},{"p":"During a solar eclipse, the daytime sky darkens for a few minutes. What arrangement causes a solar eclipse?","a":"The Moon passes directly between the Sun and Earth","w":["Earth passes directly between the Sun and the Moon","The Sun moves behind Earth for a few minutes","The Sun stops shining for a short time each year"],"h":"Something must block the Sun's light from reaching part of Earth.","e":"A solar eclipse occurs when the Moon moves between the Sun and Earth, casting its shadow on Earth."},{"p":"During a lunar eclipse, the full Moon can turn a dim reddish color. What arrangement causes a lunar eclipse?","a":"Earth passes between the Sun and the Moon, casting its shadow on the Moon","w":["The Moon passes between the Sun and the Earth","The Moon travels through the outer part of the Sun","The Sun blocks the Moon from Earth's view"],"h":"This time it is Earth's shadow that does the covering, and it falls on the Moon.","e":"A lunar eclipse happens when Earth is between the Sun and Moon, and Earth's shadow falls on the Moon."},{"p":"Surfers plan their trips around the ocean's tides. What is the main cause of Earth's ocean tides?","a":"The gravitational pull of the Moon on Earth's oceans","w":["Strong winds pushing the ocean water back and forth","Earth's rotation flinging water toward the shore","The Sun heating the water and making it rise"],"h":"A nearby object's gravity tugs on the water, creating bulges in the ocean.","e":"Tides are primarily caused by the Moon's gravitational pull, which raises bulges of water on Earth."},{"p":"When you drop a basketball, it falls straight down to the court. What force pulls it toward the ground?","a":"Gravity pulling the ball toward Earth's center","w":["Air in the gym pushing the ball downward","The ball being heavier than the air around it","Earth's spin throwing the ball toward the floor"],"h":"This is the same force that keeps you on the ground and the Moon in orbit.","e":"Gravity is the attractive force that pulls objects with mass toward each other, drawing the ball toward Earth's center."},{"p":"A student asks whether the Sun is a planet or something else. What type of object is the Sun?","a":"A star","w":["A planet","A galaxy","A comet"],"h":"It produces its own light and heat, unlike the planets that orbit it.","e":"The Sun is a star, a hot ball of gas that generates energy through nuclear fusion in its core."},{"p":"An astronaut on the Moon jumps much higher than she could on Earth. Why would she also weigh less on the Moon?","a":"The Moon's gravity is weaker than Earth's","w":["The Moon's gravity is stronger than Earth's","She loses all of her mass in space","The Moon has no gravity at all"],"h":"Weaker gravity means a smaller pull on her body, even though her mass stays the same.","e":"The Moon's surface gravity is about one-sixth of Earth's, so objects weigh less there while keeping the same mass."},{"p":"Planets travel in nearly circular paths around the Sun instead of flying off into space. What keeps them in orbit?","a":"The Sun's gravity pulling on the planets","w":["The planets' magnetic fields locking them in place","The solar wind pushing them along their paths","The Moon's gravity holding the planets steady"],"h":"The same force that makes an apple fall keeps planets curving around the Sun.","e":"The Sun's gravity continuously pulls on the planets, bending their motion into orbits."},{"p":"A calendar year is a natural unit of time based on Earth's motion. What defines one year?","a":"One complete orbit of Earth around the Sun","w":["One complete spin of Earth on its axis","One complete orbit of the Moon around Earth","One complete rotation of the Sun on its axis"],"h":"A day comes from spinning, but a year comes from traveling around something.","e":"A year is the time Earth takes to make one full orbit around the Sun, about 365.25 days."},{"p":"During a full moon, the entire face of the Moon looks bright and round. Where is the Moon relative to the Sun and Earth at this phase?","a":"On the opposite side of Earth from the Sun, so Earth is between them","w":["Directly between the Sun and Earth","Hidden inside Earth's dark shadow","Directly in front of the Sun in the sky"],"h":"For the whole near side to be lit, sunlight must reach the side of the Moon facing us.","e":"A full moon occurs when Earth is between the Sun and Moon, so the Moon's Earth-facing side is fully sunlit."},{"p":"On a clear night, stars appear as tiny points of light, but they are actually enormous. What are stars mostly made of?","a":"Hot glowing gas, mainly hydrogen and helium","w":["Solid rock like the surface of Earth","Frozen ice and dust packed together","Molten metal like the core of a planet"],"h":"Stars, including our Sun, are giant balls of gas that fuse elements to make energy.","e":"Stars are huge spheres of hot gas, primarily hydrogen and helium, that release energy through nuclear fusion."},{"p":"A student ranking planets by temperature guesses Mercury must be the hottest because it sits closest to the Sun. Surprisingly, Venus is hotter. Why is Venus hotter than Mercury even though Mercury is closer to the Sun?","a":"Venus has a thick atmosphere that traps heat like a blanket","w":["Venus spins so fast that friction heats it up","Venus is actually closer to the Sun than Mercury","Venus reflects far more sunlight from its bright clouds"],"h":"Think about what Mercury is missing that Venus has a lot of surrounding it.","e":"This is the greenhouse effect: Venus's dense carbon-dioxide atmosphere traps heat, so it stays hotter than airless Mercury even though it is farther from the Sun."},{"p":"A fisherman keeps a tide chart and notices the highest high tides and lowest low tides happen around the full moon and the new moon. What causes these especially strong 'spring tides'?","a":"The Sun and Moon line up so their gravitational pulls combine","w":["The Moon reaches its closest point to Earth in its orbit","The season changes to spring and warms the ocean water","The Sun and Moon pull on Earth at right angles to each other"],"h":"Consider where the Sun, Moon, and Earth are during full and new moons.","e":"Spring tides occur when the Sun and Moon are aligned with Earth, so their gravitational pulls add together to create larger tidal ranges. The name has nothing to do with the season."},{"p":"Every night the Moon shows the same face, with the same dark patches always pointed toward us. Why do we always see the same side of the Moon from Earth?","a":"The Moon rotates once for each orbit it makes around Earth","w":["The Moon does not rotate on its axis at all","The far side is too far away for us to ever see","Earth's shadow permanently covers the Moon's far side"],"h":"The Moon does spin, but its spin is timed with its trip around Earth.","e":"This is synchronous rotation (tidal locking): the Moon turns exactly once per orbit, keeping the same hemisphere facing Earth."},{"p":"Photos sent back from rovers show that Mars has a rusty, reddish-orange surface, earning it the nickname the Red Planet. What gives Mars its reddish color?","a":"Iron oxide, or rust, in its soil and dust","w":["Glowing red-hot lava covering the surface","Reflection of the Sun appearing red from Mars","Large amounts of reddish plant life on the ground"],"h":"The same chemical reaction happens to an old bike left out in the rain.","e":"Mars's surface is rich in iron oxide (rust), which reflects red light and gives the planet its color."},{"p":"In a space video game, your ship must fly through a thick field of tumbling rocks that circles the Sun between two planets. In our real solar system, where is the main asteroid belt located?","a":"Between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter","w":["Between the orbits of Earth and Mars","Beyond Neptune at the outer edge of the solar system","Between the Sun and the orbit of Mercury"],"h":"It separates the small rocky inner planets from the giant outer planets.","e":"The main asteroid belt lies between Mars and Jupiter, holding millions of rocky bodies that never formed into a planet."},{"p":"A comet swings close to the Sun and grows a long, glowing tail that stretches across the sky. Which direction does a comet's tail generally point?","a":"Away from the Sun","w":["Toward the Sun","Behind the comet's path no matter where the Sun is","Toward the nearest large planet"],"h":"Something streaming out from the Sun is pushing on the tail.","e":"The solar wind and sunlight push a comet's gas and dust outward, so the tail always points away from the Sun, even as the comet moves away."},{"p":"Older textbooks list nine planets, but newer ones list only eight and call Pluto a 'dwarf planet.' Why is Pluto no longer classified as a full planet?","a":"It has not cleared other objects out of its orbital path","w":["It stopped orbiting the Sun and drifted away","It became too far away for telescopes to observe","It collided with another object and broke apart"],"h":"One of the three rules for being a planet is about a body dominating the space around its orbit.","e":"To be a planet, an object must orbit the Sun, be round, and clear its orbital neighborhood. Pluto shares its zone with many other icy bodies, so it is a dwarf planet."},{"p":"An astronomer says a certain star is about 4 light-years away from Earth. A student thinks that means the star is 4 years old. What does a light-year actually measure?","a":"The distance that light travels in one year","w":["The time it takes light to reach Earth from the star","The age of a star measured in years","How fast light moves during one year"],"h":"Focus on the second half of the word and what light does through space.","e":"A light-year is a unit of distance, about 9.5 trillion kilometers, equal to how far light travels in a year."},{"p":"On a clear night the Sun looks like a calm ball of light, but it is actually releasing enormous amounts of energy every second. What process produces the Sun's energy?","a":"Nuclear fusion, joining hydrogen into helium","w":["Burning of gases the way a campfire burns wood","Nuclear fission, splitting heavy atoms apart","Friction created by the Sun spinning quickly"],"h":"The Sun combines the lightest element to make a slightly heavier one.","e":"In the Sun's core, nuclear fusion presses hydrogen nuclei together to form helium, releasing huge amounts of energy. It is not chemical burning."},{"p":"Looking up on a clear night, a student notices that stars seem to flicker and twinkle, while the planets shine with a steadier light. Why do stars appear to twinkle?","a":"Earth's moving atmosphere bends their light as it passes through","w":["The stars are actually turning on and off","The stars are sending out flashing signals","The stars are quickly moving back and forth in space"],"h":"The effect is strongest near the horizon, where light passes through the most air.","e":"Twinkling (scintillation) happens as starlight passes through Earth's turbulent atmosphere, which bends the light slightly and makes it seem to flicker."},{"p":"A student sorts the planets into two groups and puts Mercury, Venus, Earth, and Mars together as the 'inner planets.' What are these four inner planets mainly made of?","a":"Rock and metal","w":["Mostly hydrogen and helium gas","Mostly ice and frozen gases","Mostly liquid water oceans"],"h":"Compare them to the giant, mostly gaseous outer planets.","e":"The inner planets are terrestrial planets, made of rock and metal with solid surfaces, unlike the gas giants farther out."},{"p":"Just after a new moon, a stargazer sees a thin sliver of Moon low in the west after sunset, and each night the lit part grows a little larger. What is this phase called?","a":"Waxing crescent","w":["Waning crescent","Waxing gibbous","Waning gibbous"],"h":"'Waxing' means growing, and a thin sliver is a crescent shape.","e":"A waxing crescent is a thin, growing sliver seen after the new moon. 'Waxing' means the lit portion is increasing each night."},{"p":"A surfer notices that around the first-quarter moon the tides are unusually weak, with smaller differences between high and low tide. What causes these weaker 'neap tides'?","a":"The Sun and Moon pull at right angles, partly canceling each other","w":["The Moon is at its farthest point from Earth","The Sun and Moon line up on the same side of Earth","The ocean water cools down and moves less"],"h":"Think about the angle between the Sun and Moon during a quarter moon.","e":"Neap tides happen when the Sun and Moon are at right angles relative to Earth, so their gravitational pulls partly offset, producing smaller tidal ranges."},{"p":"At a summer camp, everyone gasps as a bright streak of light flashes across the night sky for a second. Someone shouts 'shooting star!' What is that brief streak of light correctly called?","a":"A meteor","w":["A meteorite","A meteoroid","A comet"],"h":"The name changes depending on whether the rock is in space, glowing in the air, or on the ground.","e":"A meteor is the streak of light made as a space rock burns up in Earth's atmosphere. In space it is a meteoroid, and if it lands it is a meteorite."},{"p":"On a clear winter night, a student connects bright stars into the familiar shape of Orion the Hunter. What is a constellation like Orion?","a":"A recognizable pattern of stars as seen from Earth","w":["A group of stars physically bound tightly together in space","A cluster of planets lined up in the sky","A small galaxy located near the Milky Way"],"h":"The stars in the pattern can actually be at very different distances from us.","e":"A constellation is an apparent pattern of stars seen from Earth. The stars often lie at vastly different distances and only appear grouped from our viewpoint."},{"p":"An astronaut says that traveling to the Moon changes her weight but not her mass. A classmate thinks mass and weight mean the same thing. What is the real difference between mass and weight?","a":"Mass is the amount of matter; weight is the pull of gravity on that matter","w":["Mass changes with location while weight always stays the same","They are simply two different words for the exact same thing","Weight is the amount of matter; mass is the pull of gravity"],"h":"One depends on where you are; the other stays the same everywhere.","e":"Mass measures how much matter an object contains and does not change, while weight is the force of gravity on that mass and changes with the local gravity."},{"p":"Through a small telescope, a student is amazed to see Saturn surrounded by bright, flat rings. What are Saturn's rings mostly made of?","a":"Countless pieces of ice and rock","w":["A few solid sheets of metal","Glowing clouds of hot gas","A thin layer of trapped dust only"],"h":"The rings are not solid; they are made of many separate orbiting objects.","e":"Saturn's rings are made of billions of chunks of ice and rock, ranging from tiny grains to house-sized pieces, all orbiting the planet."},{"p":"Read: 'Videos from the International Space Station show astronauts floating, tumbling, and letting water form floating blobs.' A student says this proves there is no gravity in space. Why do astronauts actually float inside the orbiting station?","a":"The station and astronauts are constantly falling around Earth together, a state called free fall","w":["There is no gravity at all once you leave Earth's atmosphere","The station is too far from Earth for Earth's gravity to reach it","The vacuum of space cancels out the pull of gravity"],"h":"Earth's gravity is still strong at the station's altitude — think about what an 'orbit' really is.","e":"Objects in orbit are in continuous free fall, circling Earth so fast they keep missing it; this weightlessness is not the absence of gravity."},{"p":"An astronomer compares two stars: a blue-white one and a reddish one. A student assumes the red star must be hotter because we call things 'red hot.' Which star is actually hotter?","a":"The blue-white star, because bluer stars have higher surface temperatures","w":["The red star, because red always signals the greatest heat","They must be equal, since all stars have the same temperature","The dimmer of the two, no matter what color it appears"],"h":"Think about the color of the hottest part of a flame compared to its cooler edges.","e":"A star's color reveals its surface temperature: blue and white stars are the hottest, while red stars are relatively cool."},{"p":"Read: 'On about September 22, a calendar marks the autumn equinox.' On this date, day and night are each close to 12 hours nearly everywhere on Earth. What causes this equal split of day and night?","a":"Earth's axis leans neither toward nor away from the Sun, so sunlight is shared evenly between hemispheres","w":["Earth reaches its closest point to the Sun on that exact date","Earth briefly stops rotating, balancing day and night","The Sun temporarily dims, which shortens the daylight hours"],"h":"Think about how Earth's tilt is oriented relative to the Sun on this particular day.","e":"At an equinox, Earth's axis points sideways to the Sun, so both hemispheres receive nearly equal daylight — about 12 hours of day and night."},{"p":"Read: 'A rock from space streaks through the sky, and a chunk of it survives to land in a farmer's field.' A collector wants to name the piece that actually reached the ground. What is that recovered space rock correctly called?","a":"A meteorite that landed on the ground","w":["A meteor blazing through the sky","A meteoroid drifting through space","A comet swinging past the Sun"],"h":"The name changes depending on whether the rock is in space, in the sky, or on the ground.","e":"A meteoroid travels in space, a meteor is the streak of light it makes burning up, and a meteorite is the piece that survives and lands."},{"p":"A science channel shows an artist's view of the Milky Way from far away, with curved arms winding out from a bright central bulge. What type of galaxy is the Milky Way?","a":"A spiral galaxy, with arms winding out from a central bulge","w":["An elliptical galaxy, shaped like a smooth football","An irregular galaxy, with no clearly defined shape","A ring galaxy, shaped like a hollow doughnut"],"h":"The description of curved arms winding outward is the biggest clue to its shape.","e":"The Milky Way is a spiral galaxy, featuring a central bulge and curving arms of stars, gas, and dust."},{"p":"Read: 'Near the North Pole, tourists watch shimmering green curtains of light ripple across the night sky — the northern lights.' What mainly causes these glowing auroras?","a":"Charged particles from the Sun striking gases in Earth's upper atmosphere near the poles","w":["Sunlight reflecting off large sheets of ice at the poles","City lights bouncing off high clouds over cold regions","Moonlight scattering through ice crystals in the polar air"],"h":"The Sun sends out more than just light — it also streams tiny charged particles into space.","e":"Auroras form when charged particles in the solar wind funnel toward Earth's magnetic poles and energize atmospheric gases, making them glow."},{"p":"Scientists sometimes call comets 'dirty snowballs.' Before a comet nears the Sun and grows a tail, what is its solid core mostly made of?","a":"Ice, dust, and rocky material frozen together","w":["Molten rock and streams of liquid metal","Burning gases glowing like a tiny star","Solid iron wrapped in a thick layer of air"],"h":"The nickname 'dirty snowball' hints at both a frozen part and a gritty part.","e":"A comet's nucleus is a mix of ices, dust, and rock; as it nears the Sun, the ices vaporize to form the glowing coma and tail."},{"p":"A student studying a tide chart is puzzled that most coastlines get two high tides and two low tides each day, not just one. Why are there usually two high tides daily?","a":"The Moon's gravity raises a bulge of water on both the near side and the far side of Earth","w":["The Moon passes directly over each coastline exactly twice every day","The Sun and the Moon each create one separate high tide per day","Earth's spin flings ocean water outward once each morning and evening"],"h":"There is a water bulge facing the Moon — but think about what happens on the opposite side of Earth too.","e":"Tidal bulges form on both the side nearest the Moon and the side farthest from it, so a rotating coastline passes through two highs each day."},{"p":"Read: 'Engineers move a satellite into a much higher orbit, farther from Earth's center.' What happens to the pull of Earth's gravity on the satellite as it moves farther away?","a":"The gravitational pull grows weaker as the distance increases","w":["The gravitational pull grows stronger as the distance increases","The gravitational pull stays exactly the same at any distance","The gravitational pull disappears completely once it leaves the ground"],"h":"Think about how a magnet's pull changes as you slowly slide it away from a paperclip.","e":"Gravitational force weakens with distance, so an object farther from Earth's center feels a smaller pull, though it never drops to zero."},{"p":"A student notices that Earth takes 1 year to orbit the Sun, but Neptune takes about 165 years. Why do planets farther from the Sun take so much longer to complete one orbit?","a":"They travel a longer path and move more slowly, since the Sun's pull is weaker farther out","w":["They stop and rest partway around because the sunlight is too dim","They are much heavier, so they simply need more time to move","They spin more slowly on their axis, which delays the whole orbit"],"h":"A distant planet has both a bigger loop to travel and a gentler pull from the Sun.","e":"Distant planets follow much longer paths at slower speeds because the Sun's gravity weakens with distance, making their years far longer."},{"p":"About a week after a full moon, a student sees the lit part of the Moon shrinking a little each night, heading toward the new moon. What do we call any phase when the visible lit portion is shrinking?","a":"A waning phase, when the lit part is shrinking","w":["A waxing phase, when the lit part is growing","A new phase, when no lit part shows","An eclipsed phase, when a shadow blocks it"],"h":"There are special words for when the lit part is getting bigger versus getting smaller.","e":"'Waning' describes the shrinking of the Moon's lit portion between full moon and new moon, while 'waxing' is the growing half of the cycle."},{"p":"Read: 'Our Sun is a middle-aged star, roughly halfway through its life.' Astronomers predict that billions of years from now, as it runs low on fuel, it will swell enormously. What will the Sun most likely become in this later stage?","a":"A red giant, expanding to many times its current size","w":["A black hole, collapsing into a tiny point","A brand-new galaxy filled with planets","A giant supernova that shatters into new stars"],"h":"The Sun is not massive enough to explode as a giant supernova — but it will puff up first.","e":"Medium-mass stars like the Sun expand into red giants near the end of their lives, later shedding their outer layers to leave a white dwarf."},{"p":"A student learns that even the nearest large galaxy to the Milky Way lies over 2 million light-years away. What is the name of that nearest large spiral galaxy?","a":"The Andromeda Galaxy, our nearest large neighbor","w":["The Orion Galaxy, named for the hunter","The Sombrero Galaxy, shaped like a hat","The Polaris Galaxy, home of the North Star"],"h":"This galaxy shares its name with a constellation in the northern sky.","e":"The Andromeda Galaxy is the nearest large spiral galaxy to our own and is slowly moving toward the Milky Way."},{"p":"A student wonders how the tiny Moon can perfectly cover the enormous Sun during a total solar eclipse. What makes this remarkable coverage possible?","a":"The Sun is much larger but also much farther away, so both appear nearly the same size in our sky","w":["The Moon temporarily grows until it matches the real size of the Sun","The Sun shrinks each time the Moon passes in front of it","The Moon is actually a little bit larger than the Sun in reality"],"h":"Hold your thumb up to block a faraway building — both size and distance affect how big something looks.","e":"By coincidence, the Sun is about 400 times wider than the Moon but also about 400 times farther away, so they appear nearly equal, letting the Moon just cover the Sun."},{"p":"Read: 'Most planets spin like slightly leaning tops, but one gas giant is tipped so far it seems to roll around the Sun on its side.' Which planet rotates on its side like this?","a":"Uranus, tipped almost completely on its side","w":["Jupiter, the largest planet of all","Saturn, famous for its bright rings","Neptune, the most distant gas giant"],"h":"It is one of the outer gas giants, and its extreme tilt gives it very strange seasons.","e":"Uranus has an axial tilt of about 98 degrees, so it essentially rotates on its side, likely because of an ancient collision."},{"p":"A student in the United States is enjoying a hot July while a pen pal in Australia is bundled up for winter at the same time. Why are the seasons opposite in the two hemispheres?","a":"When one hemisphere tilts toward the Sun, the other tilts away and gets less direct sunlight","w":["Australia is simply much farther from the Sun than the United States is","The two countries sit on opposite sides of the Sun at all times","Earth spins backward below the equator, which reverses the seasons"],"h":"Earth's tilt means the two halves of the planet can't both lean toward the Sun at once.","e":"Because of Earth's axial tilt, the hemisphere leaning toward the Sun has summer while the other, leaning away, has winter, so seasons are reversed."},{"p":"Read: 'Around June 21 in the Northern Hemisphere, a town holds a festival on the day with the most daylight hours of the whole year.' What is this longest day of the year called?","a":"The summer solstice, the year's longest day","w":["The winter solstice, the year's shortest day","The autumn equinox, with balanced day and night","The spring equinox, with balanced day and night"],"h":"'Solstice' marks the extremes of daylight, while 'equinox' marks the balanced days.","e":"The summer solstice, around June 21 in the Northern Hemisphere, is when that hemisphere tilts most toward the Sun, giving the longest daylight of the year."},{"p":"Through a telescope, a student photographs a giant glowing cloud of gas and dust in space where brand-new stars are forming. What is such a cloud called?","a":"A nebula, a cloud of gas and dust","w":["A constellation, a pattern of stars","A galaxy cluster, a group of galaxies","A meteor shower, a burst of falling meteors"],"h":"The word comes from the Latin for 'cloud' or 'mist.'","e":"A nebula is a cloud of gas and dust in space, and gravity can pull parts of it together to form new stars."}],"sp.1.colors":[{"p":"How do you say the color \"red\" in Spanish?","a":"rojo","w":["azul","verde","negro"],"h":"Think of the color of a shiny apple or a fire truck.","e":"The color \"red\" is \"rojo\" in Spanish. This is a basic color word."},{"p":"Your friend waves and says \"Hola!\" What does \"Hola\" mean in English?","a":"Hello","w":["Goodbye","Thank you","Please"],"h":"It is the friendly word you say when you first see someone.","e":"\"Hola\" is a common Spanish greeting that means \"Hello.\""},{"p":"How do you say the number \"three\" in Spanish?","a":"tres","w":["dos","cinco","seis"],"h":"Count on your fingers: uno, dos, then the next one.","e":"The number 3 is \"tres\" in Spanish. It comes right after \"dos\" (2)."},{"p":"What color is \"amarillo\" in English?","a":"yellow","w":["blue","green","brown"],"h":"Think of the bright sun in the sky or a banana.","e":"\"Amarillo\" means \"yellow,\" the color of the sun and bananas."},{"p":"How do you say the number \"ten\" in Spanish?","a":"diez","w":["nueve","ocho","doce"],"h":"It is the number you reach after counting all your fingers.","e":"The number 10 is \"diez\" in Spanish."},{"p":"How do you say \"blue\" in Spanish?","a":"azul","w":["rojo","rosa","gris"],"h":"Think of the color of the sky on a sunny day.","e":"The color \"blue\" is \"azul\" in Spanish."},{"p":"Your teacher says \"Adios\" as you leave school. What does \"Adios\" mean?","a":"Goodbye","w":["Hello","Good morning","Welcome"],"h":"You say it when you are leaving, not arriving.","e":"\"Adios\" means \"Goodbye\" in Spanish."},{"p":"How do you say the number \"one\" in Spanish?","a":"uno","w":["dos","tres","cuatro"],"h":"It is the very first number you say when you start counting.","e":"The number 1 is \"uno\" in Spanish."},{"p":"What color is \"verde\" in English?","a":"green","w":["yellow","red","purple"],"h":"Think of the color of grass and leaves on a tree.","e":"\"Verde\" means \"green,\" the color of grass and leaves."},{"p":"How do you say the number \"five\" in Spanish?","a":"cinco","w":["cuatro","seis","siete"],"h":"It is how many fingers are on one hand.","e":"The number 5 is \"cinco\" in Spanish."},{"p":"How do you say \"black\" in Spanish?","a":"negro","w":["blanco","rojo","azul"],"h":"Think of the color of the dark night sky.","e":"The color \"black\" is \"negro\" in Spanish."},{"p":"What does \"Buenos dias\" mean in English?","a":"Good morning","w":["Good night","Goodbye","See you later"],"h":"You say it early in the day when you first wake up.","e":"\"Buenos dias\" is a greeting that means \"Good morning.\""},{"p":"How do you say the number \"seven\" in Spanish?","a":"siete","w":["seis","ocho","nueve"],"h":"It comes right after \"seis\" (6) when you count.","e":"The number 7 is \"siete\" in Spanish."},{"p":"What color is \"blanco\" in English?","a":"white","w":["black","pink","gray"],"h":"Think of the color of fresh snow or clouds.","e":"\"Blanco\" means \"white,\" the color of snow and clouds."},{"p":"How do you say the number \"two\" in Spanish?","a":"dos","w":["uno","tres","diez"],"h":"It is how many eyes you have.","e":"The number 2 is \"dos\" in Spanish."},{"p":"How do you say \"cat\" in Spanish?","a":"gato","w":["perro","pez","pajaro"],"h":"Think of the furry pet that says \"meow.\"","e":"\"Gato\" is the Spanish word for \"cat.\""},{"p":"How do you say the number \"eight\" in Spanish?","a":"ocho","w":["siete","nueve","seis"],"h":"It comes right after \"siete\" (7) when you count.","e":"The number 8 is \"ocho\" in Spanish."},{"p":"How do you say \"dog\" in Spanish?","a":"perro","w":["gato","raton","caballo"],"h":"Think of the pet that barks \"woof\" and wags its tail.","e":"\"Perro\" is the Spanish word for \"dog.\""},{"p":"Read: Ana has cuatro crayons. Then she finds dos more crayons under her desk. How many crayons does Ana have now? Say the number in Spanish.","a":"seis","w":["ocho","cinco","dos"],"h":"First count what she starts with, then count on as she finds more.","e":"Adding in Spanish: cuatro (4) plus dos (2) equals seis (6)."},{"p":"Read: Pedro paints a pumpkin the color 'naranja'. What color is 'naranja' in English?","a":"Orange","w":["Purple","Pink","Brown"],"h":"Think about the color of a pumpkin or a juicy fruit with the same name.","e":"'Naranja' means orange, and it is also the Spanish word for the orange fruit."},{"p":"How do you say the number 'four' in Spanish?","a":"cuatro","w":["catorce","cuarto","cinco"],"h":"It starts with the 'cu' sound, like the beginning of 'cuckoo'.","e":"'Cuatro' means four; 'catorce' is fourteen and 'cinco' is five."},{"p":"Read: In Spanish the days go lunes, martes, miercoles... Which day comes right after 'lunes' (Monday)?","a":"martes","w":["domingo","viernes","sabado"],"h":"Look at the order in the passage and find the very next word after lunes.","e":"The days of the week: after lunes (Monday) comes martes (Tuesday)."},{"p":"How do you say the number 'twelve' in Spanish?","a":"doce","w":["dos","diez","trece"],"h":"It rhymes with the Spanish words for eleven (once) and thirteen.","e":"'Doce' means twelve; 'dos' is two and 'trece' is thirteen."},{"p":"Read: Lucia wears a 'rosa' bow in her hair, just like her favorite flower. What color is 'rosa' in English?","a":"Pink","w":["Red","Purple","Orange"],"h":"Think of the soft color of a rose petal, not a bright fire-truck color.","e":"'Rosa' means pink; the red color is 'rojo'."},{"p":"Read: Maria has seis stickers. She gives dos of them to her friend. How many stickers does Maria have left? Say the number in Spanish.","a":"cuatro","w":["ocho","tres","cinco"],"h":"Start with what she had, then take away the ones she gave to her friend.","e":"Subtracting in Spanish: seis (6) minus dos (2) equals cuatro (4)."},{"p":"Read: Your friend shares her snack with you at recess. You smile and say 'Gracias!' What does 'Gracias' mean?","a":"Thank you","w":["Please","Hello","Goodbye"],"h":"It is the polite word you say when someone gives you something.","e":"'Gracias' means thank you, used to show you are grateful."},{"p":"What does 'Buenas noches' mean in English?","a":"Good night","w":["Good morning","Good afternoon","Good day"],"h":"'Noche' points to the time when the stars come out and you go to sleep.","e":"'Buenas noches' means good night; 'Buenos dias' means good morning."},{"p":"How do you say the number 'nine' in Spanish?","a":"nueve","w":["nuevo","nieve","diez"],"h":"It comes right before diez when you count up.","e":"'Nueve' means nine; 'nuevo' means new and 'nieve' means snow."},{"p":"How do you say the number 'six' in Spanish?","a":"seis","w":["siete","tres","diez"],"h":"It comes right after cinco when you count on your fingers.","e":"'Seis' means six; 'siete' is seven and 'tres' is three."},{"p":"How do you say the color 'purple' in Spanish?","a":"morado","w":["rosa","marron","naranja"],"h":"It is the color you get by mixing blue and red, like a grape.","e":"'Morado' means purple; 'rosa' is pink and 'naranja' is orange."},{"p":"How do you say 'house' in Spanish?","a":"casa","w":["cosa","mesa","gato"],"h":"It is the place where your family lives and sleeps.","e":"'Casa' means house; 'cosa' means thing and 'mesa' means table."},{"p":"Read: Your teacher hands you a 'libro' and asks you to read it quietly. What is a 'libro'?","a":"A book","w":["A pen","A desk","A backpack"],"h":"Think of something with pages full of stories that you read.","e":"'Libro' means book, the thing you read in class."},{"p":"Read: Diego packs a red 'manzana' in his lunch for a healthy snack. What is a 'manzana' in English?","a":"An apple","w":["A banana","An orange","A grape"],"h":"It is a round, crunchy fruit that can be red or green.","e":"'Manzana' means apple, a common lunchbox fruit."},{"p":"How do you say the number 'twenty' in Spanish?","a":"veinte","w":["treinta","doce","dos"],"h":"It is the biggest number you reach counting all your fingers and toes.","e":"'Veinte' means twenty; 'treinta' is thirty and 'doce' is twelve."},{"p":"How do you say 'Saturday' in Spanish?","a":"sabado","w":["domingo","viernes","semana"],"h":"It is a weekend day, right before Sunday (domingo).","e":"'Sabado' means Saturday; 'domingo' is Sunday and 'semana' means week."},{"p":"How do you say the number 'eleven' in Spanish?","a":"once","w":["uno","diez","doce"],"h":"It is the first number you say after reaching ten (diez).","e":"'Once' means eleven; 'diez' is ten and 'doce' is twelve."},{"p":"How do you say the number \"fifteen\" in Spanish?","a":"quince","w":["catorce","dieciseis","cinco"],"h":"It comes right after fourteen when you count.","e":"The Spanish number 'quince' means fifteen (15)."},{"p":"How do you say the number \"thirteen\" in Spanish?","a":"trece","w":["doce","catorce","tres"],"h":"It comes right after twelve when you count.","e":"The Spanish number 'trece' means thirteen (13)."},{"p":"Read: There are nueve kids playing tag at recess. Then cinco more kids join the game. How many kids are playing now? Say the number in Spanish.","a":"catorce","w":["trece","quince","diez"],"h":"Add the two groups of kids together, then say that number in Spanish.","e":"Nine plus five is fourteen, which is 'catorce' in Spanish (addition)."},{"p":"How do you say the number \"eighteen\" in Spanish?","a":"dieciocho","w":["diecisiete","diecinueve","ocho"],"h":"It comes right after seventeen when you count.","e":"The Spanish number 'dieciocho' means eighteen (18)."},{"p":"How do you say the color \"gray\" in Spanish?","a":"gris","w":["negro","azul","verde"],"h":"Think of the color of a rainy cloud in the sky.","e":"The Spanish word 'gris' means the color gray."},{"p":"What color is \"marron\" in English?","a":"brown","w":["purple","gray","orange"],"h":"Think of the color of chocolate or a tree trunk.","e":"The Spanish color word 'marron' means brown."},{"p":"Read: You want your friend to pass you the crayons, so you say \"Por favor.\" What does \"Por favor\" mean?","a":"Please","w":["Thank you","You're welcome","Excuse me"],"h":"It is the polite word you use when you ask for something.","e":"'Por favor' is the Spanish way to say please."},{"p":"Read: You give your sister a cookie and she says \"Gracias.\" You smile and reply \"De nada.\" What does \"De nada\" mean?","a":"You're welcome","w":["Please","Good morning","See you later"],"h":"It is the polite thing to say after someone thanks you.","e":"'De nada' is the Spanish reply meaning you're welcome."},{"p":"What does \"Buenas tardes\" mean in English?","a":"Good afternoon","w":["Good morning","Good night","Goodbye"],"h":"It is the greeting you use after lunchtime, when the sun is still up.","e":"'Buenas tardes' is a Spanish greeting meaning good afternoon."},{"p":"How do you say \"Sunday\" in Spanish?","a":"domingo","w":["sabado","viernes","lunes"],"h":"It is the day right after Saturday, often a day to rest.","e":"'Domingo' is the Spanish word for Sunday."},{"p":"Read: You see your friend at the park and ask \"Como estas?\" What does \"Como estas?\" mean?","a":"How are you?","w":["What is your name?","How old are you?","Where are you?"],"h":"You are asking your friend about how they feel today.","e":"'Como estas?' is the Spanish way to ask how are you."},{"p":"How do you say \"water\" in Spanish?","a":"agua","w":["leche","jugo","pan"],"h":"Think of the clear drink you sip when you are thirsty.","e":"'Agua' is the Spanish word for water."},{"p":"Read: Every morning Sofia walks to la escuela to learn and play with her friends. What is \"escuela\" in English?","a":"school","w":["house","park","store"],"h":"It is the place where you have a teacher and learn to read.","e":"'Escuela' is the Spanish word for school."},{"p":"Read: Miguel draws a big, bright yellow sol at the top of his picture. What is \"sol\" in English?","a":"sun","w":["moon","star","sky"],"h":"It is the bright thing that shines during the daytime.","e":"'Sol' is the Spanish word for sun."},{"p":"Read: Carla counts diez red apples and siete green apples in one basket. How many apples are there in all? Say the number in Spanish.","a":"diecisiete","w":["dieciseis","dieciocho","quince"],"h":"Put the red and green apples together, then say that number in Spanish.","e":"Ten plus seven is seventeen, which is 'diecisiete' in Spanish (addition)."},{"p":"Read: Rosa picks a pretty flor from the garden to give to her mom. What is a \"flor\" in English?","a":"flower","w":["tree","leaf","plant"],"h":"It is the colorful thing that grows in a garden and smells nice.","e":"'Flor' is the Spanish word for flower."},{"p":"How do you say the number \"nineteen\" in Spanish?","a":"diecinueve","w":["dieciocho","diecisiete","nueve"],"h":"It is the number that comes just one before twenty.","e":"The Spanish number 'diecinueve' means nineteen (19)."},{"p":"Read: At lunch, Ben drinks a cold glass of leche with his cookies. What is \"leche\" in English?","a":"milk","w":["water","juice","tea"],"h":"It is the white drink that comes from cows.","e":"'Leche' is the Spanish word for milk."}],"s.9.genetics":[{"p":"In a DNA molecule, which nitrogenous base pairs with adenine (A)?","a":"Thymine (T)","w":["Guanine (G)","Cytosine (C)","Uracil (U)"],"h":"Complementary base pairing follows a specific purine-pyrimidine rule unique to DNA.","e":"By Chargaff's base-pairing rule, adenine pairs with thymine and guanine pairs with cytosine in DNA."},{"p":"Which statement best defines a gene?","a":"A segment of DNA that codes for a specific protein or trait","w":["An entire chromosome made of tightly coiled DNA","A protein that determines an organism's traits","A single nucleotide within a DNA strand"],"h":"Think about the level of organization between a nucleotide and a whole chromosome.","e":"A gene is the basic unit of heredity: a DNA sequence that encodes a functional product such as a protein."},{"p":"A typical human body (somatic) cell contains how many chromosomes?","a":"46 chromosomes arranged in 23 pairs","w":["23 chromosomes arranged in 23 pairs","46 chromosomes arranged in 46 pairs","92 chromosomes arranged in 46 pairs"],"h":"Somatic cells are diploid, carrying two copies of each chromosome.","e":"Human somatic cells are diploid (2n = 46): 23 homologous pairs, one set inherited from each parent."},{"p":"An organism's phenotype is best described as its...","a":"observable physical traits","w":["complete set of alleles","full sequence of DNA nucleotides","specific combination of two alleles"],"h":"The root of the word relates to what is shown or appears.","e":"Phenotype is the observable expression of a trait, whereas genotype is the underlying allele combination."},{"p":"An organism with the genotype Bb is described as...","a":"heterozygous for that gene","w":["homozygous dominant for that gene","homozygous recessive for that gene","hemizygous for that gene"],"h":"Consider whether the two alleles present are the same or different.","e":"Heterozygous means an organism carries two different alleles for a trait; homozygous means two identical alleles."},{"p":"In a heterozygous organism, a dominant allele is one that...","a":"is expressed in the phenotype, masking the recessive allele","w":["is expressed only when two copies are present","is always more common within a population","is lost and does not appear in the offspring"],"h":"Think about which allele's effect you can see when both are present together.","e":"A dominant allele masks the recessive allele in a heterozygote, determining the observed phenotype."},{"p":"Two heterozygous tall plants are crossed (Tt x Tt), where tall (T) is dominant to short (t). What is the expected phenotypic ratio of the offspring?","a":"3 tall : 1 short","w":["1 tall : 1 short","1 tall : 2 medium : 1 short","4 tall : 0 short"],"h":"Count how many boxes of the Punnett square contain at least one dominant allele.","e":"A monohybrid cross between two heterozygotes produces a 3:1 phenotypic ratio of dominant to recessive."},{"p":"In a cross Tt x Tt, what is the expected genotypic ratio of the offspring?","a":"1 TT : 2 Tt : 1 tt","w":["3 TT : 1 tt","1 TT : 1 tt","2 TT : 2 tt"],"h":"Genotype ratios count each specific allele combination separately, not just appearance.","e":"Two heterozygotes yield a 1:2:1 genotypic ratio: homozygous dominant, heterozygous, and homozygous recessive."},{"p":"A heterozygous tall plant (Tt) is crossed with a short plant (tt), where tall is dominant. What fraction of the offspring are expected to be short?","a":"1/2 (50%)","w":["1/4 (25%)","3/4 (75%)","0 (none are short)"],"h":"Set up the cross and count how many boxes contain two recessive alleles.","e":"A testcross of Tt x tt gives a 1:1 ratio, so half the offspring are homozygous recessive (short)."},{"p":"The term \"allele\" refers to...","a":"an alternative version of a gene","w":["a short segment of a finished protein","a matched pair of homologous chromosomes","the physical trait an organism displays"],"h":"Different forms of the same gene occupy the same position on a chromosome.","e":"Alleles are alternative forms of a gene located at the same locus on homologous chromosomes."},{"p":"According to Mendel's law of segregation, how many alleles for a given gene does each gamete carry?","a":"one allele","w":["two alleles","four alleles","none, alleles form only after fertilization"],"h":"Gametes are haploid, produced when paired alleles separate.","e":"The law of segregation states that allele pairs separate during gamete formation, so each gamete carries one allele."},{"p":"A recessive trait appears in an organism's phenotype only when the organism...","a":"has two recessive alleles","w":["has one recessive allele","has one dominant and one recessive allele","has two dominant alleles"],"h":"A recessive allele's effect is hidden whenever a dominant allele is also present.","e":"Recessive phenotypes require a homozygous recessive genotype, since a single dominant allele would mask the trait."},{"p":"The overall three-dimensional shape of a DNA molecule is best described as a...","a":"double helix","w":["single helix","branched chain","folded flat sheet"],"h":"Two strands twist around each other like a spiral ladder.","e":"Watson and Crick described DNA as a double helix: two antiparallel strands coiled around a common axis."},{"p":"In humans, which pair of sex chromosomes is typically found in a biological male?","a":"XY","w":["XX","YY","XO"],"h":"A male inherits one sex chromosome from each parent, and the two differ.","e":"Human males are typically XY and females XX; the Y chromosome carries male-determining genes such as SRY."},{"p":"A person with blood type AB expresses both the A and B antigens fully and equally. This inheritance pattern is an example of...","a":"codominance","w":["incomplete dominance","complete dominance","recessive inheritance"],"h":"Both alleles are fully and simultaneously expressed rather than blended.","e":"In codominance both alleles are fully expressed in the heterozygote, as with the I^A I^B genotype for blood type AB."},{"p":"Crossing a red-flowered snapdragon (RR) with a white-flowered snapdragon (WW) produces all pink-flowered offspring. This pattern is an example of...","a":"incomplete dominance","w":["codominance","complete dominance","multiple alleles"],"h":"The heterozygote shows a blended, intermediate phenotype between the two parents.","e":"Incomplete dominance produces a heterozygous phenotype intermediate between the two homozygotes, such as pink from red and white."},{"p":"A person who is heterozygous for a recessive genetic disorder but shows no symptoms is called a...","a":"carrier","w":["sufferer","mutant","hybrid"],"h":"This individual can pass the recessive allele to offspring without expressing the disorder.","e":"A carrier is a heterozygote who possesses one recessive disease allele masked by a dominant allele, so no symptoms appear."},{"p":"A dihybrid cross RrYy x RrYy is performed, where round (R) and yellow (Y) are both dominant and the two genes assort independently. What is the expected phenotypic ratio of the offspring?","a":"9:3:3:1","w":["3:1","1:2:1","9:3:4"],"h":"Each gene on its own produces a 3:1 ratio; consider what happens when two such genes are combined.","e":"By the law of independent assortment, a cross between two dihybrid heterozygotes produces the classic 9:3:3:1 phenotypic ratio."},{"p":"A DNA sample is found to contain 30% adenine. Based on this, what percentage of the sample is guanine?","a":"20%","w":["30%","40%","70%"],"h":"Adenine and its partner occur in equal amounts; the remaining percentage is shared equally between the other two bases.","e":"By Chargaff's rule, %A = %T and %G = %C. If A = T = 30%, then G + C = 40%, so G = C = 20%."},{"p":"A plant shows the dominant round-seed phenotype, but whether its genotype is RR or Rr is unknown. Which cross would best reveal its genotype?","a":"Cross it with a homozygous recessive (rr) plant","w":["Cross it with a homozygous dominant (RR) plant","Cross it with another round-seeded plant of unknown genotype","Cross it with a heterozygous (Rr) plant"],"h":"You want a cross in which any hidden recessive allele in the unknown parent would clearly show up in the offspring.","e":"This is a test cross: crossing an unknown dominant phenotype with a homozygous recessive lets the offspring ratio reveal the unknown genotype."},{"p":"Red-green colorblindness is an X-linked recessive trait. A carrier mother (X^N X^n) has children with a father who has normal vision (X^N Y). What fraction of their sons is expected to be colorblind?","a":"1/2","w":["1/4","0","all of them"],"h":"Sons receive their single X chromosome from the mother; look only at the male offspring.","e":"In X-linked recessive inheritance, sons inherit their one X from the carrier mother, so half receive the X^n allele and are colorblind."},{"p":"A man with type O blood and a woman with type AB blood have children. Which blood types are possible among their children?","a":"Type A or type B","w":["Type AB or type O","Type A, B, AB, or O","Type O only"],"h":"The type O parent can pass on only one kind of allele; pair it with each allele the AB parent can contribute.","e":"With multiple alleles, the O parent (ii) contributes i while the AB parent (I^A I^B) contributes I^A or I^B, giving type A (I^A i) or type B (I^B i)."},{"p":"Assuming independent assortment, how many genetically different types of gametes can an organism with the genotype AaBb produce?","a":"4","w":["2","8","16"],"h":"Each heterozygous gene pair offers two allele choices; combine the choices across genes.","e":"By independent assortment, the number of gamete types equals 2^n for n heterozygous gene pairs, so 2^2 = 4."},{"p":"Which statement correctly distinguishes incomplete dominance from codominance?","a":"In incomplete dominance the heterozygote shows a single blended intermediate phenotype","w":["In incomplete dominance the heterozygote shows both alleles fully and separately","In incomplete dominance the heterozygote always matches the dominant homozygote","In incomplete dominance no heterozygous offspring can survive"],"h":"Focus on whether the two alleles blend into one new appearance or appear side by side.","e":"Incomplete dominance yields an intermediate blended phenotype (e.g., pink), while codominance expresses both alleles fully at once (e.g., AB blood)."},{"p":"In a family, two parents who do not show a particular trait have a child who does show the trait. This pattern indicates the trait is most likely...","a":"recessive","w":["dominant","located on the Y chromosome","impossible to inherit"],"h":"If neither parent displays the trait, each must be carrying a hidden allele that combined in the child.","e":"Two unaffected parents producing an affected child indicates a recessive trait; both parents were heterozygous carriers."},{"p":"DNA replication is described as semiconservative. After one round of replication, each new double helix consists of...","a":"one original (template) strand and one newly made strand","w":["two newly made strands","two original strands","one strand of DNA and one strand of RNA"],"h":"The term 'semiconservative' hints that half of each new molecule is conserved from the parent.","e":"In semiconservative replication, each daughter molecule keeps one parental strand paired with one newly synthesized complementary strand."},{"p":"Down syndrome (trisomy 21) most often results from nondisjunction. Nondisjunction is best described as...","a":"the failure of chromosomes to separate properly during meiosis","w":["the substitution of one DNA base for another","the failure of DNA to replicate before cell division","the exchange of segments between homologous chromosomes"],"h":"'Trisomy' means a gamete ended up with an extra copy of a chromosome.","e":"Nondisjunction is the failure of homologous chromosomes or sister chromatids to separate during meiosis, producing a gamete with an abnormal chromosome number."},{"p":"Human traits such as height and skin color vary along a smooth, continuous range rather than falling into a few distinct categories. This pattern is best explained by...","a":"polygenic inheritance, in which many genes contribute to one trait","w":["a single gene with only two alleles","complete dominance of one allele over another","nondisjunction occurring during meiosis"],"h":"Continuous variation across a population usually signals that more than one gene affects the trait.","e":"Polygenic inheritance means several genes each add small effects to one trait, producing continuous, bell-curve-like variation."},{"p":"Homologous chromosomes are best described as...","a":"a pair of chromosomes carrying the same genes, one inherited from each parent","w":["two identical sister chromatids joined at a centromere","the X and Y chromosomes found together in a male","a chromosome paired with its messenger RNA copy"],"h":"Think about the matched pairs that line up during meiosis, not the two halves of one replicated chromosome.","e":"Homologous chromosomes are matched maternal and paternal pairs with the same gene loci, though they may carry different alleles."},{"p":"In a cross Tt x Tt, where tall (T) is dominant to short (t), what is the probability that the first two offspring will BOTH be tall?","a":"9/16","w":["3/4","3/16","1/2"],"h":"Find the probability that one offspring is tall, then apply the multiplication rule for independent events.","e":"By the rule of multiplication, each offspring has a 3/4 chance of being tall, so both being tall is 3/4 x 3/4 = 9/16."},{"p":"In a cross AaBb x AaBb, where the two genes assort independently, what is the probability of an offspring with the genotype aabb?","a":"1/16","w":["1/4","1/8","9/16"],"h":"Determine the chance of aa and the chance of bb separately, then combine them.","e":"By independent assortment and the multiplication rule, aa = 1/4 and bb = 1/4, so aabb = 1/4 x 1/4 = 1/16."},{"p":"A change in a single nucleotide base in a DNA sequence, such as replacing an A-T pair with a G-C pair, is called a...","a":"point mutation","w":["nondisjunction event","chromosomal deletion","crossing-over event"],"h":"The change affects only one base position, not entire chromosomes or their arrangement.","e":"A point (substitution) mutation changes a single nucleotide, which may or may not alter the resulting amino acid."},{"p":"Of the 46 chromosomes in a human somatic cell, how many are autosomes (non-sex chromosomes)?","a":"44","w":["46","23","22"],"h":"Subtract the single pair of sex chromosomes from the total number of chromosomes.","e":"Humans have 23 pairs of chromosomes; 22 pairs (44 chromosomes) are autosomes and one pair are the sex chromosomes."},{"p":"A father with the genotype I^A i and a mother with the genotype I^B i have children. What is the probability that a child will have type O blood?","a":"1/4","w":["1/2","0","3/4"],"h":"Type O requires two recessive i alleles; find the chance of inheriting i from each parent.","e":"With multiple alleles, each parent has a 1/2 chance of passing i, so the ii (type O) combination = 1/2 x 1/2 = 1/4."},{"p":"During transcription, an mRNA strand is built using a DNA template. Which base does RNA use in place of the thymine (T) found in DNA?","a":"uracil (U)","w":["cytosine (C)","guanine (G)","adenine (A)"],"h":"RNA shares three of DNA's four bases but swaps out one of the pyrimidines.","e":"In RNA, uracil replaces thymine and pairs with adenine during transcription."},{"p":"Calico (tortoiseshell) cats show patches of both orange and black fur, and this coloring is almost always seen in females. It arises because the coat-color gene is X-linked and one X chromosome is randomly switched off in each cell. This process is called...","a":"Random inactivation of one X chromosome (X-inactivation)","w":["Codominance of the two coat-color alleles","Crossing over between the two X chromosomes","Nondisjunction of the X chromosome during meiosis"],"h":"Female mammals carry two X chromosomes but keep only one active per cell.","e":"X-inactivation (Lyonization) randomly silences one X chromosome in each cell of a female mammal, forming a Barr body and producing the mosaic patches seen in calico cats."},{"p":"In mice, the yellow-coat allele (A^Y) is dominant to gray (a), but embryos with two copies (A^Y A^Y) die before birth. When two yellow mice (A^Y a) are crossed, what phenotypic ratio is expected among the surviving offspring?","a":"2 yellow : 1 gray","w":["3 yellow : 1 gray","1 yellow : 1 gray","All offspring yellow"],"h":"One of the four Punnett-square genotypes never survives to be counted.","e":"A^Y is a recessive lethal allele: A^Y a x A^Y a gives 1 A^YA^Y (dies) : 2 A^Ya (yellow) : 1 aa (gray), leaving a surviving 2:1 ratio."},{"p":"In sickle cell disease, a single mutated gene affects red blood cell shape, oxygen transport, spleen function, and joint pain. When one gene influences many seemingly unrelated traits, the phenomenon is called...","a":"Pleiotropy","w":["Polygenic inheritance","Epistasis","Incomplete dominance"],"h":"Here it is one gene producing many effects, not many genes shaping one trait.","e":"Pleiotropy occurs when a single gene influences multiple, often unrelated phenotypic traits; it is the reverse of polygenic inheritance."},{"p":"In Labrador retrievers, one gene sets pigment color (black vs. brown), but a second gene can block pigment deposition entirely, producing a yellow dog regardless of the first gene's alleles. This interaction, where one gene masks the effect of another gene, is called...","a":"Epistasis","w":["Codominance","Pleiotropy","Incomplete dominance"],"h":"This involves two different genes, one of which overrides the other.","e":"Epistasis is a gene interaction in which the alleles at one gene locus mask or modify the phenotypic expression of a different gene."},{"p":"In regions where malaria is common, people heterozygous for the sickle cell allele are more likely to survive than either homozygote. This survival benefit for individuals carrying one of each allele is best described as...","a":"Heterozygote advantage","w":["Simple codominance","Incomplete dominance","Random genetic drift"],"h":"The benefit belongs specifically to individuals with one copy of each allele.","e":"Heterozygote advantage (a form of balancing selection) keeps the sickle cell allele common because carriers resist malaria while escaping severe sickle cell disease."},{"p":"Cystic fibrosis is an autosomal recessive disorder. Two unaffected parents who are both carriers (Cc) plan to have a child. What is the probability that their child will be affected (cc)?","a":"1/4","w":["1/2","1/3","2/3"],"h":"Draw a Cc x Cc Punnett square and count only the fully recessive box.","e":"A monohybrid cross of two heterozygotes yields a 1:2:1 genotypic ratio, so 1/4 of offspring are homozygous recessive, per Mendel's law of segregation."},{"p":"Two parents who are both carriers (Cc) for an autosomal recessive disorder have a child who is unaffected. Given that the child does not show the disorder, what is the probability that this child is a carrier (Cc)?","a":"2/3","w":["1/2","1/4","3/4"],"h":"Among unaffected offspring only, compare the Cc boxes to the CC box; the cc box is ruled out.","e":"The three unaffected genotypes occur in a 1 CC : 2 Cc ratio, so two of every three unaffected children are carriers; this is a conditional probability that excludes the affected outcome."},{"p":"Mitochondrial DNA is carried almost entirely in the egg cell, so a mitochondrial disorder passes only from an affected mother to all of her children, while affected fathers never transmit it. This pattern is known as...","a":"Maternal (cytoplasmic) inheritance","w":["X-linked recessive inheritance","Autosomal dominant inheritance","Y-linked inheritance"],"h":"Consider which parent's gamete supplies the cytoplasm and organelles to the zygote.","e":"Mitochondrial (maternal/cytoplasmic) inheritance passes only through the egg, so an affected mother transmits the trait to all offspring and affected fathers transmit it to none."},{"p":"Hemophilia is an X-linked recessive disorder. A carrier mother (X^H X^h) has children with a father who has hemophilia (X^h Y). What fraction of their daughters is expected to be affected?","a":"1/2","w":["1/4","All of the daughters","None of the daughters"],"h":"Every daughter receives X^h from the father; her status then depends on the X she gets from the mother.","e":"Each daughter inherits the father's X^h, and half also receive X^h from the carrier mother, making 1/2 of daughters homozygous recessive and affected."},{"p":"Coat color in rabbits is set by one gene with four alleles in a dominance series: full color (C) > chinchilla (c^ch) > Himalayan (c^h) > albino (c). A rabbit with the genotype c^ch c will display which coat color?","a":"Chinchilla","w":["Full color","Himalayan","Albino"],"h":"In a dominance series, the allele ranked higher determines a heterozygote's phenotype.","e":"With multiple alleles in a dominance hierarchy, c^ch is dominant to c (albino), so a c^ch c rabbit shows the chinchilla phenotype."},{"p":"Two genes located close together on the same chromosome do not follow Mendel's law of independent assortment; instead they tend to be inherited together as a unit. Such genes are described as...","a":"Linked genes","w":["Homologous genes","Codominant genes","Polygenic genes"],"h":"Their shared physical location keeps them traveling together during meiosis.","e":"Genes on the same chromosome are linked and tend to be inherited together; only crossing over between them can separate the alleles and break the linkage."},{"p":"Two genes on the same chromosome show a recombination (crossover) frequency of 12%. In genetic mapping, this value indicates that the two genes are...","a":"About 12 map units apart on the chromosome","w":["Located on two different chromosomes","Completely linked and never separated","Assorting fully independently during meiosis"],"h":"One percent recombination corresponds to one unit of map distance.","e":"Recombination frequency estimates the distance between linked genes: 1% recombination equals one map unit (centimorgan), so 12% places the genes about 12 map units apart."},{"p":"A person with Turner syndrome has only a single X chromosome and no second sex chromosome (written 45,X). Compared with a typical human cell, this individual's cells contain...","a":"One fewer chromosome than the typical 46","w":["One more chromosome than the typical 46","Exactly the typical 46 chromosomes","Twice the typical number of chromosomes"],"h":"Count the total when one sex chromosome is missing from the usual pair.","e":"Turner syndrome (monosomy X, 45,X) results from nondisjunction and leaves the individual with 45 chromosomes, one fewer than the typical 46."},{"p":"In the genetic code, the bases of mRNA are read in groups that each specify one amino acid. How many nucleotide bases make up one such group, called a codon?","a":"Three","w":["One","Two","Four"],"h":"The genetic code is often described as a \"triplet\" code.","e":"The genetic code is read in codons of three nucleotides, each specifying one amino acid or a start/stop signal during translation."},{"p":"A single nucleotide is inserted near the start of a gene's coding sequence, changing how every codon downstream is read. This type of mutation is called a...","a":"Frameshift mutation","w":["Silent mutation","Point substitution mutation","Chromosomal inversion"],"h":"Adding or removing a base changes the reading \"frame\" of all following codons.","e":"An insertion or deletion that is not a multiple of three shifts the reading frame, causing a frameshift mutation that alters every codon after the change."},{"p":"The two strands of a DNA double helix run in opposite directions: one strand runs 5' to 3' while its partner runs 3' to 5'. This opposite orientation of the two strands is described as...","a":"Antiparallel","w":["Complementary","Semiconservative","Supercoiled"],"h":"The term describes the strands' direction, not their base pairing.","e":"The two DNA strands are antiparallel, running in opposite 5'-to-3' orientations, an arrangement required for complementary base pairing and replication."},{"p":"Huntington's disease is caused by a dominant allele (H) and typically appears in mid-adulthood. A parent who is heterozygous (Hh) has children with an unaffected partner (hh). What is the probability that a given child will inherit the disease allele?","a":"1/2","w":["1/4","3/4","Zero, because symptoms appear only late in life"],"h":"Cross Hh x hh and count the offspring carrying at least one H allele.","e":"In an Hh x hh cross, half the offspring receive the dominant H allele; because Huntington's is autosomal dominant, a single copy is enough to cause the disease."}],"sp.3.family":[{"p":"How do you say \"mother\" in Spanish?","a":"la madre","w":["el padre","la hermana","el abuelo"],"h":"Think of the person who might tuck you in at night in many families.","e":"\"La madre\" means mother; family words like this are vocabulary for La Familia."},{"p":"Marcos has a boy who was born to the same parents. He is Marcos's ___. Which Spanish word fits?","a":"el hermano","w":["la hermana","el primo","el tío"],"h":"A boy in your family who shares your parents uses a word ending in -o.","e":"\"El hermano\" means brother; the -o ending marks a male family member."},{"p":"Which room of the house is la cocina?","a":"the kitchen","w":["the bathroom","the bedroom","the living room"],"h":"It is the room where yummy snacks and dinner get made.","e":"\"La cocina\" means kitchen, the room for cooking food."},{"p":"Sofía is sleepy and goes to bed. Which room does she go to?","a":"el dormitorio","w":["la cocina","el comedor","el garaje"],"h":"Think about the room with a bed for sleeping.","e":"\"El dormitorio\" means bedroom, the room where you sleep."},{"p":"You sleep on it every night. What is \"la cama\" in English?","a":"the bed","w":["the chair","the table","the lamp"],"h":"It is soft and you close your eyes on it at night.","e":"\"La cama\" means bed, a common household object in the bedroom."},{"p":"Which household object is \"la silla\"?","a":"the chair","w":["the bed","the door","the window"],"h":"You sit on it at the dinner table.","e":"\"La silla\" means chair, something you sit on."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Yo ___ Ana.\" (I am Ana.)","a":"soy","w":["estoy","eres","es"],"h":"You are telling your name, and the word starts with \"yo.\"","e":"For saying who you are with \"yo,\" we use \"soy\" from the verb ser."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"El gato ___ en la casa.\" (The cat is in the house.)","a":"está","w":["es","soy","son"],"h":"You are telling WHERE the cat is right now.","e":"For location, Spanish uses estar, so \"el gato está en la casa.\""},{"p":"In Spanish, \"grande\" describes something that is ___.","a":"big","w":["small","happy","fast"],"h":"Picture a huge elephant, not a tiny mouse.","e":"\"Grande\" means big; it is a basic description word."},{"p":"Your new puppy is tiny. Which Spanish word means \"small\"?","a":"pequeño","w":["grande","viejo","nuevo"],"h":"Think of the opposite of grande.","e":"\"Pequeño\" means small, the opposite of grande."},{"p":"How do you say \"grandfather\" in Spanish?","a":"el abuelo","w":["la abuela","el padre","el hijo"],"h":"He is your parent's dad, and the word ends in -o for a man.","e":"\"El abuelo\" means grandfather; the -o ending shows he is male."},{"p":"Lucía has a girl born to the same parents. She is Lucía's ___.","a":"la hermana","w":["el hermano","la madre","la prima"],"h":"A girl in your family who shares your parents uses a word ending in -a.","e":"\"La hermana\" means sister; the -a ending marks a female family member."},{"p":"Which room is \"el baño\"?","a":"the bathroom","w":["the kitchen","the garden","the living room"],"h":"It is the room where you wash your hands and brush your teeth.","e":"\"El baño\" means bathroom, the room for washing up."},{"p":"You look through it to see outside. What is \"la ventana\"?","a":"the window","w":["the door","the wall","the roof"],"h":"Sunlight comes through this glass part of the house.","e":"\"La ventana\" means window, a part of the house you see through."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Nosotros ___ una familia.\" (We are a family.)","a":"somos","w":["soy","es","están"],"h":"The word \"nosotros\" means we, so pick the \"we\" form.","e":"With \"nosotros\" for telling who you are, we use \"somos\" from ser."},{"p":"Read: \"Mi casa es grande. En la sala hay un sofá.\" Where is the sofa?","a":"en la sala","w":["en la cocina","en el baño","en el garaje"],"h":"Look for the room word that comes right before \"un sofá.\"","e":"The passage says the sofa is \"en la sala\" (in the living room)."},{"p":"How do you say \"father\" in Spanish?","a":"el padre","w":["la madre","el abuelo","el tío"],"h":"He is a parent, and the word here is for the dad.","e":"\"El padre\" means father, a family member word."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Estoy ___.\" to say you feel happy.","a":"feliz","w":["triste","cansado","enojado"],"h":"Choose the word that means happy, the opposite of sad.","e":"\"Estoy feliz\" means I am happy; estar is used for feelings, and only feliz means happy."},{"p":"How do you say \"aunt\" in Spanish?","a":"la tía","w":["la prima","la abuela","la sobrina"],"h":"This is the sister of your mom or dad.","e":"La tía means \"aunt\" — it is family vocabulary for your parent's sister."},{"p":"Your uncle's son is your cousin. How do you say \"cousin\" (a boy) in Spanish?","a":"el primo","w":["el sobrino","el nieto","el tío"],"h":"Think of the kid you play with at family parties, not a brother.","e":"El primo means a male \"cousin\" — family vocabulary for your aunt or uncle's son."},{"p":"How do you say \"daughter\" in Spanish?","a":"la hija","w":["la niña","la hermana","la madre"],"h":"This is what parents call their own girl.","e":"La hija means \"daughter\" — family vocabulary for a parent's girl child."},{"p":"The whole family sits at the big table to eat dinner together in this room. Which room is it?","a":"el comedor","w":["la cocina","la sala","el dormitorio"],"h":"You eat here, but it is not where the food is cooked.","e":"El comedor is the \"dining room\" — the room with the table for eating, different from la cocina (kitchen)."},{"p":"You go outside to play near the flowers and green grass. Which part of the house is this?","a":"el jardín","w":["el garaje","el baño","la cocina"],"h":"Plants and flowers grow here.","e":"El jardín means \"garden/yard\" — the outdoor space of the house."},{"p":"You open it to walk into a room. What is \"la puerta\" in English?","a":"door","w":["window","wall","floor"],"h":"It swings open and shut when you enter.","e":"La puerta means \"door\" — a household object you open to go in and out."},{"p":"You put your plate of food on top of it to eat. What is \"la mesa\" in English?","a":"table","w":["chair","bed","lamp"],"h":"You sit at it, but you do not sit ON it.","e":"La mesa means \"table\" — a household object you set your food on."},{"p":"It turns on to give you light so you can read at night. What is \"la lámpara\" in English?","a":"lamp","w":["window","door","clock"],"h":"You switch it on when the room is dark.","e":"La lámpara means \"lamp\" — a household object that gives light."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Mi hermana ___ alta.\" (My sister is tall.)","a":"es","w":["está","soy","están"],"h":"Being tall is how she always is, not just today.","e":"We use ser (es) for permanent traits like height, so \"My sister is tall\" uses es."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Los libros ___ en la mesa.\" (The books are on the table.)","a":"están","w":["son","es","está"],"h":"There is more than one book, and you are telling WHERE they are.","e":"We use estar for location, and \"los libros\" is plural, so it takes están."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Mamá ___ cansada.\" (Mom is tired.)","a":"está","w":["es","son","estás"],"h":"Being tired is a feeling right now, not forever.","e":"We use estar (está) for feelings and conditions like being tired."},{"p":"Your dog is not young anymore; he is old. Which Spanish word means \"old\"?","a":"viejo","w":["nuevo","pequeño","grande"],"h":"It is the opposite of new.","e":"Viejo means \"old\" — a describing word (adjective) that is the opposite of nuevo."},{"p":"Grandma's house looks lovely with flowers everywhere. Which Spanish word means \"pretty\" for \"la casa\"?","a":"bonita","w":["fea","vieja","nueva"],"h":"It is the opposite of ugly.","e":"Bonita means \"pretty\" — it ends in -a to match la casa, which is feminine."},{"p":"How do you say \"grandmother\" in Spanish?","a":"la abuela","w":["la tía","la nieta","la madre"],"h":"This is your mom's or dad's mom.","e":"La abuela means \"grandmother\" — family vocabulary for a parent's mother."},{"p":"The newest and tiniest member of the family just learned to crawl. How do you say \"baby\"?","a":"el bebé","w":["el niño","el primo","el hijo"],"h":"This little one cannot walk or talk yet.","e":"El bebé means \"baby\" — the youngest family member."},{"p":"Read: \"Mi abuelo es viejo. Él está en el jardín.\" Where is the grandfather?","a":"in the garden","w":["in the house","in the garage","in the bathroom"],"h":"Look for the word that names an outdoor place.","e":"The passage says \"está en el jardín,\" and el jardín means \"the garden.\""},{"p":"Your father's brother is your ___. Which Spanish word fits?","a":"tío","w":["primo","abuelo","sobrino"],"h":"He is your dad's brother, not your dad's dad.","e":"Tío means \"uncle\" — family vocabulary for your parent's brother."},{"p":"How do you say \"son\" in Spanish?","a":"el hijo","w":["el padre","el primo","el tío"],"h":"It is the boy child of a mom and dad.","e":"\"El hijo\" means son. It is a family member word."},{"p":"Your sister just had a baby boy. That boy is your ___. Which Spanish word fits?","a":"sobrino","w":["primo","hermano","abuelo"],"h":"He is the child of your brother or sister, not your own child.","e":"\"Sobrino\" means nephew, the son of your sibling."},{"p":"You look into it to see your own face and hair. What is \"el espejo\" in English?","a":"mirror","w":["window","clock","picture"],"h":"You use it to check how you look before school.","e":"\"El espejo\" means mirror, a common household object."},{"p":"This is the part of the house where the family parks the car. Which one is \"el garaje\"?","a":"garage","w":["kitchen","bathroom","garden"],"h":"Cars sleep here, not people.","e":"\"El garaje\" is the garage, where a car is kept."},{"p":"You keep milk, fruit, and cheese cold inside it. What is \"la nevera\" in English?","a":"refrigerator","w":["stove","oven","sink"],"h":"It stays cold inside so food does not spoil.","e":"\"La nevera\" means refrigerator, a kitchen object."},{"p":"After playing in the mud, your shoes are covered in dirt. Which Spanish word means \"dirty\"?","a":"sucio","w":["limpio","nuevo","bonito"],"h":"It is the opposite of clean.","e":"\"Sucio\" means dirty, a describing word (adjective)."},{"p":"You just got shoes that have never been worn before. Which Spanish word means \"new\"?","a":"nuevo","w":["viejo","pequeño","feo"],"h":"It is the opposite of old.","e":"\"Nuevo\" means new, a describing word (adjective)."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Mi hermano ___ enfermo hoy.\" (My brother is sick today.)","a":"está","w":["es","son","estoy"],"h":"Feeling sick is how someone is right now, and it can change.","e":"Use \"estar\" (está) for how someone feels or their health today."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Mis padres ___ altos.\" (My parents are tall.)","a":"son","w":["están","es","somos"],"h":"Being tall is what someone is always like, not just today.","e":"Use \"ser\" (son) for what people are always like, such as tall."},{"p":"It hangs on the wall, has two hands, and tells you the time. What is \"el reloj\" in English?","a":"clock","w":["lamp","mirror","window"],"h":"You check it to know if it is time for recess.","e":"\"El reloj\" means clock, an object that shows the time."},{"p":"You walk up these steps to reach the second floor of the house. What is \"la escalera\"?","a":"stairs","w":["door","window","floor"],"h":"You climb up and down them to change floors.","e":"\"La escalera\" means the stairs (or staircase)."},{"p":"How do you say \"parents\" (mom and dad together) in Spanish?","a":"los padres","w":["los abuelos","los hermanos","los primos"],"h":"It means both grown-ups who take care of you at home.","e":"\"Los padres\" means parents, the mom and dad together."},{"p":"Read: \"Mi tío es alto y mi tía es baja. Ellos están en la sala.\" Who is short?","a":"the aunt","w":["the uncle","the mother","the grandfather"],"h":"Look for the person described with \"baja.\"","e":"\"Baja\" means short, and \"tía\" means aunt, so the aunt is short."},{"p":"You open it and hang your shirts and pants inside it. What is \"el armario\" in English?","a":"closet","w":["bed","table","chair"],"h":"Your clothes live inside it in the bedroom.","e":"\"El armario\" means closet or wardrobe, where clothes are kept."},{"p":"The tiny baby brother is only one month old. Which Spanish word means \"young\"?","a":"joven","w":["viejo","grande","alto"],"h":"It is the opposite of old.","e":"\"Joven\" means young, a describing word (adjective)."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Mis primos ___ en el jardín.\" (My cousins are in the garden.)","a":"están","w":["son","es","está"],"h":"Being in a place is about where they are right now.","e":"Use \"estar\" (están) to tell where people are located."},{"p":"Fill in the blank: \"Tú ___ mi amigo.\" (You are my friend.)","a":"eres","w":["estás","es","soy"],"h":"Being someone's friend is part of who they are.","e":"Use \"ser\" (eres) with \"tú\" to tell who someone is."},{"p":"Read: \"La familia come en el comedor. Después, mamá lava los platos en la cocina.\" Where does mom wash the dishes?","a":"in the kitchen","w":["in the dining room","in the bathroom","in the garden"],"h":"Find the room named right after \"lava los platos.\"","e":"\"La cocina\" means kitchen, where dishes are washed."}],"s.11.physics":[{"p":"A hockey puck slides across frictionless ice at a constant velocity. What is the net force acting on the puck while it slides?","a":"Zero net force, because no unbalanced force is needed to maintain constant velocity","w":["A constant forward force equal in magnitude to the puck's weight","A net force pointing in the direction of motion that keeps it moving","A small net force that gradually decreases as the puck slows"],"h":"Think about what Newton's first law says is required to change an object's state of motion.","e":"Newton's first law (law of inertia): an object moves at constant velocity when the net force on it is zero; motion does not require a sustaining force."},{"p":"A net force is applied to a 5 kg object, giving it an acceleration of 3 m/s². What is the magnitude of the net force?","a":"15 N","w":["1.67 N","8 N","45 N"],"h":"Relate force, mass, and acceleration using Newton's second law.","e":"Newton's second law: F = ma = (5 kg)(3 m/s²) = 15 N."},{"p":"A swimmer pushes backward on the water with a force of 200 N. According to Newton's third law, what force does the water exert on the swimmer?","a":"200 N directed forward on the swimmer","w":["Less than 200 N forward, because the water moves and yields","More than 200 N forward, which is what propels the swimmer","200 N directed backward on the swimmer"],"h":"Consider the direction and magnitude of the reaction force in an action–reaction pair.","e":"Newton's third law: forces come in equal-magnitude, opposite-direction pairs acting on different objects, so the water pushes the swimmer forward with 200 N."},{"p":"A car starts from rest and accelerates uniformly at 4 m/s² for 6 s. What is its final velocity?","a":"24 m/s","w":["0.67 m/s","10 m/s","48 m/s"],"h":"Use the kinematics equation relating final velocity, initial velocity, acceleration, and time.","e":"Using v = u + at with u = 0: v = 0 + (4 m/s²)(6 s) = 24 m/s."},{"p":"An object is dropped from rest and falls freely for 3.0 s. Using g = 9.8 m/s², how far does it fall (neglecting air resistance)?","a":"44.1 m","w":["29.4 m","14.7 m","88.2 m"],"h":"Displacement during free fall depends on the square of the time.","e":"Using d = ½gt² = ½(9.8 m/s²)(3.0 s)² = 44.1 m for an object released from rest."},{"p":"A 2.0 kg ball moves with a speed of 10 m/s. What is its kinetic energy?","a":"100 J","w":["20 J","200 J","10 J"],"h":"Kinetic energy depends on the square of the speed and on one-half the mass.","e":"Kinetic energy KE = ½mv² = ½(2.0 kg)(10 m/s)² = 100 J."},{"p":"A 4.0 kg box is lifted to a shelf 5.0 m above the floor. Using g = 9.8 m/s², what is its gravitational potential energy relative to the floor?","a":"196 J","w":["20 J","39.2 J","98 J"],"h":"Gravitational potential energy depends on mass, the gravitational field strength, and height.","e":"Gravitational potential energy PE = mgh = (4.0 kg)(9.8 m/s²)(5.0 m) = 196 J."},{"p":"A constant 50 N force pushes a crate 4.0 m across a floor in the same direction as the force. How much work does the force do on the crate?","a":"200 J","w":["12.5 J","54 J","100 J"],"h":"Work done by a constant force in the direction of motion is force times displacement.","e":"Work W = Fd = (50 N)(4.0 m) = 200 J, since the force is parallel to the displacement."},{"p":"A machine does 600 J of work in 30 s. What is its average power output?","a":"20 W","w":["18,000 W","0.05 W","630 W"],"h":"Power measures how quickly work is done over time.","e":"Power P = W/t = (600 J)/(30 s) = 20 W."},{"p":"A 1200 kg car travels at 15 m/s. What is the magnitude of its momentum?","a":"18,000 kg·m/s","w":["80 kg·m/s","1215 kg·m/s","9000 kg·m/s"],"h":"Linear momentum is the product of mass and velocity.","e":"Momentum p = mv = (1200 kg)(15 m/s) = 18,000 kg·m/s."},{"p":"A 2.0 kg cart moving at 3.0 m/s collides with and sticks to a stationary 1.0 kg cart on a frictionless track. What is their common velocity after the collision?","a":"2.0 m/s","w":["3.0 m/s","1.5 m/s","6.0 m/s"],"h":"Total momentum before equals total momentum after in an isolated collision.","e":"Conservation of momentum: (2.0)(3.0) = (2.0+1.0)v, so v = 6.0/3.0 = 2.0 m/s (perfectly inelastic collision)."},{"p":"According to the work–energy theorem, the net work done on an object is equal to its change in which quantity?","a":"Kinetic energy","w":["Total mechanical energy","Gravitational potential energy","Linear momentum"],"h":"The theorem links net work to a change in a form of energy associated with motion.","e":"The work–energy theorem states W_net = ΔKE: the net work done on an object equals its change in kinetic energy."},{"p":"Starting from rest, a runner accelerates uniformly to 20 m/s over a time of 10 s. What distance does the runner cover during this interval?","a":"100 m","w":["200 m","50 m","2 m"],"h":"For uniform acceleration, distance equals average velocity multiplied by time.","e":"With uniform acceleration from rest, average velocity = (0 + 20)/2 = 10 m/s, so d = (10 m/s)(10 s) = 100 m."},{"p":"A 2.0 kg block is pushed with a 10 N horizontal force while a 4.0 N friction force opposes its motion. What is the block's acceleration?","a":"3.0 m/s²","w":["5.0 m/s²","7.0 m/s²","2.0 m/s²"],"h":"First find the net force by combining the applied force and friction, then apply Newton's second law.","e":"Net force = 10 N − 4.0 N = 6.0 N, so a = F_net/m = 6.0 N / 2.0 kg = 3.0 m/s²."},{"p":"A constant force of 20 N acts on an object for 5.0 s. What is the magnitude of the impulse delivered, which equals the object's change in momentum?","a":"100 kg·m/s","w":["4.0 kg·m/s","25 kg·m/s","15 kg·m/s"],"h":"Impulse is the product of force and the time over which it acts.","e":"Impulse–momentum theorem: J = FΔt = (20 N)(5.0 s) = 100 N·s = 100 kg·m/s."},{"p":"A ball is dropped from rest at a height of 20 m. Using g = 9.8 m/s² and neglecting air resistance, what is its speed just before it hits the ground?","a":"19.8 m/s","w":["196 m/s","14 m/s","39.6 m/s"],"h":"Set the potential energy at the top equal to the kinetic energy at the bottom.","e":"Conservation of mechanical energy: mgh = ½mv², so v = √(2gh) = √(2·9.8·20) ≈ 19.8 m/s."},{"p":"A motor exerts a constant 100 N force on a load that moves at a steady 5.0 m/s in the direction of the force. What is the power delivered?","a":"500 W","w":["20 W","105 W","250 W"],"h":"When force and velocity are in the same direction, power can be found directly from them.","e":"Power P = Fv = (100 N)(5.0 m/s) = 500 W."},{"p":"An astronaut has a mass of 60 kg. Using g = 9.8 m/s², what is the astronaut's weight on Earth?","a":"588 N","w":["60 N","6.1 N","9.8 N"],"h":"Weight is the gravitational force on a mass, distinct from the mass itself.","e":"Weight W = mg = (60 kg)(9.8 m/s²) = 588 N; mass (60 kg) is a measure of inertia, not force."},{"p":"A 0.50 kg ball moving at 4.0 m/s strikes a wall head-on and rebounds straight back at 4.0 m/s. What is the magnitude of the ball's change in momentum?","a":"4.0 kg·m/s","w":["0 kg·m/s","2.0 kg·m/s","8.0 kg·m/s"],"h":"Momentum is a vector; assign opposite signs to the two directions before subtracting.","e":"Change in momentum Δp = m(v_f − v_i) = 0.50 × (−4.0 − 4.0) = −4.0 kg·m/s, so the magnitude is 4.0 kg·m/s. A reversal doubles the momentum change rather than leaving it unchanged."},{"p":"A car's speed increases from 10 m/s to 20 m/s. By what factor does its kinetic energy increase?","a":"4","w":["2","8","1.4"],"h":"Kinetic energy depends on the square of the speed, not the speed itself.","e":"Since KE = ½mv², doubling the speed multiplies KE by 2² = 4. Kinetic energy scales with the square of speed."},{"p":"A ball is thrown horizontally at 15 m/s from the top of a 20 m cliff. Using g = 9.8 m/s² and neglecting air resistance, how long is the ball in the air?","a":"2.0 s","w":["1.3 s","2.9 s","4.0 s"],"h":"Vertical and horizontal motions are independent; the horizontal speed does not affect fall time.","e":"Time aloft depends only on the vertical drop: t = √(2h/g) = √(2×20/9.8) ≈ 2.0 s. Horizontal velocity is irrelevant to how long it falls."},{"p":"A 10 kg block rests on a frictionless ramp inclined at 30° to the horizontal. Using g = 9.8 m/s², what is the component of the block's weight directed along the ramp's surface?","a":"49 N","w":["98 N","85 N","20 N"],"h":"Resolve the weight into components parallel and perpendicular to the incline using the incline angle.","e":"The component of weight along the incline is mg sin θ = 10×9.8×sin30° = 49 N. This parallel component is what accelerates the block down the ramp."},{"p":"A spring with force constant 200 N/m is compressed by 0.10 m from its natural length. How much elastic potential energy is stored in the spring?","a":"1.0 J","w":["2.0 J","10 J","0.50 J"],"h":"Elastic potential energy depends on the square of the compression distance.","e":"Elastic PE = ½kx² = ½×200×(0.10)² = 1.0 J. Omitting the factor of ½ is a common error that doubles the answer."},{"p":"A pendulum bob is released from rest at a height of 0.80 m above its lowest point. Using g = 9.8 m/s² and ignoring friction, what is its speed at the lowest point?","a":"4.0 m/s","w":["2.8 m/s","8.0 m/s","16 m/s"],"h":"Set the gravitational potential energy lost equal to the kinetic energy gained.","e":"By conservation of energy, mgh = ½mv², so v = √(2gh) = √(2×9.8×0.80) ≈ 4.0 m/s. The bob's mass cancels out."},{"p":"A 4.0 kg rifle fires a 0.020 kg bullet at 300 m/s. Assuming the rifle was initially at rest, what is the magnitude of the rifle's recoil velocity?","a":"1.5 m/s","w":["6.0 m/s","0.50 m/s","300 m/s"],"h":"Total momentum is conserved and starts at zero, so the two momenta must be equal and opposite.","e":"Conservation of momentum gives m_b v_b = m_r v_r, so v_r = (0.020×300)/4.0 = 1.5 m/s. The system's total momentum remains zero."},{"p":"A 1000 kg car traveling at 20 m/s brakes to a stop under a constant 5000 N friction force. Using the work–energy theorem, what distance does it travel while stopping?","a":"40 m","w":["80 m","20 m","4.0 m"],"h":"The braking force does negative work equal in magnitude to the car's initial kinetic energy.","e":"By the work–energy theorem, F·d = ½mv², so d = (½×1000×20²)/5000 = 40 m. All the kinetic energy is removed by friction work."},{"p":"A 60 kg person climbs a staircase, rising 3.0 m in vertical height in 4.0 s. Using g = 9.8 m/s², what is the person's average power output against gravity?","a":"441 W","w":["180 W","1764 W","45 W"],"h":"Power is the rate of doing work; first find the work done against gravity.","e":"Power = work/time = mgh/t = (60×9.8×3.0)/4.0 = 441 W. Power is the rate at which gravitational potential energy is gained."},{"p":"A ball is thrown straight up with an initial speed of 20 m/s. Using g = 9.8 m/s² and neglecting air resistance, how long does it take to reach its highest point?","a":"2.0 s","w":["4.1 s","1.0 s","10 s"],"h":"At the highest point the ball's vertical velocity is momentarily zero.","e":"Using v = v₀ − gt with v = 0, t = v₀/g = 20/9.8 ≈ 2.0 s. The 4.1 s value is the full up-and-down flight time."},{"p":"A ball is launched straight upward with a speed of 14 m/s. Using g = 9.8 m/s² and ignoring air resistance, what maximum height does it reach?","a":"10 m","w":["20 m","14 m","5.0 m"],"h":"Use a kinematics relation linking speed, acceleration, and displacement without time.","e":"From v² = v₀² − 2gh with v = 0, h = v₀²/(2g) = 14²/(2×9.8) = 10 m. The kinetic energy fully converts to potential energy at the top."},{"p":"A 5.0 kg block slides across level ground where a 20 N kinetic friction force opposes its motion. Using g = 9.8 m/s², what is the coefficient of kinetic friction?","a":"0.41","w":["0.20","4.0","2.5"],"h":"The coefficient of friction relates the friction force to the normal force.","e":"μ = f/N = f/(mg) = 20/(5.0×9.8) ≈ 0.41. On level ground the normal force equals the block's weight."},{"p":"A 0.15 kg baseball moving at 40 m/s is caught and brought to rest in 0.010 s. What is the magnitude of the average force the glove exerts on the ball?","a":"600 N","w":["6.0 N","60 N","4000 N"],"h":"Average force equals the change in momentum divided by the contact time.","e":"By the impulse–momentum theorem, F = Δp/Δt = (0.15×40)/0.010 = 600 N. Very short contact times produce large forces."},{"p":"On a straight track, a 3.0 kg cart moves right at 2.0 m/s while a 2.0 kg cart moves left at 1.0 m/s. What is the magnitude of the system's total momentum?","a":"4.0 kg·m/s","w":["8.0 kg·m/s","2.0 kg·m/s","0 kg·m/s"],"h":"Momentum is a vector; choose a positive direction and give oppositely moving objects opposite signs.","e":"Total momentum = (3.0×2.0) − (2.0×1.0) = 4.0 kg·m/s to the right. Momenta in opposite directions partly cancel rather than add."},{"p":"A 60 kg astronaut stands on the Moon, where the gravitational field strength is g = 1.6 m/s². What is the astronaut's weight there?","a":"96 N","w":["60 N","588 N","38 N"],"h":"Weight is the gravitational force, which depends on the local gravitational field strength.","e":"Weight W = mg = 60×1.6 = 96 N. The astronaut's mass is unchanged, but weight scales with the local value of g."},{"p":"A worker pushes a 50 kg crate at constant velocity across a level floor, applying a 100 N force over a distance of 5.0 m. What is the net work done on the crate?","a":"0 J","w":["500 J","2500 J","250 J"],"h":"Relate the net work to the change in the crate's kinetic energy.","e":"By the work–energy theorem, net work equals the change in kinetic energy, which is zero at constant velocity because friction work cancels the applied work."},{"p":"A 70 kg skydiver descends at a constant (terminal) velocity. Using g = 9.8 m/s², what is the magnitude of the air-resistance force acting on the skydiver?","a":"686 N","w":["0 N","70 N","343 N"],"h":"At constant velocity the acceleration is zero, so the forces on the skydiver must balance.","e":"At terminal velocity the net force is zero, so air resistance equals the weight: mg = 70×9.8 = 686 N. Balanced forces produce constant velocity, not zero force."},{"p":"A car travels 100 m in 4.0 s, then travels another 100 m in 6.0 s. What is the car's average speed for the entire 200 m trip?","a":"20 m/s","w":["20.8 m/s","25 m/s","16.7 m/s"],"h":"Average speed is total distance divided by total elapsed time, not the average of the two leg speeds.","e":"Average speed = total distance/total time = 200/10 = 20 m/s. Averaging the two individual speeds (25 and 16.7 m/s) is a common mistake."},{"p":"A 1000 kg car drives up a slope at a steady 20 m/s. The slope rises 1.0 m in vertical height for every 20 m measured along the road, so sinθ = 0.050. Using g = 9.8 m/s² and ignoring friction and air resistance, what power must the engine supply to overcome gravity?","a":"9800 W","w":["196000 W","490 W","4900 W"],"h":"The resisting force is the component of the car's weight directed along the road, and power equals that force times the car's speed.","e":"Using P = Fv with the gravity component F = mg sinθ = 1000·9.8·0.050 = 490 N gives P = 490·20 = 9800 W."},{"p":"A box rests on a ramp whose angle is slowly increased. The box just begins to slide when the ramp angle reaches 30°. What is the coefficient of static friction between the box and the ramp?","a":"0.58","w":["0.50","0.87","1.7"],"h":"At the slipping angle the maximum static friction exactly balances the weight component along the incline; set those two expressions equal and solve for μ.","e":"At the critical angle μs = tanθ, so μs = tan30° = 0.58."},{"p":"On a frictionless track, a 0.50 kg glider moving at 6.0 m/s makes a head-on elastic collision with an identical 0.50 kg glider that is at rest. What is the velocity of the initially moving glider just after the collision?","a":"0 m/s","w":["3.0 m/s","6.0 m/s","-6.0 m/s"],"h":"For a one-dimensional elastic collision between equal masses, consider what happens to each object's velocity when both momentum and kinetic energy are conserved.","e":"In a 1-D elastic collision between equal masses the two objects exchange velocities, so the incoming glider stops (0 m/s) and the target moves off at 6.0 m/s."},{"p":"A 2.0 kg object and an 8.0 kg object are found to have equal magnitudes of momentum. What is the ratio of the kinetic energy of the lighter object to that of the heavier object?","a":"4:1","w":["1:4","1:1","2:1"],"h":"Rewrite kinetic energy in terms of momentum and mass rather than speed, then compare the two objects at equal momentum.","e":"Since KE = p²/(2m), at equal p the kinetic energy is inversely proportional to mass, so the ratio is m_heavy : m_light = 8 : 2 = 4 : 1."},{"p":"A 70 kg person stands on a bathroom scale inside an elevator that is accelerating upward at 2.0 m/s². Using g = 9.8 m/s², what force does the scale read (the normal force on the person)?","a":"826 N","w":["686 N","546 N","140 N"],"h":"Apply Newton's second law to the person; the scale reads the normal force, which must both support the weight and produce the upward acceleration.","e":"By Newton's second law N − mg = ma, so N = m(g + a) = 70·(9.8 + 2.0) = 826 N."},{"p":"A projectile is launched from the ground at 20 m/s directed 30° above the horizontal. Using g = 9.8 m/s² and neglecting air resistance, what is the maximum height it reaches?","a":"5.1 m","w":["20 m","10 m","2.6 m"],"h":"Only the vertical component of the launch velocity determines the peak height; at the top that vertical component is momentarily zero.","e":"With v_y = 20 sin30° = 10 m/s, the peak height is h = v_y²/(2g) = 100/19.6 ≈ 5.1 m."},{"p":"A 2.0 kg block slides 4.0 m down the surface of a 30° incline. The coefficient of kinetic friction between the block and the incline is 0.25. Using g = 9.8 m/s², how much mechanical energy is dissipated by friction over this distance?","a":"17 J","w":["20 J","9.8 J","39 J"],"h":"Friction acts along the surface with magnitude μ times the normal force, and on an incline the normal force is only the perpendicular component of the weight.","e":"The friction force is f = μmg cosθ = 0.25·2.0·9.8·cos30° ≈ 4.24 N, so the energy dissipated is f·d = 4.24·4.0 ≈ 17 J."},{"p":"A cart starts from rest at the top of a frictionless track 25 m above the ground and rolls to a point that is 10 m above the ground. Using g = 9.8 m/s², what is the cart's speed at that lower point?","a":"17 m/s","w":["22 m/s","14 m/s","24 m/s"],"h":"Conservation of mechanical energy converts the drop in height into speed; use only the vertical height the cart has actually descended.","e":"By energy conservation v = √(2gΔh) with Δh = 25 − 10 = 15 m, giving v = √(2·9.8·15) ≈ 17 m/s."},{"p":"On a frictionless horizontal surface, a 0.20 kg puck moving east at 3.0 m/s collides with and sticks to a 0.20 kg puck moving north at 4.0 m/s. What is the speed of the combined pucks just after the collision?","a":"2.5 m/s","w":["3.5 m/s","1.25 m/s","5.0 m/s"],"h":"Momentum is a vector, so conserve the east and north components separately, then combine the total momentum before dividing by the total mass.","e":"Conserving momentum by component gives p = √((0.20·3.0)² + (0.20·4.0)²) = 1.0 kg·m/s, so v = 1.0/0.40 = 2.5 m/s."},{"p":"An electric hoist consumes 500 J of electrical energy to lift a 5.0 kg mass a vertical height of 6.0 m at constant speed. Using g = 9.8 m/s², what is the efficiency of the hoist?","a":"59%","w":["85%","41%","100%"],"h":"Efficiency compares the useful output energy (the gain in gravitational potential energy) with the total energy supplied.","e":"Useful output is mgh = 5.0·9.8·6.0 = 294 J, so efficiency = 294/500 ≈ 59%."},{"p":"A 1200 kg car accelerates uniformly from rest to 25 m/s in 8.0 s on a level road. Ignoring friction and air resistance, what is the average power output of the engine during this interval?","a":"47 kW","w":["94 kW","23 kW","375 kW"],"h":"Average power is the total work done divided by the time; use the work–energy theorem to find the work from the change in kinetic energy.","e":"By the work–energy theorem W = ½mv² = ½·1200·25² = 375000 J, so average power = 375000/8.0 ≈ 4.7×10⁴ W (47 kW)."},{"p":"A spring obeys Hooke's law and requires a steady 12 N force to hold it stretched 0.030 m beyond its natural length. How much work must be done to stretch the spring that far starting from its natural length?","a":"0.18 J","w":["0.36 J","0.060 J","12 J"],"h":"Because the force grows from zero as the spring stretches, use the average force over the stretch (or the elastic potential energy formula), not the final force alone.","e":"The elastic potential energy stored is W = ½Fx = ½·12·0.030 = 0.18 J (equivalently ½kx² with k = 400 N/m)."},{"p":"A stone is thrown straight down from a bridge with an initial speed of 5.0 m/s and strikes the water 2.0 s later. Using g = 9.8 m/s² and neglecting air resistance, what is the stone's speed just before it hits the water?","a":"25 m/s","w":["20 m/s","15 m/s","30 m/s"],"h":"The stone already has a downward speed at release, and gravity adds to that speed each second; combine both contributions.","e":"Using v = v₀ + gt = 5.0 + 9.8·2.0 = 24.6 ≈ 25 m/s (kinematics for constant acceleration)."},{"p":"Two blocks, 3.0 kg and 2.0 kg, sit on a frictionless table connected by a light string. A horizontal 10 N force pulls the 3.0 kg block, dragging the 2.0 kg block behind it. What is the tension in the connecting string?","a":"4.0 N","w":["10 N","6.0 N","5.0 N"],"h":"First find the shared acceleration of the whole system, then apply Newton's second law to only the block that the string must accelerate.","e":"The system accelerates at a = 10/(3.0+2.0) = 2.0 m/s², and the string alone accelerates the 2.0 kg block, so T = 2.0·2.0 = 4.0 N."},{"p":"A ball is dropped from a height of 2.0 m and rebounds to a height of 1.5 m. What fraction of its mechanical energy is lost during the bounce?","a":"25%","w":["75%","33%","50%"],"h":"At the top of each rise all the ball's energy is gravitational potential energy, which is proportional to the rebound height.","e":"Since gravitational PE is proportional to height, the fraction lost is (2.0 − 1.5)/2.0 = 0.25, or 25%."},{"p":"A stationary 3.0 kg object explodes into two pieces. A 1.0 kg piece flies off at 6.0 m/s in one direction. What is the speed of the remaining 2.0 kg piece?","a":"3.0 m/s","w":["6.0 m/s","1.5 m/s","12 m/s"],"h":"Total momentum is conserved and starts at zero, so the momenta of the two pieces must be equal in magnitude and opposite in direction.","e":"By conservation of momentum m₁v₁ = m₂v₂, so v₂ = (1.0·6.0)/2.0 = 3.0 m/s in the opposite direction."},{"p":"A person pulls a sled across level snow using a rope held at 37° above the horizontal, applying a 50 N force along the rope while the sled moves 10 m horizontally. Using cos37° = 0.80, how much work does the rope do on the sled?","a":"400 J","w":["500 J","300 J","250 J"],"h":"Only the component of the force in the direction of motion does work; the rope points partly upward, so account for the angle.","e":"Work is W = Fd cosθ = 50·10·cos37° = 50·10·0.80 = 400 J."}],"sp.6.routine":[{"p":"Marta escribe sobre su mañana. Read: \"Yo ___ a las seis y media todos los días para entrenar fútbol.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo levantarse completa la oración?","a":"me levanto","w":["levanto","me levanta","te levantas"],"h":"El sujeto es \"yo\", así que el pronombre reflexivo debe coincidir con esa persona.","e":"En los verbos reflexivos, \"yo\" usa el pronombre \"me\" con el verbo conjugado: me levanto."},{"p":"Tu amigo te pregunta por tu rutina antes del partido: \"¿A qué hora ___ tú por la mañana?\" ¿Qué forma de ducharse completa la pregunta?","a":"te duchas","w":["me ducho","se ducha","duchas"],"h":"Fíjate en el sujeto \"tú\" y busca el pronombre reflexivo que le corresponde.","e":"Para \"tú\", el reflexivo usa \"te\" más el verbo en segunda persona: te duchas."},{"p":"Read: \"___ me lavo los dientes y después desayuno.\" ¿Qué palabra de secuencia va bien al inicio para indicar la PRIMERA acción?","a":"Primero","w":["Después","Luego","Finalmente"],"h":"Piensa en la palabra que marca el comienzo de una serie de pasos.","e":"\"Primero\" es una palabra de secuencia que señala la acción inicial de una rutina."},{"p":"Read: \"Nosotros ___ temprano porque el juego empieza al amanecer.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo despertarse completa la oración para \"nosotros\"?","a":"nos despertamos","w":["me despierto","se despiertan","despertamos"],"h":"El pronombre reflexivo cambia según quién hace la acción; aquí somos varios.","e":"Para \"nosotros\" el reflexivo es \"nos\": nos despertamos."},{"p":"En español, la frase \"de la mañana\" se usa para aclarar la parte del día de una hora. ¿Cuál oración la usa correctamente?","a":"Corro a las siete de la mañana.","w":["Corro a las siete en la mañana temprano.","Corro las siete de la mañana.","Corro a siete de la mañana."],"h":"Recuerda que necesitas la preposición de hora y el artículo antes del número.","e":"La estructura correcta es \"a las + hora + de la mañana\" para dar la hora del día."},{"p":"Read: \"Ella ___ el pelo antes de ir al concierto.\" ¿Qué forma de peinarse completa la oración para \"ella\"?","a":"se peina","w":["me peino","te peinas","peina"],"h":"Busca el pronombre reflexivo de tercera persona singular.","e":"Para \"él/ella\" el reflexivo es \"se\": ella se peina."},{"p":"Read: \"Los jugadores ___ las manos antes de comer.\" ¿Qué forma de lavarse completa la oración para \"ellos\"?","a":"se lavan","w":["nos lavamos","se lava","lavan"],"h":"El sujeto es plural en tercera persona; ajusta el pronombre y el verbo.","e":"Para \"ellos/ellas\" el reflexivo es \"se\" con el verbo en plural: se lavan."},{"p":"¿Cómo se dice la hora \"1:00\" correctamente en español?","a":"Es la una.","w":["Son la una.","Es las una.","Son las una."],"h":"La una es singular, así que el verbo y el artículo también deben ir en singular.","e":"Solo con la una se usa el singular \"Es la una\"; las demás horas usan \"Son las\"."},{"p":"Read: \"Yo ___ la cara con agua fría para despertarme.\" ¿Qué forma de lavarse completa la oración para \"yo\"?","a":"me lavo","w":["se lava","te lavas","lavo"],"h":"El pronombre reflexivo debe coincidir con el sujeto \"yo\".","e":"Para \"yo\" el reflexivo es \"me\": me lavo la cara."},{"p":"En una rutina, ¿qué palabra usarías para decir que una acción ocurre INMEDIATAMENTE DESPUÉS de otra?","a":"luego","w":["primero","siempre","nunca"],"h":"Buscas una palabra de secuencia, no de frecuencia.","e":"\"Luego\" (o \"después\") indica que una acción sigue a otra en el tiempo."},{"p":"Read: \"¿A qué hora ___ ustedes para el entrenamiento?\" ¿Qué forma de vestirse completa la pregunta para \"ustedes\"?","a":"se visten","w":["nos vestimos","se viste","visten"],"h":"\"Ustedes\" usa la misma persona gramatical que \"ellos\".","e":"Para \"ustedes/ellos\" el reflexivo es \"se\" con el verbo en plural: se visten."},{"p":"Read: \"Son las tres ___ la tarde cuando termina el partido.\" ¿Qué palabras completan la expresión de tiempo?","a":"de","w":["en","por","a"],"h":"Es la misma preposición que usas en \"de la mañana\".","e":"Para indicar la parte del día con una hora exacta se usa \"de la tarde\"."},{"p":"El verbo \"acostarse\" es reflexivo. ¿Cuál oración lo usa correctamente para \"tú\"?","a":"Tú te acuestas tarde los fines de semana.","w":["Tú acuestas tarde los fines de semana.","Tú se acuesta tarde los fines de semana.","Tú me acuesto tarde los fines de semana."],"h":"El pronombre reflexivo debe coincidir con el sujeto \"tú\".","e":"Para \"tú\" el reflexivo es \"te\": tú te acuestas."},{"p":"Read: \"Después de correr, yo ___ la ropa deportiva y me pongo el uniforme.\" ¿Qué forma de quitarse completa la oración para \"yo\"?","a":"me quito","w":["se quita","te quitas","quito"],"h":"Elige el pronombre reflexivo que corresponde a \"yo\".","e":"Para \"yo\" el reflexivo es \"me\": me quito la ropa."},{"p":"¿Cuál de estas oraciones ordena una rutina con palabras de secuencia de forma lógica?","a":"Primero me levanto, luego me ducho y finalmente desayuno.","w":["Finalmente me levanto, primero me ducho y luego desayuno.","Luego me levanto, finalmente me ducho y primero desayuno.","Después me levanto, primero me ducho y luego desayuno."],"h":"Piensa en el orden real: comienzo, en medio y final.","e":"Las palabras de secuencia primero, luego y finalmente deben seguir el orden inicio-medio-final."},{"p":"Read: \"Mi hermana y yo ___ temprano los sábados para ir al mercado.\" ¿Qué forma de levantarse completa la oración?","a":"nos levantamos","w":["se levantan","me levanto","levantamos"],"h":"\"Mi hermana y yo\" equivale al sujeto \"nosotros\".","e":"Para \"nosotros\" el reflexivo es \"nos\" con el verbo en plural: nos levantamos."},{"p":"Read: \"Mis compañeros de equipo ___ el uniforme en el vestuario antes del partido.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo reflexivo ponerse completa la oración para 'ellos'?","a":"se ponen","w":["se pone","nos ponemos","me pongo"],"h":"Fíjate en quién hace la acción: 'mis compañeros' son varias personas (ellos).","e":"En los verbos reflexivos el pronombre concuerda con el sujeto: para 'ellos' se usa 'se' + la forma 'ponen'."},{"p":"Un estudiante dice: \"Yo me cepillo los dientes.\" ¿Por qué el verbo lleva el pronombre 'me'?","a":"Porque es un verbo reflexivo: la acción recae sobre la misma persona que la hace","w":["Porque 'me' significa 'mi' y muestra posesión de los dientes","Porque todos los verbos en español necesitan un pronombre antes","Porque el verbo está en tiempo pasado y 'me' marca el pasado"],"h":"Pregúntate quién recibe la acción de cepillar en la oración.","e":"Los verbos reflexivos usan pronombres como 'me', 'te', 'se' porque el sujeto realiza y recibe la acción sobre sí mismo."},{"p":"¿Cómo se dice la hora \"2:30\" correctamente en español?","a":"Son las dos y media","w":["Es la dos y media","Son las dos y medio","Son las dos con treinta"],"h":"Recuerda que 'media' concuerda con 'la hora' y que para horas después de la una se usa 'son'.","e":"Para las horas plurales se usa 'son las'; los treinta minutos se expresan con 'y media', que es femenino como 'la hora'."},{"p":"Read: \"Nosotros ___ la cara y las manos antes de entrar a la piscina.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo lavarse completa la oración para 'nosotros'?","a":"nos lavamos","w":["se lavan","nos lavan","me lavo"],"h":"El sujeto 'nosotros' necesita su propio pronombre reflexivo y su propia terminación verbal.","e":"Para 'nosotros', el reflexivo es 'nos' y el verbo termina en '-amos': 'nos lavamos'."},{"p":"Read: \"Yo llego a casa, ceno y, ___, me acuesto a dormir.\" ¿Qué palabra de secuencia indica MEJOR la última acción del día?","a":"finalmente","w":["primero","luego","mientras"],"h":"Busca la palabra que señala el cierre o el final de una serie de acciones.","e":"'Finalmente' (o 'por último') marca la acción que cierra una secuencia; 'primero' y 'luego' señalan acciones anteriores."},{"p":"¿Cuál oración usa correctamente 'de la noche' para aclarar la parte del día?","a":"Me acuesto a las diez de la noche","w":["Me acuesto a las diez en la noche","Me acuesto a las diez por la noche exacta","Me acuesto a las diez de noche"],"h":"La fórmula fija junta una hora concreta con 'de la' más la parte del día.","e":"Cuando se menciona una hora exacta, se usa 'de la mañana/tarde/noche'; 'por la noche' se usa sin hora específica."},{"p":"Read: \"¿A qué hora ___ tu hermano para ir a la escuela?\" ¿Qué forma del verbo despertarse completa la pregunta para 'él'?","a":"se despierta","w":["te despiertas","se despiertan","me despierto"],"h":"El sujeto es una sola persona distinta de ti: 'tu hermano' (él).","e":"Para 'él' el reflexivo es 'se' y el verbo cambia la raíz e→ie: 'se despierta'."},{"p":"Un amigo escribe: \"Primero desayuno, después me levanto y luego me despierto.\" ¿Por qué esta secuencia NO tiene sentido lógico?","a":"Porque despertarse debe ir antes de levantarse, y ambas antes de desayunar","w":["Porque usa demasiadas palabras de secuencia en una oración","Porque 'después' y 'luego' no pueden ir en la misma oración","Porque los verbos reflexivos no pueden empezar una rutina"],"h":"Piensa en el orden real: ¿qué haces primero al abrir los ojos por la mañana?","e":"Las palabras de secuencia deben reflejar el orden real de los hechos: despertarse, luego levantarse y después desayunar."},{"p":"Read: \"Tú ___ temprano los días de partido, pero yo me levanto tarde.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo levantarse completa la oración para 'tú'?","a":"te levantas","w":["se levanta","me levanto","nos levantamos"],"h":"Compara con la segunda parte: 'yo me levanto'; ahora necesitas la forma para 'tú'.","e":"Para 'tú' el pronombre reflexivo es 'te' y el verbo termina en '-as': 'te levantas'."},{"p":"En español, ¿cómo se expresa que faltan quince minutos para las cuatro, es decir la hora \"3:45\"?","a":"Son las cuatro menos cuarto","w":["Son las tres menos cuarto","Son las cuatro y cuarto","Son las tres cuarenta y cinco menos"],"h":"Cuando pasan de la media, muchas veces se nombra la hora siguiente y se resta con 'menos'.","e":"Para minutos después de la media se usa la hora siguiente con 'menos': las 3:45 son 'las cuatro menos cuarto'."},{"p":"Read: \"Antes de dormir, ella ___ el maquillaje y se pone la pijama.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo quitarse completa la oración para 'ella'?","a":"se quita","w":["me quito","se quitan","te quitas"],"h":"El sujeto es una sola persona: 'ella'.","e":"Para 'ella' el reflexivo es 'se' y el verbo termina en '-a': 'se quita'."},{"p":"¿Cuál oración usa correctamente la preposición para decir a qué hora empieza una acción?","a":"El entrenamiento empieza a las siete","w":["El entrenamiento empieza en las siete","El entrenamiento empieza de las siete","El entrenamiento empieza son las siete"],"h":"Para señalar el momento exacto en que ocurre algo, se usa una preposición corta antes de 'las'.","e":"Se usa 'a' + 'la(s)' para indicar la hora en que ocurre una acción: 'a las siete'."},{"p":"Read: \"Yo ___ el pelo con una toalla después de ducharme.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo secarse completa la oración para 'yo'?","a":"me seco","w":["me seca","te secas","se seca"],"h":"El pronombre y la terminación deben concordar con 'yo'.","e":"Para 'yo' el reflexivo es 'me' y el verbo termina en '-o': 'me seco'."},{"p":"Un estudiante dice \"Son la una y cuarto\" y su maestra lo corrige. ¿Cuál es la forma correcta?","a":"Es la una y cuarto","w":["Son las una y cuarto","Es las una y cuarto","Son la una y cuarta"],"h":"La una es la única hora que usa el verbo en singular.","e":"Con la una se usa 'es la' (singular); las demás horas usan 'son las'."},{"p":"Read: \"Los sábados nosotros ___ tarde porque no hay entrenamiento.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo acostarse completa la oración para 'nosotros'?","a":"nos acostamos","w":["se acuestan","nos acostan","me acuesto"],"h":"Para 'nosotros' la raíz del verbo NO cambia (no diptonga) y el pronombre es 'nos'.","e":"Para 'nosotros' se usa 'nos' y la forma regular 'acostamos'; la raíz o→ue solo cambia en otras personas, no en nosotros."},{"p":"Read: \"Me levanto, ___ me visto y salgo corriendo al autobús.\" ¿Qué expresión de tiempo muestra que estas acciones pasan una tras otra muy rápido?","a":"en seguida","w":["hace mucho","de vez en cuando","todos los años"],"h":"Busca la frase que indica que algo pasa inmediatamente después, casi sin pausa.","e":"'En seguida' (o 'luego') indica que una acción ocurre inmediatamente después de otra en una secuencia rápida."},{"p":"Read: \"Yo me levanto ___ las seis, pero mi hermana se levanta ___ las siete y media.\" ¿Qué preposición se repite para indicar la hora exacta de cada acción?","a":"a","w":["de","en","por"],"h":"Es la misma palabra corta que usas siempre para decir a qué hora sucede algo.","e":"La preposición 'a' señala la hora exacta en que ocurre una acción: 'a las seis', 'a las siete y media'."},{"p":"Read: \"Después del partido, nosotros vamos a ___ en los vestuarios.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo ducharse es correcta con el infinitivo?","a":"ducharnos","w":["duchamos","ducharse","nos duchar"],"h":"Con 'vamos a' + infinitivo, el pronombre concuerda con el sujeto 'nosotros' y se une al final del verbo.","e":"Colocación del pronombre reflexivo con infinitivo: se adjunta al infinitivo y concuerda con el sujeto (ducharnos)."},{"p":"Read: \"El autobús del equipo sale a las siete ___; ni un minuto más ni menos.\" ¿Qué expresión indica una hora exacta, sin minutos de más?","a":"en punto","w":["y media","menos cuarto","de la tarde"],"h":"Busca la expresión que significa una hora exacta y redonda.","e":"'En punto' equivale a 'o'clock exactly', una hora sin minutos adicionales."},{"p":"¿Cómo se dice la hora \"5:50\" correctamente en español?","a":"Son las seis menos diez.","w":["Son las cinco menos diez.","Son las seis menos veinte.","Son las cinco y diez."],"h":"Cuando pasan de la media hora, se cuentan los minutos que faltan para la próxima hora.","e":"Para los minutos después de :30 se usa 'menos', restando de la hora siguiente (seis menos diez)."},{"p":"Read: \"Comemos el almuerzo a las doce del día, justo al ___.\" ¿Qué palabra nombra ese momento del día?","a":"mediodía","w":["medianoche","amanecer","atardecer"],"h":"Es el punto medio del día, cuando el sol está más alto.","e":"'Mediodía' es noon, las 12:00 del día."},{"p":"Read: \"___ me ducho, mi hermano prepara el desayuno.\" ¿Qué palabra indica que las dos acciones ocurren al mismo tiempo?","a":"Mientras","w":["Después","Finalmente","Antes"],"h":"Busca la palabra que muestra dos acciones sucediendo a la vez.","e":"'Mientras' (while) señala simultaneidad: dos acciones que pasan al mismo tiempo."},{"p":"Read: \"Yo me cepillo ___ dientes después de cada comida.\" Con verbos reflexivos y partes del cuerpo, ¿qué palabra es correcta?","a":"los","w":["mis","mi","unos"],"h":"En español, con verbos reflexivos no se usa el posesivo con las partes del cuerpo.","e":"Con verbos reflexivos las partes del cuerpo llevan artículo definido ('los'), no posesivo ('mis')."},{"p":"Read: \"Mi entrenador ___ la barba cada mañana antes de venir al gimnasio.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo afeitarse completa la oración para \"él\"?","a":"se afeita","w":["me afeito","se afeitan","te afeitas"],"h":"El sujeto es 'él' (mi entrenador), tercera persona del singular.","e":"Afeitarse en tercera persona del singular = se afeita."},{"p":"Read: \"___ desayunar, me lavo la cara.\" ¿Qué expresión indica una acción que ocurre PRIMERO respecto a desayunar?","a":"Antes de","w":["Después de","Mientras","Durante"],"h":"Busca la expresión que va seguida de un infinitivo y significa 'previo a'.","e":"'Antes de + infinitivo' expresa una acción anterior a otra (before doing)."},{"p":"Read: \"En el estadio, nosotros ___ en las gradas para ver el partido.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo sentarse completa la oración para \"nosotros\"?","a":"nos sentamos","w":["nos sentimos","me siento","se sientan"],"h":"El verbo es sentarse (to sit down); no lo confundas con sentirse (to feel).","e":"Sentarse para 'nosotros' = nos sentamos; 'nos sentimos' viene de sentirse."},{"p":"Read: \"___ los días me levanto temprano para entrenar natación.\" ¿Qué palabra completa la expresión que significa 'diariamente'?","a":"Todos","w":["Toda","Todo","Cualquier"],"h":"La palabra que falta debe concordar en género y número con 'días' (masculino plural).","e":"'Todos los días' significa every day; concuerda masculino plural con 'días'."},{"p":"Read: \"Los niños ___ en el río después de jugar todo el día al sol.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo bañarse completa la oración para \"ellos\"?","a":"se bañan","w":["se baña","nos bañamos","te bañas"],"h":"El sujeto 'los niños' es tercera persona del plural.","e":"Bañarse para 'ellos' = se bañan."},{"p":"Read: \"El vuelo del equipo sale a las tres ___, cuando todavía está oscuro.\" ¿Qué expresión aclara que son las 3:00 muy temprano, antes del amanecer?","a":"de la madrugada","w":["de la tarde","del mediodía","de la noche"],"h":"Piensa en las horas muy tempranas, antes de que salga el sol.","e":"'De la madrugada' aclara las horas de la muy temprana mañana (aprox. 1-5 a. m.)."},{"p":"Read: \"___ correr cinco kilómetros, siempre estiro los músculos.\" ¿Qué expresión significa una acción que ocurre LUEGO de correr?","a":"Después de","w":["Antes de","Mientras","En vez de"],"h":"Busca la expresión + infinitivo que indica que algo pasa a continuación.","e":"'Después de + infinitivo' expresa una acción posterior a otra (after doing)."},{"p":"Un estudiante escribe: \"Nosotros se levantamos a las seis.\" ¿Por qué está incorrecta la oración?","a":"El pronombre reflexivo de 'nosotros' es 'nos', no 'se'.","w":["El verbo debe ser 'levanta', no 'levantamos'.","Debe decir 'nos levantan' con otra terminación.","El pronombre 'se' va después del verbo."],"h":"Cada sujeto tiene su propio pronombre reflexivo; revisa cuál corresponde a 'nosotros'.","e":"El pronombre reflexivo de 'nosotros' es 'nos': la forma correcta es 'nos levantamos'."},{"p":"Read: \"La actriz ___ frente al espejo antes de salir al escenario.\" ¿Qué forma del verbo maquillarse completa la oración para \"ella\"?","a":"se maquilla","w":["me maquillo","se maquillan","te maquillas"],"h":"El sujeto 'la actriz' es tercera persona del singular.","e":"Maquillarse para 'ella' = se maquilla."}],"sp.5.verbs":[{"p":"Yo ___ en el recreo con mis amigos. (caminar)","a":"camino","w":["caminas","camina","caminamos"],"h":"The subject is 'yo' (I). Think about which ending goes with 'I' for -ar verbs.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use the ending -o for 'yo': camin-ar becomes camino."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ pizza en la fiesta. (comer)","a":"comemos","w":["como","comen","comes"],"h":"'Nosotros' means 'we'. Which -er ending shows a whole group including you?","e":"Regular -er verbs use -emos for 'nosotros': com-er becomes comemos."},{"p":"Tú ___ un libro divertido. (leer)","a":"lees","w":["leo","lee","leen"],"h":"'Tú' means 'you' (a friend). Which ending matches 'you' for -er verbs?","e":"Regular -er verbs use -es for 'tú': le-er becomes lees."},{"p":"Ella ___ mucho para el examen. (estudiar)","a":"estudia","w":["estudio","estudias","estudiamos"],"h":"'Ella' means 'she'. Which -ar ending goes with one other person?","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -a for 'él/ella': estudi-ar becomes estudia."},{"p":"Ellos ___ muy rápido en la carrera. (correr)","a":"corren","w":["corro","corres","corremos"],"h":"'Ellos' means 'they'. Which -er ending fits a group of other people?","e":"Regular -er verbs use -en for 'ellos/ellas': corr-er becomes corren."},{"p":"Yo ___ agua después de jugar. (beber)","a":"bebo","w":["bebes","bebe","bebemos"],"h":"The subject is 'yo' (I). What ending do -er verbs use for 'I'?","e":"Regular -er verbs use -o for 'yo': beb-er becomes bebo."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ una carta a la abuela. (escribir)","a":"escribimos","w":["escribo","escribe","escriben"],"h":"'Nosotros' means 'we'. Which -ir ending shows the whole group?","e":"Regular -ir verbs use -imos for 'nosotros': escrib-ir becomes escribimos."},{"p":"Tú ___ la puerta del salón. (abrir)","a":"abres","w":["abro","abre","abrimos"],"h":"'Tú' means 'you' (a friend). Which -ir ending matches 'you'?","e":"Regular -ir verbs use -es for 'tú': abr-ir becomes abres."},{"p":"___ hablo español en la escuela. Which subject pronoun completes the sentence?","a":"Yo","w":["Tú","Él","Nosotros"],"h":"The verb 'hablo' ends in -o. Which person does that ending point to?","e":"The verb ending -o matches 'yo' (I), the first-person singular subject pronoun."},{"p":"Which Spanish subject pronoun means 'we'?","a":"nosotros","w":["yo","tú","ellos"],"h":"Think about the word you use for yourself plus your friends together.","e":"'Nosotros' is the first-person plural pronoun meaning 'we'."},{"p":"María y yo ___ en el jardín de la escuela. (trabajar)","a":"trabajamos","w":["trabajo","trabajas","trabajan"],"h":"'María y yo' is like saying 'we'. Which -ar ending fits that?","e":"When the subject includes 'yo' plus others it means 'nosotros', so -ar verbs use -amos: trabajamos."},{"p":"Read: \"Ana está en el coro. A ella le gusta la música.\" Ana ___ una canción bonita. (cantar)","a":"canta","w":["canto","cantas","cantamos"],"h":"Ana is one person, like 'she'. Which -ar ending goes with one other person?","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -a for 'él/ella', so for Ana it is canta."},{"p":"El perro ___ feliz en el patio. (correr)","a":"corre","w":["corro","corres","corren"],"h":"'El perro' is one animal, treated like 'he/she'. Which -er ending fits?","e":"Regular -er verbs use -e for one subject like 'él/ella': corr-er becomes corre."},{"p":"Yo ___ mis juguetes con mi hermano. (compartir)","a":"comparto","w":["compartes","comparte","compartimos"],"h":"The subject is 'yo' (I). What ending do -ir verbs use for 'I'?","e":"Regular -ir verbs use -o for 'yo': compart-ir becomes comparto."},{"p":"Tú ___ música en tu cuarto. (escuchar)","a":"escuchas","w":["escucho","escucha","escuchan"],"h":"'Tú' means 'you' (a friend). Which -ar ending matches 'you'?","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -as for 'tú': escuch-ar becomes escuchas."},{"p":"Los niños ___ la cuerda en el recreo. (saltar)","a":"saltan","w":["salto","saltas","saltamos"],"h":"'Los niños' means 'they' (the kids). Which -ar ending fits a group of others?","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -an for 'ellos/ellas': salt-ar becomes saltan."},{"p":"Which Spanish subject pronoun means 'he'?","a":"él","w":["ella","yo","tú"],"h":"Think about the word you use to talk about one boy.","e":"'Él' is the third-person singular pronoun meaning 'he'."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ en una ciudad grande. (vivir)","a":"vivimos","w":["vivo","vives","viven"],"h":"'Nosotros' means 'we'. Which -ir ending shows the whole group?","e":"Regular -ir verbs use -imos for 'nosotros': viv-ir becomes vivimos."},{"p":"Usted ___ en la oficina todos los días. (trabajar)","a":"trabaja","w":["trabajas","trabajan","trabajo"],"h":"'Usted' is the polite way to say 'you', and it uses the same ending as él/ella.","e":"'Usted' takes the third-person singular form, so a regular -ar verb ends in -a: trabaja."},{"p":"Ustedes ___ muchos regalos en la fiesta. (recibir)","a":"reciben","w":["recibimos","recibes","recibo"],"h":"'Ustedes' means 'you all' and uses the same ending as ellos/ellas.","e":"For -ir verbs, the ustedes/ellos form ends in -en: reciben."},{"p":"Mi amigo y yo ___ español en la clase. (aprender)","a":"aprendemos","w":["aprenden","aprendo","aprendes"],"h":"'Mi amigo y yo' is a group that includes you, so think 'nosotros'.","e":"The nosotros form of an -er verb ends in -emos: aprendemos."},{"p":"Mi hermana ___ un gato bonito en su cuaderno. (dibujar)","a":"dibuja","w":["dibujan","dibujo","dibujas"],"h":"'Mi hermana' is one person you talk about, like ella.","e":"An -ar verb with a third-person singular subject ends in -a: dibuja."},{"p":"Yo ___ las escaleras corriendo para llegar a clase. (subir)","a":"subo","w":["subes","sube","subimos"],"h":"When the subject is 'yo', the verb ending changes to match me.","e":"For the yo form, -ir verbs end in -o: subo."},{"p":"Read: \"Diego siempre tiene dudas en clase.\" Él ___ muchas cosas a la maestra. (preguntar)","a":"pregunta","w":["preguntan","pregunto","preguntas"],"h":"The passage points to one boy, so use the él ending.","e":"With él, a regular -ar verb ends in -a: pregunta."},{"p":"Pedro y Luis tienen sed y ___ jugo de naranja. (tomar)","a":"toman","w":["tomamos","toma","tomo"],"h":"Two people together act like 'ellos'.","e":"The ellos form of an -ar verb ends in -an: toman."},{"p":"What ending do regular -ar verbs use for 'nosotros'?","a":"-amos","w":["-emos","-imos","-an"],"h":"Match the verb type (-ar) with the 'we' form.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -amos for nosotros (like hablamos, jugamos)."},{"p":"Which Spanish subject pronoun is the polite way to say 'you' to an adult?","a":"usted","w":["tú","ustedes","nosotros"],"h":"Think about which word shows respect to one grown-up.","e":"'Usted' is the formal singular 'you'; 'tú' is informal and 'ustedes' is plural."},{"p":"Yo ___ muy bien la lección de hoy. (comprender)","a":"comprendo","w":["comprendes","comprende","comprendemos"],"h":"The subject 'yo' changes the ending to match me.","e":"For the yo form, -er verbs end in -o: comprendo."},{"p":"Read: \"A Sofía le encantan los animales; tiene un perro y un gato.\" Sofía ___ a sus mascotas cada día. (cuidar)","a":"cuida","w":["cuidan","cuido","cuidas"],"h":"Sofía is one girl, so use the ella ending.","e":"With a third-person singular subject, an -ar verb ends in -a: cuida."},{"p":"Ellas ___ fútbol en el parque los sábados. (practicar)","a":"practican","w":["practicamos","practica","practico"],"h":"'Ellas' is a group of girls, the plural 'they'.","e":"The ellas form of an -ar verb ends in -an: practican."},{"p":"Tú ___ qué película vamos a ver esta noche. (decidir)","a":"decides","w":["decido","decide","decidimos"],"h":"'Tú' is one friend you talk to directly.","e":"For the tú form, -ir verbs end in -es: decides."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ el autobús en la esquina de la escuela. (esperar)","a":"esperamos","w":["esperan","espero","esperas"],"h":"'Nosotros' means 'we', a group that includes you.","e":"The nosotros form of an -ar verb ends in -amos: esperamos."},{"p":"Read: \"A mi familia le gusta el ejercicio.\" Nosotros ___ en el parque cada mañana. (correr)","a":"corremos","w":["corren","corro","corres"],"h":"'Nosotros' is the 'we' form for the whole family plus you.","e":"The nosotros form of an -er verb ends in -emos: corremos."},{"p":"El maestro ___ la lección en la pizarra. (explicar)","a":"explica","w":["explican","explico","explicas"],"h":"'El maestro' is one person, like él.","e":"With a third-person singular subject, an -ar verb ends in -a: explica."},{"p":"Read: \"Marta y su mamá van al mercado.\" Ellas ___ frutas frescas. (comprar)","a":"compran","w":["compramos","compro","compra"],"h":"Two people acting together are 'ellas'.","e":"The ellas form of an -ar verb ends in -an: compran."},{"p":"The verb 'escribir' belongs to which group of verbs?","a":"-ir verb","w":["-ar verb","-er verb","irregular verb"],"h":"Look at the last two letters of the infinitive.","e":"'Escribir' ends in -ir, so it is a regular -ir verb."},{"p":"Ellos ___ en la piscina toda la tarde en el verano. (nadar)","a":"nadan","w":["nadamos","nadas","nada"],"h":"'Ellos' means more than one person doing the action.","e":"Regular -ar verbs take the ending -an for 'ellos/ellas': nad- + -an = nadan."},{"p":"The verb form 'vendes' goes with which subject pronoun?","a":"tú","w":["yo","él","nosotros"],"h":"Look at the ending -es and think about who it belongs to.","e":"For regular -er verbs, the 'tú' form ends in -es, so 'vendes' matches tú."},{"p":"Read: \"Es el cumpleaños de Lucía y todos sus amigos vienen a su casa.\" Ellos ___ mucho en la fiesta. (bailar)","a":"bailan","w":["bailamos","bailáis","baila"],"h":"The friends are the ones dancing at the party.","e":"'Ellos' (the friends) with a regular -ar verb uses -an: bail- + -an = bailan."},{"p":"Vosotros ___ en España con vuestra familia. (vivir)","a":"vivís","w":["viven","vivimos","vives"],"h":"'Vosotros' is the 'you all' form used in Spain.","e":"Regular -ir verbs use the ending -ís for 'vosotros': viv- + -ís = vivís."},{"p":"What ending do regular -er verbs use for 'ellos'?","a":"-en","w":["-an","-emos","-es"],"h":"Think of the verb 'comer' with 'ellos'.","e":"Regular -er verbs take -en for 'ellos/ellas', like comen or corren."},{"p":"Read: \"A Tomás le encanta la naturaleza.\" Él ___ fotos de las flores en el parque. (sacar)","a":"saca","w":["sacas","sacamos","sacan"],"h":"Only one person, Tomás, is taking the photos.","e":"'Él' with a regular -ar verb ends in -a: sac- + -a = saca."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ la casa juntos los domingos. (limpiar)","a":"limpiamos","w":["limpian","limpias","limpio"],"h":"'Nosotros' means 'we' — you and others together.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -amos for 'nosotros': limpi- + -amos = limpiamos."},{"p":"Yo ___ a mi mamá a poner la mesa. (ayudar)","a":"ayudo","w":["ayudas","ayuda","ayudamos"],"h":"'Yo' always ends the same way in the present tense.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -o for 'yo': ayud- + -o = ayudo."},{"p":"Read: \"Carla y yo estamos en la clase de arte.\" Nosotras ___ un paisaje bonito. (pintar)","a":"pintamos","w":["pintan","pinto","pintáis"],"h":"'Carla y yo' together means 'nosotras'.","e":"'Nosotras' with a regular -ar verb takes -amos: pint- + -amos = pintamos."},{"p":"___ vendemos limonada en la esquina. Which subject pronoun completes the sentence?","a":"Nosotros","w":["Yo","Ellos","Tú"],"h":"Look at the verb ending -emos and think who it belongs to.","e":"The ending -emos on a regular -er verb matches 'nosotros', so 'nosotros vendemos'."},{"p":"Ellos ___ a la escuela temprano todos los días. (asistir)","a":"asisten","w":["asistimos","asistes","asiste"],"h":"'Ellos' means several people going to school.","e":"Regular -ir verbs use -en for 'ellos/ellas': asist- + -en = asisten."},{"p":"Mi tío ___ frutas frescas en el mercado. (vender)","a":"vende","w":["vendes","vendo","venden"],"h":"'Mi tío' is one person, like 'él'.","e":"Regular -er verbs use -e for 'él/ella': vend- + -e = vende."},{"p":"Ustedes ___ la televisión por la noche. (mirar)","a":"miran","w":["miráis","miramos","miras"],"h":"'Ustedes' means 'you all' and uses the same ending as 'ellos'.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -an for 'ustedes': mir- + -an = miran."},{"p":"What ending do regular -ir verbs use for 'yo'?","a":"-o","w":["-es","-imos","-e"],"h":"The 'yo' ending is the same for -ar, -er, and -ir verbs.","e":"All three verb groups use -o for 'yo', like vivo, escribo, or subo."},{"p":"Yo ___ mi mochila antes de salir para la escuela. (buscar)","a":"busco","w":["buscas","busca","buscamos"],"h":"'Yo' takes the same ending in every regular -ar verb.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -o for 'yo': busc- + -o = busco."},{"p":"Read: \"Ana y Pablo tienen una tarea de matemáticas.\" Ellos ___ los números juntos. (sumar)","a":"suman","w":["sumamos","sumas","suma"],"h":"Ana and Pablo together are 'ellos'.","e":"'Ellos' with a regular -ar verb uses -an: sum- + -an = suman."},{"p":"Mi papá ___ la cena para toda la familia. (cocinar)","a":"cocina","w":["cocinas","cocino","cocinamos"],"h":"'Mi papá' is one person, like 'él'.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -a for 'él/ella': cocin- + -a = cocina."}],"sp.7.preterite":[{"p":"Ayer yo ___ con mi abuela por teléfono durante una hora. (hablar)","a":"hablé","w":["hablo","habló","hablaba"],"h":"Ask yourself who did the action (yo) and remember the sentence starts with 'ayer', a completed past moment.","e":"Regular -ar verbs in the preterite take -é in the yo form (hablar → hablé) to show a finished past action."},{"p":"¿Tú ___ en el concierto de la escuela anoche? (cantar)","a":"cantaste","w":["cantas","cantó","cantabas"],"h":"The subject is tú, and 'anoche' points to something that already happened and finished.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use the ending -aste for tú in the preterite (cantar → cantaste)."},{"p":"Ella ___ mucho dinero vendiendo limonada la semana pasada. (ganar)","a":"ganó","w":["gané","ganaste","gana"],"h":"Focus on the él/ella subject and notice the time marker 'la semana pasada'.","e":"Regular -ar verbs take the accented ending -ó for él/ella in the preterite (ganar → ganó)."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ toda la noche para el examen de matemáticas. (estudiar)","a":"estudiamos","w":["estudiemos","estudiaron","estudiábamos"],"h":"For -ar verbs, the nosotros preterite looks exactly like the nosotros present, so let the time context guide you.","e":"Regular -ar verbs use -amos for nosotros in the preterite (estudiar → estudiamos); it is identical to the present form."},{"p":"Los jugadores ___ el partido de fútbol el domingo pasado. (ganar)","a":"ganaron","w":["ganó","ganaban","ganan"],"h":"The subject is a plural group (ellos), and the game is over.","e":"Regular -ar verbs take -aron for ellos/ellas in the preterite (ganar → ganaron)."},{"p":"Anoche yo ___ un libro entero antes de dormir. (leer)","a":"leí","w":["leyó","leo","leía"],"h":"Think about the yo form of an -er verb and that 'anoche' means the action is complete.","e":"Regular -er verbs take -í in the yo preterite (leer → leí), showing a completed past action."},{"p":"Mi hermano ___ tres tacos en la cena de ayer. (comer)","a":"comió","w":["comí","comieron","comía"],"h":"The subject is él, and 'ayer' signals a finished past event.","e":"Regular -er verbs take the accented -ió for él/ella in the preterite (comer → comió)."},{"p":"El año pasado yo ___ en la Ciudad de México con mis tíos. (vivir)","a":"viví","w":["vivo","vivió","vivía"],"h":"Match the yo subject with an -ir verb, and note 'el año pasado' is a closed time period.","e":"Regular -ir verbs take -í in the yo preterite (vivir → viví), just like -er verbs."},{"p":"Los estudiantes ___ una canción original en la clase de música. (escribir)","a":"escribieron","w":["escribió","escriben","escribían"],"h":"The subject is a plural group (ellos) doing a completed action.","e":"Regular -ir verbs take -ieron for ellos/ellas in the preterite (escribir → escribieron)."},{"p":"Ayer por la tarde nosotros ___ al cine a ver una película. (ir)","a":"fuimos","w":["vamos","fueron","íbamos"],"h":"'Ir' is irregular in the preterite and its forms look nothing like the present; think about the nosotros ending.","e":"The verb ir is irregular in the preterite: nosotros → fuimos (its forms are identical to ser)."},{"p":"El verano pasado yo ___ a la playa con mi familia. (ir)","a":"fui","w":["voy","fue","iba"],"h":"'Ir' is irregular; focus on the yo form for a completed trip.","e":"Ir is irregular in the preterite: yo → fui, which is the same form used for ser."},{"p":"Anoche yo ___ toda mi tarea antes de la cena. (hacer)","a":"hice","w":["hací","hizo","hacía"],"h":"'Hacer' is irregular in the preterite and changes its stem; watch the spelling of the yo form.","e":"Hacer is irregular in the preterite with the stem 'hic-': yo → hice."},{"p":"¿Qué ___ ella el fin de semana pasado? (hacer)","a":"hizo","w":["hació","hice","hacía"],"h":"'Hacer' is irregular; the él/ella form changes its spelling from c to z to keep the sound.","e":"Hacer is irregular in the preterite: él/ella → hizo, spelled with a z to preserve the soft sound."},{"p":"La semana pasada nosotros ___ un examen muy difícil de ciencias. (tener)","a":"tuvimos","w":["tenimos","tuvieron","teníamos"],"h":"'Tener' is irregular and uses a special stem in the preterite; focus on the nosotros ending.","e":"Tener is irregular in the preterite with the stem 'tuv-': nosotros → tuvimos."},{"p":"Ayer yo ___ en casa todo el día porque estaba enfermo. (estar)","a":"estuve","w":["esté","estuvo","estaba"],"h":"'Estar' is irregular in the preterite and uses a special stem; find the yo ending.","e":"Estar is irregular in the preterite with the stem 'estuv-': yo → estuve."},{"p":"Read: \"El sábado pasado, María fue al mercado. Primero compró frutas frescas y después habló con los vendedores. Finalmente caminó a casa muy contenta.\" Según el texto, ¿qué hizo María justo antes de hablar con los vendedores?","a":"Compró frutas frescas","w":["Caminó a casa contenta","Preparó una ensalada","Llamó a sus amigos"],"h":"Look for the word 'primero' (first) and the action that comes right before she talked to the sellers.","e":"The preterite verbs (fue, compró, habló, caminó) narrate completed past actions in sequence; 'compró frutas' happens before 'habló'."},{"p":"Which time expression is a signal that you should use the preterite tense?","a":"ayer (yesterday)","w":["todos los días (every day)","generalmente (generally)","siempre (always)"],"h":"The preterite describes a single completed action; look for a word that points to one specific, finished moment.","e":"Time markers like 'ayer', 'anoche', and 'la semana pasada' signal a completed past action, which calls for the preterite."},{"p":"Ayer yo ___ al básquetbol con mis amigos en el parque. (jugar)","a":"jugué","w":["jugé","jugó","jugaba"],"h":"Piensa en la persona 'yo'. Los verbos que terminan en -gar cambian la ortografía en esta forma para conservar el sonido de la 'g'.","e":"En 'yo', los verbos en -gar como jugar cambian a -gué (jugué) para mantener el sonido fuerte de la g. Este es un cambio ortográfico del pretérito."},{"p":"Anoche yo ___ la guitarra en la fiesta de mi vecino. (tocar)","a":"toqué","w":["tocé","tocó","tocaba"],"h":"Fíjate en 'yo' y en la letra 'c'. Los verbos en -car cambian su ortografía para no perder el sonido 'k'.","e":"Los verbos en -car como tocar cambian a -qué en la forma de 'yo' (toqué) para conservar el sonido /k/. Es un cambio ortográfico del pretérito."},{"p":"El lunes pasado yo ___ a leer una novela de aventuras. (empezar)","a":"empecé","w":["empezé","empezó","empezaba"],"h":"Con 'yo', los verbos en -zar cambian la 'z'. Recuerda que en español la 'z' casi nunca va antes de la 'e'.","e":"Los verbos en -zar como empezar cambian a -cé en la forma de 'yo' (empecé), porque la z se convierte en c antes de e. Es un cambio ortográfico del pretérito."},{"p":"Yo no ___ dormir anoche porque estaba muy emocionado por el juego. (poder)","a":"pude","w":["podí","pudo","podía"],"h":"Poder es irregular en el pretérito: cambia su raíz y no lleva acento en 'yo'. No sigue el patrón normal de los verbos en -er.","e":"Poder tiene raíz irregular en el pretérito (pud-) y termina sin acento: pude. Es un verbo de raíz irregular."},{"p":"Esta mañana ella ___ todos sus libros en la mochila antes de salir. (poner)","a":"puso","w":["ponió","ponó","ponía"],"h":"Poner es irregular: su raíz cambia por completo en el pretérito. No termina como los verbos regulares en -er.","e":"Poner usa la raíz irregular pus- en el pretérito, así que 'ella' es puso, no 'ponió'. Es un verbo de raíz irregular."},{"p":"Mis primos ___ a mi casa a jugar videojuegos el fin de semana pasado. (venir)","a":"vinieron","w":["venieron","vinioron","venían"],"h":"Venir es irregular: su raíz cambia a 'vin-'. Aplica la terminación de 'ellos' a esa raíz nueva, no a la original.","e":"Venir tiene raíz irregular (vin-) en el pretérito, así que 'ellos' es vinieron. Es un verbo de raíz irregular."},{"p":"El profesor nos ___ la respuesta correcta después del examen. (decir)","a":"dijo","w":["dició","deció","decía"],"h":"Decir es muy irregular: su raíz cambia a 'dij-'. Cuando una raíz termina en 'j', la terminación de 'él' es solo -o.","e":"Decir usa la raíz irregular dij- en el pretérito, y 'él/ella' es dijo. Los verbos con raíz en -j (dijo, trajo) pierden la i de la terminación."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ sándwiches y frutas para el picnic en el parque. (traer)","a":"trajimos","w":["traímos","trajemos","traíamos"],"h":"Traer es irregular: la raíz cambia a 'traj-'. Ten cuidado con la vocal de la terminación de 'nosotros'.","e":"Traer usa la raíz irregular traj- en el pretérito, y 'nosotros' es trajimos. Es un verbo de raíz irregular en -j."},{"p":"Mis abuelos me ___ muchos regalos en mi cumpleaños. (dar)","a":"dieron","w":["daron","daban","dioron"],"h":"Dar es irregular: aunque termina en -ar, toma las terminaciones de los verbos en -er/-ir en el pretérito.","e":"Dar es irregular y usa terminaciones de -er/-ir sin acentos: di, dio, dieron. Por eso 'ellos' es dieron, no 'daron'."},{"p":"Ayer yo ___ a mi jugador de fútbol favorito en el centro comercial. (ver)","a":"vi","w":["ví","veí","veía"],"h":"Ver en 'yo' es una sola sílaba. En español, las formas del pretérito de una sílaba no llevan acento escrito.","e":"Ver en pretérito da formas cortas de una sílaba (vi, vio) que no llevan tilde. Escribir 'ví' con acento es un error común."},{"p":"Nadie ___ la historia increíble que contó Juan sobre el partido. (creer)","a":"creyó","w":["creió","creó","creía"],"h":"Cuando la raíz de un verbo en -er/-ir termina en vocal, la 'i' de la terminación de 'él' se convierte en otra letra.","e":"En creer, la i de la terminación se vuelve y entre vocales: creyó. Este cambio i→y también ocurre en leyó, oyó y cayó."},{"p":"El bebé ___ toda la noche sin despertarse ni una vez. (dormir)","a":"durmió","w":["dormió","durmó","dormía"],"h":"Dormir cambia la vocal de la raíz solo en las formas de 'él/ella' y 'ellos'. La 'o' se convierte en 'u'.","e":"Los verbos en -ir con cambio de raíz como dormir cambian o→u en tercera persona: durmió, durmieron. Es un cambio de raíz del pretérito."},{"p":"En el restaurante, ella ___ tacos de pollo y agua fresca de limón. (pedir)","a":"pidió","w":["pedió","pidó","pedía"],"h":"Pedir cambia su vocal de raíz en 'él/ella' y 'ellos'. La 'e' se convierte en 'i' en esas formas.","e":"Los verbos en -ir como pedir cambian e→i en tercera persona del pretérito: pidió, pidieron. Es un cambio de raíz."},{"p":"Mis amigos ___ ver la película de acción en vez de la comedia. (preferir)","a":"prefirieron","w":["preferieron","prefierieron","preferían"],"h":"Preferir cambia la vocal de la raíz de 'e' a 'i' en las formas de 'él' y 'ellos', igual que pedir y servir.","e":"Los verbos en -ir como preferir cambian e→i en tercera persona: prefirió, prefirieron. Es un cambio de raíz del pretérito."},{"p":"Read: 'El domingo, Carlos y su equipo llegaron al estadio a las nueve de la mañana. Jugaron dos horas, ganaron el partido y celebraron con pizza. Por la noche, Carlos durmió muy bien.' Según el texto, ¿cuánto tiempo jugó el equipo de Carlos?","a":"Dos horas","w":["Nueve horas","Una hora","Tres horas"],"h":"Busca el número que se refiere a cuánto duró el juego, no la hora en que llegaron al estadio.","e":"El texto dice 'Jugaron dos horas', que indica duración. 'A las nueve' es la hora de llegada, no la duración; hay que distinguir esos datos."},{"p":"Read: 'La fiesta fue en la casa de Ana. Todos mis amigos fueron muy simpáticos.' En la oración 'La fiesta fue en la casa de Ana', ¿de qué verbo viene 'fue'?","a":"ser","w":["ir","ver","hacer"],"h":"Dos verbos comparten exactamente las mismas formas en el pretérito. Aquí la frase describe dónde ocurrió algo, no un movimiento.","e":"Ser e ir tienen formas idénticas en el pretérito (fui, fue, fueron). Aquí 'fue' significa 'ocurrió/tuvo lugar', así que viene de ser."},{"p":"¿Cuál oración usa correctamente el pretérito para una acción terminada en un momento específico?","a":"Ayer corrí cinco kilómetros en el parque.","w":["Todos los días corría en el parque.","Mientras corría, escuchaba música.","Siempre corría por las mañanas."],"h":"El pretérito describe una acción completa que empezó y terminó. Las acciones repetidas o habituales usan otro tiempo pasado.","e":"El pretérito (corrí) expresa una acción terminada en un momento concreto. Las acciones habituales o en progreso usan el imperfecto (corría)."},{"p":"¿Cuál de estas expresiones de tiempo NO es una señal para usar el pretérito?","a":"todos los días","w":["anoche","el año pasado","hace dos semanas"],"h":"Busca la expresión que describe algo repetido o habitual, no un momento único ya terminado.","e":"'Todos los días' indica una acción habitual y suele acompañar al imperfecto. Anoche, el año pasado y hace dos semanas marcan momentos terminados y piden el pretérito."},{"p":"Ayer yo ___ tarde al entrenamiento de básquetbol porque perdí el autobús. (llegar)","a":"llegué","w":["llegé","llegí","llegaba"],"h":"With 'yo', verbs ending in -gar need a spelling change to keep the hard 'g' sound before the ending.","e":"Verbs ending in -gar change g to gu in the 'yo' preterite form (llegar → llegué) to preserve the hard sound."},{"p":"El sábado yo ___ una buena nota en el examen de música. (sacar)","a":"saqué","w":["sacé","saqé","sacaba"],"h":"Verbs ending in -car change spelling in the 'yo' form to keep the hard 'k' sound.","e":"Verbs ending in -car change c to qu in the 'yo' preterite (sacar → saqué) so the sound stays hard before -é."},{"p":"Ayer yo ___ el río con cuidado durante la excursión al campo. (cruzar)","a":"crucé","w":["cruzé","crucí","cruzaba"],"h":"Spanish avoids writing 'z' directly before an 'e', so the spelling changes in the 'yo' form.","e":"Verbs ending in -zar change z to c in the 'yo' preterite (cruzar → crucé) because z is not written before e."},{"p":"El mesero nos ___ la comida muy rápido en el restaurante anoche. (servir)","a":"sirvió","w":["servió","sirvó","servía"],"h":"Some -ir verbs change the stem vowel only in the él/ella and ellos forms of the preterite.","e":"Stem-changing -ir verbs like servir change e to i in the third person preterite (servir → sirvió)."},{"p":"La planta ___ porque nadie la regó durante las vacaciones de verano. (morir)","a":"murió","w":["morió","muró","moría"],"h":"This -ir verb changes its stem vowel in the third person, similar to 'dormir'.","e":"The -ir verb morir changes o to u in the third person preterite (morir → murió), like dormir → durmió."},{"p":"Yo ___ ir al concierto, pero no tenía dinero para el boleto. (querer)","a":"quise","w":["querí","quisé","quería"],"h":"This is an irregular verb with a special preterite stem and no accent on the 'yo' ending.","e":"Querer has the irregular preterite stem 'quis-' with unstressed endings (yo quise), so there is no written accent."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ la noticia del partido cancelado por la radio esta mañana. (saber)","a":"supimos","w":["sabimos","supemos","sabíamos"],"h":"Saber is irregular in the preterite and often means 'found out' rather than 'knew'.","e":"Saber uses the irregular stem 'sup-' in the preterite (nosotros supimos) and can mean 'we found out'."},{"p":"Mi papá ___ el coche hasta las montañas el fin de semana pasado. (conducir)","a":"condujo","w":["conducó","condució","conducía"],"h":"Verbs ending in -ducir take a special preterite stem ending in 'j'.","e":"Verbs like conducir use the irregular 'j' stem (conduj-) in the preterite (él condujo)."},{"p":"Nosotros ___ por el bosque durante tres horas buscando animales. (andar)","a":"anduvimos","w":["andamos","anduvamos","andábamos"],"h":"Andar looks regular but has a completely irregular preterite stem, like 'tener'.","e":"Andar has the irregular preterite stem 'anduv-' (nosotros anduvimos), not a regular -ar pattern."},{"p":"De repente, ella ___ un ruido extraño en el jardín durante la noche. (oír)","a":"oyó","w":["oió","oyió","oía"],"h":"When the ending would put an unstressed 'i' between two vowels, the 'i' becomes a 'y'.","e":"In oír, the third person preterite changes i to y between vowels (oír → oyó), like creer → creyó."},{"p":"El ciclista se ___ durante la carrera, pero se levantó y terminó el recorrido. (caer)","a":"cayó","w":["caió","cayió","caía"],"h":"This verb follows the same spelling rule as 'leer' and 'oír' in the third person.","e":"Caer changes i to y in the third person preterite (se cayó) because the i falls between two vowels."},{"p":"Esta mañana yo me ___ muy temprano para ver salir el sol en la playa. (despertarse)","a":"desperté","w":["despertí","despertaba","desperto"],"h":"This is a regular -ar verb in the preterite; the stem change only happens in the present tense.","e":"Reflexive despertarse is regular in the preterite (yo me desperté); e→ie stem changes do not occur in the preterite of -ar verbs."},{"p":"Los niños se ___ mucho en el parque de diversiones el domingo pasado. (divertirse)","a":"divirtieron","w":["divertieron","divirtaron","divertían"],"h":"This -ir verb changes its stem vowel in the ellos/ellas form of the preterite.","e":"The -ir verb divertirse changes e to i in the third person plural preterite (se divirtieron)."},{"p":"¿Cuál de estas oraciones está en el pretérito?","a":"El equipo ganó el campeonato el año pasado.","w":["El equipo gana el campeonato cada año.","El equipo ganaba muchos partidos antes.","El equipo está ganando el partido ahora."],"h":"Look for a single, completed action finished at a specific point in the past.","e":"The preterite expresses completed past actions; 'ganó' is preterite, while the others are present, imperfect, and present progressive."},{"p":"En la oración 'Hace tres días compramos las entradas para el partido', ¿qué indica la expresión 'hace tres días'?","a":"Que la acción ocurrió tres días atrás en el pasado.","w":["Que la acción va a ocurrir dentro de tres días.","Que la acción todavía sigue pasando ahora.","Que la acción se repite cada tres días."],"h":"Notice that the verb 'compramos' here refers to a finished action, not the present or future.","e":"'Hace + [tiempo]' with a preterite verb means 'ago', showing how long before now the completed action happened."},{"p":"Read: 'El martes los estudiantes hicieron un experimento de ciencias. Mezclaron vinagre con bicarbonato y observaron una reacción. La mezcla produjo muchas burbujas y todos aplaudieron.' Según el texto, ¿qué produjo la mezcla?","a":"Muchas burbujas","w":["Mucho humo","Una llama de fuego","Un olor terrible"],"h":"Find the sentence that uses the verb 'produjo' and read what comes right after it.","e":"Reading for the completed action 'produjo' (from producir) shows the mixture produced many bubbles."},{"p":"Read: 'Hace una semana mi familia y yo fuimos de campamento al lago. Pusimos la tienda cerca del agua, hicimos una fogata y vimos las estrellas. Yo no pude dormir por la emoción.' Según el texto, ¿por qué no durmió bien el narrador?","a":"Porque estaba muy emocionado","w":["Porque tenía mucho frío","Porque escuchó un animal","Porque la tienda se cayó"],"h":"Look at the last sentence and what the phrase 'por la emoción' is explaining.","e":"The preterite 'no pude dormir' plus 'por la emoción' tells us the narrator could not sleep because of excitement."}],"sp.8.culture":[{"p":"You are mailing a postcard to a friend in the capital of Mexico. Which city do you write on the envelope?","a":"Mexico City","w":["Guadalajara","Cancún","Monterrey"],"h":"The capital shares its name with the country and is one of the largest cities in the world.","e":"Mexico City (Ciudad de México) is the capital of Mexico; the other cities are large or popular but are not the seat of government."},{"p":"A soccer fan is flying to watch Real Madrid play in Spain's capital. Where does the plane land?","a":"Madrid","w":["Barcelona","Seville","Valencia"],"h":"The famous club Real Madrid is named after this city.","e":"Madrid is the capital of Spain; Barcelona, Seville, and Valencia are major Spanish cities but not the capital."},{"p":"Tango music drifts from the streets of Argentina's capital. Which city is it?","a":"Buenos Aires","w":["Córdoba","Rosario","Mendoza"],"h":"Its name means 'good airs' in Spanish, and its people are called porteños.","e":"Buenos Aires is the capital of Argentina; the other cities are important but are not the capital."},{"p":"Machu Picchu draws tourists who first fly into the capital of Peru. What is that city?","a":"Lima","w":["Cusco","Arequipa","Quito"],"h":"It sits on Peru's Pacific coast, not in the mountains.","e":"Lima is the coastal capital of Peru; Cusco is near Machu Picchu, and Quito is actually the capital of Ecuador."},{"p":"A student researching coffee farms wants to visit Colombia's capital. Which city should she look up?","a":"Bogotá","w":["Medellín","Cali","Cartagena"],"h":"It is a high-altitude city in the Andes near the center of the country.","e":"Bogotá is the capital of Colombia; Medellín, Cali, and Cartagena are well-known Colombian cities but not the capital."},{"p":"Nestled in a valley between the Andes and the coast is the capital of Chile. What is it called?","a":"Santiago","w":["Valparaíso","Concepción","Viña del Mar"],"h":"Its name is a common Spanish first name honoring Saint James.","e":"Santiago is the capital of Chile; Valparaíso and the others are notable coastal or southern cities."},{"p":"During Día de los Muertos, families build colorful altars called ofrendas. What is the main purpose of this holiday?","a":"To honor and remember loved ones who have died","w":["To celebrate a country's independence","To give thanks for the year's harvest","To mark the start of a new school year"],"h":"The holiday's name translates to 'Day of the Dead.'","e":"Día de los Muertos is a celebration of memory, welcoming back the spirits of deceased relatives with ofrendas and favorite foods."},{"p":"Día de los Muertos, with its sugar skulls and marigold altars, is most famously celebrated in which country?","a":"Mexico","w":["Spain","Argentina","Peru"],"h":"This country also gave the world tacos and mariachi music.","e":"Día de los Muertos is rooted in Mexico, blending Indigenous and Catholic traditions; it is not native to the other countries listed."},{"p":"On Día de los Muertos, bright orange flowers guide spirits to the ofrenda with their color and scent. Which flower is traditionally used?","a":"Marigold","w":["Red rose","White lily","Sunflower"],"h":"Its Nahuatl name is cempasúchil, and it is often called the 'flower of the dead.'","e":"The marigold, or cempasúchil, is the traditional flower of Día de los Muertos; its scent and color are believed to guide the spirits home."},{"p":"Cinco de Mayo is often misunderstood. What historical event does it actually commemorate?","a":"Mexico's victory at the Battle of Puebla","w":["Mexico's independence from Spain","The founding of Mexico City","The signing of a peace treaty with the United States"],"h":"It marks a battle won against a French army, not the start of independence.","e":"Cinco de Mayo celebrates Mexico's 1862 victory over France at the Battle of Puebla; Mexican Independence Day is actually September 16."},{"p":"A dancer stamps her heels and claps a fierce rhythm to guitar music born in southern Spain. What is this art form called?","a":"Flamenco","w":["Tango","Salsa","Merengue"],"h":"It comes from the region of Andalusia and features guitar, singing, and hand-clapping.","e":"Flamenco is a Spanish musical and dance tradition from Andalusia; tango, salsa, and merengue come from Latin America and the Caribbean."},{"p":"Two dancers glide across the floor to a dramatic dance that grew up in the neighborhoods of Buenos Aires. What is it?","a":"Tango","w":["Flamenco","Cumbia","Bachata"],"h":"This dance shares its birthplace with the capital of Argentina.","e":"The tango originated in Argentina (and Uruguay) around Buenos Aires; the other styles come from Spain, Colombia, and the Dominican Republic."},{"p":"A band in charro suits with trumpets, violins, and guitars serenades diners at a Mexican restaurant. What kind of music are they playing?","a":"Mariachi","w":["Flamenco","Reggaeton","Tango"],"h":"This ensemble is a symbol of Mexican culture, often heard at weddings and celebrations.","e":"Mariachi is a traditional Mexican musical ensemble; flamenco, reggaeton, and tango come from other countries and regions."},{"p":"A chef simmers rice with saffron, seafood, and vegetables in a wide, shallow pan. This famous dish comes from the Valencia region of which country?","a":"Spain","w":["Mexico","Cuba","Argentina"],"h":"The dish is paella, and its home is on the Mediterranean coast.","e":"Paella is a signature dish of Spain, especially Valencia; its saffron-colored rice cooked in a wide pan is iconic Spanish cuisine."},{"p":"An ancient Incan city sits high in the Andes mountains, drawing hikers from around the world. In which country is Machu Picchu located?","a":"Peru","w":["Bolivia","Ecuador","Chile"],"h":"This country's capital is Lima, and the Inca Empire was centered near Cusco.","e":"Machu Picchu is in Peru, built by the Inca civilization; it is one of the New Seven Wonders of the World."},{"p":"Stretching more than 7,000 km down the western edge of South America is the world's longest continental mountain range. What is it called?","a":"The Andes","w":["The Rockies","The Sierra Madre","The Pyrenees"],"h":"It runs through Peru, Chile, and Argentina along the Pacific side of the continent.","e":"The Andes is the longest mountain range on land, running down western South America; the Rockies are in North America and the Pyrenees are in Europe."},{"p":"Most of Latin America speaks Spanish, but one large country is the exception. In which South American country is Portuguese the official language?","a":"Brazil","w":["Colombia","Venezuela","Paraguay"],"h":"It is the biggest country in South America by both area and population.","e":"Brazil speaks Portuguese due to Portuguese colonization; the surrounding countries were colonized by Spain and speak Spanish."},{"p":"A traveler in Mexico buys a snack and needs to pay in the local currency. What money will she use?","a":"Peso","w":["Euro","Dollar","Real"],"h":"Several Spanish-speaking countries share the name of this currency.","e":"Mexico's currency is the peso; the euro is used in Spain, the U.S. uses the dollar, and Brazil uses the real."},{"p":"A tourist lands in Madrid and, because Spain uses the European Union's shared currency, exchanges her dollars for what money?","a":"Euro","w":["Peseta","Brazilian real","Colombian peso"],"h":"France, Germany, and Italy all use this same currency today.","e":"Spain adopted the euro in 2002, replacing its older currency, the peseta."},{"p":"A chain of volcanic islands off the mainland's coast, famous for giant tortoises and Darwin's studies of evolution. The Galapagos Islands are a province of which country?","a":"Ecuador","w":["Chile","Peru","Costa Rica"],"h":"The islands lie west of a mainland country named after the equator.","e":"The Galapagos Islands belong to Ecuador and sit about 1,000 km off its Pacific coast."},{"p":"A fast, upbeat dance music driven by accordion and drums that serves as the national genre of the Dominican Republic. What is it called?","a":"Merengue","w":["Tango","Flamenco","Cumbia"],"h":"It happens to share its name with a fluffy whipped egg-white dessert.","e":"Merengue is the national music and dance of the Dominican Republic."},{"p":"Read: 'Fresh raw fish is not cooked with heat but by soaking in lime juice, then tossed with onion, chili, and cilantro.' This seafood dish is a national favorite of which country?","a":"Peru","w":["Argentina","Spain","Bolivia"],"h":"Think of the South American country famous for its Pacific coast and Machu Picchu.","e":"Ceviche is a signature Peruvian dish where citrus acid, not heat, cures the raw fish."},{"p":"High in the Andes, straddling the border between Peru and Bolivia, lies the world's highest lake that large boats can still navigate. What is its name?","a":"Lake Titicaca","w":["Lake Maracaibo","Lake Nicaragua","Lake Poopo"],"h":"It sits on the shared border of two Andean countries.","e":"Lake Titicaca is known as the world's highest navigable lake, at about 3,800 m elevation."},{"p":"Read: 'Some weather stations here have never recorded a single drop of rain.' This desert along Chile's northern coast is often called the driest place on Earth. What is it?","a":"Atacama Desert","w":["Sonoran Desert","Patagonian Desert","Sahara Desert"],"h":"It lies in the same long, narrow country as Santiago.","e":"The Atacama Desert in Chile is the driest non-polar desert in the world."},{"p":"This capital city is known for classic 1950s cars, colorful colonial buildings, and lively music clubs on the largest island in the Caribbean. What city is it?","a":"Havana","w":["San Juan","Santo Domingo","Kingston"],"h":"It is the capital of the largest Caribbean island nation.","e":"Havana (La Habana) is the capital of Cuba, the Caribbean's largest island."},{"p":"In many Latin American cultures, a girl's 15th birthday is marked by a large party with a special gown, a formal dance, and a religious ceremony. What is this celebration called?","a":"Quinceanera","w":["Cumpleanos","Bautizo","Primera Comunion"],"h":"The name comes from the Spanish word for the number fifteen.","e":"A quinceanera celebrates a girl's coming of age at fifteen, a major milestone in many Hispanic cultures."},{"p":"Read: 'In Spain and much of Latin America, children leave out shoes on the night of January 5, hoping gifts appear by morning, brought not by Santa but by three visitors from the Nativity story.' What holiday is this?","a":"Dia de los Reyes Magos","w":["Nochebuena","Dia de la Candelaria","Dia de los Muertos"],"h":"Think of the wise men who followed a star to visit baby Jesus.","e":"Dia de los Reyes Magos (Three Kings Day / Epiphany) on January 6 is a major gift-giving day in Hispanic cultures."},{"p":"Read: 'Every August, thousands gather in the Spanish town of Bunol to hurl overripe tomatoes at one another in a giant, messy street battle.' What is this festival called?","a":"La Tomatina","w":["Las Fallas","La Feria de Abril","El Carnaval"],"h":"The festival's name comes from a common red kitchen ingredient.","e":"La Tomatina is an annual tomato-throwing festival held in Bunol, Spain."},{"p":"In Pamplona, Spain, daring runners sprint down narrow streets just ahead of charging bulls each July. This week-long festival is best known by what name?","a":"San Fermin","w":["La Tomatina","Semana Santa","Dia de la Hispanidad"],"h":"It is named for the city's patron saint, not for the animals themselves.","e":"The Festival of San Fermin in Pamplona features the famous encierro, or running of the bulls."},{"p":"A round, grilled cornmeal patty sliced open and stuffed with cheese, meat, or beans is an everyday staple in Venezuela and Colombia. What is it?","a":"Arepa","w":["Tortilla","Tamal","Empanada"],"h":"It is made from ground corn and shaped like a thick, round disc.","e":"The arepa is a cornmeal cake central to Venezuelan and Colombian cuisine."},{"p":"Puerto Rico is a territory of the United States, so shoppers strolling through Old San Juan pay for souvenirs with which currency?","a":"US dollar","w":["Puerto Rican peso","Euro","Mexican peso"],"h":"Think about which country Puerto Rico belongs to politically.","e":"As a US territory, Puerto Rico uses the US dollar as its official currency."},{"p":"A famous stepped pyramid called El Castillo rises from the jungle of Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula. Which ancient civilization built the city of Chichen Itza?","a":"Maya","w":["Aztec","Inca","Olmec"],"h":"This culture thrived in the Yucatan and Central America, far from central Mexico.","e":"The Maya built Chichen Itza; the Aztecs ruled near modern Mexico City and the Inca lived in the Andes."},{"p":"Read: 'Born from Cuban son and Puerto Rican rhythms, this dance music was popularized by Caribbean communities in New York City in the 1960s and 70s.' What genre is it?","a":"Salsa","w":["Reggaeton","Bachata","Mariachi"],"h":"It happens to share its name with a spicy sauce found on many tables.","e":"Salsa music blends Afro-Cuban and Puerto Rican styles and grew popular in New York."},{"p":"Bolivia is unusual for having two capital cities. Which one serves as its seat of government, home to the president and congress high in the Andes?","a":"La Paz","w":["Sucre","Santa Cruz","Cochabamba"],"h":"It is one of the highest-altitude government seats in the world.","e":"La Paz is Bolivia's administrative capital and seat of government, while Sucre is the constitutional capital."},{"p":"Ecuador takes its very name from the equator that crosses it. Which capital city sits in the Andes almost exactly on that imaginary line?","a":"Quito","w":["Guayaquil","Cuenca","Bogota"],"h":"The country's name is a strong clue to where this city sits on the globe.","e":"Quito, Ecuador's capital, lies at nearly 0 degrees latitude, right on the equator."},{"p":"Read: 'Just before midnight on September 15, Mexico's president rings a bell and shouts Viva Mexico! as huge crowds cheer.' This marks the eve of which holiday, which many people confuse with a May celebration?","a":"Mexican Independence Day","w":["Cinco de Mayo","Dia de los Muertos","Dia de la Raza"],"h":"It celebrates freedom from Spanish rule, not a single battle in May.","e":"Mexican Independence Day (Sept 16) marks the 1810 start of independence from Spain and is often confused with Cinco de Mayo."},{"p":"Read: 'This waterfall plunges nearly 1,000 meters off the edge of a flat-topped mountain in a remote jungle, making it the tallest uninterrupted waterfall on Earth.' In which country would you find Angel Falls?","a":"Venezuela","w":["Colombia","Peru","Panama"],"h":"Think of the northern South American country whose coast faces the Caribbean, east of Colombia.","e":"Angel Falls (Salto Angel) is located in Venezuela and is the world's highest waterfall."},{"p":"A network of hundreds of thundering waterfalls sits on the border between Argentina and one of its neighbors. Iguazu Falls is shared between Argentina and which country?","a":"Brazil","w":["Chile","Bolivia","Uruguay"],"h":"The falls are on Argentina's northeastern border, next to the largest country in South America.","e":"Iguazu Falls straddles the border of Argentina and Brazil, in the tropical northeast."},{"p":"Read: 'The world's largest salt flat, stretching over 10,000 square kilometers, turns into a giant mirror when a thin layer of water covers it after rain.' The Salar de Uyuni is a famous attraction in which country?","a":"Bolivia","w":["Chile","Peru","Paraguay"],"h":"This landlocked Andean country also shares Lake Titicaca with Peru.","e":"The Salar de Uyuni, in Bolivia, is the largest salt flat in the world."},{"p":"A cargo ship saves thousands of kilometers by cutting through the Panama Canal instead of sailing all the way around South America. Which two oceans does the canal connect?","a":"The Atlantic and the Pacific","w":["The Pacific and the Indian","The Atlantic and the Arctic","The Indian and the Arctic"],"h":"Think of the oceans on either side of the narrow strip of land linking North and South America.","e":"The Panama Canal links the Atlantic Ocean (via the Caribbean) and the Pacific Ocean across the Isthmus of Panama."},{"p":"This folk music and dance style, blending African drums and Indigenous flutes, was born on the Caribbean coast of Colombia before spreading across Latin America. What is it called?","a":"Cumbia","w":["Bachata","Merengue","Reggaeton"],"h":"Its name starts with the same sound as 'Colombia,' where it originated.","e":"Cumbia is a traditional music and dance genre that originated in Colombia."},{"p":"Read: 'Driven by the dembow beat and Spanish-language rap and singing, this genre exploded out of Puerto Rico in the 1990s and now tops charts worldwide.' What is it called?","a":"Reggaeton","w":["Salsa","Cumbia","Flamenco"],"h":"This modern genre grew from reggae and hip-hop rhythms on a Caribbean island.","e":"Reggaeton is a music genre that developed in Puerto Rico in the 1990s and became a global pop force."},{"p":"A thick corn cake stuffed with cheese or beans, cooked on a griddle and served with curtido (pickled cabbage), is the beloved national dish of which country?","a":"El Salvador","w":["Guatemala","Honduras","Nicaragua"],"h":"This dish is the pupusa, from the smallest country in Central America.","e":"Pupusas are the national dish of El Salvador."},{"p":"In Spain, if you order a 'tortilla espanola,' what dish will arrive at your table?","a":"A thick omelet made with eggs and potatoes","w":["A thin corn flatbread for making tacos","A sweet pastry filled with custard","A spicy stew of tomatoes and peppers"],"h":"In Spain, the word 'tortilla' means something very different from what it means in Mexico.","e":"A tortilla espanola is a Spanish omelet made of eggs and potatoes, unlike the Mexican corn tortilla."},{"p":"A popular Spanish snack is a fried dough stick, often dusted with sugar and dipped into a cup of thick hot chocolate. What is this fried treat called?","a":"Churros","w":["Empanadas","Tamales","Arepas"],"h":"These crispy, ridged sticks are usually eaten for breakfast or an afternoon merienda.","e":"Churros are fried dough pastries popular in Spain and Latin America, often served with hot chocolate."},{"p":"Read: 'This dish is made by spreading masa (corn dough) with a savory or sweet filling, wrapping it in a corn husk or banana leaf, and steaming it until firm.' What is it called?","a":"Tamales","w":["Enchiladas","Quesadillas","Tostadas"],"h":"You unwrap the husk before eating; it is a holiday favorite across Mexico and Central America.","e":"Tamales are steamed corn-dough parcels wrapped in husks or leaves, a staple of Mesoamerican cuisine."},{"p":"A rich, dark Mexican sauce famously combines dried chiles with a small amount of chocolate and many spices, and is often served over chicken. What is this sauce called?","a":"Mole","w":["Salsa verde","Guacamole","Chimichurri"],"h":"This complex sauce from Puebla and Oaxaca can contain dozens of ingredients.","e":"Mole is a traditional Mexican sauce that blends chiles, spices, and often chocolate."},{"p":"Read: 'Each June in Cusco, Peru, costumed performers reenact an ancient Inca ceremony honoring the sun god Inti with processions, music, and offerings.' What is this festival called?","a":"Inti Raymi","w":["Dia de los Muertos","La Tomatina","Semana Santa"],"h":"Its name comes from the Quechua language and means 'Festival of the Sun.'","e":"Inti Raymi is an Inca-rooted festival celebrating the sun god, held every winter solstice in Cusco, Peru."},{"p":"Read: 'Each March, the Spanish city of Valencia fills with giant papier-mache figures that are paraded, judged, and then set ablaze in enormous nighttime bonfires.' What is this festival called?","a":"Las Fallas","w":["La Tomatina","San Fermin","Feria de Abril"],"h":"Fire and burning sculptures are the highlight of this Valencian celebration.","e":"Las Fallas is a Valencian festival famous for building and then burning large satirical sculptures."},{"p":"Read: 'Mexico City was built on top of the ruins of Tenochtitlan, a great island capital in the middle of a lake, founded around the year 1325.' Which civilization built Tenochtitlan?","a":"The Aztecs","w":["The Maya","The Inca","The Olmec"],"h":"This empire's capital sat where Mexico City stands today, in central Mexico.","e":"Tenochtitlan was the capital of the Aztec (Mexica) Empire, on whose ruins modern Mexico City was built."},{"p":"Giant drawings of animals and shapes etched into a desert plateau, so large they are best seen from the air, are a mystery left by an ancient culture in southern Peru. What are they called?","a":"The Nazca Lines","w":["The Maya glyphs","The Inca terraces","The Easter Island statues"],"h":"These enormous geoglyphs were scratched into the dry ground of coastal Peru long ago.","e":"The Nazca Lines are ancient geoglyphs in the Peruvian desert, created by the Nazca culture."},{"p":"A traveler in Guatemala reads a menu priced in the national currency, which is named after the country's brilliantly colored national bird. What is this money called?","a":"The quetzal","w":["The lempira","The cordoba","The colon"],"h":"Its name matches a famous green-and-red tropical bird sacred to the ancient Maya.","e":"Guatemala's currency is the quetzal, named for its national bird."},{"p":"A student exchanges 20 US dollars and receives 400 Mexican pesos, meaning 1 dollar equals 20 pesos. If a souvenir is priced at 100 pesos, how much is that in US dollars?","a":"5 dollars","w":["10 dollars","20 dollars","2 dollars"],"h":"Since 20 pesos make 1 dollar, divide the peso price by 20.","e":"At 20 pesos per dollar, 100 pesos divided by 20 equals 5 dollars; this is unit-rate currency conversion."},{"p":"Surprising many visitors, the country of Panama uses the US dollar as its everyday paper money, alongside its own coins called the balboa. If you fly from Miami to Panama City, what paper bills can you keep spending?","a":"US dollars","w":["Euros","Mexican pesos","Colombian pesos"],"h":"Panama does not print its own paper bills and relies on a familiar North American currency.","e":"Panama uses the US dollar as legal tender for paper money, minting only its own balboa coins."}],"m.8.prealgebra":[{"p":"The temperature at midnight was -4°F. By dawn it had dropped another 7°F. What was the temperature at dawn?","a":"-11°F","w":["3°F","-3°F","11°F"],"h":"A drop in temperature moves you further down the number line, away from zero on the negative side.","e":"Dropping 7 from -4 means -4 - 7 = -11. Adding a negative (or subtracting) moves left on the number line."},{"p":"Your bank account is overdrawn, showing a balance of -$8. You then deposit $20. What is your new balance?","a":"$12","w":["-$12","$28","-$28"],"h":"A deposit adds money; think about where -8 lands after you move 20 units in the positive direction.","e":"Adding integers with different signs: -8 + 20 = 12. The positive amount is larger, so the result is positive."},{"p":"Evaluate using order of operations: 3 + 4 × 2","a":"11","w":["14","24","9"],"h":"PEMDAS says multiplication happens before addition, no matter the left-to-right order.","e":"Multiply first: 4 × 2 = 8, then 3 + 8 = 11. Doing addition first is the classic PEMDAS error."},{"p":"Evaluate using order of operations: 12 ÷ (1 + 2) + 5","a":"9","w":["19","15","4"],"h":"Handle what is inside the parentheses first, then division, then addition.","e":"Parentheses first: 1 + 2 = 3, then 12 ÷ 3 = 4, then 4 + 5 = 9. Grouping symbols take top priority in PEMDAS."},{"p":"Evaluate the expression 3x - 5 when x = 4.","a":"7","w":["2","12","17"],"h":"Substitute the value in for x, then follow order of operations to finish.","e":"Replace x with 4: 3(4) - 5 = 12 - 5 = 7. Multiplication comes before subtraction."},{"p":"Which expression represents '5 less than a number n'?","a":"n - 5","w":["5 - n","5n","n + 5"],"h":"'Less than' means you start with the number and take an amount away; watch the order carefully.","e":"'5 less than n' means n - 5. Writing 5 - n reverses the order, a common wording mistake."},{"p":"Solve for x: x + 9 = 15","a":"6","w":["24","7","-6"],"h":"To undo adding 9, do the opposite operation to both sides of the equation.","e":"Subtract 9 from both sides: x = 15 - 9 = 6. Adding instead of subtracting gives the wrong result."},{"p":"Solve for x: 4x = 32","a":"8","w":["28","128","36"],"h":"The 4 is multiplying x, so use the inverse operation to isolate x.","e":"Divide both sides by 4: x = 32 ÷ 4 = 8. Subtracting 4 instead of dividing is the misconception here."},{"p":"Solve for x: 2x + 3 = 11","a":"4","w":["7","5","28"],"h":"Undo the addition first, then undo the multiplication; reverse the order of operations.","e":"Subtract 3: 2x = 8, then divide by 2: x = 4. Dividing before subtracting the 3 leads to errors."},{"p":"Solve for x: x/3 - 2 = 4","a":"18","w":["6","14","2"],"h":"First move the -2 to the other side, then undo the division by 3.","e":"Add 2: x/3 = 6, then multiply by 3: x = 18. Forgetting to multiply back by 3 gives 6."},{"p":"A muffin recipe uses 2 cups of flour for every 3 cups of sugar. If you use 6 cups of flour, how many cups of sugar keep the same ratio?","a":"9 cups","w":["7 cups","6 cups","4 cups"],"h":"Find what you multiplied the flour by, then apply that same factor to the sugar.","e":"Flour tripled (2 to 6), so sugar triples: 3 × 3 = 9. Adding 4 to both (additive thinking) breaks the ratio."},{"p":"A car travels 60 miles in 2 hours at a steady speed. What is its speed as a unit rate?","a":"30 miles per hour","w":["120 miles per hour","15 miles per hour","62 miles per hour"],"h":"A unit rate tells the distance for exactly one hour, so divide to get 'per one hour'.","e":"Unit rate: 60 ÷ 2 = 30 miles per hour. Multiplying instead of dividing gives 120."},{"p":"What is 25% of 80?","a":"20","w":["40","25","16"],"h":"25% is the same as one quarter; think about dividing the whole into four equal parts.","e":"25% of 80 = 0.25 × 80 = 20. Confusing 25% with one half gives the incorrect 40."},{"p":"15 is what percent of 60?","a":"25%","w":["45%","15%","4%"],"h":"Compare the part to the whole as a fraction, then convert that fraction to a percent.","e":"15/60 = 1/4 = 25%. Dividing the whole by the part (60 ÷ 15 = 4) produces the wrong 4%."},{"p":"In which quadrant of the coordinate plane is the point (-3, 2) located?","a":"Quadrant II","w":["Quadrant I","Quadrant III","Quadrant IV"],"h":"Check the signs: negative x and positive y point you to a specific corner. Quadrants count counterclockwise from top right.","e":"A negative x with a positive y places a point in Quadrant II, the upper-left region."},{"p":"Which of these points lies exactly on the x-axis?","a":"(4, 0)","w":["(0, 4)","(2, 3)","(-1, -1)"],"h":"A point on the x-axis has not moved up or down at all; think about which coordinate must be zero.","e":"Points on the x-axis have a y-coordinate of 0, so (4, 0) qualifies. (0, 4) sits on the y-axis instead."},{"p":"Evaluate: -6 - (-9)","a":"3","w":["-15","-3","15"],"h":"Subtracting a negative is the same as adding its positive; rewrite the double sign first.","e":"-6 - (-9) = -6 + 9 = 3. Treating it as -6 - 9 = -15 misses that two negatives make a plus."},{"p":"A scuba diver descends at a steady rate of 5 feet per minute for 4 minutes, starting from the surface (0 ft). Using integers, what is her depth after 4 minutes?","a":"-20 feet","w":["20 feet","-9 feet","-1 foot"],"h":"Descending means the depth is below zero. Think about repeated addition of a negative rate.","e":"Multiplying a negative rate by a positive time gives a negative product: -5 x 4 = -20 feet. This models integer multiplication as repeated change."},{"p":"A mountain peak sits at an elevation of 320 feet, and a nearby valley floor sits at -80 feet (below sea level). What is the difference in elevation between the peak and the valley?","a":"400 feet","w":["240 feet","-400 feet","-240 feet"],"h":"Difference means subtract. Be careful: subtracting a negative number is the same as adding.","e":"The difference is 320 - (-80) = 320 + 80 = 400 feet. Subtracting a negative integer increases the result."},{"p":"Evaluate using order of operations: 2 + 3² × 2","a":"20","w":["50","22","14"],"h":"Follow PEMDAS: handle the exponent first, then multiplication, then addition.","e":"3² = 9, then 9 × 2 = 18, then 2 + 18 = 20. Exponents come before multiplication, which comes before addition."},{"p":"Evaluate using order of operations: 20 - 2 × (3 + 4)","a":"6","w":["126","10","14"],"h":"Do the parentheses first, then multiply before you subtract.","e":"Parentheses give 7, then 2 × 7 = 14, then 20 - 14 = 6. Multiplication is done before subtraction."},{"p":"Evaluate the expression 3x + 2y when x = -2 and y = 5.","a":"4","w":["16","-16","-4"],"h":"Substitute the values carefully and keep track of the negative sign on x.","e":"3(-2) + 2(5) = -6 + 10 = 4. Substituting a negative value and combining the signed terms gives the result."},{"p":"Which expression represents 'the quotient of a number x and 4, decreased by 7'?","a":"x/4 - 7","w":["4/x - 7","x/(4 - 7)","7 - x/4"],"h":"'Quotient of x and 4' names which number is divided by which, and 'decreased by' tells you what to subtract at the end.","e":"The quotient of x and 4 is x/4, and decreasing it by 7 gives x/4 - 7. Order matters when translating words to symbols."},{"p":"Solve for x: x - 7 = -3","a":"4","w":["-10","10","-4"],"h":"Undo the subtraction by adding 7 to both sides. Watch the signs.","e":"Adding 7 to both sides gives x = -3 + 7 = 4. This is a one-step equation solved by the inverse operation."},{"p":"Solve for x: 4x - 5 = -17","a":"-3","w":["3","-12","-5.5"],"h":"First add 5 to both sides to isolate the 4x term, then divide.","e":"Add 5 to get 4x = -12, then divide by 4 to get x = -3. Undo addition/subtraction before undoing multiplication."},{"p":"Solve for x: x/5 + 2 = 6","a":"20","w":["40","4","0.8"],"h":"Subtract 2 from both sides first, then undo the division by multiplying.","e":"Subtracting 2 gives x/5 = 4, then multiplying both sides by 5 gives x = 20. Reverse the operations in the opposite order of PEMDAS."},{"p":"A paint mix uses 3 parts blue to 5 parts white. To make 40 cups of this mix, how many cups of white paint are needed?","a":"25 cups","w":["15 cups","24 cups","20 cups"],"h":"First find how many total parts are in one batch, then find the value of a single part before scaling white.","e":"There are 3 + 5 = 8 parts total, so each part is 40 ÷ 8 = 5 cups, and white is 5 × 5 = 25 cups. This uses ratio parts to divide a total."},{"p":"A store sells 4 notebooks for $6.00. At this rate, what is the cost of a single notebook (the unit rate)?","a":"$1.50","w":["$0.67","$2.00","$24.00"],"h":"A unit rate is the cost for exactly one item. Decide which number to divide by which.","e":"Dividing total cost by quantity gives 6.00 ÷ 4 = $1.50 per notebook. A unit rate compares an amount to one unit."},{"p":"A dinner bill is $40.00, and you want to leave an 18% tip. How much money is the tip?","a":"$7.20","w":["$72.00","$0.72","$18.00"],"h":"Convert the percent to a decimal before multiplying, and check that your decimal point lands in a sensible place.","e":"18% = 0.18, and 0.18 × 40 = $7.20. Finding a percent of a number means multiplying by its decimal form."},{"p":"A basketball player made 18 of her 24 free throws this season. What percent of her free throws did she make?","a":"75%","w":["133%","25%","6%"],"h":"Write the made shots as a fraction of the total attempts, then convert that fraction to a percent.","e":"18 ÷ 24 = 0.75, which is 75%. A part-to-whole percent divides the part by the total, not the other way around."},{"p":"A jacket normally costs $60 and is on sale for 25% off. What is the sale price?","a":"$45","w":["$15","$35","$75"],"h":"First find the dollar amount of the discount, then subtract it from the original price.","e":"25% of $60 is $15, and $60 - $15 = $45. The discount is a percent of the price, and you subtract it to get the sale price."},{"p":"In which quadrant of the coordinate plane is the point (-5, -2) located?","a":"Quadrant III","w":["Quadrant II","Quadrant IV","Quadrant I"],"h":"Check the sign of each coordinate: the x-value tells you left or right, the y-value tells you up or down.","e":"Both coordinates are negative, which places the point in the lower-left region, Quadrant III."},{"p":"The point (4, -3) is reflected across the x-axis. What are the coordinates of its image?","a":"(4, 3)","w":["(-4, -3)","(-4, 3)","(-3, 4)"],"h":"Reflecting across the x-axis flips a point up or down. Decide which coordinate changes sign.","e":"A reflection across the x-axis keeps x the same and negates y, so (4, -3) becomes (4, 3)."},{"p":"Evaluate: -36 ÷ (-4)","a":"9","w":["-9","-40","-32"],"h":"Think about the rule for the sign when you divide two numbers that have the same sign.","e":"A negative divided by a negative is positive, so -36 ÷ (-4) = 9. Same-sign division yields a positive quotient."},{"p":"Evaluate using order of operations: -2 + 6 ÷ 2 × 3","a":"7","w":["-1","6","11"],"h":"Multiplication and division have equal priority, so work them left to right before adding.","e":"Going left to right, 6 ÷ 2 = 3, then 3 × 3 = 9, then -2 + 9 = 7. Division and multiplication are done in order, not multiplication first."},{"p":"A gym charges a $6 late fee for each month a payment is missed. If Maria missed 3 monthly payments, which integer represents her total late fees?","a":"-$18","w":["-$9","-$2","$18"],"h":"Owing money is a negative amount, and a repeated charge means repeated addition of that negative.","e":"This is integer multiplication: a negative amount repeated 3 times is (-6) x 3 = -18, so a negative times a positive gives a negative."},{"p":"Evaluate using order of operations: (-3)² - 4 × 5","a":"-11","w":["-29","25","-45"],"h":"Handle the exponent first, then the multiplication, and do the subtraction last. Note the negative is inside the parentheses being squared.","e":"By PEMDAS, (-3)² = 9 and 4 × 5 = 20, so 9 - 20 = -11. Squaring a negative in parentheses gives a positive."},{"p":"Evaluate using order of operations: 4 × [3 + (10 - 6) ÷ 2]","a":"20","w":["28","14","8"],"h":"Work from the innermost parentheses outward, and remember division comes before addition inside the brackets.","e":"Using nested grouping: 10 - 6 = 4, then 4 ÷ 2 = 2, then 3 + 2 = 5, and finally 4 × 5 = 20."},{"p":"Solve for x: -3x + 7 = 1","a":"2","w":["-2","-3","3"],"h":"Undo the addition first, then divide by the coefficient. Watch the signs when you divide a negative by a negative.","e":"This is a two-step equation: subtract 7 to get -3x = -6, then divide by -3 to get x = 2 (a negative divided by a negative is positive)."},{"p":"Solve for x: 2(x + 4) = 18","a":"5","w":["7","9","11"],"h":"You can either distribute the 2 first or divide both sides by 2 first, but be consistent with every term.","e":"Dividing both sides by 2 gives x + 4 = 9, so x = 5. A common error is subtracting 4 before removing the factor of 2."},{"p":"A recipe for 12 cookies uses 2 eggs. Keeping the same ratio, how many eggs are needed to make 30 cookies?","a":"5 eggs","w":["4 eggs","6 eggs","3 eggs"],"h":"Set up equivalent ratios of eggs to cookies and find the scale factor between 12 and 30.","e":"This is a proportion: 2/12 = x/30, so x = 30 × 2 ÷ 12 = 5 eggs."},{"p":"A concert ticket cost $50 last year. This year the price increased by 20%. What is the new price?","a":"$60","w":["$70","$40","$10"],"h":"First find 20% of the original price, then decide whether to add it to or subtract it from $50.","e":"This is a percent increase: 20% of 50 is 10, and adding it gives 50 + 10 = 60."},{"p":"At a club meeting, 30% of the members present are 12 people. If everyone is present, how many members does the club have in total?","a":"40 members","w":["3.6 members","15 members","36 members"],"h":"Here 12 is the part and 30% is the percent — you are solving for the whole, so division is involved.","e":"This is finding the whole from a percent: 12 ÷ 0.30 = 40, since 30% of 40 is 12."},{"p":"On a grid map where each unit is 1 block, the library is at (2, 3) and the school is at (2, -4). How many blocks apart are they along the vertical line connecting them?","a":"7 blocks","w":["1 block","12 blocks","-7 blocks"],"h":"The points share the same x-coordinate, so find the distance between the y-values. Distance is never negative.","e":"Since the x-coordinates match, the distance is |3 - (-4)| = 7 blocks."},{"p":"The point (-2, 5) is translated 4 units right and 3 units down. What are the coordinates of its image?","a":"(2, 2)","w":["(2, 8)","(-6, 2)","(-6, 8)"],"h":"Moving right increases x, and moving down decreases y. Apply each change to the matching coordinate.","e":"Translating on the coordinate plane: x goes from -2 to -2 + 4 = 2, and y goes from 5 to 5 - 3 = 2, giving (2, 2)."},{"p":"A diver is 40 feet below the surface (-40 ft). She rises 15 feet, then descends 22 feet. What is her new depth relative to the surface?","a":"-47 feet","w":["-3 feet","-77 feet","-25 feet"],"h":"Rising makes the depth value larger (less negative); descending makes it smaller (more negative). Do the steps in order.","e":"Adding and subtracting integers: -40 + 15 = -25, then -25 - 22 = -47 feet."},{"p":"A taxi charges a $3 flat fee plus $2 for each mile driven. Which expression gives the total cost for m miles?","a":"2m + 3","w":["3m + 2","5m","6m"],"h":"The per-mile charge depends on how many miles you drive, but the flat fee is charged only once.","e":"Writing an algebraic expression: the variable cost is 2m and the constant fee is 3, giving 2m + 3."},{"p":"Evaluate the expression x² - 2x when x = -3.","a":"15","w":["3","-3","-15"],"h":"Substitute -3 carefully everywhere, and remember that squaring a negative and multiplying by a negative both affect the sign.","e":"Evaluating with a negative value: (-3)² = 9 and -2(-3) = 6, so 9 + 6 = 15."},{"p":"Evaluate using order of operations: 18 ÷ 3 - 2 × 4","a":"-2","w":["16","4","-8"],"h":"Division and multiplication happen before subtraction — not simply left to right across the whole line.","e":"By PEMDAS, 18 ÷ 3 = 6 and 2 × 4 = 8, so 6 - 8 = -2. Working strictly left to right is the common mistake."},{"p":"A 12-ounce bottle of juice costs $3.00, and a 20-ounce bottle costs $4.00. Which is the better buy, based on cost per ounce?","a":"The 20-ounce bottle, at about $0.20 per ounce","w":["The 12-ounce bottle, at about $0.25 per ounce","The 20-ounce bottle, at about $0.33 per ounce","They are equal, both at about $0.25 per ounce"],"h":"Find each bottle's unit rate by dividing its price by its number of ounces, then compare.","e":"Using unit rates: $3.00 ÷ 12 = $0.25/oz and $4.00 ÷ 20 = $0.20/oz, so the 20-ounce bottle costs less per ounce."},{"p":"A $80 pair of shoes is marked 25% off. Then 8% sales tax is added to the sale price. What is the final cost?","a":"$64.80","w":["$60.00","$66.40","$86.40"],"h":"Take the discount first to find the sale price, then apply the tax to that reduced amount, not the original price.","e":"Multi-step percents: 25% off $80 gives a $60 sale price, and 8% tax on $60 adds $4.80 for a total of $64.80."},{"p":"A point has a negative x-coordinate and a y-coordinate of 0. Where is this point located?","a":"On the x-axis, to the left of the origin","w":["In Quadrant II","In Quadrant III","On the y-axis, below the origin"],"h":"A y-coordinate of 0 means the point sits on one of the axes — decide which axis, then use the sign of x for direction.","e":"Points with y = 0 lie on the x-axis; a negative x places it to the left of the origin, not in any quadrant."},{"p":"Read: \"A phone plan costs $15 per month plus $0.10 for each text message. Devon's bill for the month was $23.\" How many text messages t did Devon send?","a":"80 texts","w":["8 texts","380 texts","800 texts"],"h":"Write an equation like 15 + 0.10t = 23, then undo the flat fee before dividing by the per-text cost.","e":"Solving the two-step equation: 0.10t = 23 - 15 = 8, so t = 8 ÷ 0.10 = 80 texts."}],"sp.10.subjunctive":[{"p":"Mi madre quiere que yo ___ más despacio cuando estoy nervioso. (hablar)","a":"hable","w":["hablo","hablaré","hablé"],"h":"After 'querer que' with a change of subject, use the present subjunctive; form it from the 'yo' present-tense stem plus the opposite vowel.","e":"'Querer que' is a WEIRDO wish trigger; for -ar verbs the present subjunctive 'yo' ending is -e, giving 'hable'."},{"p":"Es necesario que nosotros ___ más verduras cada semana. (comer)","a":"comamos","w":["comemos","comeremos","comimos"],"h":"An impersonal expression like 'es necesario que' triggers the subjunctive; -er verbs take -a endings.","e":"Impersonal expressions of necessity trigger the subjunctive; -er/-ir verbs use -a endings, so the nosotros form is 'comamos'."},{"p":"Espero que tú ___ a la fiesta el sábado. (venir)","a":"vengas","w":["vienes","vendrás","viniste"],"h":"'Esperar que' expresses a wish; build the subjunctive from the irregular 'yo' present stem 'veng-'.","e":"'Esperar que' is a WEIRDO wish trigger; 'venir' keeps its irregular 'yo' stem (veng-) in the subjunctive: 'vengas'."},{"p":"Ojalá que ___ buen tiempo para el partido de mañana. (hacer)","a":"haga","w":["hace","hará","hizo"],"h":"'Ojalá' always triggers the subjunctive; use the irregular 'yo' stem 'hag-'.","e":"'Ojalá' is the 'O' in WEIRDO and always requires the subjunctive; 'hacer' uses stem 'hag-', giving 'haga'."},{"p":"Es importante que los estudiantes ___ un poco cada día. (estudiar)","a":"estudien","w":["estudian","estudiarán","estudiaron"],"h":"The impersonal expression triggers the subjunctive; -ar verbs take -e endings.","e":"'Es importante que' is an impersonal trigger; -ar verbs use -e endings, so the ellos form is 'estudien'."},{"p":"Dudo que ellos ___ razón sobre este tema. (tener)","a":"tengan","w":["tienen","tendrán","tuvieron"],"h":"'Dudar que' expresses doubt (the D in WEIRDO); use the irregular stem 'teng-'.","e":"'Dudar que' triggers the subjunctive under doubt; 'tener' uses stem 'teng-', giving 'tengan'."},{"p":"Me alegro de que tú ___ aquí con nosotros hoy. (estar)","a":"estés","w":["estás","estarás","estabas"],"h":"'Alegrarse de que' expresses emotion; 'estar' is irregular and carries a written accent in the subjunctive.","e":"'Alegrarse de que' is a WEIRDO emotion trigger; 'estar' is irregular with an accent: 'estés'."},{"p":"El médico recomienda que yo ___ ocho horas cada noche. (dormir)","a":"duerma","w":["duermo","dormiré","dormía"],"h":"'Recomendar que' gives a recommendation; the stem change o→ue appears in the 'yo' subjunctive.","e":"'Recomendar que' is a WEIRDO recommendation trigger; 'dormir' keeps its o→ue stem change, giving 'duerma'."},{"p":"Creo que mi vecino ___ una persona muy inteligente. (ser)","a":"es","w":["sea","fuera","sido"],"h":"An affirmative 'creer que' expresses certainty, not doubt, so it does NOT trigger the subjunctive.","e":"Affirmative 'creer que' states a belief held as fact and takes the indicative; the correct form is 'es'."},{"p":"No pienso que ella ___ a la reunión de esta tarde. (venir)","a":"venga","w":["viene","vendrá","vino"],"h":"Negating 'pensar que' introduces doubt, unlike its affirmative form; use the stem 'veng-'.","e":"'No pensar que' expresses doubt and triggers the subjunctive; 'venir' gives 'venga'."},{"p":"Es mejor que tú ___ al médico esta misma semana. (ir)","a":"vayas","w":["vas","irás","fuiste"],"h":"The impersonal expression triggers the subjunctive; 'ir' has the completely irregular stem 'vay-'.","e":"'Es mejor que' is an impersonal trigger; 'ir' uses the irregular subjunctive stem 'vay-', giving 'vayas'."},{"p":"Yo quiero ___ español con fluidez algún día. (hablar)","a":"hablar","w":["hable","hablo","que hable"],"h":"When the subject of 'querer' and the second verb are the same person, there is no 'que' clause.","e":"With no change of subject, the subjunctive is not triggered; the infinitive 'hablar' follows 'querer' directly."},{"p":"Ojalá que el profesor nos ___ más tiempo para el examen. (dar)","a":"dé","w":["da","dará","dio"],"h":"'Ojalá' triggers the subjunctive; the one-syllable form of 'dar' carries a written accent to distinguish it from the preposition.","e":"'Ojalá' requires the subjunctive; 'dar' becomes 'dé', accented to differ from 'de'."},{"p":"Es una lástima que él no ___ contento con el resultado. (estar)","a":"esté","w":["está","estará","estuvo"],"h":"'Es una lástima que' expresses emotion; 'estar' is irregular with a written accent.","e":"'Es una lástima que' is a WEIRDO emotion trigger; 'estar' gives the irregular, accented 'esté'."},{"p":"Mi jefe insiste en que yo ___ otra solución al problema. (buscar)","a":"busque","w":["busqué","busco","buscaré"],"h":"'Insistir en que' triggers the subjunctive; verbs ending in -car change c→qu before -e, and this form has no accent.","e":"An -car verb undergoes the c→qu spelling change in the subjunctive; the unaccented 'busque' differs from the preterite 'busqué'."},{"p":"Es necesario que nosotros ___ temprano al aeropuerto. (llegar)","a":"lleguemos","w":["llegamos","llegaremos","llegáramos"],"h":"The impersonal expression triggers the present subjunctive; -gar verbs add a 'u' (g→gu) before the ending.","e":"-gar verbs take a g→gu spelling change in the present subjunctive, giving 'lleguemos'."},{"p":"Temo que mi hermano ___ el tren de las ocho. (perder)","a":"pierda","w":["pierde","perderá","perdió"],"h":"'Temer que' expresses emotion/fear; the e→ie stem change appears in this present subjunctive form.","e":"'Temer que' is a WEIRDO emotion trigger; 'perder' keeps its e→ie stem change, giving 'pierda'."},{"p":"Es posible que ___ un examen sorpresa mañana. (haber)","a":"haya","w":["hay","habrá","hubo"],"h":"'Es posible que' expresses doubt/possibility; the subjunctive of the impersonal 'hay' uses the stem 'hay-'.","e":"'Es posible que' triggers the subjunctive; the impersonal 'haber' becomes 'haya'."},{"p":"El profesor sugiere que nosotros ___ ayuda cuando no entendemos algo en clase. (pedir)","a":"pidamos","w":["pedimos","pedamos","pidiéramos"],"h":"Un verbo de recomendación como 'sugerir que' activa el subjuntivo; recuerda que 'pedir' es un verbo -ir con cambio e→i que también afecta la forma de 'nosotros'.","e":"'Sugerir que' es un disparador de recomendación (la R de WEIRDO) que exige el presente de subjuntivo, y en los verbos -ir con cambio e→i la forma de nosotros sí cambia: pidamos."},{"p":"No dudo que ella ___ la verdad sobre lo que pasó ayer. (decir)","a":"dice","w":["diga","digas","dijera"],"h":"Fíjate en que el verbo principal está negado: 'no dudar' no expresa duda, sino certeza.","e":"Aunque 'dudar que' exige subjuntivo, al negarlo ('no dudo que') se afirma certeza, y las expresiones de certeza toman indicativo: dice."},{"p":"Es evidente que tú ___ razón en este asunto tan delicado. (tener)","a":"tienes","w":["tengas","tienas","tuvieras"],"h":"Piensa en si 'es evidente que' expresa duda o afirma un hecho como seguro.","e":"Las expresiones impersonales de certeza ('es evidente que', 'es verdad que') afirman un hecho y por eso toman indicativo, no subjuntivo: tienes."},{"p":"Ojalá que mis amigos ___ venir conmigo al concierto del viernes. (poder)","a":"puedan","w":["pueden","podan","pudieran"],"h":"'Ojalá que' siempre introduce un deseo; recuerda el cambio o→ue de 'poder' en el presente.","e":"'Ojalá' (la O de WEIRDO) expresa deseo y exige presente de subjuntivo; 'poder' mantiene el diptongo o→ue: puedan."},{"p":"Mi profesora quiere que yo ___ mejor a los autores del Siglo de Oro. (conocer)","a":"conozca","w":["conozco","conoca","conociera"],"h":"El subjuntivo se forma a partir de la raíz de la primera persona del presente ('yo conozco'); mira qué queda al quitar la -o.","e":"El presente de subjuntivo se construye sobre la raíz del 'yo' del presente indicativo (conozco → conozc-), dando la forma irregular conozca tras un verbo de deseo."},{"p":"Es importante que ustedes ___ de casa con tiempo para no perder el vuelo. (salir)","a":"salgan","w":["salen","salgen","salieran"],"h":"Es una expresión impersonal de necesidad; parte de la raíz irregular del 'yo' ('salgo').","e":"'Es importante que' es una expresión impersonal que exige subjuntivo, y 'salir' hereda la g de la primera persona (salgo → salg-): salgan."},{"p":"Nos sorprende que el equipo ___ tan bien a pesar de las lesiones. (jugar)","a":"juegue","w":["juega","juge","jugara"],"h":"Un verbo de emoción como 'sorprender' dispara el subjuntivo; recuerda el cambio u→ue de 'jugar'.","e":"'Sorprender que' expresa emoción (la E de WEIRDO) y exige subjuntivo; 'jugar' diptonga u→ue en las formas acentuadas: juegue."},{"p":"Más vale que tú ___ la verdad ahora antes de que sea demasiado tarde. (decir)","a":"digas","w":["dices","dijas","dijeras"],"h":"'Más vale que' funciona como una recomendación; parte de la raíz irregular del 'yo' ('digo').","e":"'Más vale que' es una expresión impersonal de recomendación que exige subjuntivo, formado sobre la raíz irregular de 'digo': digas."},{"p":"Read: \"Mis amigos insisten en que la nueva película de terror es fantástica, pero yo sigo sin estar convencido.\" No creo que la película ___ tan buena como todos dicen. (ser)","a":"sea","w":["es","seas","fuera"],"h":"El narrador niega su creencia; observa cómo 'no creer que' cambia la actitud hacia lo dicho.","e":"'No creer que' expresa duda o negación de la certeza (la D de WEIRDO) y exige presente de subjuntivo: sea."},{"p":"El entrenador insiste en que nosotros ___ practicando aunque estemos cansados. (seguir)","a":"sigamos","w":["seguimos","seguamos","siguiéramos"],"h":"'Insistir en que' impone una recomendación; 'seguir' es un verbo -ir con cambio e→i que afecta también a 'nosotros'.","e":"'Insistir en que' funciona como mandato indirecto y exige subjuntivo; en los verbos -ir con cambio e→i la forma de nosotros también cambia: sigamos."},{"p":"Es necesario que ella ___ todos los documentos firmados a la cita. (traer)","a":"traiga","w":["trae","traa","trajera"],"h":"Expresión impersonal de necesidad; parte de la raíz irregular del 'yo' ('traigo').","e":"'Es necesario que' exige subjuntivo, y 'traer' conserva la raíz irregular de 'traigo' (traig-): traiga."},{"p":"Es cierto que ellos ___ mucho talento para la música clásica. (tener)","a":"tienen","w":["tengan","tienan","tuvieran"],"h":"Decide si 'es cierto que' presenta un hecho seguro o algo dudoso.","e":"'Es cierto que' es una expresión impersonal de certeza que afirma un hecho, por lo que toma indicativo, no subjuntivo: tienen."},{"p":"El consejero académico me aconseja que ___ una carrera con salidas prácticas. (elegir)","a":"elija","w":["elijo","elige","eligiera"],"h":"'Aconsejar que' pide recomendación; 'elegir' combina el cambio e→i con el cambio ortográfico g→j.","e":"'Aconsejar que' es un disparador de recomendación que exige subjuntivo; 'elegir' cambia e→i y g→j ante 'a': elija."},{"p":"Me molesta mucho que mi hermano nunca ___ la puerta al salir de casa. (cerrar)","a":"cierre","w":["cierra","cerre","cerrara"],"h":"'Molestar que' expresa una reacción emocional; recuerda el cambio e→ie de 'cerrar'.","e":"'Molestar que' expresa emoción (la E de WEIRDO) y exige subjuntivo; 'cerrar' diptonga e→ie en la sílaba acentuada: cierre."},{"p":"Mis padres quieren que yo ___ buenas notas en todas las asignaturas este semestre. (sacar)","a":"saque","w":["saco","saqué","sacara"],"h":"'Querer que' con dos sujetos distintos pide subjuntivo; 'sacar' cambia c→qu para conservar el sonido /k/.","e":"'Querer que' es un disparador de deseo (la W de WEIRDO) que exige subjuntivo, y 'sacar' cambia c→qu ante 'e': saque."},{"p":"No es verdad que él ___ enfermo; solo está un poco cansado del viaje. (estar)","a":"esté","w":["está","estea","estuviera"],"h":"Observa que la expresión de certeza aparece negada; eso invierte el modo que normalmente exigiría.","e":"Negar una expresión de certeza ('no es verdad que') introduce duda y exige subjuntivo; 'estar' lleva tilde en la forma esté."},{"p":"Dudo mucho que el nuevo cajero ___ manejar el sistema informático sin ayuda. (saber)","a":"sepa","w":["sabe","sepe","saba"],"h":"El verbo saber tiene una raíz irregular en el presente de subjuntivo que no deriva de la forma 'yo' regular.","e":"Tras una expresión de duda ('Dudo que') se usa el subjuntivo (WEIRDO: doubt); saber es uno de los verbos totalmente irregulares (sep-)."},{"p":"Ojalá que la conferencia ___ puntualmente para que podamos irnos a tiempo. (empezar)","a":"empiece","w":["empieza","empieze","empeze"],"h":"Este verbo cambia la raíz e→ie y, además, la -z- delante de -e debe ajustarse ortográficamente.","e":"'Ojalá que' siempre exige subjuntivo; empezar combina el cambio de raíz e→ie con el cambio ortográfico z→c ante -e (empiece)."},{"p":"Es fundamental que nosotros ___ los bosques de la tala ilegal. (proteger)","a":"protejamos","w":["protegemos","protejemos","protegamos"],"h":"Parte de la forma 'yo' (protejo) para hallar la raíz del subjuntivo.","e":"La expresión impersonal 'Es fundamental que' activa el subjuntivo; los verbos en -ger cambian g→j ante -a (protejamos)."},{"p":"A mis padres les preocupa que yo ___ tan rápido por la autopista. (conducir)","a":"conduzca","w":["conduzco","conduce","condusca"],"h":"La forma 'yo' del presente (conduzco) marca la raíz irregular -zc-.","e":"Un verbo de emoción ('les preocupa que') exige subjuntivo; los verbos en -ducir mantienen la raíz -zc- de la forma 'yo' (conduzca)."},{"p":"El chef exige que el camarero ___ los platos en cuanto salgan de la cocina. (servir)","a":"sirva","w":["sirve","serva","sierva"],"h":"Es un verbo -ir que cambia e→i en todas las personas del subjuntivo.","e":"El verbo de mandato/recomendación 'exige que' pide subjuntivo; servir es un verbo -ir con cambio de raíz e→i (sirva)."},{"p":"Es poco probable que los invitados ___ antes de que termine la tormenta. (volver)","a":"vuelvan","w":["vuelven","volvan","vuelvon"],"h":"Aplica el cambio de raíz o→ue y la terminación propia de los verbos en -er.","e":"'Es poco probable que' expresa duda y exige subjuntivo; volver cambia o→ue en las formas acentuadas en la raíz (vuelvan)."},{"p":"Es natural que nosotros nos ___ nerviosos antes de un examen tan importante. (sentir)","a":"sintamos","w":["sentimos","sentamos","sientamos"],"h":"En la forma 'nosotros', los verbos -ir con cambio e→ie sufren en su lugar un cambio e→i.","e":"La expresión impersonal 'Es natural que' pide subjuntivo; en 'nosotros/vosotros' los verbos -ir tipo sentir cambian e→i, no e→ie (sintamos)."},{"p":"El contador aconseja que ustedes ___ los impuestos antes del plazo límite. (pagar)","a":"paguen","w":["pagan","paguan","pagen"],"h":"Para conservar el sonido /g/ delante de -e hace falta añadir una letra.","e":"El verbo de consejo 'aconseja que' exige subjuntivo; los verbos en -gar añaden -u- ante -e para mantener el sonido /g/ (paguen)."},{"p":"Es preciso que tú ___ todos los documentos en orden antes de la entrevista. (poner)","a":"pongas","w":["pones","pongues","ponas"],"h":"Parte de la forma 'yo' del presente (pongo) para obtener la raíz.","e":"La expresión impersonal de necesidad 'Es preciso que' activa el subjuntivo; poner conserva la raíz irregular -g- de la forma 'yo' (pongas)."},{"p":"Mi abuela prefiere que nosotros ___ todos juntos los domingos en su casa. (almorzar)","a":"almorcemos","w":["almuercemos","almorzemos","almorcamos"],"h":"En 'nosotros' no hay diptongo, pero la -z- ante -e sí cambia ortográficamente.","e":"'Prefiere que' expresa deseo y exige subjuntivo; almorzar no diptonga en 'nosotros' pero cambia z→c ante -e, con terminación -emos (almorcemos)."},{"p":"Está claro que nuestro equipo ___ el campeonato este año con ese nivel de juego. (ganar)","a":"gana","w":["gane","ganen","ganes"],"h":"Fíjate en si la expresión introductoria afirma una certeza o expresa una duda.","e":"Las expresiones de certeza como 'Está claro que' llevan indicativo, no subjuntivo; por eso se usa 'gana'."},{"p":"Read: \"Marta llevaba meses buscando trabajo y por fin la llamaron para una segunda entrevista.\" Me alegra mucho que ella por fin ___ una oportunidad tan buena. (conseguir)","a":"consiga","w":["consigue","consegue","consga"],"h":"Es un verbo -ir con cambio e→i; parte de la forma 'yo' (consigo).","e":"El verbo de emoción 'Me alegra que' exige subjuntivo; conseguir cambia e→i y pierde la -u- ortográfica (consiga)."},{"p":"El profesor quiere que los alumnos ___ una bibliografía completa al final del trabajo. (incluir)","a":"incluyan","w":["incluyen","incluigan","includan"],"h":"Los verbos terminados en -uir insertan una consonante antes de la terminación del subjuntivo.","e":"El verbo de deseo 'quiere que' exige subjuntivo; los verbos en -uir intercalan una -y- ante las vocales fuertes (incluyan)."},{"p":"Es difícil que ellos te ___ bien con tanto ruido de fondo en la sala. (oír)","a":"oigan","w":["oyen","oigen","oyan"],"h":"Parte de la forma 'yo' del presente (oigo), que muestra la raíz irregular -ig-.","e":"'Es difícil que' expresa improbabilidad y exige subjuntivo; oír conserva la raíz -ig- de la forma 'yo' (oigan)."},{"p":"El consejero sugiere que tú ___ las asignaturas según tus intereses reales. (escoger)","a":"escojas","w":["escoges","escojes","escogas"],"h":"Parte de la forma 'yo' (escojo); recuerda el cambio ortográfico de los verbos en -ger.","e":"El verbo de recomendación 'sugiere que' exige subjuntivo; los verbos en -ger cambian g→j ante -a (escojas)."},{"p":"Es importante que el profesor nos ___ de nuevo esa regla tan confusa. (explicar)","a":"explique","w":["explica","explice","expliquen"],"h":"La -c- delante de -e cambia de grafía para conservar el sonido /k/.","e":"La expresión impersonal 'Es importante que' activa el subjuntivo; los verbos en -car cambian c→qu ante -e (explique), concordando con el sujeto singular."},{"p":"Es una lástima que tantas especies ___ a causa de la deforestación acelerada. (morir)","a":"mueran","w":["mueren","muran","moran"],"h":"Aplica el cambio de raíz o→ue en las formas acentuadas en la raíz.","e":"El verbo de emoción 'Es una lástima que' exige subjuntivo; morir cambia o→ue en las personas cuya raíz es tónica (mueran)."}],"m.11.precalc":[{"p":"The parent function is f(x) = x². The transformed function is g(x) = x² − 4. Which statement describes the transformation from f to g?","a":"The graph shifts down 4 units.","w":["The graph shifts up 4 units.","The graph shifts left 4 units.","The graph shifts right 4 units."],"h":"A constant added or subtracted outside the function acts on the output values, not the input.","e":"For g(x) = f(x) + k, the graph translates vertically; here k = −4 produces a downward shift of 4 units."},{"p":"Starting from f(x) = x², a student writes g(x) = (x + 3)². Which transformation does this represent?","a":"The graph shifts left 3 units.","w":["The graph shifts right 3 units.","The graph shifts up 3 units.","The graph shifts down 3 units."],"h":"Changes inside the function affect the input, and they behave opposite to the sign shown.","e":"Replacing x with x + h gives a horizontal translation; x + 3 shifts the graph left 3 units."},{"p":"How does the graph of g(x) = −√x compare to the graph of f(x) = √x?","a":"It is a reflection across the x-axis.","w":["It is a reflection across the y-axis.","It is a reflection across the line y = x.","It is a reflection across the origin."],"h":"Ask whether the negative sign is applied to the output of the function or to its input.","e":"Negating the entire output, g(x) = −f(x), reflects the graph across the x-axis."},{"p":"What is the domain of the rational function f(x) = 1/(x − 5)?","a":"All real numbers except x = 5","w":["All real numbers except x = −5","All real numbers except x = 0","All real numbers"],"h":"A rational expression is undefined wherever its denominator equals zero.","e":"The denominator x − 5 equals zero at x = 5, so that value must be excluded from the domain."},{"p":"Where is the vertical asymptote of the rational function f(x) = (x + 2)/(x − 3)?","a":"Vertical asymptote at x = 3","w":["Vertical asymptote at x = −2","Vertical asymptote at x = 2","Vertical asymptote at x = −3"],"h":"Vertical asymptotes occur where the denominator is zero but the numerator is not.","e":"Setting the denominator x − 3 = 0 gives the vertical asymptote at x = 3."},{"p":"What is the horizontal asymptote of f(x) = (2x + 1)/(x − 4)?","a":"Horizontal asymptote at y = 2","w":["Horizontal asymptote at y = 0","Horizontal asymptote at y = 1/4","Horizontal asymptote at y = −4"],"h":"Compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator, then focus on the leading coefficients.","e":"When numerator and denominator have equal degree, the horizontal asymptote is the ratio of leading coefficients, 2/1 = 2."},{"p":"Solve the exponential equation 2^x = 32.","a":"x = 5","w":["x = 4","x = 6","x = 16"],"h":"Rewrite 32 as a power of the same base that appears on the left side.","e":"Since 32 = 2⁵, matching the equal bases gives x = 5."},{"p":"Evaluate log₂ 8.","a":"3","w":["2","4","16"],"h":"Ask what exponent turns the base 2 into the value 8.","e":"Because 2³ = 8, the logarithm log₂ 8 equals 3 by the definition of a logarithm."},{"p":"Which equation is the equivalent exponential form of log₃ 81 = 4?","a":"3⁴ = 81","w":["4³ = 81","81³ = 4","3⁸¹ = 4"],"h":"In log_b(y) = x, the base stays the base and the result of the log is the exponent.","e":"By definition, log_b(y) = x is equivalent to b^x = y, so log₃ 81 = 4 becomes 3⁴ = 81."},{"p":"Using the unit circle, what is the exact value of cos(π/3)?","a":"1/2","w":["√3/2","√2/2","1"],"h":"Locate the angle 60° on the unit circle and read its x-coordinate.","e":"The point on the unit circle at π/3 has x-coordinate 1/2, so cos(π/3) = 1/2."},{"p":"Using the unit circle, what is the exact value of tan(π/4)?","a":"1","w":["0","√3","√3/3"],"h":"Tangent is the ratio of the y-coordinate to the x-coordinate at that angle.","e":"At π/4 both coordinates equal √2/2, so tan(π/4) = (√2/2)/(√2/2) = 1."},{"p":"Which equation is the Pythagorean identity for all real angles θ?","a":"sin²θ + cos²θ = 1","w":["sin²θ − cos²θ = 1","1 + tan²θ = sin²θ","sin²θ + cos²θ = 2 sinθ cosθ"],"h":"This identity comes directly from the equation of the unit circle x² + y² = 1.","e":"Because cosθ and sinθ are the coordinates of a unit-circle point, sin²θ + cos²θ = 1."},{"p":"Which expression is equal to sec θ?","a":"1/cosθ","w":["1/sinθ","cosθ/sinθ","sinθ/cosθ"],"h":"Secant is defined as the reciprocal of one of the basic trigonometric functions.","e":"By the reciprocal identities, sec θ is defined as 1/cos θ."},{"p":"An arithmetic sequence has first term a₁ = 3 and common difference d = 5. What is the 10th term, a₁₀?","a":"48","w":["53","43","50"],"h":"Use the explicit formula and remember how many differences separate the 1st and 10th terms.","e":"With aₙ = a₁ + (n − 1)d, a₁₀ = 3 + (9)(5) = 48."},{"p":"A geometric sequence has first term a₁ = 2 and common ratio r = 3. What is the 4th term, a₄?","a":"54","w":["162","18","24"],"h":"Use the explicit formula and count how many times the ratio is applied to reach the 4th term.","e":"With aₙ = a₁·r^(n−1), a₄ = 2·3³ = 54."},{"p":"Find the sum of the first 5 terms of the arithmetic series with a₁ = 2 and common difference d = 3.","a":"40","w":["50","35","30"],"h":"First find the 5th term, then average the first and last terms and multiply by the count.","e":"The terms are 2, 5, 8, 11, 14; using Sₙ = n/2(a₁ + aₙ) gives 5/2(2 + 14) = 40."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit lim (x→3) (x² − 9)/(x − 3).","a":"6","w":["0","3","The limit does not exist"],"h":"Direct substitution gives 0/0, so factor the numerator and simplify before substituting.","e":"Factoring gives (x − 3)(x + 3)/(x − 3) = x + 3; substituting x = 3 yields 6."},{"p":"Describe the end behavior of the polynomial f(x) = −2x³ + 4x − 1.","a":"As x→+∞, f(x)→−∞; as x→−∞, f(x)→+∞","w":["As x→+∞, f(x)→+∞; as x→−∞, f(x)→−∞","As x→+∞, f(x)→+∞; as x→−∞, f(x)→+∞","As x→+∞, f(x)→−∞; as x→−∞, f(x)→−∞"],"h":"End behavior is governed by the degree (odd or even) and the sign of the leading coefficient.","e":"An odd-degree polynomial with a negative leading coefficient falls on the right and rises on the left."},{"p":"The function g(x) = −(x − 2)² + 5 is a transformation of the parent function f(x) = x². Which sequence of transformations produces g from f?","a":"Shift right 2, reflect across the x-axis, shift up 5","w":["Shift left 2, reflect across the x-axis, shift up 5","Shift right 2, reflect across the y-axis, shift up 5","Shift right 2, reflect across the x-axis, shift down 5"],"h":"Read (x − 2) as a horizontal shift, the leading minus as a reflection, and the +5 as a vertical shift.","e":"By the order of transformations for f(x) = a(x − h)² + k, the −(x − 2)² reflects across the x-axis and shifts right 2, and +5 shifts up 5."},{"p":"The function g(x) = 2|x − 1| is a transformation of the parent function f(x) = |x|. Which description is correct?","a":"Shift right 1, then vertically stretch by a factor of 2","w":["Shift left 1, then vertically stretch by a factor of 2","Shift right 1, then horizontally stretch by a factor of 2","Shift right 2, then vertically stretch by a factor of 1"],"h":"The number inside the absolute value affects horizontal position; the factor outside scales vertically.","e":"For g(x) = a|x − h|, (x − 1) shifts the graph right 1 and the factor 2 vertically stretches it by 2."},{"p":"What is the horizontal asymptote of the rational function f(x) = (3x² + 1)/(x³ − x)?","a":"y = 0","w":["y = 3","y = 1","There is no horizontal asymptote"],"h":"Compare the degree of the numerator to the degree of the denominator.","e":"When the numerator degree (2) is less than the denominator degree (3), the horizontal asymptote is y = 0."},{"p":"Which statement best describes the graph of f(x) = (x² − 1)/(x − 1)?","a":"The line y = x + 1 with a hole at (1, 2)","w":["The line y = x + 1 with a vertical asymptote at x = 1","The line y = x − 1 with a hole at (1, 0)","The line y = x + 1 with no discontinuity"],"h":"Factor the numerator and cancel the common factor with the denominator; note where the original was undefined.","e":"Since (x² − 1)/(x − 1) = x + 1 for x ≠ 1, the graph is the line y = x + 1 with a removable discontinuity (hole) at x = 1, where y would be 2."},{"p":"A radioactive sample has a half-life of 5 years. If 80 grams are present initially, how much remains after 15 years?","a":"10 grams","w":["20 grams","5 grams","26.7 grams"],"h":"Determine how many half-life periods fit into 15 years, then halve repeatedly.","e":"Using A = A₀(1/2)^(t/5), 15 years is 3 half-lives, so 80 × (1/2)³ = 10 grams."},{"p":"Written as a single logarithm, log 2 + log x − log 3 equals which expression?","a":"log(2x/3)","w":["log(2x − 3)","log(2 + x − 3)","log(6x)"],"h":"Sums of logs become products and differences become quotients inside one log.","e":"By the product and quotient laws of logarithms, log 2 + log x − log 3 = log(2x/3)."},{"p":"Solve for x: log₂(x) + log₂(x − 2) = 3.","a":"x = 4","w":["x = −2","x = 4 and x = −2","x = 8"],"h":"Condense the left side into one logarithm, rewrite in exponential form, then check each solution in the original equation.","e":"Combining gives log₂(x(x − 2)) = 3, so x² − 2x − 8 = 0 with roots 4 and −2; x = −2 is rejected because logarithms require positive arguments, leaving x = 4."},{"p":"Using the unit circle, what is the exact value of sin(5π/6)?","a":"1/2","w":["−1/2","√3/2","−√3/2"],"h":"Find the reference angle for 5π/6 and determine the sign of sine in the second quadrant.","e":"The reference angle is π/6 and sine is positive in Quadrant II, so sin(5π/6) = 1/2."},{"p":"Simplify the trigonometric expression (1 − cos²θ)/sin θ, assuming sin θ ≠ 0.","a":"sin θ","w":["cos θ","tan θ","sec θ"],"h":"Replace 1 − cos²θ using a Pythagorean identity before simplifying the fraction.","e":"Since 1 − cos²θ = sin²θ, the expression becomes sin²θ/sin θ = sin θ."},{"p":"Which angle is coterminal with a 30° angle in standard position?","a":"390°","w":["330°","210°","−30°"],"h":"Coterminal angles differ from the original by a whole number of full 360° rotations.","e":"Adding 360° to 30° gives 390°, which shares the same terminal side (coterminal angle)."},{"p":"Find the sum of the first 20 terms of the arithmetic series with first term a₁ = 4 and common difference d = 3.","a":"650","w":["610","1300","325"],"h":"Use Sₙ = (n/2)(2a₁ + (n − 1)d) with n = 20.","e":"Sₙ = (20/2)(2·4 + 19·3) = 10(8 + 57) = 650 by the arithmetic series sum formula."},{"p":"What is the sum of the infinite geometric series 8 + 4 + 2 + 1 + …?","a":"16","w":["8","32","The series diverges"],"h":"Identify the common ratio and confirm its absolute value is less than 1 before applying the sum formula.","e":"With a₁ = 8 and r = 1/2, the sum is S = a₁/(1 − r) = 8/(1 − 1/2) = 16."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit lim (x→0) (√(x + 4) − 2)/x.","a":"1/4","w":["0","1/2","The limit does not exist"],"h":"Multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the numerator to remove the indeterminate form.","e":"Rationalizing gives 1/(√(x + 4) + 2), which at x = 0 equals 1/4."},{"p":"For the polynomial f(x) = (x − 1)²(x + 3), how does the graph behave at x = 1?","a":"It touches the x-axis and turns around","w":["It crosses straight through the x-axis","It crosses the x-axis with a flattening (inflection)","It has a vertical asymptote"],"h":"Consider the multiplicity of the factor (x − 1) and whether it is even or odd.","e":"Because (x − 1) has even multiplicity (2), the graph touches the x-axis at x = 1 and turns around rather than crossing."},{"p":"If f(x) = (x − 3)/2, what is the inverse function f⁻¹(x)?","a":"f⁻¹(x) = 2x + 3","w":["f⁻¹(x) = 2x − 3","f⁻¹(x) = (x + 3)/2","f⁻¹(x) = 2/(x − 3)"],"h":"Swap x and y, then solve the resulting equation for y.","e":"Replacing f(x) with y, swapping variables, and solving x = (y − 3)/2 gives y = 2x + 3, the inverse function."},{"p":"What is the domain of the function f(x) = log(x − 4)?","a":"x > 4","w":["x ≥ 4","x < 4","x ≠ 4"],"h":"The argument of a logarithm must be strictly greater than zero.","e":"Requiring x − 4 > 0 gives the domain x > 4, since logarithms are undefined for nonpositive arguments."},{"p":"What are the amplitude and period of the function y = 3 sin(2x)?","a":"Amplitude 3, period π","w":["Amplitude 3, period 2π","Amplitude 2, period π","Amplitude 6, period π"],"h":"The amplitude is the coefficient in front of sine; the period is 2π divided by the coefficient of x.","e":"For y = a sin(bx), amplitude = |a| = 3 and period = 2π/b = 2π/2 = π."},{"p":"In the arithmetic sequence 5, 9, 13, 17, …, which term equals 101?","a":"The 25th term","w":["The 24th term","The 26th term","The 20th term"],"h":"Write the nth-term formula aₙ = a₁ + (n − 1)d, set it equal to 101, and solve for n.","e":"Solving 5 + (n − 1)·4 = 101 gives 4(n − 1) = 96, so n = 25 by the arithmetic sequence formula."},{"p":"An investment of $2000 earns 4% annual interest compounded continuously. Using A = Pe^(rt), what is the value after 5 years (to the nearest cent)?","a":"$2442.81","w":["$2433.31","$2400.00","$2200.00"],"h":"Substitute P = 2000, r = 0.04, and t = 5 into A = Pe^(rt); continuous compounding uses the base e, not a yearly multiplier.","e":"The continuous-growth model A = Pe^(rt) gives A = 2000e^(0.2) ≈ $2442.81, slightly more than annual compounding because interest accrues instantaneously."},{"p":"A bacterial culture starts with 200 cells and triples every 4 hours. How many cells are present after 12 hours?","a":"5400 cells","w":["1800 cells","600 cells","16,200 cells"],"h":"Count how many 4-hour tripling periods fit into 12 hours, then apply the geometric growth model a·rⁿ.","e":"Exponential growth gives 200·3^(12/4) = 200·3³ = 200·27 = 5400, since 12 hours is exactly three tripling periods."},{"p":"On the Richter scale, an earthquake's intensity is 10^M. How many times more intense is a magnitude 6 earthquake than a magnitude 4 earthquake?","a":"100 times","w":["2 times","20 times","1000 times"],"h":"Because the scale is logarithmic, form the ratio 10^6 / 10^4 and simplify using exponent rules.","e":"The logarithmic Richter scale means the intensity ratio is 10^(6−4) = 10² = 100, so each whole unit represents a tenfold increase in intensity."},{"p":"What is the equation of the oblique (slant) asymptote of f(x) = (x² + 3x + 2)/(x − 1)?","a":"y = x + 4","w":["y = x − 4","y = x + 3","y = x"],"h":"A slant asymptote occurs when the numerator's degree is exactly one more than the denominator's; use polynomial long division and take the quotient.","e":"Dividing x² + 3x + 2 by x − 1 gives quotient x + 4 with remainder 6, so the slant asymptote is y = x + 4 (the remainder term vanishes as x → ±∞)."},{"p":"If sin θ = 3/5 and θ lies in the first quadrant, what is sin(2θ)?","a":"24/25","w":["6/5","12/25","7/25"],"h":"Apply the double-angle identity sin(2θ) = 2 sin θ cos θ; find cos θ first using the Pythagorean identity.","e":"With cos θ = 4/5, the double-angle identity gives sin(2θ) = 2·(3/5)·(4/5) = 24/25."},{"p":"Using a sum identity, what is the exact value of cos 75°?","a":"(√6 − √2)/4","w":["(√6 + √2)/4","(√2 − √6)/4","(√6 − √2)/2"],"h":"Write 75° as 45° + 30° and apply cos(A + B) = cos A cos B − sin A sin B.","e":"cos 75° = cos 45° cos 30° − sin 45° sin 30° = (√2/2)(√3/2) − (√2/2)(1/2) = (√6 − √2)/4."},{"p":"In a triangle, two sides measure 5 and 7 with an included angle of 60°. What is the length of the third side?","a":"√39 ≈ 6.24","w":["√109 ≈ 10.44","√74 ≈ 8.60","√4 = 2"],"h":"Use the Law of Cosines, c² = a² + b² − 2ab·cos C, with C being the angle between the two known sides.","e":"By the Law of Cosines, c² = 25 + 49 − 2(5)(7)cos 60° = 74 − 70(0.5) = 39, so c = √39 ≈ 6.24."},{"p":"An auditorium has 15 rows. The first row has 20 seats, and each row after has 3 more seats than the one before. How many seats are there in total?","a":"615 seats","w":["630 seats","600 seats","555 seats"],"h":"The seat counts form an arithmetic sequence; use the series sum Sₙ = (n/2)[2a₁ + (n − 1)d].","e":"With a₁ = 20, d = 3, n = 15: S₁₅ = (15/2)[2(20) + 14(3)] = 7.5(82) = 615 seats."},{"p":"A sequence is defined recursively by a₁ = 4 and aₙ = 2aₙ₋₁ − 1. What is a₄?","a":"25","w":["15","23","27"],"h":"Generate each term in order by substituting the previous term into the recursive rule; you cannot jump directly to a₄.","e":"Applying aₙ = 2aₙ₋₁ − 1: a₂ = 7, a₃ = 13, a₄ = 2(13) − 1 = 25."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit lim (x→∞) (3x² − 2x)/(5x² + 1).","a":"3/5","w":["0","3","The limit does not exist"],"h":"When numerator and denominator have equal degree, the limit at infinity is the ratio of the leading coefficients.","e":"Since both numerator and denominator have degree 2, the limit equals the ratio of leading coefficients, 3/5; lower-degree terms become negligible as x → ∞."},{"p":"Evaluate the limit lim (x→2) 1/(x − 2)².","a":"+∞","w":["−∞","0","The limit equals 1/2"],"h":"Consider the sign of the denominator as x approaches 2 from both sides; a squared quantity is always nonnegative.","e":"As x → 2, (x − 2)² → 0⁺ from both sides, so the reciprocal grows without bound; the limit is +∞."},{"p":"A polynomial has real coefficients, and 2i is one of its roots. Which value must also be a root?","a":"−2i","w":["3i","−2","2"],"h":"For polynomials with real coefficients, non-real roots occur in a specific paired form.","e":"By the Complex Conjugate Root Theorem, non-real roots of a real-coefficient polynomial come in conjugate pairs, so −2i must also be a root."},{"p":"What is the exact value of cos⁻¹(−1/2)?","a":"2π/3","w":["π/3","4π/3","5π/6"],"h":"The range of the inverse cosine function is [0, π], so the answer must lie in that interval.","e":"Since cos(2π/3) = −1/2 and 2π/3 lies within the arccosine range [0, π], cos⁻¹(−1/2) = 2π/3."},{"p":"What is the reference angle for a 210° angle in standard position?","a":"30°","w":["150°","60°","210°"],"h":"A reference angle is the acute angle between the terminal side and the x-axis; 210° lies in the third quadrant.","e":"For a third-quadrant angle, the reference angle is θ − 180°, so 210° − 180° = 30°."},{"p":"Convert 5π/6 radians to degrees.","a":"150°","w":["120°","210°","75°"],"h":"Multiply the radian measure by the conversion factor 180°/π.","e":"5π/6 × 180°/π = 5(180)/6 = 150°, using the fact that π radians equals 180°."},{"p":"If f(x) = 2x + 1 and g(x) = x², what is (f ∘ g)(3)?","a":"19","w":["49","37","13"],"h":"The composition (f ∘ g)(3) means apply g first, then feed that result into f; order matters.","e":"(f ∘ g)(3) = f(g(3)) = f(9) = 2(9) + 1 = 19; reversing the order would incorrectly give 49."},{"p":"Which of the following is an odd function?","a":"f(x) = x³ − x","w":["f(x) = x² + 1","f(x) = x³ + 1","f(x) = |x| + x"],"h":"A function is odd if f(−x) = −f(x), producing symmetry about the origin; test each by replacing x with −x.","e":"For f(x) = x³ − x, f(−x) = −x³ + x = −(x³ − x) = −f(x), so it is odd; the others fail this symmetry test."},{"p":"A Ferris wheel's height (in meters) is modeled by h(t) = 25 − 20cos((π/15)t), where t is in seconds. What is the period of one full revolution?","a":"30 seconds","w":["15 seconds","20 seconds","60 seconds"],"h":"For a sinusoid of the form cos(Bt), the period is 2π divided by the coefficient B.","e":"The period is 2π/B = 2π/(π/15) = 30 seconds, which is the time for one complete rotation of the wheel."}],"m.11.statistics":[{"p":"A real estate report lists home sale prices for a neighborhood. Read: \"Most homes sold between $200,000 and $300,000, but three mansions sold for over $2 million each.\" Which measure of center best represents the price of a typical home in this neighborhood?","a":"The median, because it resists the influence of the few extreme high prices","w":["The mean, because it uses every value in the data set","The mode, because it is the most frequently occurring price","The range, because it captures the full spread of prices"],"h":"Think about which measure gets pulled toward a small number of unusually large values.","e":"In a right-skewed distribution the median is the resistant (robust) measure of center, while the mean is pulled toward the extreme values."},{"p":"Find the median of the data set: 3, 8, 8, 12, 15, 20.","a":"10","w":["8","11","12"],"h":"With an even number of values, the median lies between the two middle numbers.","e":"For an even-sized ordered set the median is the mean of the two middle values, (8 + 12)/2 = 10."},{"p":"Find the mode of the data set: 2, 4, 4, 5, 7, 7, 7, 9.","a":"7","w":["4","9","5.6"],"h":"The mode is about frequency, not size or position.","e":"The mode is the value that occurs most often; 7 appears three times, more than any other value."},{"p":"A meteorologist records these daily high temperatures (F): 12, 5, 18, 3, 9. What is the range of this data set?","a":"15","w":["18","21","9"],"h":"The range depends only on the two most extreme values.","e":"The range is the maximum minus the minimum: 18 - 3 = 15."},{"p":"Two data sets have the same mean of 10. Set A is {10, 10, 10, 10} and Set B is {4, 8, 12, 16}. Which statement about their standard deviations is correct?","a":"Set B has the larger standard deviation because its values are more spread out from the mean","w":["Set A has the larger standard deviation because it has repeated values","The standard deviations are equal because the means are equal","Set B has a standard deviation of zero because its values are evenly spaced"],"h":"Standard deviation measures typical distance of values from the mean, not the mean itself.","e":"Standard deviation quantifies spread about the mean; Set A has zero deviation while Set B's values sit far from the mean, so Set B's standard deviation is larger."},{"p":"Every value in a data set is increased by 7. What happens to the standard deviation of the data set?","a":"It stays exactly the same","w":["It increases by 7","It increases by 49","It increases but by less than 7"],"h":"Consider whether shifting all values changes how spread out they are from each other.","e":"Adding a constant to every value shifts the entire distribution and the mean by that constant, but leaves the spread, and therefore the standard deviation, unchanged."},{"p":"A data set has a standard deviation of 4. If every value in the set is multiplied by 3, what is the new standard deviation?","a":"12","w":["4","7","36"],"h":"Scaling every value stretches the distances from the mean by the same factor.","e":"Multiplying every value by a constant k multiplies the standard deviation by |k|, so 4 x 3 = 12 (the variance would be multiplied by 9)."},{"p":"A study finds that monthly ice cream sales and the number of drowning deaths are strongly positively correlated. Read: \"As ice cream sales rise, drownings rise; as sales fall, drownings fall.\" What is the best explanation?","a":"A confounding variable, hot summer weather, increases both ice cream sales and swimming activity","w":["Buying ice cream directly causes people to drown","Drownings cause communities to buy more ice cream","The strong correlation proves ice cream sales cause drownings"],"h":"Correlation between two variables does not establish that one causes the other.","e":"This is a classic correlation-versus-causation case where a confounding (lurking) variable, warm weather, drives both associated variables."},{"p":"A scatterplot of two variables has a correlation coefficient of r = -0.92. How should this value be interpreted?","a":"A strong negative linear relationship","w":["A weak negative linear relationship","A strong positive linear relationship","No linear relationship between the variables"],"h":"The sign of r indicates direction and its distance from 0 indicates strength.","e":"A correlation coefficient near -1 indicates a strong negative linear relationship; the negative sign shows that one variable tends to decrease as the other increases."},{"p":"A fair six-sided die is rolled once. What is the probability of rolling a number that is even OR greater than 3?","a":"2/3","w":["1/2","5/6","1/3"],"h":"List the outcomes in each event and avoid counting shared outcomes twice.","e":"Using the addition rule for overlapping events, the favorable outcomes {2, 4, 5, 6} give 4/6 = 2/3."},{"p":"Events A and B are independent, with P(A) = 0.5 and P(B) = 0.4. What is P(A and B)?","a":"0.2","w":["0.9","0.1","0.45"],"h":"For independent events there is a specific rule combining the two probabilities.","e":"For independent events the multiplication rule gives P(A and B) = P(A) x P(B) = 0.5 x 0.4 = 0.2."},{"p":"A librarian wants to know how residents feel about increasing library funding, so she surveys only people currently inside the library. What type of flaw does this sampling method have?","a":"Undercoverage (selection) bias, because library users are not representative of all residents","w":["Nonresponse bias, because some people refused to answer","Response bias, because the wording of the question was leading","No bias, because everyone surveyed was chosen at random"],"h":"Consider whether the people who could be selected fairly represent the whole population.","e":"Sampling only from library users systematically excludes non-users, producing undercoverage bias that favors people already inclined toward funding."},{"p":"A survey of 100 students records sport preference by gender. Read: \"Soccer: 30 males, 25 females. Basketball: 20 males, 25 females.\" Given that a randomly chosen student prefers soccer, what is the probability the student is female?","a":"5/11","w":["6/11","1/4","1/2"],"h":"Restrict attention to only the students in the relevant column, then find the fraction of interest.","e":"This conditional probability uses only soccer fans as the denominator: 25 females out of 55 total soccer fans = 5/11."},{"p":"Adult IQ scores are approximately normally distributed with a mean of 100 and a standard deviation of 15. Approximately what percent of adults have scores between 85 and 115?","a":"About 68%","w":["About 95%","About 34%","About 99.7%"],"h":"Determine how many standard deviations 85 and 115 are from the mean, then apply the empirical rule.","e":"By the empirical (68-95-99.7) rule, about 68% of values fall within one standard deviation of the mean, here 85 to 115."},{"p":"Adult IQ scores are approximately normally distributed with a mean of 100 and a standard deviation of 15. Approximately what percent of adults score above 130?","a":"About 2.5%","w":["About 5%","About 47.5%","About 95%"],"h":"First find how many standard deviations 130 lies above the mean, then use the empirical rule and symmetry.","e":"A score of 130 is two standard deviations above the mean; the empirical rule leaves about 5% in both tails combined, so about 2.5% lies in the single upper tail."},{"p":"A histogram of household incomes has most of its bars clustered at lower values with a long tail extending toward the higher values. How is this distribution described, and how do its mean and median compare?","a":"Right-skewed, with the mean greater than the median","w":["Left-skewed, with the mean less than the median","Symmetric, with the mean equal to the median","Uniform, with the mean equal to the mode"],"h":"A skewed distribution is named for the direction of its long tail, and the mean follows that tail.","e":"A long tail toward large values indicates a right-skewed (positively skewed) distribution, and the extreme high values pull the mean above the median."},{"p":"A researcher divides a city into neighborhoods, randomly selects several entire neighborhoods, and surveys every household in each chosen neighborhood. Which sampling method is this?","a":"Cluster sampling","w":["Stratified sampling","Systematic sampling","Simple random sampling"],"h":"Focus on the fact that whole pre-existing groups are chosen, and everyone within a chosen group is included.","e":"Cluster sampling divides the population into groups (clusters), randomly selects some clusters, and samples all members within them, unlike stratified sampling which samples within every group."},{"p":"Find the interquartile range (IQR) of the data set: 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14, 16.","a":"8","w":["14","9","7"],"h":"Split the ordered data into lower and upper halves, then find the median of each half.","e":"The IQR is Q3 - Q1; here Q1 = 5 and Q3 = 13, so IQR = 13 - 5 = 8, a resistant measure of spread."},{"p":"The mean of five numbers is 14. Four of the numbers are 10, 12, 16, and 18. What is the value of the fifth number?","a":"14","w":["12","56","70"],"h":"The mean times the count gives the total of all five numbers.","e":"By the definition of the arithmetic mean, the sum of all values equals mean x count = 14 x 5 = 70; subtracting the four known values (56) leaves 70 - 56 = 14."},{"p":"A data set has a mean of 50 and a median of 50. A single extreme value of 200 is then added to the set. Which outcome is most likely?","a":"The mean increases substantially more than the median","w":["The median increases substantially more than the mean","Both the mean and the median stay exactly 50","Only the median increases while the mean is unchanged"],"h":"Think about which measure of center is resistant to extreme values.","e":"The median is a resistant (robust) statistic that barely shifts, while the mean is pulled toward the outlier, so the mean rises much more than the median."},{"p":"A data set has a variance of 36. What is its standard deviation?","a":"6","w":["1296","18","72"],"h":"Recall the algebraic relationship between variance and standard deviation.","e":"Standard deviation is the square root of the variance, so sqrt(36) = 6; squaring (36^2 = 1296) reverses the relationship."},{"p":"On an exam with a mean of 70 and a standard deviation of 8, a student scores an 86. What is the student's z-score?","a":"2","w":["16","-2","0.5"],"h":"A z-score measures how many standard deviations a value lies from the mean.","e":"The z-score formula is z = (x - mean)/SD = (86 - 70)/8 = 2, meaning the score is 2 standard deviations above the mean."},{"p":"Adult heights are approximately normally distributed with a mean of 170 cm and a standard deviation of 10 cm. Approximately what percent of adults have heights between 150 cm and 190 cm?","a":"About 95%","w":["About 68%","About 99.7%","About 47.5%"],"h":"Determine how many standard deviations 150 cm and 190 cm are from the mean.","e":"150 cm and 190 cm are each 2 standard deviations from the mean, and by the empirical (68-95-99.7) rule about 95% of data lie within 2 SD of the mean."},{"p":"Scores on a standardized test are normally distributed with a mean of 500 and a standard deviation of 100. Approximately what percent of test-takers score below 600?","a":"About 84%","w":["About 68%","About 16%","About 34%"],"h":"600 is exactly one standard deviation above the mean; combine the lower half with the region up to +1 SD.","e":"By the empirical rule, 50% score below the mean and about 34% score between the mean and +1 SD, so about 50% + 34% = 84% score below 600."},{"p":"A student's score on a college placement exam is reported to be at the 80th percentile. What does this indicate?","a":"About 80% of test-takers scored at or below this student's score","w":["The student answered about 80% of the questions correctly","The student scored higher than about 20% of test-takers","About 80% of test-takers scored higher than this student"],"h":"A percentile describes a value's rank relative to the rest of the distribution, not a raw percent correct.","e":"By definition, the kth percentile is the value at or below which about k% of the data fall, so the 80th percentile means roughly 80% scored at or below this student."},{"p":"A box-and-whisker plot displays the five-number summary of a data set. What percent of the data values lie between the first quartile (Q1) and the third quartile (Q3)?","a":"50%","w":["25%","75%","100%"],"h":"Recall what fraction of the data each quartile boundary marks off.","e":"Q1 and Q3 mark the 25th and 75th percentiles, so the interquartile range between them contains the middle 50% of the data."},{"p":"In a class, the probability a student is in honors is 0.3, the probability a student plays a sport is 0.4, and the probability of both is 0.1. What is the probability a randomly chosen student is in honors OR plays a sport?","a":"0.6","w":["0.7","0.12","0.1"],"h":"These events overlap, so a plain sum would count some students twice.","e":"By the general addition rule, P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B) = 0.3 + 0.4 - 0.1 = 0.6."},{"p":"A basketball player makes 80% of her free throws, and her attempts are independent. If she takes two free throws, what is the probability she makes at least one of them?","a":"0.96","w":["0.64","0.80","0.16"],"h":"It is easier to find the probability of the opposite event first.","e":"By the complement rule, P(at least one) = 1 - P(none) = 1 - (0.2)(0.2) = 1 - 0.04 = 0.96."},{"p":"A bag contains 5 red marbles and 3 blue marbles. Two marbles are drawn one after another without replacement. What is the probability that both are red?","a":"5/14","w":["25/64","5/16","5/28"],"h":"After the first red is drawn, the counts of red marbles and total marbles both change.","e":"For dependent events, multiply the conditional probabilities: (5/8)(4/7) = 20/56 = 5/14; using 5/8 twice wrongly assumes replacement."},{"p":"In a carnival game, a player wins $5 with probability 0.2 and loses $1 with probability 0.8. What is the expected value of one play for the player?","a":"A gain of $0.20","w":["A gain of $4.00","A loss of $0.20","A gain of $2.00"],"h":"Multiply each outcome by its probability and add the products, keeping the sign of losses.","e":"Expected value = (0.2)($5) + (0.8)(-$1) = $1.00 - $0.80 = $0.20, a small average gain per play."},{"p":"A quality manager inspects a production line by selecting every 10th item that comes off the conveyor belt. Which sampling method is this?","a":"Systematic sampling","w":["Stratified sampling","Cluster sampling","Simple random sampling"],"h":"Focus on the fixed interval pattern used to choose items.","e":"Selecting units at a fixed periodic interval (every 10th item) from an ordered sequence is the definition of systematic sampling."},{"p":"A town survey asks residents: \"Do you support the wasteful spending on the unnecessary new stadium?\" What flaw does this question most clearly introduce?","a":"Response bias from loaded, leading wording","w":["Undercoverage of certain residents","Nonresponse bias from unreturned surveys","Sampling bias from a small sample size"],"h":"Examine the emotionally charged adjectives built into the question itself.","e":"Loaded or leading wording pushes respondents toward a particular answer, a form of response bias tied to how the question is phrased rather than who is sampled."},{"p":"A city report notes a pattern in fire records. Read: \"Fires that had more firefighters present tended to cause more property damage.\" What is the best explanation for this positive association?","a":"A lurking variable, the size of the fire, drives both quantities","w":["Sending more firefighters causes more property damage","The two variables have a negative correlation","There is no real association between the variables"],"h":"Ask what third factor would naturally raise both the number of firefighters and the damage.","e":"Correlation does not imply causation; a lurking (confounding) variable, the fire's size, increases both the firefighter count and the damage."},{"p":"Four studies each report a correlation coefficient between two variables: r = -0.85, r = 0.60, r = 0.30, and r = -0.10. Which value indicates the strongest linear relationship?","a":"r = -0.85","w":["r = 0.60","r = 0.30","r = -0.10"],"h":"The strength of a linear relationship depends on distance from zero, not on the sign.","e":"Strength is measured by the absolute value of r; |-0.85| = 0.85 is closest to 1, so it is the strongest linear relationship even though it is negative."},{"p":"A histogram of a data set shows two separate, distinct peaks with a dip between them. How is this distribution best described?","a":"Bimodal","w":["Skewed right","Uniform","Symmetric and unimodal"],"h":"Count how many clear high points (modes) the shape has.","e":"A distribution with two distinct peaks is called bimodal, often signaling two different subgroups combined in one data set."},{"p":"A course grade is weighted as follows: tests count 50%, homework 20%, and the final exam 30%. A student earns 80 on tests, 90 on homework, and 70 on the final exam. What is the student's weighted final grade?","a":"79","w":["80","78","82"],"h":"Multiply each score by its decimal weight, then add the products together.","e":"This is a weighted mean: (0.50)(80) + (0.20)(90) + (0.30)(70) = 79, which differs from the simple average of 80 because the components carry unequal weights."},{"p":"Class A has 20 students with a mean test score of 75. Class B has 30 students with a mean test score of 85. What is the mean score of all 50 students combined?","a":"81","w":["80","82","79"],"h":"You cannot simply average the two means because the classes have different sizes.","e":"The combined (pooled) mean weights each group by its size: (20*75 + 30*85)/50 = 4050/50 = 81."},{"p":"On a math test (mean 70, SD 10), Maria scored 85. On a history test (mean 60, SD 5), she scored 68. Relative to her classmates, on which test did she perform better?","a":"History, because her z-score of 1.6 is higher than her math z-score of 1.5.","w":["Math, because her z-score of 1.5 is higher than her history z-score of 1.6.","Math, because her raw score of 85 is higher than her history score of 68.","They were equal, because both scores fell above their respective means."],"h":"Convert each raw score to a z-score so the two different distributions can be compared fairly.","e":"z-scores standardize scores across distributions: math z = (85-70)/10 = 1.5, history z = (68-60)/5 = 1.6, so history is the relatively stronger performance."},{"p":"Adult heights at a clinic are approximately normally distributed with a mean of 170 cm and a standard deviation of 6 cm. Approximately what percent of adults have heights between 152 cm and 188 cm?","a":"99.7%","w":["95%","68%","99.9%"],"h":"Determine how many standard deviations each endpoint lies from the mean.","e":"By the empirical (68-95-99.7) rule, 152 and 188 are exactly 3 standard deviations from the mean, so about 99.7% of values fall in that interval."},{"p":"The lifespan of a certain battery is approximately normally distributed with a mean of 40 hours and a standard deviation of 5 hours. Approximately what percent of these batteries last between 40 and 45 hours?","a":"34%","w":["68%","47.5%","16%"],"h":"About 68% of values lie within one standard deviation, split symmetrically about the mean.","e":"By the empirical rule, 68% lie within one SD of the mean; the half from the mean up to +1 SD (40 to 45 hours) is about 34%."},{"p":"Which of the following measures of spread is LEAST affected by a single extreme outlier in a data set?","a":"Interquartile range (IQR)","w":["Range","Standard deviation","Variance"],"h":"Consider which measures are computed using every value, including the most extreme ones.","e":"The IQR is a resistant measure because it depends only on the middle 50% of the data; range, variance, and standard deviation all use the extreme values and are pulled by outliers."},{"p":"A data set contains one value that is far larger than all the others (an outlier). If that single largest value is removed from the set, what happens to the mean and the range?","a":"Both the mean and the range decrease.","w":["The mean decreases but the range stays the same.","The range decreases but the mean stays the same.","Both the mean and the range increase."],"h":"Think about how the maximum value contributes to each measure separately.","e":"Removing the large outlier lowers the sum (so the mean decreases) and lowers the maximum (so the range, max minus min, decreases as well)."},{"p":"A scatterplot of two variables has a correlation coefficient of exactly r = 0. Which conclusion is best supported?","a":"There is no linear relationship, though a nonlinear relationship may still exist.","w":["The two variables have no relationship of any kind.","The two variables are perfectly but inversely related.","Increasing one variable always decreases the other."],"h":"Remember precisely what quantity the correlation coefficient is designed to measure.","e":"The correlation coefficient measures only the strength of a LINEAR association, so r = 0 rules out a linear trend but not a curved (nonlinear) relationship."},{"p":"Read: \"At each of two hospitals, Hospital A had a higher survival rate than Hospital B for both mild cases and severe cases. Yet when all patients were combined, Hospital B had the higher overall survival rate.\" What best explains this?","a":"A lurking variable, the differing mix of case severity, reverses the overall comparison (Simpson's paradox).","w":["The data must contain an arithmetic error, because this situation is impossible.","Hospital A is clearly better overall since it wins in both separate categories.","Survival rate is not a valid statistic for comparing two hospitals."],"h":"Consider whether the two hospitals treat the same proportion of severe versus mild cases.","e":"This is Simpson's paradox: a confounding variable (case-severity mix) can reverse an association when subgroups are aggregated, so within-group and overall comparisons disagree."},{"p":"Read: \"Of 200 people screened, 40 have the disease and test positive, 10 have the disease and test negative, 20 are disease-free but test positive, and 130 are disease-free and test negative.\" Given that a person tests positive, what is the probability that they actually have the disease?","a":"2/3","w":["4/5","1/3","1/2"],"h":"Restrict the sample space to only the people who tested positive.","e":"This is a conditional probability, P(disease | positive): of the 60 positive tests (40 + 20), 40 truly have the disease, giving 40/60 = 2/3."},{"p":"An insurance policy sells for a $200 annual premium. The company expects to pay $10,000 with probability 0.01 and $1,000 with probability 0.05; otherwise it pays nothing. What is the company's expected profit per policy?","a":"$50","w":["$150","$100","$250"],"h":"First find the expected payout, then compare it to the premium collected.","e":"Expected payout = 0.01($10,000) + 0.05($1,000) = $150, so expected profit = $200 premium minus $150 = $50, using the definition of expected value."},{"p":"A single card is drawn at random from a standard 52-card deck. What is the probability that it is a king OR a queen?","a":"2/13","w":["1/13","4/13","1/26"],"h":"A single card cannot be both a king and a queen at the same time.","e":"Because the two events are mutually exclusive, P(king or queen) = P(king) + P(queen) = 4/52 + 4/52 = 8/52 = 2/13."},{"p":"A basketball player makes 70% of her free throws, and her attempts are independent. If she takes three free throws, what is the probability she makes at least one of them?","a":"0.973","w":["0.343","0.657","0.900"],"h":"Use the complement: it is easier to compute the probability of making none.","e":"By the complement rule, P(at least one) = 1 - P(none) = 1 - (0.30)^3 = 1 - 0.027 = 0.973."},{"p":"Read: \"A TV station invites viewers to call a phone number to vote on a controversial issue, and only those who feel strongly about it bother to call in.\" Which type of bias is MOST clearly present?","a":"Voluntary response bias","w":["Undercoverage bias","Nonresponse bias","Response (wording) bias"],"h":"Focus on who decides whether or not to participate in the poll.","e":"Voluntary response bias occurs when a self-selected sample (people who choose to respond) overrepresents those with strong opinions, distorting the results."},{"p":"Read: \"A survey of 80 commuters records travel mode and satisfaction. Car: 25 satisfied, 15 not satisfied. Transit: 20 satisfied, 20 not satisfied.\" What is the probability that a randomly chosen commuter is satisfied?","a":"9/16","w":["5/8","1/2","5/9"],"h":"Count all satisfied commuters and divide by the total number of commuters.","e":"This is a marginal probability: total satisfied = 25 + 20 = 45 out of 80, giving 45/80 = 9/16."},{"p":"Read: \"On a box plot, the whisker on the right (toward higher values) is much longer than the whisker on the left, and the median line sits closer to Q1.\" What does this indicate about the distribution's shape?","a":"It is skewed right (positively skewed).","w":["It is skewed left (negatively skewed).","It is symmetric with no skew.","It is uniform across all values."],"h":"The direction in which the longer tail points signals the direction of the skew.","e":"A longer right whisker and a median near Q1 both indicate a longer tail toward high values, which is the signature of a right-skewed (positively skewed) distribution."},{"p":"A machine produces parts that are defective 5% of the time, with each part independent of the others. What is the probability that three consecutive parts are all non-defective?","a":"0.857","w":["0.950","0.150","0.143"],"h":"Find the probability a single part is non-defective, then apply it to all three parts.","e":"By the multiplication rule for independent events, P(all three good) = (0.95)^3 = 0.857."}],"m.12.calculus":[{"p":"Evaluate lim_{x→4} (x²−16)/(x−4).","a":"8","w":["0","16","undefined"],"h":"Factor the numerator as a difference of squares and cancel the common factor before substituting.","e":"The numerator factors as (x−4)(x+4); canceling (x−4) leaves x+4, and substitution gives 8. This is a removable discontinuity."},{"p":"Evaluate lim_{x→0} (sin x)/x, where x is in radians.","a":"1","w":["0","∞","undefined"],"h":"This is a standard trigonometric limit; examine the ratio's behavior for very small angles.","e":"The special trigonometric limit lim_{x→0} (sin x)/x = 1 is a foundational result used to derive the derivatives of the trigonometric functions."},{"p":"A function f is continuous at x = a if and only if which condition holds?","a":"f(a) is defined, lim_{x→a} f(x) exists, and lim_{x→a} f(x) = f(a)","w":["f(a) is defined and f is bounded near x = a","the one-sided limit lim_{x→a⁺} f(x) exists at x = a","f is differentiable at the point x = a"],"h":"Continuity requires both the two-sided limit and the function value to exist and to agree.","e":"The formal definition of continuity requires the function value to exist, the two-sided limit to exist, and the two to be equal."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = x^7.","a":"7x^6","w":["x^6","7x^7","6x^6"],"h":"Apply the power rule: bring the exponent down as a coefficient and reduce it by one.","e":"By the power rule, d/dx[x^n] = n·x^(n−1), so the derivative of x^7 is 7x^6."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = x² sin x.","a":"2x sin x + x² cos x","w":["2x cos x + x² sin x","2x sin x + x² sin x","2x cos x + sin x"],"h":"Use the product rule: (derivative of first)(second) + (first)(derivative of second).","e":"The product rule gives (x²)′ sin x + x²(sin x)′ = 2x sin x + x² cos x."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = x/(x+1).","a":"1/(x+1)²","w":["−1/(x+1)²","(2x+1)/(x+1)²","x/(x+1)²"],"h":"Apply the quotient rule (low·d(high) − high·d(low))/low², then simplify the numerator.","e":"By the quotient rule, [(x+1)(1) − x(1)]/(x+1)² = 1/(x+1)²."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = (3x²+1)^4.","a":"24x(3x²+1)³","w":["4(3x²+1)³","24x(3x²+1)⁴","6x(3x²+1)³"],"h":"Differentiate the outer power first, then multiply by the derivative of the inside expression.","e":"The chain rule gives 4(3x²+1)³·(6x) = 24x(3x²+1)³."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = sin(3x).","a":"3 cos(3x)","w":["cos(3x)","−3 cos(3x)","3 sin(3x)"],"h":"Differentiate the outer sine, then multiply by the derivative of the inner argument 3x.","e":"The chain rule gives cos(3x)·3 = 3 cos(3x)."},{"p":"A particle moves so that its position is s(t) = t³ − 6t² + 9t meters, with t in seconds. What is its velocity at t = 2 s?","a":"−3 m/s","w":["3 m/s","−1 m/s","6 m/s"],"h":"Velocity is the first derivative of position; find it, then evaluate at the given time.","e":"v(t) = s′(t) = 3t² − 12t + 9, so v(2) = 12 − 24 + 9 = −3 m/s; the negative sign indicates motion in the negative direction."},{"p":"Find the minimum value of f(x) = x² − 4x + 7.","a":"3","w":["2","7","−4"],"h":"Set the derivative equal to zero to find the critical point, then evaluate the function there.","e":"f′(x) = 2x − 4 = 0 gives x = 2, and f(2) = 4 − 8 + 7 = 3, a minimum since the parabola opens upward."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₀² 3 dx.","a":"6","w":["3","5","2"],"h":"Interpret the integral as the area of the rectangle under the constant function.","e":"The definite integral of a constant c over [a,b] equals c(b−a) = 3(2−0) = 6, the area of the rectangle."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₁³ 2x dx.","a":"8","w":["4","9","6"],"h":"Find an antiderivative, then apply the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus by evaluating at the bounds and subtracting.","e":"An antiderivative of 2x is x²; by the FTC, [x²]₁³ = 9 − 1 = 8."},{"p":"Compute d/dx ∫₀ˣ t² dt.","a":"x²","w":["2x","x³/3","t²"],"h":"The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, Part 1, treats differentiation and integration as inverse operations.","e":"By the FTC Part 1, d/dx ∫₀ˣ f(t) dt = f(x), so the derivative equals x²."},{"p":"Find the indefinite integral ∫ x² dx.","a":"x³/3 + C","w":["2x + C","x³ + C","3x³ + C"],"h":"Reverse the power rule: raise the exponent by one and divide by the new exponent.","e":"By the reverse power rule, ∫ x^n dx = x^(n+1)/(n+1) + C, giving x³/3 + C."},{"p":"The derivative f′(a) is best interpreted geometrically as which of the following?","a":"The slope of the line tangent to the graph of f at x = a","w":["The slope of the secant line through the graph's endpoints","The area under the graph of f from 0 to x = a","The average rate of change of f over its entire domain"],"h":"Think about the limit of secant-line slopes as the second point approaches x = a.","e":"The derivative is defined as the limit of secant slopes, which equals the slope of the tangent line at that point."},{"p":"For what value of k is the function f(x) = (x²−1)/(x−1) for x ≠ 1, with f(1) = k, continuous at x = 1?","a":"2","w":["0","1","−1"],"h":"Simplify the rational expression to find the limit as x approaches 1, then match f(1) to that limit.","e":"Since (x²−1)/(x−1) = x + 1 for x ≠ 1, the limit at x = 1 is 2; continuity requires k to equal that limit."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₀^{2π} sin x dx.","a":"0","w":["2","−2","4"],"h":"Consider how the positive region above the axis compares with the negative region below over one full period.","e":"Over a full period, the area above the axis exactly cancels the area below, so the net signed area is 0."},{"p":"Find the average rate of change of f(x) = x² on the interval [1, 4].","a":"5","w":["3","9","8"],"h":"The average rate of change is the slope of the secant line: change in output divided by change in input.","e":"The average rate of change is (f(4) − f(1))/(4 − 1) = (16 − 1)/3 = 5, the slope of the secant line."},{"p":"Evaluate lim_{x→∞} (2x² + 3x)/(5x² − 1).","a":"2/5","w":["5/2","0","2"],"h":"Compare the degrees of the numerator and denominator, or divide every term by the highest power of x.","e":"For a rational function where numerator and denominator have equal degree, the limit at infinity is the ratio of the leading coefficients, 2/5."},{"p":"Let f(x) = ax + 1 for x ≤ 1 and f(x) = x² + 2 for x > 1. For what value of a is f continuous at x = 1?","a":"2","w":["3","1","−2"],"h":"Continuity requires the left-hand and right-hand pieces to agree in value at x = 1.","e":"Continuity demands lim from the left equals lim from the right equals f(1); setting a(1) + 1 = 1² + 2 gives a = 2."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = x³eˣ.","a":"x²eˣ(x + 3)","w":["3x²eˣ","x²eˣ(3 − x)","x³eˣ"],"h":"This is a product of two functions, so apply the product rule rather than differentiating each factor separately.","e":"By the product rule, f′ = 3x²eˣ + x³eˣ = x²eˣ(x + 3)."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = (2x + 1)/(x² + 1).","a":"(2 − 2x − 2x²)/(x² + 1)²","w":["(2x² + 2x − 2)/(x² + 1)²","(2 − 2x − 2x²)/(x² + 1)","2/(2x)"],"h":"Use the quotient rule and be careful with the order (low·d-high minus high·d-low) and squaring the denominator.","e":"By the quotient rule, f′ = [2(x² + 1) − (2x + 1)(2x)]/(x² + 1)² = (2 − 2x − 2x²)/(x² + 1)²."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = cos(x²).","a":"−2x sin(x²)","w":["2x sin(x²)","−sin(x²)","−2x cos(x²)"],"h":"The cosine has an inside function x²; use the chain rule and don't forget its derivative.","e":"By the chain rule, d/dx cos(u) = −sin(u)·u′, so with u = x² the derivative is −2x sin(x²)."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = √(4x² + 1).","a":"4x/√(4x² + 1)","w":["8x/√(4x² + 1)","1/(2√(4x² + 1))","4x·√(4x² + 1)"],"h":"Rewrite the root as a power (4x² + 1)^{1/2} and apply the chain rule.","e":"By the chain rule, f′ = ½(4x² + 1)^{−1/2}·8x = 4x/√(4x² + 1)."},{"p":"A particle has position s(t) = t³ − 3t² meters, with t in seconds. What is its acceleration at t = 2 s?","a":"6 m/s²","w":["0 m/s²","12 m/s²","−6 m/s²"],"h":"Acceleration is the second derivative of position; differentiate twice before substituting.","e":"Since v(t) = s′(t) = 3t² − 6t and a(t) = s″(t) = 6t − 6, the acceleration at t = 2 is 6 m/s²."},{"p":"A farmer uses 40 m of fencing to enclose a rectangular pen along a straight wall, fencing only the three sides not against the wall. What is the maximum possible area?","a":"200 m²","w":["100 m²","400 m²","150 m²"],"h":"Write the area as a function of one side using the perimeter constraint, then find where its derivative is zero.","e":"With sides x, x, and 40 − 2x, area A = x(40 − 2x) is maximized where A′ = 40 − 4x = 0, giving x = 10 and A = 200 m²."},{"p":"Find the local maximum value of f(x) = x³ − 3x.","a":"2","w":["−2","0","1"],"h":"Locate the critical points from f′(x) = 0, then use the second derivative or sign of f′ to identify which is a maximum.","e":"f′(x) = 3x² − 3 = 0 gives x = ±1; since f″(x) = 6x < 0 at x = −1, the local maximum value is f(−1) = 2."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₁² 3x² dx.","a":"7","w":["8","21","9"],"h":"Find an antiderivative of 3x², then apply the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus using both limits.","e":"An antiderivative of 3x² is x³, so by the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus the value is 2³ − 1³ = 7."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₀¹ eˣ dx.","a":"e − 1","w":["e","1 − e","e + 1"],"h":"The antiderivative of eˣ is itself; evaluate it at both limits.","e":"Since d/dx eˣ = eˣ, by the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus ∫₀¹ eˣ dx = e¹ − e⁰ = e − 1."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₀^{π/2} cos x dx.","a":"1","w":["0","−1","π/2"],"h":"Recall which trig function has cosine as its derivative, then evaluate at the two limits.","e":"An antiderivative of cos x is sin x, so the integral equals sin(π/2) − sin(0) = 1."},{"p":"Find the average value of f(x) = x² on the interval [0, 3].","a":"3","w":["9","6","4.5"],"h":"The average value is the definite integral over the interval divided by the interval's length.","e":"The average value equals (1/(3−0))∫₀³ x² dx = (1/3)(9) = 3."},{"p":"Evaluate lim_{x→0} (1 − cos x)/x², where x is in radians.","a":"1/2","w":["0","1","2"],"h":"This is a 0/0 indeterminate form; consider a known trigonometric limit or apply L'Hôpital's rule.","e":"This is an indeterminate 0/0 form; applying L'Hôpital's rule twice (or the known limit) gives 1/2."},{"p":"Which statement about f(x) = |x| at x = 0 is true?","a":"f is continuous at 0 but not differentiable at 0.","w":["f is differentiable at 0 but not continuous at 0.","f is both continuous and differentiable at 0.","f is neither continuous nor differentiable at 0."],"h":"Check whether the graph has a break versus whether it has a well-defined single tangent slope at the origin.","e":"|x| has no jump so it is continuous at 0, but its left and right slopes (−1 and +1) differ, so it is not differentiable there; continuity does not imply differentiability."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫_{−1}^{1} x³ dx.","a":"0","w":["1/2","2","1/4"],"h":"Consider the symmetry of x³ about the origin, or compute the antiderivative and evaluate at both limits.","e":"x³ is an odd function, so its integral over the symmetric interval [−1, 1] is 0; equivalently x⁴/4 gives 1/4 − 1/4 = 0."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₀² (2x + 1) dx.","a":"6","w":["4","5","8"],"h":"Integrate term by term to get an antiderivative, then apply the limits — don't forget the constant term.","e":"An antiderivative is x² + x, so by the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus the value is (4 + 2) − 0 = 6."},{"p":"A tank's water volume is V(t) = 100 − 5t² liters, with t in seconds. At what rate is the volume changing at t = 2 s?","a":"−20 liters per second","w":["−10 liters per second","−40 liters per second","80 liters per second"],"h":"The rate of change is the derivative dV/dt, not the value of V itself; differentiate before substituting.","e":"dV/dt = −10t, so at t = 2 the volume is decreasing at −20 liters per second."},{"p":"A piecewise function is defined by f(x) = x + 1 for x < 2 and f(x) = x² for x ≥ 2. Evaluate the left-hand limit lim_{x→2⁻} f(x).","a":"3","w":["4","7","The limit does not exist"],"h":"As x approaches 2 from the left, only the rule that applies to inputs less than 2 is relevant.","e":"A one-sided (left-hand) limit uses the branch valid for x < 2, so lim_{x→2⁻} f(x) = 2 + 1 = 3; the value 4 is the right-hand limit."},{"p":"Describe the behavior of lim_{x→∞} (x³ + 2x)/(x² + 1).","a":"It diverges to +∞","w":["It converges to 0","It converges to 1","It converges to 2"],"h":"Compare the degree of the numerator polynomial with the degree of the denominator polynomial.","e":"When the numerator's degree exceeds the denominator's degree, the rational function grows without bound, so it diverges to +∞ rather than approaching a finite horizontal asymptote."},{"p":"The function f(x) = (x² − x − 6)/(x − 3) is undefined at x = 3. What type of discontinuity occurs there?","a":"Removable discontinuity","w":["Jump discontinuity","Infinite discontinuity","No discontinuity (f is continuous)"],"h":"Try factoring the numerator and see whether the troublesome factor cancels.","e":"Since x² − x − 6 = (x − 3)(x + 2), the (x − 3) factor cancels and the limit exists (equals 5), so the gap is a removable discontinuity."},{"p":"The circle x² + y² = 25 defines y implicitly as a function of x. Use implicit differentiation to find dy/dx.","a":"−x/y","w":["x/y","−y/x","−x²/y²"],"h":"Differentiate both sides with respect to x, treating y as a function of x, then solve for dy/dx.","e":"Implicit differentiation gives 2x + 2y·(dy/dx) = 0, so dy/dx = −x/y."},{"p":"Given f(x) = ln x, find the second derivative f″(x).","a":"−1/x²","w":["1/x²","−1/x","1/x"],"h":"First find f′(x), then differentiate that result again using the power rule on a negative exponent.","e":"Since f′(x) = 1/x = x⁻¹, differentiating again gives f″(x) = −x⁻² = −1/x²."},{"p":"Air is pumped into a spherical balloon at a rate of 100 cm³/s. Using V = (4/3)πr³, how fast is the radius increasing at the instant when r = 5 cm?","a":"1/π cm/s","w":["4/π cm/s","1/(4π) cm/s","100/π cm/s"],"h":"Differentiate the volume formula with respect to time and substitute the known dV/dt and radius.","e":"This related-rates problem gives dV/dt = 4πr²·(dr/dt), so 100 = 4π(25)(dr/dt) = 100π(dr/dt), yielding dr/dt = 1/π cm/s."},{"p":"A 10 m ladder leans against a wall while its base slides away from the wall at 2 m/s. How fast is the top of the ladder sliding down when the base is 6 m from the wall?","a":"1.5 m/s downward","w":["2 m/s downward","12 m/s downward","4/3 m/s downward"],"h":"Use x² + y² = 100 to find the height, then differentiate with respect to time.","e":"With x = 6, y = 8; differentiating x² + y² = 100 gives x(dx/dt) + y(dy/dt) = 0, so 6(2) + 8(dy/dt) = 0 and dy/dt = −1.5 m/s."},{"p":"A factory's cost to produce x units is C(x) = 0.01x² + 5x + 200 dollars. What is the marginal cost when x = 50 units?","a":"$6 per unit","w":["$5 per unit","$9.50 per unit","$10 per unit"],"h":"Marginal cost is the derivative of the cost function evaluated at the given production level, not the average cost.","e":"Marginal cost is C′(x) = 0.02x + 5, so C′(50) = 1 + 5 = $6 per unit; the $9.50 value is the average cost per unit."},{"p":"Find the x-coordinate of the inflection point of f(x) = x³ − 6x² + 5.","a":"x = 2","w":["x = 0","x = 4","x = 1"],"h":"An inflection point occurs where concavity changes, which is signaled by the second derivative.","e":"Since f″(x) = 6x − 12 = 0 gives x = 2, and concavity changes there, the inflection point is at x = 2; x = 0 and x = 4 are the critical points from f′."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = ln(3x² + 1).","a":"6x/(3x² + 1)","w":["1/(3x² + 1)","6x","(3x² + 1)/(6x)"],"h":"Apply the chain rule: the derivative of ln(u) is (1/u) times the derivative of u.","e":"By the chain rule, f′(x) = (1/(3x² + 1))·(6x) = 6x/(3x² + 1)."},{"p":"Differentiate f(x) = tan(2x).","a":"2 sec²(2x)","w":["sec²(2x)","2 sec²(x)","−2 csc²(2x)"],"h":"The derivative of tan(u) is sec²(u), and the inner function's derivative must be included.","e":"By the chain rule, f′(x) = sec²(2x)·2 = 2 sec²(2x); forgetting the inner derivative gives sec²(2x)."},{"p":"Evaluate the definite integral ∫₀¹ 2x(x² + 1)³ dx.","a":"15/4","w":["15","1/4","4"],"h":"Use substitution with u = x² + 1 and change the limits of integration accordingly.","e":"With u = x² + 1 (du = 2x dx), the integral becomes ∫₁² u³ du = [u⁴/4]₁² = (16 − 1)/4 = 15/4."},{"p":"Find the area of the region enclosed between the curves y = x and y = x² from x = 0 to x = 1.","a":"1/6","w":["1/2","1/3","5/6"],"h":"Integrate the difference (upper curve minus lower curve) over the interval; on (0,1), x lies above x².","e":"The area is ∫₀¹ (x − x²) dx = [x²/2 − x³/3]₀¹ = 1/2 − 1/3 = 1/6."},{"p":"A particle moves along a line with velocity v(t) = t − 2 meters per second, with t in seconds. What is the particle's displacement over the interval from t = 0 to t = 3 seconds?","a":"−1.5 m","w":["2.5 m","1.5 m","−6 m"],"h":"Displacement is the signed integral of velocity, so negative velocity contributes negative area.","e":"Displacement is ∫₀³ (t − 2) dt = [t²/2 − 2t]₀³ = 4.5 − 6 = −1.5 m; the value 2.5 m would be the total distance traveled."},{"p":"Compute d/dx ∫₀^{x²} sin t dt.","a":"2x sin(x²)","w":["sin(x²)","2x cos(x²)","−2x cos(x²)"],"h":"Apply the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus together with the chain rule for the variable upper limit.","e":"By the FTC and chain rule, d/dx ∫₀^{g(x)} sin t dt = sin(g(x))·g′(x) = sin(x²)·2x = 2x sin(x²)."},{"p":"For f(x) = x² on the interval [0, 4], the Mean Value Theorem guarantees a value c in (0, 4) where f′(c) equals the average rate of change. Find c.","a":"c = 2","w":["c = 4","c = 1","c = 2√2"],"h":"Set the derivative equal to the average rate of change (slope of the secant) over the interval and solve.","e":"The average rate of change is (16 − 0)/4 = 4, and f′(c) = 2c = 4 gives c = 2, as guaranteed by the Mean Value Theorem."},{"p":"A company's daily profit (in dollars) from selling x items is P(x) = −2x² + 40x − 50. How many items should be sold to maximize profit?","a":"10 items","w":["20 items","5 items","40 items"],"h":"Maximum profit occurs at a critical point where the derivative of the profit function is zero.","e":"Setting P′(x) = −4x + 40 = 0 gives x = 10; since P″(x) = −4 < 0, this critical point is a maximum."},{"p":"Evaluate lim_{x→0} x² sin(1/x).","a":"0","w":["1","Does not exist","Undefined"],"h":"The sine factor stays bounded between −1 and 1; consider what the x² factor does near 0.","e":"By the Squeeze Theorem, since −x² ≤ x² sin(1/x) ≤ x² and both bounds approach 0, the limit is 0."}]};
